<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-DEFINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HEDGE FUND' LACKS A SIMPLE DEFINITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: With HEDGEFUND-SCENE) 
(mk) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the extent that the term ``hedge fund'' conjures up any image
in the public's mind these days, it is likely to be a picture of
financial calamity created by Long-Term Capital Management, the
Greenwich, Conn., investment pool that nearly went belly up.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier day and among a smaller group of people, a hedge
fund might have been personified by George Soros, the billionaire
investor who battered the British pound and tried to bankroll
democracy in Eastern Europe. Among an even smaller set, the phrase
might bring to mind investors like Michael Steinhardt, Julian
Robertson or Leon Cooperman, all known for being very quiet and
very, very rich.
</P>
<P>
   But in point of fact, ``hedge fund'' does not really mean much
at all. ``There is no legal definition of hedge fund,'' said Lois
Pelz, editor of MAR/Hedge, a publication that tracks hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   Her organization defines them generally as investment pools in
which the managers get a big share of the profits _ 20 percent, on
average. Mutual fund managers, by contrast, can charge only an
annual fee; regulators worry that awarding them a slice of the
profits will encourage them to take big risks.
</P>
<P>
   Other characteristics of hedge funds, Ms. Pelz said, are that
they tend to invest in more than one kind of market (not just
stocks, but also futures, for example), and that they often borrow
money to increase their bets.
</P>
<P>
   Some hedge funds speculate on corporate takeovers and mergers;
others bet on bankruptcies. Some focus on particular sectors of the
stock market, like technology, but the largest number are global
funds that may focus on particular countries or regions (Russia,
lately, has been a disaster). The big, famous ones, like Soros'
Quantum and Robertson's Tiger, invest all over the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The first hedge funds tried to hedge their bets, usually by
splitting their portfolios between stocks they expected to rise and
those they expected to fall. (That way, they could make some money,
no matter what happened.)
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that investing in hedge funds was only for the
superrich; now, the merely somewhat rich may invest in them.
Various federal laws require that hedge-fund investors have a net
worth of $1 million, or annual income of $200,000 for two
successive years, or a $5 million investment portfolio. The funds
cannot advertise or do anything that might make the government
suspect that they are trying to attract the financial hoi polloi.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of their air of exclusivity, hedge funds have
been attracting increasing numbers of amateur investors. James
O'Shaughnessy, who already manages private accounts and mutual
funds, said he was opening a hedge fund because his clients were
clamoring for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be everything Long-Term Capital was not,''
O'Shaughnessy said. But because of all the bad publicity hedge
funds are getting these days, he added, ``We may have to come up
with another clever name for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
