</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GOLISANO ADS ENLIVEN SLEEPY CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a humorous bite that had been absent from the
gubernatorial campaign, a flurry of advertisements attacking Gov.
George Pataki went on the air Monday, courtesy of B. Thomas
Golisano, the wealthy third-party candidate who is trying to shake
up a contest that is shaping up as an easy stroll to re-election
for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a month, Golisano has blanketed the state with
millions of dollars' worth of sober television, radio and newspaper
advertisements criticizing the governor's handling of state
finances, to no apparent effect.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have shown that Pataki still holds a wide lead over the
Democratic candidate, Peter Vallone, while Golisano and Lt. Gov.
Betsy McCaughey Ross, the Liberal Party candidate, remain stuck in
single digits.
</P>
<P>
   But the new advertisements _ with the catch phrase ``that's a
Pataki,'' a reference to what Golisano says are fiscal foul-ups by
the Pataki administration _ are a departure, easily the liveliest
messages yet in this sleepy contest. Four advertisements were
broadcast for the first time Monday, and Golisano said eight more
are scheduled to be broadcast in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Golisano, the Independence Party candidate, said at a news
conference in midtown Manhattan Monday that he had committed $7
million to the new advertising effort, and that more money might
follow before the Nov. 3 election. He has said he would spend up to
$20 million of his own money on the campaign, a figure that puts
him in the league of the biggest spenders in New York politics this
year, Pataki and U.S. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, declined to comment directly on the
advertisements or on Golisano, saying only, ``The state is doing
well, and I'm very proud of the changes we've made to give us a
better future.''
</P>
<P>
   Golisano's attacks could shrink the governor's commanding lead
over Vallone, the New York City council speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters say the Independence candidate is most popular with
upstate conservatives, the core of Pataki's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golisano's carrying some of the heavy load right now for
Vallone, who doesn't have the money to do it himself,'' said Lee
Miringoff, director of the Marist Institute for Public Opinion in
Poughkeepsie, N.Y. ``Somebody spending $15 million or more to
attack the governor could certainly hurt him if the message is
focused, but all that does is change the size of the margin.''
</P>
<P>
   Golisano's advertisements harp on the sharp increase in state
debt, up 30 percent in less than four years under Pataki, and this
year's 8 percent increase in state spending over last year. Vallone
has made similar points, but he does not have the money to
broadcast them the way Golisano has.
</P>
<P>
   In one advertisement, a man sitting on a brownstone stoop
regales three friends with a tale about someone who borrows from
one person to pay off another, then borrows again to pay the second
debt. Finally, the storyteller says, ``What are you trying to pull
on me here, a Pataki?''
</P>
<P>
   In two other advertisements, a cabdriver, asked about increasing
state debt, a low state credit rating and other problems,
repeatedly answers, ``That's a Pataki.''
</P>
<P>
   But the harshest advertisement features a stand-in for the
governor, with his back to the camera, asking a bank officer for a
$20 billion loan, ``so I can say I'm showing a surplus even though
my business is billions of dollars in debt.'' The incredulous loan
officer asks the name of the business, and the faceless figure
replies, ``New York State,'' to which the bank man says, ``How nice
to meet you, Pataki.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that Golisano's appeal as a protest candidate is
limited. He ran for governor in 1994, never rising above a 10
percent share in voter preference polls and receiving just 4
percent of the vote, despite spending $6.6 million. His message is
almost entirely about matters fiscal, a subject likely to draw
yawns from voters in the absence of a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Golisano said Monday that he saw himself as the only real
alternative to the incumbent because Vallone's campaign is
flagging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly with the weakness of the second candidate, Vallone,
this is an excellent opportunity for me to step up,'' Golisano
said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference outside City Hall, Vallone
shrugged off that assessment, saying he was also written off during
the primary campaign. Last week, his campaign reported having just
$248,000 left, compared with $9.2 million for Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real poll is how the people feel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki Monday received the endorsement of the Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association and other New York City police unions, which
gave him some of the credit for the statewide drop in crime since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone protested that most of that decline has occurred in New
York City, and that he and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani deserve the
credit.
</P>
<P>
   And, as he has done almost daily during the general election
campaign, Vallone accused the governor of ducking debates, a charge
Golisano also made.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, the Vallone campaign sent people
dressed as duck hunters to blow duck calls outside one of Pataki's
campaign events.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he wanted to debate and believed that debates would
take place. But he insisted that he had nothing to do with making
the arrangements, which he said would be done by the respective
campaign managers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
