<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO OPINIONS ON A STREET NAME 
EAST COAST CRITIC, WEST COAST HOME  
 FREED FOR FLYING  
 GENERATION TRAP
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 BY JAMES BARRON with ALAN FEUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Apparently Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has been learning
about Manhattan by riding around with out-of-town journalists like
the Washington-based columnist George F. Will.
</P>
<P>
   In a column that appeared in The Washington Post and The New
York Post on Sunday, Will praised the return of street signs that
say ``Sixth Avenue'' on the Avenue of the Americas. Will wrote that
the mayor had not noticed the signs before.
</P>
<P>
   Neither had Maria Smith, a spokeswoman for the Department of
Transportation. ``I checked, and yes, indeed, there are new signs
for Sixth Avenue,'' she said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Contradicting Will's argument that New Yorkers never call it
anything but Sixth Avenue, she said that she often referred to it
as Avenue of the Americas, sometimes even in taxis.
</P>
<P>
   Contradicting her, Mark Patterson, also with the Transportation
Department, called and said the signs were anything but new.
``They've been like that for the last 10 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His historicizing meshed with Ms. Smith's explanation for the
one-street, two-name situation. The City Council approved the dual
name _ Avenue of the Americas and Sixth Avenue _ in the 1980s, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had done a major reconstruction project on Sixth Avenue,
and my guess is that some of the dual signs weren't replaced,'' she
said. ``They should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EAST COAST CRITIC, WEST COAST HOME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He is the new film critic for New York magazine, but he is not
moving to New York. Peter Rainer, the chief film critic for New
Times-Los Angeles and the chairman of the National Society of Film,
was named Monday to succeed David Denby, who is leaving New York
magazine to become a film critic for The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm based in LA,'' Rainer, 47, said, noting that a number of
critics for other New York-based publications live there.
</P>
<P>
   But he and Jeremy Gerard, a features editor at New York, said
that he would spend ``extended periods'' in New York. ``I'm
bicoastal,'' Rainer said.
</P>
<P>
   How will his approach differ from Denby's? ``I'm very simpatico
with the way he writes about movies,'' Rainer said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FREED FOR FLYING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing hooky,'' Bill Maher said, explaining his presence
in New York on a weekday. His talk show, ``Politically Incorrect,''
originates in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But hooky was not the right word: He taped Monday night's show
on Friday. That freed him to fly east for a one-man show in Rhode
Island on Saturday and for lunch Monday at Rolling Stone magazine,
where he was asked about President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's out of the woods,'' Maher said. ``He has to
survive. That's as important as getting Nixon out in Watergate.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GENERATION TRAP &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Friars Club, worried about its reputation as an outpost for
aging comedians like Alan King, Abe Vigoda and Freddie Roman, is
trying to attract a different crowd these days. But young bucks can
sometimes kick hard.
</P>
<P>
   Although the honoree at the annual roast on Friday was Drew
Carey, the 40-year-old sitcom star, a few young comedians took aim
at their counterparts in the older generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the best wine to serve with Abe Vigoda?'' asked Joy
Behar, a host of the ABC talk show ``The View.'' ``Formaldehyde?''
</P>
<P>
   And the comic Jeffrey Ross, saying he had seen younger faces on
printed money, commented: ``It's not a roast. It's a rot.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan King had the best comeback _ or precomeback. In a
conversation the day before the roast, he said that nothing the
young comics could say would sting. ``Are you kidding? We invented
roasting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
