</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-CHIX-BANKRUPTCY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON CHICKEN'S $283 MILLION DEBT PROMPTS BANKRUPTCY FILING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Boston Chicken Inc., once a restaurant industry
high flier, has hit some severe turbulence that forced it to file
Chapter 11 bankruptcy on Monday and close 178 stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden, Colo., company took the action because it is
strapped for cash and is faced with about $283 million in debt that
is due Oct. 17. Chapter 11 permits a company to continue operating
while it works out a payment plan with creditors.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 100 Boston Market stores from Fresno to San
Diego franchised to Boston West L.L.C. They are unaffected by the
closing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bankruptcy of Boston Chicken is not a bankruptcy of Boston
West. At the present time we will not be closing any (stores) in
Southern California,'' said Andrew Puzder, executive vice president
of Carl Karcher Enterprises of Anaheim, a stakeholder in Boston
West, a limited liability company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't mean that some restaurants might not be closed in
the future. You always evaluate which ones to keep open or
closed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy filing could have a financial impact on Boston
West because it has borrowed money from time to time from Boston
Chicken. Those loans will no longer be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hoped to restructure out of court and gave it our best
effort. We have considerably improved restaurant operations,
significantly reduced overhead and have made progress with our
creditors toward a financial restructuring,'' Boston Chicken
Chairman J. Michael Jenkins said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Chicken and its Boston Market restaurants, which feature
home-style cooking, stormed Wall Street in 1993 with an initial
public offering priced at $20. The company's stock soon rocketed to
$50 a share and it split 2-for-1 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It has since tanked, closing Monday at 50 cents, down 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been downhill for some time now,'' said Janet Lowder, an
analyst at Restaurant Management Services in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   She said the company's ``replacement dinner'' meals -- that is,
full meals prepared as quickly as at a fast-food restaurant -- are
getting tough competition from similar restaurant chains and even
from the deli sections of supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supermarkets have just done a tremendous job. I think they
are making their mark in this arena and we didn't think that they
could,'' Lowder said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
