A1167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KARIYA-CONCUSSION     10-06 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KARIYA-CONCUSSIONS-2TAKES(1110)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARIYA IS HAUNTED BY NEXT BIG HIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ After Paul Kariya sustained another concussion
last Feb. 1, the Anaheim Mighty Ducks medical staff expected him to
be back in the lineup in a few days. The Canadian Olympic team was
counting on him to join it in Japan later that month. Young,
talented and charismatic, Kariya is important to the National
Hockey League on several levels.
</P>
<P>
   But when the aftereffects worsened, his prognosis for recovery
stretched from days to weeks to months. He missed the Olympics and
could not bear watching them much on television. He would wake up
with headaches and they would occasionally intensify, even when his
car bounced lightly over a bump in the road. Mature for his 23
years, Kariya found himself in an emotional valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was having real problems,'' said Kariya, who missed the rest
of the season, 28 games. ``I didn't want to talk to anybody. I
didn't want to see anybody. The last thing I wanted to do was watch
hockey. My mind just couldn't operate. It was frustrating. I had no
clue what was going on. My memory was very poor, especially my
short-term memory. I didn't remember what I had just done. I'd have
three messages on my phone, I'd play them, and then I couldn't
remember who called.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people called, and among them were Eric Lindros and Pat
LaFontaine, fellow players who were also the victims of
concussions. Lindros recommended acupuncture. LaFontaine expressed
sympathy and encouragement. Kariya's symptoms finally dissipated in
May, when the best NHL teams were in the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing better head protection and bearing a harsher attitude,
Kariya is preparing for the 1998-99 season, which begins on Friday
night. More than many stories, Kariya's comeback will be watched
closely by fellow players, league executives, fans, corporate
sponsors and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya's concussion was one of an epidemic last season that
victimized players such as Lindros, one of the league's premier
players, and LaFontaine, a longtime star, who was finally forced to
retire in the off season after his sixth career concussion. For a
league trying to broaden its appeal and increase its attractiveness
as a marketing and television commodity, the loss of a young star
like Kariya was a source of concern.
</P>
<P>
   That concern spurred a crackdown by league authorities. On the
dressing room door of the Mighty Ducks practice rink is taped a
stern letter sent to all teams. It reads in part, ``The league
intends to apply a much stricter standard of supplementary
discipline for any deliberate action by a player that is either
directed to the head of an opponent or results in an injury to the
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, too, was apprehensive. He admitted that there were times
he thought about doing something else and not playing hockey,
though he acknowledged: ``I don't know what I would have done. It's
basically been my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Conceding that he may now be ``more at risk'' than other
players, Kariya added: ``If it happens, it happens. I'll have to
deal with it at that time.'' So far, through training camp and the
exhibition season, he said, ``I've taken some good shots to the
head and I feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   His attitude is certainly upbeat. Passing through the doorway of
the Ducks' dressing room last week after a brisk practice, a
visitor could hear the loud banter, raucous joking and cursing
common to the environment as the athletes untied their skates, hung
up their pads and tossed sweat-soaked clothing into laundry bins.
Over the din blared a television tuned to a baseball playoff game.
Among the voices surrounding it was that of Kariya, who shouted
encouragement to the Boston Red Sox against the Cleveland Indians.
A native of Vancouver, British Columbia, Kariya played in college
at Maine and grew to like the Red Sox on visits to Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   In his first few seasons, Kariya was often portrayed as an
overly serious professional. ``Paul's having more fun these days
than when I first got here,'' said Stu Grimson, a former teammate
who has rejoined Kariya and the Ducks this season. ``He understands
now that it's a long season and he's going to have a long career
and he's got to be able to enjoy himself while he's at it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the optimistic scenario. In the worst-case scenario, it
may already be too late. Although post-concussion syndrome is still
not fully understood, doctors believe the risk of concussion, the
damage and the recovery time all can increase with the frequency of
the injury. Kariya's last concussion was his fourth. Although
LaFontaine recovered from a fifth concussion to play last season
with the Rangers, his career ended after he suffered a sixth in an
accidental collision with a teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya's most recent concussion last season was less accidental.
After scoring against the Chicago Blackhawks, he was cross-checked
in the jaw by defenseman Gary Suter. Kariya didn't lose
consciousness. His head never hit the ice. He remembered the score
of the game, the team's record, the details. Suter was suspended
for four games, but some thought that was inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if a crackdown on head-hunting is necessary, Kariya
replied: ``Oh, absolutely, it's a serious problem. You want your
best players playing and performing to make the league the best
league possible. They have to do something. Guys intentionally
going after someone's head have to be punished and punished
severely. You start handing out five- and 10-game suspensions, guys
will start thinking `Maybe I shouldn't be doing this.' They've put
a mandate out that they are going to crack down. It will be
interesting to see if they do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In case they don't, Kariya and his team might intensify the
vigilante justice that is part of hockey's unwritten code. During
the off season, the Ducks added Grimson and Jim McKenzie, veterans
known for fighting. Kariya, a two-time winner of the Lady Byng
trophy for gentlemanly play and good sportsmanship, has said he
will be more willing to raise his stick in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to protect myself,'' said Kariya, listed as 5 feet 11
inches and 180 pounds. ``Sometimes, I've just let people hit me
instead of either avoiding it or getting your stick up. Hopefully,
you never have to do that. But, if guys are coming at my head, I
mean I've got to start protecting myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Suter now plays for the San Jose Sharks, Anaheim's divisional
rival. Suter and Kariya share the same business agent. According to
Kariya, Suter asked the agent if he should call Kariya. The agent
passed on the query, but it ended there. ``I said, `What's the
point?''' Kariya said. ``What's done is done. Go forward.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, Kariya was cleared to play by Dr. James Kelly,
the director of the brain-injury program at the Rehabilitation
Institute of Chicago, who has been consulted by other hockey
players for post-concussion diagnoses. Like LaFontaine last season,
Kariya is wearing extra padding in his helmet, a tighter strap
around his chin and a mouth guard between his teeth that works as a
shock absorber.
</P>
<P>
   Should he reach his potential, Kariya's career could define an
era. In only 220 games over four seasons as a professional, he has
129 goals and 148 assists for what has been, at best, a mediocre
team. He played in only 22 games last season, missing the first 32
in a contract dispute. A Canadian of Japanese and Scottish descent,
Kariya has the good looks, poise and verbal skills that appeal to
television producers and sports magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Should Kariya's Ducks contend, they could be the sort of team
that helps edge hockey more into the sports mainstream. The Ducks
are owned by the Walt Disney Co. and named after a Disney film.
Even on a bad team, Kariya is the kind of star who attracts fans
and television viewers.
</P>
<P>
   He works particularly well with Teemu Selanne, the other ace
wing on the Ducks' first line. Kariya plays the left side and
Selanne the right. But they crisscross, swirl and find each other
with soft touch passes while speeding up and down the ice with the
grace of dancers. In an exhibition last week against Los Angeles,
Kariya had two assists, and he has three goals and four assists in
four games. But Selanne said Kariya is not yet in top form.
</P>
<P>
   More than Kariya, Selanne is vocal in the campaign against dirty
checking. ``The players have to start to respect each other more,''
Selanne said. ``It's just ridiculous if, on the ice, it's not a
safe place anymore. You know when somebody is trying to hurt you.
All the hits these days, especially last year, they always get your
head first. The players have to realize it is dangerous. We can't
lose any more star players with stupid concussions.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kariya still says hockey is ``the best game in the
world,'' he also said the incident caused him to think more
seriously when people rationalize setbacks with the expression,
``Well, at least you've got your health.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would always say: `What are you talking about? There's so
much more to life than that,''' Kariya said. ``But it really caused
me to simplify things and say, `If you don't have your health,
especially in your head area, you can't operate and you can't live
a normal life.' It made me appreciate that, and now I'm very
pleased and grateful that I've got it and want to continue.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
