<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-MAYOR-FUNERAL-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY REMEMBERED AS MENTOR, CITY BUILDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles said farewell to former Mayor Tom
Bradley on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Political foes and allies alike eulogized Bradley, who died last
week at 80, as a man with simple tastes and grand dreams, as a
coalition builder and as the architect of the city's growth during
his historic 20 years in office.
</P>
<P>
   They spoke of Bradley's determination, demonstrated by his rise
from poverty as the son of a Texas sharecropper to become the first
African-American mayor of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there had been no Tom Bradley there would be no Police
Chief Bernard Parks,'' Parks told the overflow crowd of more than
2,000 mourners gathered in and around the First AME Church in the
West Adams district.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour ceremony was televised live across the city.
Following the service, Bradley was interred at Inglewood Park
Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Parks, who counted Bradley as one of his mentors, was among some
two dozen people who praised the mayor for what he had accomplished
during his five terms.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley changed the face of Los Angeles government, bringing in
minorities and women to posts previously unavailable. He also
opened up city business to minorities and women.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bradley oversaw the development of downtown
Los Angeles, shepherding projects that changed the skyline and gave
the city something to boast about to rival the storied profiles of
San Francisco and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and the city hosted the world during the Summer Olympics
of 1984, the most successful run this century.
</P>
<P>
   The First AME choir and singer Stevie Wonder were among
performers who moved the crowd to their feet, with songs including
``My Way,'' ``The Impossible Dream'' and ``Wind Beneath My Wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, Gov. Pete Wilson, Lt. Gov. Gray Davis,
Mayor Richard Riordan and Los Angeles County Supervisor Yvonne
Brathwaite Burke were among the speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore entered the church shortly before the ceremony began and
stood momentarily looking at Bradley's body, lying in a black
casket decorated with white lilies and red roses. The vice
president hugged Bradley's widow, Ethel, and two daughters,
Lorraine and Phyllis.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this day, as we gather round our fallen brother, we do so
not to recite his many titles: mayor, healer, husband, father,
leader, but to testify of those lives grown out of his life,'' Gore
told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Bradley's whole life was a testament to justice, hope and
an audacious view of the future. Los Angeles may have lost an
angel. But an angel is now with other angels.''
</P>
<P>
   The funeral also drew George Deukmejian, who defeated Bradley
twice in his runs for governor; former U.S. Secretary of State
Warren Christopher; the Rev. Jesse Jackson; attorney Johnnie
Cochran Jr.; San Francisco Mayor Willie L. Brown Jr.; District
Attorney Gil Garcetti and Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's storied rise began when his family moved to Los
Angeles from Texas when he was 7 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley excelled in sports and ran track at the University of
California, Los Angeles. From there, he joined the Los Angeles
Police Department, where he worked for more than 20 years,
eventually achieving lieutenant, the highest rank then earned by an
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from the department, Bradley went to law school
and became active in local politics, winning a City Council seat in
1963 _ the first African-American elected to the council. In 1973,
after a bitter defeat four years earlier, Bradley became the city's
mayor and the first minority mayor of a major white-majority city.
</P>
<P>
   It was that victory that inspired many young African-Americans
to get involved in politics, said Robert T. Moore, a deputy to Sen.
Dianne Watson, D-Los Angeles, who was in the crowd of mourners
gathered outside the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the reason so many people got involved in politics,''
Moore said. ``He became the model. He was an icon to the black
community.''
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED IN 2ND TAKE) &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
