r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-MAYOR-FUNERAL-LADN     10-06 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-MAYOR-FUNERAL-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: black community.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sharon Williams of Los Angeles wiped away tears when asked what
Bradley meant to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the greatest,'' Williams said. ``Everyone knew him in
the community. He never forgot where he came from.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that ability that struck ``Sweet'' Alice Harris of
Parents of Watts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Tom Bradley, we couldn't get anyone at City Hall to
answer our calls,'' Harris said. ``But, I had his private number.
When we called, he answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Bradley understood poor folks. I don't know about you rich
ones, but he understood us.''
</P>
<P>
   Actor and environmentalist Ed Begley Jr. also was one of those
who was not able to make it inside the 1,200-seat sanctuary and he
described the former mayor ``as a dear, dear friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could talk to him and he understood the issues,'' Begley
said. ``In his final years in office he became a real friend to the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson recalled that he first met Bradley when Wilson was mayor
in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard for me to accept that Tom is gone from us,'' Wilson
said. ``Divine nature gave us Tom Bradley. It was more our good
fortune than Tom's that God put this extraordinary man, this
grandson of slaves, on a path that led him to this great city that
he would one day lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the Democratic candidate for governor, said he first met
Bradley when he worked in his 1973 mayoral race.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first mentor was Tom Bradley, and you never forget the
lessons of your first mentor,'' Davis said. ``You keep them dear
for the rest of your life and you pass them on to the next
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan, who succeeded Bradley as mayor in 1993, called the
funeral one of the most emotional events in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man was a giant,'' Riordan said. ``He turned the city
around and made it a world-class city.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's political mentor, the Rev. H.H. Brookins, recalled how
community leaders gathered behind Bradley in his first City Council
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went from zero to hero,'' Brookins said, adding the changes
made by Bradley will never be lost to the African-American
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``He opened the door and it will not be closed again,'' Brookins
said. ``We went from the back of the bus to the front of the bus
and we aren't going back. Now, we're buying the bus company.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
