<HEADLINE>
SONICS RUNNING ON IDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A day earmarked for the swapping of vacation stories
has been overtaken by lockout lingo.
</P>
<P>
   NBA training camps, once scheduled to begin Tuesday, have been
postponed indefinitely because there is no collective bargaining
agreement between the league and its players.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the NBA canceled all preseason games. Meanwhile, players
planned to show up at practice facilities and arenas in NBA cities
Tuesday to talk about the lockout with fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just life in the NBA,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal
said. ``That's why it's an interesting business.''
</P>
<P>
   While the NBA might miss regular-season games for the first
time, Westphal and his staff are preparing as though the lockout
will end Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They are meeting about twice a week in order to crystallize
offensive and defensive strategies. They are watching film and
evaluating free agents. With only six players under contract, they
are trying to make something out of nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, we'd have all those things clear-cut by now,'' Sonics
assistant Dwane Casey said. ``We're just doing what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal and his assistants _ Casey, Bob Weiss and Nate McMillan
_ cannot do much during a lockout. They are prohibited from
communicating with players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've spent a lot of time talking through various scenarios,''
Sonic president Wally Walker said. ``You don't know what the system
is going to be. It's guess work. . . . You're doing evaluations
without getting too charged up.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the NBA and the players union are scheduled to
meet on Thursday. It will be only the second formal negotiation
since owners locked out players July 1. NBA commissioner David
Stern told The Rocky Mountain News in Denver recently that a
60-game schedule is the minimum required to play a season.
</P>
<P>
   A decision about the cancellation of regular-season games will
be made next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't play a partial season that doesn't give the regular
season an integrity of sorts,'' Stern said. ``My view is you should
be playing a minimum of 60 games. If you lose more than that, I
think you're really taking a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than 180 NBA players without contracts, the Sonics are
not risking their stake in free agency. During the next two weeks,
each member of the coaching staff plans to visit various cities to
watch pickup games among NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go out and beat the bushes,'' Casey said. ``You
can't talk to them (free agents) and interact, but you can
observe.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, Houston and Atlanta are among the target cities to
see premium pick-up games. Westpahl said that whenever the lockout
ends, the free-agent signing period will move swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   The league has said it will need about three weeks to conduct
training camps and a free-agent signing period.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things will depend on what happens immediately after
the lockout ends,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, there isn't much to do but wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 0042EDT &QL; 
