<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES, SEAHAWKS TAP IRON MEN FOR NEEDED HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Joe Jarzynka has never seen a punt or kickoff he did
not think he could take all the way for a touchdown. That is why
the Husky junior is constitutionally unable to lift up that right
arm and signal a fair catch.
</P>
<P>
   Jarzynka is the kind of gritty gridiron player who leaves no
doubt what he would have been doing during the Battle of Gettysburg
or the storming of the Normandy beaches on D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the answer,'' Jarzynka said Monday. ``That one
fair catch might be the one you take to the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarzynka might be the only player on the University of
Washington roster who could make you believe he can single-footedly
cure the Husky program's Achilles' heel of these past few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no problem. I played soccer all during high school. I
kicked for my high school football team. I want to be part of
everything I can to help this program,'' the confident and now
neatly shorn Jarzynka said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Jarzynka gave what amounted to be the only happy,
positive, upbeat, confident and encouraging interview of anyone
associated with a Seattle football team, college or pro. The
Huskies are 2-2 for the first time since 1989, but they are not the
only football team in town looking for answers in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks were beaten Sunday by the Chiefs in the Arrowhead
Rain Bowl, 17-6. The loss dropped the Hawks to 3-2 and, more
important, it makes Sunday's AFC West matchup against Denver in the
Kingdome feel a lot more like a must-win deal than it probably is.
</P>
<P>
   Where does all this leave Seattle football fans, who might be
more plentiful this fall now that the Mariners are dead and the NBA
season is likely to be, too?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it has them wondering if answers will come _ and when.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks and Huskies together went 5-0 over the first three
weeks (the UW had a bye week in there), but the home teams are 0-4
since then and running into problems in key areas.
</P>
<P>
   For the Huskies, it is a kicking game that needs someone who can
stick a field goal or extra point through the uprights with some
regularity.
</P>
<P>
   For the Seahawks, it is another receiver besides Joey Galloway
who can get the football to stay in his hands long enough to count
as a completion.
</P>
<P>
   So, wouldn't you know it, just as the Huskies will look to see
if their jack-of-all-trades Iron Man, Jarzynka, can make a
contribution in their kicking game, the Seahawks are calling on the
services of their most veteran and prolific pass catcher, Brian
Blades.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Jarzynka is a man who knows no danger during Husky
games, Blades has never found a pass pattern too frightening to
run.
</P>
<P>
   Over the middle, into triple coverage? No sweat. Blades will run
it, offering himself up for all hard-hitting linebackers and
safeties if that's what it takes to get the job done. His 570
catches make him second only to Hall of Famer Steve Largent in the
Seahawks' record book. But the man who set the Seahawks'
single-season mark with 81 receptions in 1994 has logged 77, 43 and
30 catches the past three seasons, and just four in this season's
first five games.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jarzynka and his steadfast (and sometimes dangerous)
refusal to call for a fair catch, Blades has given up his body over
the past 11 seasons to make any catch his coach, offensive
coordinator or quarterback called for.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we kept him on the team,'' Seahawks coach Dennis
Erickson said Monday, fresh off a film session in which it was
clear that not even the Bermuda Triangle weather in Kansas City
could explain all the balls dropped by Mike Pritchard and James
McKnight.
</P>
<P>
   Those two guys were great playmakers last season. But so far in
1998, the Hawks offense has lacked the reliability it needs even
more, now that there is a commitment to the running game and,
therefore, each pass attempt becomes more selective and critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have a chance to make a catch, we have to make a
catch,'' said Erickson. ``Not necessarily a touchdown or a big
play, but just making a catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Blades barely caught on with the team this season, since his
body has been broken, whipped and pureed for all the times he has
gone fearlessly over the middle to catch a ball and move the
chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our fourth receiver right now, and our fourth receiver
hasn't played much,'' Erickson said. ``But he'll play a lot more.
Brian's made a lot of plays over the years, and the best thing to
do is take a guy that's done it and put him out there. We knew this
time might come for one reason or another, whether it's injuries or
the productivity isn't what we want, which happens to be the case
here.''
</P>
<P>
   This is exactly the time to trot out the old pro. Like the
gritty kid named Jarzynka on the Huskies who believes he can help
his program, Blades might have the hands and the heart to make a
difference, too.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
