<HEADER>
A1219 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTOROLA-AZR &LR;      10-06 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED INK FILLS MOTOROLA'S 3RD QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROLWING  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Motorola Inc., the world's largest maker of mobile
phones, pagers and telecommunications equipment and a longtime
bellwether for the high-tech industry, announced a third-quarter
loss Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The news underscores observers' forecasts that the semiconductor
industry, which employs 31,900 workers in Arizona, will wrap up the
year with a drop in sales of about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's earnings have been widely seen as an early indicator
of how much the Asian economic crisis has affected profits for the
entire high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call (Motorola) a bellwether of the industry because
they have a very broad product line,'' said Jim Feldhan, president
of Semico Research Corp. in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The lower earnings follow Motorola's decision to slash its
workforce 10 percent, delay construction of plants and cut costs.
About 20,000 people work for Motorola in Arizona, making it the
state's largest employer.
</P>
<P>
   Other semiconductor companies and their vendors in Arizona have
made similar layoffs. Intel, which employs about 9,200 workers in
Arizona, has cut its worldwide workforce 4 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   But despite Motorola's drop in profits, experts say the industry
should recover, growing 10 percent to 16 percent next year, as
older manufacturing plants shut down worldwide and companies cut
workers to reach an equilibrium between supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter that ended Sept. 26, Schaumburg, Ill.-based
Motorola reported sales of $7.2 billion, down 3 percent from $7.4
billion &UR; last year.
</P>
<P>
   For the three months, the company reported a loss of $42
million, or 7 cents a diluted share. Motorola earned $266 million,
or 44 cents a share, in the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The current quarter included a charge of $117 million, or 14
cents a diluted share. Excluding those charges, the company would
have reported a third-quarter profit of $40 million, or 7 cents a
diluted share, which beat Wall Street expectations of 1 cent a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, computer chip sales tumbled 14 percent to $1.8
billion from $2.1 billion in the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's stock, which closed Monday before earnings were
released, fell $1.4375, or 3.6 percent, to $38.5625.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much of a mixed picture for the chip industry right
now,'' said Jeff Weir, a spokesman for the Semiconductor Industry
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Financial troubles in Asia, where American companies sell 30
percent of their products, have caused dramatic drops in sales.
Also, competitors in the region have slashed prices as they
struggle to weather the downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola has tied its woes to the Asian economic crunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrettably, the Asian economy and slowing of global economic
growth have impacted Motorola since earlier this year, just as
those factors are now readily apparent and affecting many other
global corporations,'' Chief Executive Christopher Galvin said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the financial pressure are prices for memory chips,
which store the information on a computer, which have fallen more
than 70 percent over the past year. While an oversupply of the
chips means good news for consumers, it's bad news for
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony for all the memory companies is that the demand for
memory products continues to grow, but as long as there's so many
on the market the price won't grow,'' Weir said.
</P>
<P>
   While it's uncertain whether many factors plaguing the
semiconductor industry will persist next year, observers remain
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Cahners In-Stat Group, a Scottsdale semiconductor research
organization, expects the industry to grow 10 percent, despite all
the dire warnings issued by companies about lower sales and
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are areas of growth that will buoy semiconductor growth
rates for a period of time beginning with fourth quarter of this
year,'' Cahners In-Stat wrote in its September report.
</P>
<P>
   While problems will continue for Japan, South Korea and other
Asian countries, In-Stat noted that U.S. high-tech exports to China
through the first half of 1998 grew 50 percent compared with the
same period last year. Exports to Mexico, Costa Rica and Venezuela
also rose.
</P>
<P>
   Weir shrugged off Motorola's drop in profits, saying what
happened in its third quarter doesn't dictate what will happen next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation for a strong growth market is shared by all
the companies. The only question is when it will happen, not if it
will happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the forecasts, it will be six to eight months before
Arizona suppliers like SpeedFam International Inc. and others feel
relief, Feldhan said. &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
