A1220 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-PHARMACEUTICAL-LA     10-06 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-PHARMACEUTICAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO DRUG DEAL HAS SIDE-EFFECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Two California legislators have asked the state
Department of Corporations to investigate a deal in which a New
York pharmaceutical firm would pay managed care giant Foundation
Health Systems Inc. $1 million a month to give preference to its
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The call for action stems from a proposed deal in which Health
Net, Foundation's main HMO, would instruct doctors to select
Bristol-Myers Squibb drugs when prescribing medicine for patients
in five therapeutic categories. The categories range from high
cholesterol to bacterial infection.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the drug maker would pay a Foundation subsidiary
that manages pharmaceutical purchases a fee of $1 million a month.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan were enacted, physicians treating Health Net members
still could prescribe nonpreferred drugs, but the medicine would be
paid for by the health plan only if approved by appeals group
within the managed care company.
</P>
<P>
   In separate letters, California state Sen. Herschel Rosenthal,
D-Van Nuys, and Assemblywoman Liz Figueroa, D-Fremont, criticized
the Department of Corporations for statements made by its staff
that the department has no authority to look into such matters.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Rosenthal said the department was ``turning its
back'' on existing law in its failure to ``remedy and investigate
this violation'' of the state Health and Safety Code, which
stipulates that medical decisions must be unhampered by economic
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa said in her letter that deals such as the one proposed
between Squibb and Foundation are ``precisely the kind of thing the
DOC is supposed to prevent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of no clearer example of a deal in which the
economic incentives that benefit individual companies work to the
express disadvantage of patients,'' Figueroa said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial arrangement, which has not been enacted, is
the latest version of a practice known as rebating, in which
pharmaceutical companies compensate health care groups for making
high-volume purchases of their drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A Department of Corporations spokeswoman said the agency is
studying deals like the Squibb-Foundation arrangement, but must
wait until those companies submit their proposal for government
approval to take action on it specifically.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Yukelson, a spokesman for Foundation, said terms of the
proposed deal have changed significantly since the draft outline
was written in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal in the draft is not the deal that will be executed,''
Yukelson said. Among changes made is that while Squibb drugs will
remain the preferred product in their categories, they will not be
the only drugs available to physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Yukelson said Foundation expected the proposed deal to raise
eyebrows but has moved forward because ultimately the arrangement
should benefit patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it'd be controversial,'' Yukelson said. ``But dollars
aside, we think we're doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 0129EDT &QL; 
