<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1223 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS-PACKERS-H     10-06 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-PACKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
GREEN BAY, Wis. _ Randy Moss may not be Deion Sanders, but the
Minnesota Vikings' magnificent rookie receiver proved Monday night
that he is a prime-time player extraordinaire.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a battle of NFC Central unbeatens, Minnesota quarterback
Randall Cunningham outplayed Green Bay's Brett Favre as the Vikings
shocked the Packers 37-24 to end Green Bay's 25-game winning streak
at Lambeau Field.
</P>
<P>
   In a thunderstorm before 59,849 rain-soaked fans, Cunningham and
Moss showed the NFL something old and something new by putting on
one of the great shows in the history of Monday Night Football.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham continues to excel in place of injured starter Brad
Johnson, completing 20 of 32 passes for 442 yards and four
touchdowns. Cunningham's passing yards were the most ever against
Green Bay, surpassing the 411 put up by San Francisco's Joe Montana
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Stars are born on Monday nights in the NFL, and few will shine
brighter in their prime-time debut than Moss, the controversial No.
1 draft choice who caught five passes for 190 yards and two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-4, 205-pound Moss exasperated Green Bay's defensive backs,
especially cornerback Travis Williams. When Williams was able to
cover Moss, he couldn't jump with him and he wasn't strong enough
to take the ball away from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken a lot of criticism, and lot of people want me to
fail, but I think I turned a lot of heads tonight,'' Moss said.
``There's no room on this bandwagon for all the people who want to
climb on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going deep was in our plan. I was hungry for the ball, and
when it was in my vicinity, I'm going to get my hands on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (4-1) goes only as far as Favre can take it. In this
game, he couldn't take the Packers far enough, turning in one of
the worst games of his career. He was 13-of-23 passing for just 114
yards.
</P>
<P>
   This night belonged to Cunningham, who has resurrected his
career and who ignited the Vikings (5-0) to 542 yards total offense
against one of the NFL's best defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randall was outstanding,'' Minnesota coach Dennis Green said.
``He throws a great deep ball. It cuts through the wind. He can
beat a deep zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to take advantage of their man coverage. Randall got
great pass protection. He didn't even have to scramble.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half alone, Cunningham was 13-of-19 for 282 yards
and three touchdowns, connecting on touchdown passes of 56 yards to
Jake Reed, 52 to Moss and 24 to running back Robert Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an incredible number of passing yards,'' Packers coach
Mike Holmgren said. ``We just couldn't stop them. Their wide
receivers did a fantastic job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Packers didn't score an offensive touchdown in the first two
quarters. Ryan Longwell kicked a 40-yard field goal, and Roell
Preston returned a kickoff 101 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham and Moss entertained the national television audience
and frustrated the Packers' defensive backs, who for the most part
provided good coverage and still got embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   Moss had three catches for 100 yards and a 52-yard touchdown
catch in the first half. He also had a 75-yard touchdown reception
called back because of a holding penalty.
</P>
<P>
   On Moss' touchdown _ his fifth of the season _ he was covered
well by Williams, but Moss outjumped the defender to make the
catch. Then, he pulled away from safety Darren Sharper to score the
touchdown that made it 17-10.
</P>
<P>
   With five minutes left in the first half, Moss caught a 41-yard
bomb down the left sideline. Two plays later, Cunningham threw a
short screen pass to Smith over the middle. Smith evaded the
Packers and turned it into a 24-yard touchdown and a 24-10 halftime
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings shut down Green Bay's running game. The only way the
Packers gained any yards on the ground was on draw plays to Travis
Jervey, their special-teams standout.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 17-10, the Packers reached Minnesota's 34. On first
down, Favre was hit as he threw, and his floater over the middle
was intercepted by Orlando Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham returned the favor by fumbling at the Minnesota 44,
but the Vikings stuffed Green Bay's running game three times for
less than a yard and Minnesota responded when Smith scored on a
screen pass to make it 24-10 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Two Gary Anderson field goals around a Robert Griffith
interception of a Favre pass in the end zone pushed the Vikings
safely out front 30-10.
</P>
<P>
   On the Packers' next series, Favre threw his third interception,
this one also going to Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got outplayed,'' Favre said. ``The conditions were
terrible, but they handled it and we didn't. That's kind of
frustrating. We have no one to blame but ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Down 37-10, Favre was replaced by Doug Pederson, who threw an
11-yard touchdown pass to Tyrone Davis. After the Packers got the
onside kick, Pederson passed 16 yards to Bill Schroeder to finish
the scoring in the final minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1224 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROSWRAPUP-HNS &LR;      10-06 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROSWRAPUP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
A day of reflection, soul-searching and wondering what might have
been didn't change the reality of the Astros' situation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their season is still over, and the mere thought of it is just
as painful as it was Sunday night when they watched the San Diego
Padres celebrate the Division Series victory that sent the Astros
into what figures to be a gut-wrenching offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Almost to a man, they said their team was good enough to reach
the World Series. But if they want to go this year, they'll need
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes it so tough is that this wasn't a mediocre team,''
shortstop Ricky Gutierrez said. ``Getting knocked out the way we
did would be like the (Chicago) Bulls getting knocked out in the
first round of the playoffs. I guess you could say we choked; you
could call it anything you want to call it, because we lost. I
really feel like we had the better team.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the reference to the Bulls was a bit much. When last we
checked, the Astros had not won six championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're like the Bulls in the beginning,'' left fielder
Moises Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   Only time will tell. But a second straight fast break from the
playoffs had some of the Astros feeling like also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're no different than the Florida Marlins,'' said
pitcher Jose Lima, who won 16 games during the regular season but
never took the mound during the playoffs. ``The Marlins lost 100
games, and we won 100 games, but right now we're the same. We're
both going home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was devastating. I know there's no crying in baseball,
but last night was only the second time I've ever cried because of
baseball (the other time was when he pitched a no-hitter at the
Class AAA level). I feel like we went all the way to San Diego for
nothing _ to get beat. This will stay with us for a while. We had
the best club in the league, but we failed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros needed a victory Sunday to force a decisive fifth
game at the Astrodome on Monday night. Most of the players dropped
by the Dome on Monday, but it wasn't to get ready for one of the
biggest games in franchise history. It was to clean out their
lockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real disappointing to come into this clubhouse and see
everything so empty,'' Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   Added second baseman Craig Biggio: ``I really wish we could have
brought the series back to our fans in Houston, because I really
think they would have been fired up for this one. These guys
(people in San Diego) were kind of down on our fans in Houston, but
I really think it would have been fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Astros who don't live in Houston during the
offseason won't be able to leave town until the end of the week
because they have so many loose ends to tie up. Forgive them if
they didn't expect their season to end so abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in shock,'' reliever Doug Henry said as he cleared
out his locker. ``I didn't even consider this (getting knocked out
in the first round) a possibility. This might have been easier to
take if we had made it to the second round, but this is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Making things even more difficult to accept was the Astros'
belief that they were better than the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be embarrassed,'' center fielder Carl Everett said.
``We got beat by a team that was a lot older and a lot slower.
Their bones are breaking. They basically crawled onto the field and
beat us. It's a shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had so much talent. We were the feared team, and no one
wanted to play us. The way we played, we deserved to go home. What
you do in the regular season means nothing in the playoffs. It
comes down to whichever team wants it the most. They wanted it
more, and that's why they're going on and we're packing.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though they were packing to go their separate ways _
only to see each other again at spring training in Kissimmee, Fla.,
come February _ it still was hard for the Astros to believe their
season was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really didn't hit me until I woke up this morning and there
was no game to go to,'' Alou said. ``If we keep this team together,
I think we have a chance to do it again next season. But for now,
we just have to accept the fact that we didn't make it. We don't
like it, but we have to accept it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
