<HEADER>
A1226 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     10-06 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
GERRY Hunsicker stood in a place just down the hallway from where
the San Diego Padres were enjoying spontaneous champagne baths and
tried so hard not to linger over the taste of sour grapes.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, the man who so shrewdly built the
Astros into NL Central champs had watched them come apart like a
paper kite in a rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a special offensive talent this club demonstrated all
year, to come into this series and get shut down, not just by Kevin
Brown but by every other pitcher on their staff, that's, well,
ironic,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironic. Anemic. Lethargic. Pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Pick your insult, heave it into the crowd like a hand grenade,
and you will surely hit a deserving target:
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell, Craig Biggio, Derek Bell _ the Killer Breeze _
who've come up with a collective eight hits in 78 official at-bats
in two playoff seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou, who hit his last home run Aug. 24 and failed to
deliver a single RBI in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Ausmus, who couldn't get the tying run home from third base
in the top of the seventh inning Sunday, thereby forcing manager
Larry Dierker to lift ace Randy Johnson for a pinch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, for staying with Ausmus in that situation after two
previous whiffs in the game and then seeing him take a called
strike three.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Berry, for his throwing error in the bottom of the sixth
that opened the door for the Padres to take a 2-1 lead and
eventually the series.
</P>
<P>
   There are, indeed, more goats than at a tin-can buffet. But it
says here that these Astros are not incapable of winning in the
playoffs. They just don't know how, and the failure is more in
their personal makeup than in any lack of skills.
</P>
<P>
   This is a collection of individuals _ led by Biggio and Bagwell
_ who spend so much of their time trying to keep their emotions
bottled up on and off the field that when playoff time arrives, the
cork remains stuck in their bottle. The addition of Alou from the
1997 world champion Marlins was supposed to change that, but he
instead became simply one more part of the bland Astros recipe
rather than stirring the pot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must decide,'' Hunsicker said, ``whether it was just one of
those things and chalk it up to their great pitching and our
untimely slump. Or are there flaws, and it took the postseason to
bring them out? Do we have the right mix?''
</P>
<P>
   Proper chemistry, in the lab and on the playing fields, is
everything. Look no further in this town than the years immediately
preceding the Rockets' championships of 1994 and 1995, when many
dissatisfied customers wanted management to trade Hakeem Olajuwon
and start anew.
</P>
<P>
   But shooting the horse doesn't make him run faster. You change
the jockey, or you employ a new tactic. In the case of the Rockets,
they found young spark plugs in Robert Horry and Sam Cassell and a
veteran in Mario Elie to supplement the core of a contender, and
confetti soon rained down from the rafters.
</P>
<P>
   For a parallel in baseball, go back two decades to the
Philadelphia Phillies, who had an every-day lineup that included
Mike Schmidt, Greg Luzinski, Garry Maddox, Larry Bowa and Bob
Boone. That team lost three straight years in the National League
Championship Series from 1976 to 1978 before finally winning a
World Series title in 1980. Schmidt, now a Hall of Famer, openly
admitted ``choking'' in the heat of the playoffs. That team was
never gutted but eventually added a firebrand named Pete Rose, who
showed it the path to the top.
</P>
<P>
   For the Astros this offseason, Hunsicker says, ``Priority No. 1,
priority No. 2 and priority No. 3 are re-signing Randy Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   It's different from a year ago, when the hard decision was how
much to invest in Darryl Kile. Johnson is a proven commodity with a
10-1 regular-season record for the Astros and two playoff outings
that were belied by an undeserving 0-2 record. His return would
give the Astros the swagger they'll need to repeat their 102-win
season.
</P>
<P>
   Alou, who can request a trade, says he wants to stay and finish
the job. The Astros must tell him that job is to do more than live
in a quiet corner of the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Make a regular place in the lineup for Richard Hidalgo. Settle
on an every-day third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Try to get Bagwell and Biggio to open up and embrace the
situation and stop trying to keep their own celebrity and
leadership responsibilities at an arm's length. Then stay the
course.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning after, when you're surrounded by smoldering
ashes, it's easy to recall the fire but more prudent to remember
what you've built in the first place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
