<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1228 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROSOFFSEASON-H     10-06 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROSOFFSEASON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The season ended Sunday night for the Astros' players, but the work
is just beginning for general manager Gerry Hunsicker.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His list of offseason chores includes:
</P>
<P>
   Trying to convince free-agent-to-be Randy Johnson to re-sign
with the Astros. Hunsicker already has told the Big Unit and his
agent that the Astros are interested in discussing a new contract,
but Johnson intends to sort out his options with his wife over the
next couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore, Cleveland, Anaheim, Arizona, San Francisco and
Colorado also are expected to pursue Johnson, but the Astros have
exclusive negotiating rights with him until 15 days after the
completion of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is in their court,'' Hunsicker said of Johnson's
status. ``They know how we feel. I suspect that in the coming days,
I'll make a call to them if I haven't heard from them before
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with Moises Alou and discussing whether the All-Star
left fielder intends to return to the Astros next season or
exercise an option in his contract that allows him to demand a
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Alou has said his first season in Houston was a happy one, but
there are indications he might asked to be traded to Los Angeles if
his father, Felipe, is hired to manage the Dodgers. The Astros are
not obligated to trade Alou, but if they deny his request, he could
become a free agent March 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I feel like I (want to return to the Astros),''
Alou said. ``That's just a gut feeling I had (Sunday) night. I
couldn't leave this place losing. I want to leave winning. I told
Gerry that there are a few delicate issues that I'd like to talk
about, and he said he'd be willing to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not a main topic. If I use my option to leave, money
won't be the reason. Sure, everyone wants to get paid, but my
decision won't be based on getting a better salary. Hopefully, they
want me to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou would not elaborate on the ``delicate issues,'' although he
has said in the past that he wants to be sure the Astros are
committed to being competitive over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker seems optimistic Alou will be wearing an Astros
uniform next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's signed for the next three years,'' Hunsicker said. ``Mo
has indicated to me that he wants to talk about a few things _
things we can do to make it better around here. He hasn't given me
any indication that he's unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Formulating an alternative plan in the event Johnson decides to
play elsewhere. Without Johnson, the Astros are right where they
were before they traded for him July 31 _ a team with good pitching
but no bona fide ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to try to put a competitive team on the
field,'' Hunsicker said. ``Even if we don't re-sign Randy, we don't
feel pressure to sign someone like him, because we feel like we
have a quality product on the field even if we don't re-sign him.''
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson isn't re-signed, expect the Astros to at least
inquire about potential free agents Kevin Brown, Al Leiter and Todd
Stottlemyre. And don't rule out Roger Clemens, who might ask to be
traded from Toronto if he isn't convinced the Blue Jays have a
chance to compete for a championship next season. The Astros and
Rangers are at the top of Clemens' wish list.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays likely would want three or four front-line players
in exchange for Clemens. Nevertheless, you can bet the Astros would
explore the possibility of acquiring him if he became available.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the budget with owner Drayton McLane Jr. The Astros
spent close to $42 million on players this season, and that figure
will increase significantly if they keep the nucleus of the team
together. Center fielder Carl Everett, shortstop Ricky Gutierrez
and pitchers Jose Lima, Sean Bergman and Jay Powell are
arbitration-eligible, and each figures to get a nice raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be meeting in the next week or so on the
budget,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Creating an every-day spot in the outfield for Richard Hidalgo,
who split time with Everett for most of the season. Everett and
Hidalgo will come cheaper than Alou and Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Astros have financial constraints, it's likely the
1999 starting outfield will consist of Everett, Hidalgo and either
Alou or Bell. Of course, that won't be an issue if Alou demands a
trade and the Astros grant his request.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, this is going to be the most challenging offseason
we've had since I've been here,'' said Hunsicker, who joined the
Astros before the 1996 season. ``There are certainly more issues to
begin the offseason. Major issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
