<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN DIEGO _ Football season can begin now.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros team that captured this city's imagination showed
none. The bats that for six months split the air with sharp cracks
broke. The smart management and managerial moves that made the
Astros look like World Series material were left in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had high expectations for us. Sure, they should have
had those expectations,'' Astros ace Randy Johnson said. ``We were
good enough to go a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros went home, quickly. And the worst thing about
their collapse in the Division Series loss to the San Diego Padres
might not have been that it happened.
</P>
<P>
   We are, after all, Houston. We know playoff disappointments the
way we know highway construction _ it's always there, always
irritating, always testing our nerves. And just when it looks like
we finally can step on the pedal and go places, some numbskull cuts
us off. We knew this could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Astros catcher Brad Ausmus willingly pointed the finger, so to
speak, at himself for Sunday's series-deciding loss. Ausmus did
everything but call himself a numbskull after a poor at-bat and
strikeout in a critical bases-loaded situation in the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Give the man credit for one thing. Ausmus struck out three
times, knew he messed up with the game on the line and stood there
and took the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do the job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one argued with him, but know this: The worst thing about
this collapse was not one at-bat, one decision or one game. The
worst thing was that it all happened with such a wicked fury and
spirited team futility.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a slow slide from the top of the mountain, a subtle
slip here or an unlucky misstep there. It was a headlong leap. It
was chin up, chest out, the Astros standing arm-in-arm at the top
of the world, then jumping and crashing to the ground together.
</P>
<P>
   All for one, Padres in four.
</P>
<P>
   If it were football, the Astros' regular season was like Oilers
35, Bills 3. And you remember what happened in the rest of that
game.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that we do everything big in Texas. We win big. We
build up big hopes. We swing big and miss big. We make big trades
and have big seasons. We lose the ball in the lights big. We crash
big.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros lost it. Big. Arm-in-arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this team was good enough to go to the World
Series,'' Ausmus said. ``We didn't get any breaks and never made
the plays at the crucial times. We didn't come through at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of a game-winning single by Bill Spiers in Game 2,
Ausmus was right. He merely missed one opportunity in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   For the series, how many did Jeff Bagwell, Craig Biggio and
Derek Bell miss? The 8-for-78 at the plate by the Killer B's over
the past two postseasons will be a staggering statistic that hangs
over their heads until they drastically change their playoff fate.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou _ Mo Baseball _ was less than himself, too, winding
up in the middle of a pair of critical plays in this series. Alou
missed a blooper in Game 4 that led to the Padres' go-ahead run. He
also got rung up at third base on a great throw from Tony Gwynn in
Game 3, helping quash a potential big inning in that loss.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson was good, very good, but not The Difference
everyone expected. The defense was average, which rarely is enough
in the playoffs, and the throwing error by Sean Berry on Sunday
helped seal the Astros' fate.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen, so often the team's salvation during the regular
season, was more Salvation Army _ in a giving mood _ against the
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Even the gut-feeling decisions of manager Larry Dierker that had
been so reliable throughout the year left an empty feeling in
everyone's stomach, especially his own, this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker will replay this series over and over again in his mind,
second-guessing himself. He will wonder why he didn't pinch-hit for
Ausmus in Game 4. He will wonder about lineups and pitching
rotations and if there was anything he could have done that might
have taken some pressure off the B's or helped them find a playoff
groove.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing Dierker or the Astros do now will change what
happened in 1998. It was a great season for the team but a great
team collapse in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This year is over. We can move on now to our usual rites of
autumn _ tailgating, Friday-night football, wondering what the
Cowboys will do next, wondering when the Longhorns will find a
defense and the Aggies an offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe we're done,'' Ausmus said. ``It would be
good if we can keep this team together. Not only will it make us
better in terms of experience but because of what we went through
in this series. Because of the way we didn't play the way we were
capable of playing, we'll be a lot hungrier next year. We could be
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes. Another rite of autumn _ maybe next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
