<HEADER>
A1283 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTIONS-SCANDAL-SFC     10-06 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTIONS-SCANDAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-LEWINSKY SCANDAL MAY AID STATE GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLA MARINUCCI and ROBERT B. GUNNISON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Clinton-Lewinsky scandal is likely to have a
profound effect on close election races in California _ and
Republicans are poised to reap the benefits, according to a new
Field Poll.
</P>
<P>
   The poll predicts that 44 percent of eligible adults will vote
in the November general election, in which close margins could
decide contests for governor, U.S. Senate and at least eight
congressional seats. But Democrats appear more likely to sit the
election out, while Republicans appear more fired up about voting
because of the Lewinsky revelations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republican anger translates into a greater intensity and
intention to vote than the Democrats, who are hoping for the best
and trying to hang on for the next two years,'' Field Poll Director
Mark DiCamillo said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The poll marks the first detailed look at the most tantalizing
question about the crucial November election _ how the
scandal-saturated atmosphere in Washington will affect voters 3,000
miles away in the nation's most populous state.
</P>
<P>
   For months, both Republicans and Democrats have been gathering
thousands of volunteers for get-out-the-vote efforts to counter
anticipated fallout from the Clinton affair. Those efforts have
been more difficult because there is no hot-button issue this year
that is likely to swell voter interest.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the poll predicts that 9.1 million voters out of a
total 20.7 eligible will cast ballots in California on November 3.
Four years ago, 47 percent _ or 8.9 million voters out of 18.9
million eligible _ voted.
</P>
<P>
   But because there is a greater likelihood that Republicans will
turn out at the polls, ``it looks like (California) Republicans
have a chance to carve into the present 29-to-23 (Democratic)
advantage in the House,'' DiCamillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats outnumber Republicans on the voter rolls, 45 percent
to 37 percent. But with the election less than a month away,
Republicans gain about 3 percentage points among those who say they
plan to vote, DiCamillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Among demographic groups, the most likely voters are white,
college-educated and over 60, the survey found. Least likely voter
groups include Latinos, those with high school educations or less
and 18-to-29-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   About 1 in 5 likely voters said the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal
will be a factor. Statewide, 31 percent said it has made them more
likely to vote for Republican congressional candidates; 28 percent
said they are more likely to vote Democratic _ a three-point
Republican advantage. But 41 percent still say it will not affect
their preferences.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was conducted September 27 through October 4 among a
statewide sample of 916 registered voters, of whom 644 were
determined likely to vote in November. The margin of error for the
survey ranges from plus or minus 3 to 7 percentage points. The
findings reflect some of the same trends in voter turnout elsewhere
in the nation, said Curtis Gans of the Center for the Study of the
American Electorate.
</P>
<P>
   He said California enjoyed an upswing in voter participation in
June _ much of it largely attributed to two controversial ballot
measures, Propositions 226 and 227. But there's no guarantee that
activism seen particularly among California labor and Latino voters
will hold in November, especially now that the Lewinsky scandal has
blown up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some (voters) will say, `A pox on all your houses,''' and will
sit the election out, disgusted by the antics in Washington, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But in these uncharted waters, there's also possibility of
backfire, that if ``Republicans may keep making pronouncements''
and are perceived as partisan bullies, voters will get fired up and
send them a message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see about 70 percent chance of the former happening and
about 30 percent of the latter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the last day for voters to register for the November
election, ending the intensive search by both parties for new
members.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to find new Latino Republicans, GOP volunteers
looked through county records for house purchases showing Hispanic
names, said Mike Madrid, the party's political director.
</P>
<P>
   Madrid said these voters he dubbed ``Volvo Latinos'' tend to
become Republicans because they are newly concerned about issues
like taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He said the effort largely focused in the San Fernando, San
Gabriel and Southbay regions of Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   Madrid said the GOP was losing the registration war with
Democrats until mid-August, when Clinton made his confession speech
to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only at that point did we see increases in Republican numbers
in the 20 largest counties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have sought new members at federal ceremonies to
swear in new citizens. Madrid said Republicans are getting about 40
percent of the new voters.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, helped by absentee ballot drives by organized labor,
have also done door-to-door registration to target likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had thousands of people out this weekend to get out the
vote,'' said Democratic campaign strategist Bob Mulholland. ``We've
already called 700,000 households. We're working on the people who
vote Democratic in the base areas to make sure they vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland said the Lewinsky scandal hasn't changed the major
efforts. ``We always worry,'' he said. ``That's why we're
working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 0330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 03:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-COMMITTEE-SFC     10-06 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-COMMITTEE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL OKS IMPEACHMENT PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee voted along party
lines Monday to recommend a presidential impeachment inquiry for
only the third time in U.S. history, after a daylong debate over
the intentions of the Founding Fathers, the lessons of Watergate
and the significance of extramarital sex.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 21 Republican members of the committee voted in
favor of the resolution to begin open-ended impeachment hearings
modeled after the proceedings that drove President Richard Nixon
from office a quarter-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   All 16 Democrats voted against the measure. A pair of amendments
offered by Democrats to limit the length and scope of the inquiry
were defeated, also on party-line votes. The full House is expected
to vote on the resolution as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite predictions that the debate would be marred by partisan
bickering, the nine-hour session was marked by sober comments from
Republicans and Democrats regarding the historic task before the
committee and their near-unanimous declaration that Clinton
committed a grave error by concealing a sexual affair with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky from investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the debate revealed a deep partisan divide over the
seriousness of Clinton's wrongdoings and provided a preview of the
arguments that are certain to be heard repeatedly over the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what we now know, do we have a duty to look further
or to look away?'' Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., asked as he gaveled
the committee to order in the same ornate committee room where
articles of impeachment were approved against Nixon in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Republican after Republican chastised Clinton for the gravity of
his deception and his betrayal of the public trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are witnessing nothing less than the symptoms of a cancer
on the American presidency,'' said Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., evoking
images of presidential aide John Dean's famous line about the Nixon
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than defend Clinton's behavior, Democrats insisted that
his transgressions, though wrong, do not warrant the first
impeachment trial since Andrew Johnson's in 1868. Johnson was
impeached by the House for firing a Cabinet official, but was
acquitted by the Senate. Nixon, who was charged with obstruction of
justice and conspiracy following the break-in at the Watergate
office complex, resigned before the House had a chance to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Watergate; it is an extramarital affair,'' said
Michigan Rep. John Conyers, the committee's ranking Democrat. ``The
drafters (of the Constitution) might shake their heads in
puzzlement at the action that is proposed by the majority that we
take here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not mention the committee's proceedings in a brief
appearance before reporters on the South Lawn of the White House.
He was accompanied by House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt,
D-Mo., and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., whose
support will be critical as the White House tries to counter the
impeachment push in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Even as polls suggest that Americans are tiring of the
9-month-old scandal, the committee hearing was high drama in
Washington, which is normally consumed at this time of year with
last-minute budget deals as lawmakers race home to campaign for
re-election. The hallway outside the packed committee room was
crowded with reporters, camera crews and curiosity seekers hoping
for a glimpse of the proceedings, which were broadcast live on
several cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the committee's 37 members sat through the entire
proceedings. Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-San Jose, glanced through a copy
of the ``Federalist Papers,'' while others read briefing papers and
fought off yawns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be better off if we spent more time reading what
George Mason and James Madison said to each other than what Ms.
Lewinsky and (Linda) Tripp said to each other,'' Lofgren said when
it was her turn to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats offered a pair of amendments _ one that would have
provided a November 25 deadline for the impeachment inquiry and
another that would have limited its scope to the matters contained
in the report submitted by independent counsel Kenneth Starr. Both
were defeated.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came after a scathing assessment of Clinton's behavior
by the GOP's chief counsel, David Schippers, who cited
``substantial and credible evidence'' of 15 grounds for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The counts closely parallel the counts in the Starr report,
although they dropped what most legal experts had said were Starr's
weakest contentions: that Clinton had obstructed justice by
asserting executive privilege and by refusing to testify before the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the counts relate to giving ``false testimony under
oath'' in the Paula Jones civil case and before Starr's federal
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers argued that ``the subject matter of the underlying
case, whether civil or criminal, and the circumstances under which
the testimony is given, are of no significance whatsoever. It is
the oath itself that is sacred and must be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principle that every witness in every case must tell the
truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth is the foundation
of the American system of justice which is the envy of every
civilized nation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' chief attorney, Abbe Lowell, said the GOP was
working under the mistaken impression ``that there is some kind of
equal sign between a violation by a president of any of a number of
laws in statute books on one side, and the impeachment provisions
of Article II, Section 4 of the Constitution on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read the precedents differently and see that initiation of
an impeachment process for only the third time in American history
takes a far higher threshold than simply making a laundry list of
laws a president might have violated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is known for its partisan differences,
and a straight party-line vote is unlikely before the full House,
where it is expected that between 15 and 50 Democrats will join
Republicans later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their partisan reputations, members of the committee
avoided the acrimony that had been evident during news conferences
in the days leading up to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, chairman Hyde defended his sense of due process by
saying: ``It's like pornography; you know it when you see it, but
you have trouble defining it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure I knew pornography when I saw it until I got a
chance to read the (Starr) report,'' interrupted Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass., to laughter from both sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 0339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 03:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1304 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMF-CLINTON-SFCHRON &LR;      10-06 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-CLINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PLEADS FOR IMF ACTION TO STOP CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an unusual appearance before a group of finance
ministers from 22 industrialized and developing nations, President
Clinton pressed for action Monday to arrest what could be the most
dangerous global economic slide since the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also released a study showing that California
has been hit hard by the crisis, with exports to Asia falling 11
percent from the first quarter of last year to the first three
months of this year. California is the nation's biggest exporter to
Asia, accounting for more than one-fourth of U.S. shipments to the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is urging world leaders to adopt a U.S.
proposal for an emergency lending fund to stop the financial storm
from toppling Brazil and the rest of South America _ an even bigger
market for U.S. exports _ and threatening the long-running U.S.
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   But while limousines clog the streets around the IMF's
headquarters and the world's finance ministers and central bankers
float competing ideas about reforming the world's ``financial
architecture,'' no consensus on concrete action has emerged from
the top-level IMF meetings now under way in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that ``every leading industrial economy has a role to
play,'' Clinton touched on two big stumbling blocks: Congress'
refusal to approve more money for the IMF, and Japan's inability to
stimulate its economy, now in its worst postwar recession, and to
shore up its banking system, which is staggering under at least $1
trillion in bad debt.
</P>
<P>
   After saying nothing all summer as the world economic turmoil
spread, Clinton is now trying to seize the initiative, speaking out
three times in the past three weeks. Clinton plans to address the
entire 182-member-nation IMF tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Washington itself seemed caught up in a surreal split between
domestic political upheaval at one end of Pennsylvania Avenue and
global economic meltdown at the other.
</P>
<P>
   Congress appears oblivious to the economic chaos _ very few
members, Democrat or Republican, have addressed the crisis _ and a
House coalition of conservatives and liberals is trying to block
IMF funding, saying the fund helped cause the chaos and is deaf to
environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's inability to get House approval for an additional
$14.5 billion U.S. contribution _ which, combined with money from
181 other nations, would bolster IMF reserves by $90 billion _ has
undercut U.S. credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Top officials from Japan and Europe said Clinton's proposed
emergency fund cannot get off the ground if the United States does
not bolster current IMF loan programs. The U.S. plan has so far
received only a promise from the Group of Seven industrialized
nations to ``explore'' the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The administration plan would provide a preapproved line of
international credit, operated by the IMF, to help countries stave
off investor panics before their economies come under severe
stress. The proposed fund would be run by the IMF but would have
none of the conditions that the IMF attaches to its emergency loans
to countries such as Korea, Thailand, Indonesia and Russia, which
are requested by countries only after they have run out of reserves
and are on the verge of default.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the fund would lend to countries such as Brazil that
run generally sound economic policies but have been hit by a sudden
withdrawal of funds from frightened investors since Russia's Aug.
17 default.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining the foreign-exchange value of Brazil's currency, the
real, has been key to killing Brazil's once roaring hyperinflation.
Authorities there fear that its collapse would trigger a severe
investor panic and an economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But defending the real in the face of unprecedented capital
flight has severely depleted Brazil's dollar reserves and forced
interest rates up to nearly 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   IMF officials Monday reiterated their commitment to providing
emergency loans to Brazil _ investors are expecting a $30 billion
package _ as soon as President Fernando Henrique Cardoso announces
a package of budget cuts to address Brazil's huge fiscal deficit.
Bundesbank President Hans Tietmeyer said private creditors would
also have to take part in any rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is considered a linchpin because of South America's close
trade ties to the United States. U.S. exporters, from Silicon
Valley to the Midwest farm belt, have already been hit hard by a
steep falloff in demand for their products in Asia. If the
Brazilian economy buckles under withdrawals of investor funds, the
contagion would likely spread quickly to its neighbors and then
north to U.S. shores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, events in Asia, Russia and Latin America are having a
direct impact on the prosperity of America's farmers, workers and
businesses,'' U.S. Treasury Secretary Rubin said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The administration released the state-by-state impact of the
economic crisis Monday to pressure Congress to approve the IMF
funding. The study said 30 percent of total U.S. exports go to
Asia, including 40 percent of farm exports.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy is already slowing sharply, hit by lower
corporate earnings, downturns in business and consumer confidence
and an emerging credit crunch as investors everywhere, including
U.S. banks, become more risk averse.
</P>
<P>
   The fear is that a recession in the United States, the world's
biggest economy, would pull down Europe as well, igniting a
full-blown world recession. Without any economic engine left to
restart global growth, countries would find it extremely difficult
to regenerate domestic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
