   COVEREDBRIDGES _ A guide to Georgia's historic covered bridges,
keyed to a festival Oct. 10-11 in Thomaston, Ga. (Townsend, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FESTIVALS _ Southern Happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI _ Five years after the Jack in the Box E. coli outbreak
that nearly killed her, Brianne Kiner is starting high school.
Doctors gave her up for dead a dozen times; during the six months
she was hospitalized, virtually every one of her body systems shut
down. She is a walking miracle, but one that will need a kidney
transplant before long and constant medical vigilance the rest of
her life. We're spending some time with her to profile what life is
like for the sickest E. coli patient to ever survive. (Guthrie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-KIDS _ How, in general, kids suffering from E. coli's
wrath fair. Interviewed a cross section from different outbreaks;
some needed kidney transplants; some did not; some have immune
problems; others do not. Even doctors say it is very hard to
predict the long-term affects because there just are not enough
kids to study. (Guthrie/Anderson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HESAID-SHESAID _ Bo and Maureen on ``The Nurture Assumption.''
(Emerson/Downey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-LAMBERT _ She has her ideas about how fashion should be.
But she pauses and looks across her small sitting room and out at
Central Park, which is a blur to her eyes. (Anna, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-SIDEBAR _ Tips on fashion by Eleanor Lambert. (Anna,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   IRONING-PERSONALITY _ Do-it-yourself psychology on how, when and
where ironing occurs, and what it says about you. (Anna, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOSTELS-MAIN _ Two skiers were complaining about the high price
of lift tickets as we stood in line on the side of a mountain in
the exclusive ski town of Breckenridge, Colo. But I really didn't
care how much the lift tickets were because I had already saved the
real money. I wasn't staying in a $250-a-night condo. I was paying
$15 a night at a youth hostel. And that included breakfast.
(Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   with HOSTELS-RUSTIC _ BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ ``Mom, it's me. In case
you never hear from me again, I am calling from a place called The
Hostel in the Forest in Brunswick, Ga. I'm a little nervous about
staying here overnight. This guy from Germany gave me a tour of the
place _ he's a little scary-looking....'' And so begins one
person's adventure at a bare-bones hostel. (Anna, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   with HOSTELS-SOUTH _ A look at some Southern hostels. (Anna,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TV-DAWSON _ A behind-the-scenes look at Warner Brothers' hot
teen show ``Dawson's Creek'' (it's the No. 1 show on TV among teen
girls) with a set visit in North Carolina. The show starts its
second season this night. 40. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TV-DAWSONBIOS _A look at the four stars of ``Dawson's Creek.''
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ UPN airs ``Seven Days,'' a sci-fi
thriller and WB debuts ``Charmed.'' (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   LINDBERG-BIOGRAPHY _ Lindbergh managed his death in the same
exhaustively detailed way he managed everything, completing one
final act of focused detachment, one final act that demonstrated
the love and devotion he felt for his family but could rarely
verbalize. As he lay dying, Charles Lindbergh gave Anne Morrow
Lindbergh and their five surviving children something to do besides
hold down an agonizing death watch. This amazing life receives its
full due in A. Scott Berg's Lindbergh, by all odds the nonfiction
book of the year. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DIANA-PLAY _ Call it a Cinderella story. Or maybe just a
princess story. But it is certainly a dream come true for actress
Kendra Munger, 25. She opens in a new musical, Queen of Hearts, her
first role ever on a New York stage, acting the role of the late
Diana Spencer. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TV-UPN _ Let's pretend that Fox, the WB and UPN are The Brady
Bunch girls. Since the surging Fox is the most popular of the
three, it would be Marcia. The upstart, buzz-heavy WB is young and
budding with rosy potential. That makes it Cindy. UPN? Well, I
guess that leaves poor 'ol Jan. She's not the prettiest, nor the
youngest. In-the-middle Jan is just the one with the serious
identity crisis. Yup, that describes UPN. (Thompson, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TINPAN-ALLEY _ NEW YORK _ When Irving Berlin was in his 90s, he
could still find his way to Tin Pan Alley, or at least what
remained of it. Berlin died in 1989 at the age of 101, but Tin Pan
Alley lives on, in the music it produced if not in actuality.
(Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TVREVIEW-MERCY _ Bloodied patients suffering from multiple
compound fractures. Harried doctors barking, ``I'm going in!''
Newborns undergoing life-threatening surgery. Sounds a lot like ER,
doesn't it? Well, that's the point. Mercy Point, to be exact. If
Star Trek: Voyager and ER were ever combined, the show would look a
lot like UPN's promising new medical drama. (Thompson, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   WHATDREAMS-HEAVEN _ Heaven is a safe place. Heaven is fun, full
of color, filled with angels, a good place to visit and the house
of God. That's what some kids at St. Ann Roman Catholic School in
West Palm Beach, Fla. think about heaven. Last week, they drew
pictures of what heaven looks like to them. Some of them have a
more mature faith than many adults. A tie-in to the new release,
``What Dreams May Come.'' (Gushee, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
