<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Oct. 6, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POTATO-FAMINE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Concerned that New York public
schools were ignoring a mandate to teach the Irish potato famine as
a human rights issue, legislators have ordered the state Education
Department to develop a curriculum for teachers to use. By MIKE
HUREWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-VIOLENCE (San Francisco) _ The number of domestic violence
cases among same-sex couples surged both locally and nationwide due
largely to increased reporting of abusive situations, according to
a new report released Tuesday. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   HUDSON-PCBS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Though the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency has reached two historic agreements in
Massachusetts recently to clean up industrial PCB contamination in
the Housatanic River and New Bedford Harbor, those deals are
unlikely to have much impact on the cleanup of the Hudson River. By
PAUL ZIELBAUER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOGA (Albany, N.Y.) _ Relaxing isn't as easy as it sounds. At my
first yoga class, I was so impatient during the meditation that my
instructor had to signal me to lie down again. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-SEX (San Francisco) _ All the talk about Viagra and male
impotence may overshadow sexual dysfunction in women. Once chalked
up to psychological problems or dismissed as an unavoidable result
of menopause, female sexual dysfunction is getting more attention
from medical specialists. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ With stock prices felled by the turmoil
in financial markets, many companies are out to revive their stock
by announcing they'll buy back shares. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS (undated) _ No matter where they turned, investors
who put their money in stock mutual funds couldn't escape the
turmoil in financial markets over the past three months. By PAMELA
YIP.
</P>
<P>
   IDOT-COMMUTERS (Undated) _ Like Compaq Computer Corp., iDot was
conceived by technology industry veterans who met in a restaurant,
sketching out ideas on a napkin. Like Dell Computer Corp., iDot
sells its wares directly to customers, rather than going through a
reseller. But there's only one place to get an iDot system: the
World Wide Web. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-JOBS (San Francisco) _ While the San Jose area remains far
and away California's undisputed high-tech employment center, San
Francisco, Sacramento, Fresno and the Vallejo-Napa region are
quickly earning the designation ``cybercities.'' By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   PAC-BELL (San Francisco) _ The lucrative long-distance phone
market remains out of reach for Pacific Bell. That's because the
San Francisco phone giant has made little progress in proving it
has opened its vast local phone network to competitors, and should
not be entitled yet to offer long-distance service, state
regulators said. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THIRDEYE-MUSIC-REVIEW (Houston) _ Third Eye Blind lead singer
Stephan Jenkins snickered like a smart-aleck school boy who had
just pulled the wool over the principal's eyes. You get the sense
that Jenkins imagines himself a rock frontman and songwriter in the
tradition of the Who, the Clash and U2. If only he and his band
could do more to justify that ambition. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   TORIAMOS-MUSIC-REVIEW (Houston) _ With Tori Amos, you either get
it, or you don't. On the one hand, she has a gorgeous voice, clear
and supple. On the other, she spends so much time in the upper
ranges that it's almost impossible to understand the lyrics. By
STEVE CRAWFORD.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SANCTUARIES (Florence, Italy) _ Most of the year, a
convent here serves as home to an aging group of Franciscan nuns
and as a residence for young women attending college or graduate
school nearby. Off-season, the convent joins the some 2,000
religious houses worldwide that accept travelers for short stays
and guests for longer periods of quiet reflection. By CECILE S.
HOLMES.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco 49ers are sharing
the top spot in the NFC West with the New Orleans Saints. The
Falcons are up there, too. Things are getting cramped, and the
Niners have to be wondering what happened to the league's zoning
laws. Or the loitering statutes, which might be more applicable. By
GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Ever since a tearful colleague
phoned to tell me that Caroline Drewes was dead, I've been hearing
her gorgeous voice in my head and seeing the honest-to-God light of
vitality that always surrounded her. That sound and vision do not
jibe with a woman who goes out into the setting sun to walk her dog
and gets struck and killed by a car _ which is what happened to
Caroline. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
