<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1609 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREASTCANCER-DRUGS-TE     10-06 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREASTCANCER-DRUGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO PROMISING DRUGS FOCUS OF BREAST CANCER STUDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLOTTE HUFF 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Every morning for four years, Debra Smith
swallowed two tiny pills, hoping they would help shield her from
the breast cancer that took her mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old thought she was taking tamoxifen, the drug being
tracked nationally in more than 13,000 women considered at high
risk for developing the disease. She was sure of it, because she
was experiencing hot flashes and other symptoms associated with the
medication.
</P>
<P>
   But last spring, amid the buzz about promising results, Smith
learned that she was among the half left holding a sugar pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Smith said, shaking her head. ``Shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Weatherford resident plans to take part in the next
national trial designed to examine whether medication can help
prevent breast cancer. This time, tamoxifen will be measured
against raloxifene, a medication already used to combat
osteoporosis, the thinning and weakening of bones.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at M.D. Anderson Cancer Network-Tarrant County, also a
site for the tamoxifen study, will begin screening post-menopausal
women this month.
</P>
<P>
   Initial tamoxifen results showed that the drug reduced the risk
of developing breast cancer by 45 percent in 13,388 women. The
malignancy is the second-leading killer of American women, behind
lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers don't understand how breast cancer develops, but the
recent medications build on one theory that estrogen plays an
underlying role.
</P>
<P>
   V. Craig Jordan, director of the Lynn Sage breast cancer
research program at Northwestern University Medical School,
predicts that one day a battery of prevention drugs will be
available, similar to today's arsenal of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the verge of decreasing breast cancer incidence by
50 percent,'' said Jordan, who began studying tamoxifen in the late
1960s. ``That's huge. We go forward now to fine-tune this concept _
to be able to establish a standard prevention maintenance therapy
for women over the next decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Greg Marino, chief of oncology at the University of North
Texas Health Science Center, takes a more cautious view.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he said, raloxifene research has primarily been focused
on osteoporosis, with breast cancer almost an afterthought. And
it's too early to know whether tamoxifen prevents breast cancer or
merely delays its onset, Marino said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he would advise women at high risk to consider the drug.
``I think (researchers) are on to something,'' Marino said.
</P>
<P>
   Because osteoporosis also runs in Smith's family, she seized on
the news of the upcoming trial, which will enroll 22,000 women for
at least five years. She would not have qualified if her sugar pill
had been tamoxifen, because participants cannot have taken either
drug previously.
</P>
<P>
   Judi Leeper, a 52-year-old Hurst woman, has lost track of the
number of biopsies she has undergone since college. She has endured
so many, she said, ``It's like somebody else going in for a throat
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer has been diagnosed in Leeper's mother and two
aunts. But Leeper volunteers for drug trials _ first tamoxifen and
now raloxifene _ more in the hope that research will ease the path
for her 13-year-old daughter, Caitlin.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the initial tamoxifen results, the study was halted
14 months early; researchers didn't consider it ethical to continue
to keep half of the women from the promising findings.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news came with a catch. The women, ages 35 and
older, developed twice as many cases as the placebo group of
endometrial cancer, which affects the lining of the uterus. Jordan
counters that the elevated risk is small.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes described as designer estrogens, the new medications
must serve a dual purpose. Ideally, they promote the good effects
of estrogen, such as strengthening bones, and reduce the potential
harm in other tissues such as breast and endometrial.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen is far from an unknown drug; it has been used for more
than two decades to treat breast cancer. Raloxifene has been
approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Studies tracking more than 10,000 post-menopausal women taking
raloxifene for osteoporosis have shown a 54 percent reduction in
new breast cancers after an average of 33 months, according to drug
manufacturer Eli Lilly and Company. No increased endometrial cancer
risk has been identified.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollees at Tarrant County's site aren't charged for the drug
or related screening checkups, local M.D. Anderson officials said.
Minority enrollment is a priority; non-Anglo participants totaled
fewer than 4 percent nationwide in the tamoxifen trial.
</P>
<P>
   The women benefit from sharp-eyed medical care, said Smith, who
was sent several times straight from a checkup to get a mammogram.
</P>
<P>
   Since the spring, Smith has also solved the question of her
mysterious side effects. She was entering early menopause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, I felt like I had wasted my time,'' Smith said. ``I
know I didn't. They had to have some on the placebo to know whether
it works or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But she wouldn't have thrown her hat into this trial, she said,
if sugar pills were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been lucky for 4 1/2 years,'' she said. ``I don't want to
push it any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   (Charlotte Huff writes on medical issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7689. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
