<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1614 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-ANTICLINTON-TEX     10-06 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ANTICLINTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOLESOME IMAGE OF BUSH POSITIONS HIM AS THE ANTI-CLINTON FOR YEAR
2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is Gov. George W. Bush, dressed in a blue denim shirt,
speaking conversationally in a softly lit room of brown paneling.
His topic is a visit to a Texas boot camp for juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them about gangs and guns and drugs,'' Bush says of
his visits with the young offenders. A look of sadness passes
across his face. ``The most compelling story of all was a young man
who looked at me after all the discussion and said, `What do you
think of me?' It broke my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age when cynicism and politics are nearly synonymous, it
seemed the rarest of all things _ a genuinely poignant moment in a
political advertisement. Indeed, that ad in Bush's campaign for
re-election _ along with others that feature home-movielike images
of the popular Republican among the people _ almost positioned him
as the anti-Clinton, the personification of bedrock values at a
time when the president is chasing interns.
</P>
<P>
   It is that wholesome aura, as much as anything, that may have
vaulted Bush to a large lead in this year's race against Democrat
Garry Mauro, and into early front-runner status in the Republican
race for president two years hence. George W. Bush, the good guy,
the solid citizen, the real Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look as if it's the result of any particular
training. It just seems to be his personality,'' says George
Christian, former press secretary to Lyndon Johnson, whose
involvement in state politics spans 50 years. ``He doesn't take
himself seriously. He doesn't pontificate. He doesn't demagogue. I
mean, good Lord. Politicians everywhere would kill to have those
particular traits.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush advisers, while insisting that he is now running for
governor alone, nonetheless smile at what Bush media consultant
Mark McKinnon calls ``the unusual collision of coincidence and
timing.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, on the night of Aug. 17, when Clinton gave his
disastrous address on the Monica Lewinsky matter, Bush ads running
almost simultaneously featured the governor in another casual
setting, speaking of values.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether for government or individuals,'' Bush said in the ad,
``I believe in accountability and responsibility. For too long
we've encouraged a culture that says if it feels good, do it, and
blame somebody else if you've got a problem. We've got to change
our culture to one based upon responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon says many assumed the responsibility ad was filmed that
morning to capitalize on Clinton's woes. In fact, McKinnon says,
the ad had been shot the previous April.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, all we were trying to do was strip away the
filters, instead of add them on, like you would with most other
politicians; to just show the human being,'' says McKinnon, the
architect of the Bush campaign ads in his race for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone is so enamored. Mauro and his aides
challenge Bush on issues such as law and order, and HMOs, saying
Mauro's platform _ a patient's right to choose a physician, for
instance _ is more in tune with the average Texas voter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's benefited from his family. The most popular person in
Texas is Barbara Bush,'' says Mauro campaign manager Billy Rogers.
``There's no doubt he's been fortunate to have this strong economy
that Clinton gave us, but Bush had nothing to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Former State Republican Chairman Tom Pauken is one who predicts
Bush will win the Republican nomination for president in 2000. But
Pauken says he will choose to support either Republican millionaire
Steve Forbes, Missouri Sen. John Ashcroft, or former Vice President
Dan Quayle, who come with stronger conservative credentials and a
better grasp of the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the times I've been around him, I've never sensed a deep
interest in the issues, per se,'' Pauken says. ``It's more the
politics of personality, and that's where his strength is.''
</P>
<P>
   In any assessment of Bush's popularity, the governor's prominent
parents inevitably come up. President George Bush was often called
to task for political weaknesses, rarely for his integrity. Barbara
Bush ranks among history's most popular first ladies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush family is one of the premier families in America,''
Christian says. ``People like and respect his father and mother,
which certainly helps.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's grittier edge has often demonstrated itself in
his allegiance to family. While in the White House, President Bush
often called on his eldest son as a political trouble-shooter. In
that regard, George W. Bush has also been described as a ``pit
bull.'' In 1991, in the most commonly cited example, it was George
W. Bush who suggested that beleaguered White House chief of staff
John Sununu resign, a suggestion that Sununu quickly accepted.
</P>
<P>
   That edge has done little to dent Bush's popularity, even on
controversial political decisions. This year, despite an
international clamor for mercy, the governor declined to block the
execution of Texas Death Row inmate Karla Faye Tucker, a born-again
Christian. A few months later, Bush commuted the death sentence of
another notorious criminal, Henry Lee Lucas, when doubts surfaced
about his guilt. That decision angered many in law enforcement, but
the governor's march to re-election rolled on.
</P>
<P>
   And as speculation mounts about a Bush run for president two
years hence, the former president's son has become a darling of the
national media, as well.
</P>
<P>
   National radio personality Don Imus says George W. Bush is his
choice for president in two years. The Washington Post recently
published a glowing if brief profile, calling Bush ``gracious and
talkative'' and saying he ``truly seems to relish the
flesh-pressing part of the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's life and career are scrutinized much more closely in a
long cover story in the Sept. 13 New York Times Magazine. The
article chronicles George W.'s abrasiveness while defending his
father, and tells in some depth about Bush's rootlessness and heavy
drinking in his 20s and 30s. (He quit alcohol more than a decade
ago.)
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, the story concludes, the biggest questions
surrounding George W. Bush and a national candidacy are those of
politics, not character. i.e., his moderate views on issues such as
abortion and homosexuality could antagonize Republicans on the far
right.
</P>
<P>
   Much more intense national scrutiny is to come. But so far
little has surfaced about the man with which to mount a credible
personal attack.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers President Tom Schieffer, a longtime political
activist who served several terms in the state Legislature, says
simply that Bush is ``at peace with himself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been around politics and politicians for a long time,
and having reflected on that, that is a very, very rare
occurrence,'' Schieffer says. ``The less he worries about what he's
going to do in the future, the more popular he becomes.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
