A1622 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     10-06 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN SAYS SHOULDER HAS NOT HEALED ENOUGH FOR RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys will make a change in the
starting lineup for the Sunday's game against Carolina, but it
won't be the return of quarterback Troy Aikman, who has missed the
past three games with a fractured collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   Acclaimed rookie Flozell Adams will start at right guard in
place of Everett McIver, who is expected to be out six to eight
weeks with a sprained medial collateral ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, however, was put on hold for at least another week.
Though X-rays of Aikman's shoulder taken Monday showed positive
signs, Aikman, who's still experiencing pain and soreness in his
left shoulder, said the healing progress was not as substantial as
he hoped when he targeted the Carolina game for his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not play this week,'' Aikman said. ``And with that
being the case, the question is whether it's worth the risk to come
back for one game. More than likely the decision will be made that
it's not. So I would guess that my first game back would be
following the bye against Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chan Gailey said the Cowboys will re-examine Aikman's
situation before they play Chicago on Oct. 18. But considering the
Cowboys have a bye the following week, Gailey admitted that he
would prefer that Aikman not come back until the Nov. 2 matchup
against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   While Aikman and Gailey admitted that the Cowboys' success with
Jason Garrett as the starter gives them a good feeling about what
the team has accomplished during Aikman's absence, they said it has
no bearing on when he would return.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett, 2-1 as a starter since Aikman was injured, is coming
off his best game this season. He completed 14 of 17 passes for 169
yards and a touchdown to lead the Cowboys (3-2) to a 31-10 victory
against the Washington Redskins on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Aikman said, is how the shoulder feels and
``whether I feel I can go out and get hit and be taken to the
ground and not be at a considerable risk of re-breaking the
collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I don't think that's the case,'' Aikman said. ``I
don't feel like it's strong enough to withstand any kind of
punishment. I don't want to come back one or two games early and
jeopardize the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer said he supports a decision to wait
until after the bye week _ considering that the original prognosis
was four to eight weeks and the Philadelphia game would be seven
weeks from when he broke it against Denver on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week you wait, you hope the bone gets that much more
solidified,'' Maurer said. The X-ray, Maurer said, showed some
positive things about the way the bone was healing. ``He has a
higher chance of refracturing it today than two weeks from now. The
Philadelphia game would give him an optimal amount of healing
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though guard Mike Kiselak replaced McIver against the
Redskins and had a strong performance against defensive tackle Dan
Wilkinson, the move to start Adams was no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys indicated the 6-foot-7, 335-pound Adams had the most
impressive training camp of any rookie since all-pro tackle Larry
Allen debuted in 1994. As a result, Gailey created formations to
get Adams on the field, including using him as a blocking tight
end.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey praised Kiselak's play, but said Adams, who replaced
McIver when he was sidelined with a cut on his neck during the
preseason, was the obvious choice in place of McIver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt Flozell deserved it,'' Gailey said. ``He earned it. He
played well when we put him in there in the preseason. He's done a
good job. It's not like we're giving it away indiscriminantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiselak, who is in his first year with the Cowboys and played in
the Canadian Football League last year, will continue be the
Cowboys' top reserve on the offensive line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
