<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYSNOTES-TEX     10-06 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS BUILD POINTS WITH WARREN'S LATE RUNS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The site of Dallas Cowboys running back Chris
Warren high-stepping into the end zone with 1:06 to go in a
14-point ball game may have offended some Redskins fans.
</P>
<P>
   But running up the score was not what Cowboys coach Chan Gailey
was thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Points in the division _ that can determine if you make the
playoffs,'' Gailey said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The final scoring drive began on the Cowboys' 4-yard line.
Trying to run out the clock, Gailey ran Warren up the middle on
nine consecutive plays. The Redskins knew what was coming, but
couldn't stop him from gaining 90 yards on the nine plays.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith spelled Warren for one play after the last of
Warren's nine consecutive carries, a 49-yarder. Then Warren, a
native of nearby Burke, Va., came back in to score on a 1-yard run,
giving him two touchdowns and 104 yards on the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just looked like Chris was running faster than everyone
else,'' Cowboys center Clay Shiver said. ``We wore them down late.
Obviously, you could see the Redskins were discouraged. You could
see it on their faces.'' REVIEWING THE FILM
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSE: Tight end David LaFleur has been ignored for much of
the season. On passing downs, he has usually been replaced by third
wide receiver Ernie Mills. And on some running downs, he has been
replaced by offensive lineman Flozell Adams.
</P>
<P>
   But LaFleur finally had a breakout game against the Redskins,
recording a career-high four receptions. And although he netted
only 29 yards, the catches came at crucial times. Two were for
first downs. And his last one, an 8-yarder, set up Warren's first
touchdown run, giving the Cowboys a 24-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE: Defensive end Kavika Pittman continues his swift
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys led 10-7 when the Redskins faced third-and-one.
Quarterback Trent Green faked a pitch left and rolled right. He had
wide receiver Leslie Shepherd running free down the field. But
Pittman, who was not fooled by Green's fake, dropped the Redskins
quarterback for his third sack of the season. The sack forced the
Redskins to punt, and two plays later, the Cowboys increased the
lead to 17-7 on Jason Garrett's 43-yard pass to Mills.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he was pleased with the Cowboys' defensive pressure.
But the defensive unit still allows several big plays a game, a
concern for defensive coordinator Dave Campo. The Redskins
converted a 42-yard pass, a 40-yard pass, and a 24-yard run against
the Cowboys. The three plays netted 106 yards, or nearly 40 percent
of the Redskins' total offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like giving up big plays,'' Campo said, ``but we can
fix those. We'd have more of a problem if a team kept getting the
5-, 6-, and 7-yard plays on us, pounding it on us. That hasn't
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL TEAMS: Safety Charlie Williams committed two penalties
on special teams, including a holding penalty that wiped out Deion
Sanders' 71-yard punt return for a touchdown. But because the unit
has played well this year, Gailey said he does not feel as though
Sunday's performance is a sign of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be smarter, but \Rthe penalties\S have not been a
persistent thing,'' Gailey said. ``I'm sure it will be a one-time
deal.'' Gailey's corner
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go out and do something consistent before we get too
high on ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Gailey, cautioning the local media not to make too much of the
club's 3-0 record against the NFC East. Outside the East, the
Cowboys are 0-2. INJURY REPORT
</P>
<P>
   _ Guard Everett McIver will be out six to eight weeks with a
sprained medial collateral ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quarterback Troy Aikman is out with a fractured collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defensive tackle Antonio Anderson is out with a torn lateral
meniscus in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   _ Linebacker Nate Hemsley in on injured reserve with a
dislocated ankle and fractured fibula. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cowboys signed defensive lineman Nathan Davis, who was a
second-round draft choice of the Falcons last year. To make room on
the roster, the club placed Hemsley on injured reserve. Hemsley was
injured Sept. 21 at New York.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cowboys also released wide receiver Anthony Eubanks from
the practice squad and replaced him with defensive back Terry
Billups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
