r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-WRIGHT-TEX     10-06 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-WRIGHT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRIGHT'S STYLE HAS YANKEES IN FOUL MOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL C.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Right-hander Jaret Wright, the Cleveland Indians'
scheduled starter Tuesday night for Game 1 of the best-of-seven
American League Championship Series, emerged as the unsuspecting
center for mild controversy Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It appears the Yankees do not care much for the 22-year-old
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   New York's ``Daily News'' referred to Wright as a pitcher the
Yankees ``generally consider a punk.''
</P>
<P>
   That view does not stem from Wright's two victories against the
Yankees in their 1997 AL Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   It instead stems from a March 2 exhibition game during spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   Wright hit Luis Sojo with a pitch that resulted in a fracture of
the reserve infielder's left hand. The injury kept Sojo on the
15-day disabled list until April 27.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander David Wells, the Yankees' scheduled starter Tuesday,
supplied the catalyst for this subject when asked about his
ballclub wanting revenge for the Indians' 1997 playoff triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the fans as well as the media because of all the
hype that's brought into it, but sometimes,'' Wells said, ``it can
be personal through the course of the year when things go on in a
game . ...''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wright, would you care to respond to the Yankees' dislike
for you?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much I can say about that,'' Wright said. ``I'm
out there to do my job, and I don't think we need to turn this into
anything more than it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the third time I've been asked about whether I'm
hitting people (intentionally) or not. I'm out there trying to get
outs. I'm out there trying to keep my team in the ballgame, and it
is baseball. People get hit sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, though, kept his comments veiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not personal for me, but it can be personal for other
people and for other reasons,'' Wells said. ``I think when you get
two teams that are very competitive, it can go as far back as
spring training with that situation with Luis Sojo. That was a long
time ago, and sometimes you've just got to let bygones be bygones.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been situations where guys ... are a little more
aggressive and you have to pitch inside. I understand that, but you
don't have to pitch up and in and head hunt. That's one thing I
don't believe in. I don't think it's right because you can really
hurt somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Wright: ``Pitching inside is part of my game, and I'm not
trying to hurt anybody or hit anybody. That's just the way I was
taught to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Indians manager Mike Hargrove again defended his pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got those questions from you guys in spring training when
that happened,'' Hargrove said. ``First of all, there is no reason
to throw at anybody in spring training _ much less at that point of
spring training. Jaret was not throwing at anybody. Jaret is a
power pitcher, and occasionally the ball will move and get away
from him. That's what happened in Luis' situation. Jaret is not a
headhunter.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright, though, would prefer that the Yankees serve as another
big-game trophy for his collection after victories in Games 2 and 5
of the '97 AL Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat this team when I happened to be on the mound,'' Wright
said. ``My job stays the same, to keep it close and hopefully put
up some zeroes until we can score against a guy like David Wells.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
