<HEADER>
A1635 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TEX     10-06 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE TO COLTS: DON'T MESS UP A GOOD THING IN MANNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Indianapolis Colts,
</P>
<P>
   Please don't do it. Please don't mess up Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, your No. 1 choice in April's NFL draft, finally
registered his first pro victory on Sunday. It should be the first
of many, many wins. Peyton's stats aren't big; in the 17-12 victory
over fellow rookie Ryan Leaf and the Chargers, Manning was 12-of-23
for 137 yards. And he threw another pick, so he leads the NFL with
12 interceptions. Peyton's progress is slow; some of your critics
are suggesting he's being asked to do too much, others suggesting
he's being asked to do too little.
</P>
<P>
   Please, Colts. Don't mishandle this kid.
</P>
<P>
   It happens often. And it usually means not only the death of the
quarterback's career, but also the death of the head coach's
career. And the long-term need for a life-support system for the
entire franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Hey Colts, ask the Eagles. Do you realize that Ray Rhodes has
fired or benched every QB he has ever started? Or ask the
Cardinals. Is it just a coincidence they haven't won big since Jim
Hart was their signal-caller? Or ask the Redskins. After five years
of playing the quarterback domino game that has left him with
somebody named Trent Green as his starter, wanna bet that Norv
Turner sometimes, late at night, when he's all by himself, wonders
if he gave up too early on Heath Shuler?
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, Colts, you don't have to examine how other teams have
messed up this development-of-quarterbacks thing. Maybe you can
just look at yourselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the 16 years since Bob Irsay's ownership caused you to draft
and then trade John Elway to Denver, you've started 17 different
quarterbacks! Isn't that astounding? For 16 years, the Broncos' QB
has been Elway. For 16 years, your QB has been Mike Pagel (83-85),
Art Schlichter (84-85), Mark Herrmann (83-84), Matt Kofler (85),
Gary Hogeboom (86-88), Jack Trudeau (86-93), Blair Kiel (86-87),
Chris Chandler (88-89), Tom Ramsey (89), Jeff George (90-93), Don
Majkowski (93-94), Jim Harbaugh (94-97), Browning Nagle (94), Craig
Erickson (95), Paul Justin (95-97), Kelly Holcomb (97) and Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Given their backgrounds _ coach Jim Mora's resume doesn't
include QB development, and your first-time-ever QB coach is Bruce
Arians, whose greatest NFL accomplishment is having served as New
Orleans' tight ends coach _ I hope your coaching staff is up to the
task.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Colts, I don't have the how-to answer for avoiding
mistakes. When it comes to the care and feeding of your QBs, nobody
does.
</P>
<P>
   But this kid has the goods. So it's your job to find a way.
Don't mess up, or it might be another 16 years of Herrmanns and
Hogebooms and Holcombs.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck, Colts. NFL BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   Bonehead coaching decision of the year: Five seconds left.
Arizona trails Oakland, 23-20. Arizona can try a 56-yard field
goal, but instead calls one more play, a 2-yard pass. It's
complete, but of course, time runs out. Attention, Vince Tobin: Is
a 54-yard kick so much easier than a 56-yarder that you would risk
eating up all remaining five seconds? ... Yes, coach Steve Mariucci
actually blamed his 49ers' record-tying 22 penalties in Buffalo on
overzealous officials. Reality check, please. ... In beating the
Giants, Tampa Bay scored its first TD in a first quarter.
Naturally, it was scored by the Bucs defense ... Weird numbers out
of the Detroit loss to Chicago, where Barry Sanders rushed for 28
yards while teammate Charlie Batch, the QB, rushed for 58. Hey, Joe
Theismann: Shhhh. ... Atlanta's three TDs in 48 seconds vs.
Carolina is a since-the-merger record. ... Detroit blew a 27-10
fourth-quarter lead in allowing the Bears' first win. ... Seahawks
runner Ricky Watters insists he isn't such a bad guy. ``I resent
all this because it isn't a fair label,'' says Watters of his
reputation for immaturity. ``If I went out and robbed a bank. ...
then, OK, criticize me.'' That's OK, Ricky. We'll just criticize
you for two costly fumbles in Sunday night's sloppy loss at Kansas
City. ... The irony in Chicago and Washington: When Dave Wannstedt
and Norv Turner were Dallas coordinators, ``halftime adjustments''
were a specialty. This year, the Bears and Redskins have been
outscored in third quarters by a combined 124-10. ... Too bad for
the Chiefs the Super Bowl is in Miami. Under coach Marty
Schottenheimer, as they established against Seattle, Kansas City is
a good mudder. But check back with me in January: the Chiefs are
0-6 in the Sunshine State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
