<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEVELAND CALMLY APPROACHES RECORD-SETTING NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The most unintentionally funny question posed to an
Indians player after Cleveland's playoff victory over the Boston
Red Sox on Saturday went to David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Do you feel, the left fielder was asked, that your team has any
advantage against the New York Yankees in the American League
Championship Series?
</P>
<P>
   After a brief pause, Justice gave the only possible answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he replied. ``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone would have trouble giving the Indians an edge entering
their best-of-seven rematch with New York. The Yankees, after all,
``edged'' the Indians by 25 games in the American League standings
this season. There were years the old Washington Senators didn't
finish that far behind New York.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Indians have shown no signs of intimidation as they
prepare for Tuesday's opener at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees won 114 games; their record speaks for itself,''
Justice said of the team that broke the AL record for victories set
by the 1954 Indians. ``But our team has enough talent and character
to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland is drawing confidence from the fact that it beat a
superior New York team in the division playoff series last season,
and from its regular-season play this year against the Yankees.
Although New York beat the Indians in the season series, 7-4, three
of the New York victories came in the last week of the season when
neither club was especially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Indians players and management are also aware that they have
some pitching history to support their confidence. Game 1 starter
Jaret Wright is 4-1 lifetime against New York. Bartolo Colon
stifled Yankees hitters in a game against them this year. Charles
Nagy was 1-0 with a 1.72 ERA in two starts against New York. And
Dwight Gooden should be especially motivated to start against his
old teammates.
</P>
<P>
   There is a flip side, however. Wright has been wildly
inconsistent this season and was bombed out of his start against
Boston in Game 1 of the Division Series. Colon pitched well in Game
4 against the Red Sox but had a poor second half. Nagy was
atrocious against New York last year and in the 1997 postseason.
And Gooden didn't look sharp before being ejected in Game 2 of the
Red Sox series last week.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's pitching will be the key, too, by any assessment,
because Indians' hitters, like the Rangers' batters, appear
unlikely to score much against the likes of David Wells, David
Cone, Andy Pettitte, Orlando Hernandez and the rest of the Yankees'
staff.
</P>
<P>
   That realization has Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove realistic,
if still positive, about his team's chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees won 114 games this year and they didn't do that by
being lucky,'' Hargrove said. ``They have terrific players, a
wonderful manager and they are a first-class organization. But we
feel very good about ourselves and that we can match up with
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Indians were widely regarded to have underachieved
throughout the 1998 regular season, they managed in the Boston
series to play their best when it counted the most, as they
appeared to do in last year's postseason run to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Indians closer Mike Jackson had an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go through lots of ups downs over the course of a
season,'' he said. In the playoffs, he noted, ``Guys stepped up. We
have a lot of veteran players who have been in the postseason
several years. They don't panic. They stay focused. They don't try
to do things they can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether one of the things the Indians can't do is beat the
invincible Yankees is the next big question to be answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
