<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WILL START ON 1999 PLANS NEXT WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton likely ranks high among the Rangers'
list of priorities this month, but it appears general manager Doug
Melvin will wait until next week to put in motion the
organization's plan of attack for the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plans to sit down and talk about our club next week,''
Melvin said Monday. ``We're going to review strategy as to how we
go about some of the things we're going to do. I think we know what
we have to do, and I think I have a pretty good idea of how we're
going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin declined to discuss specifics, but the general manager
will begin to retool the roster for 1999 upon return from his
three-day trip to the organization's Florida Instructional League
site.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton and right-hander Todd Stottlemyre _ whom the Rangers
acquired in the July 31 trade that sent third baseman Fernando
Tatis, left-hander Darren Oliver and minor-league outfielder Mark
Little to the Cardinals _ can become free agents after the
conclusion of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even talked to them yet,'' Melvin said. McLEMORE HAS
SURGERY
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers expect second baseman Mark McLemore to be ready for
spring training after the 34-year-old infielder underwent
arthroscopic surgery to repair the patella in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Drs. John Conway and James Montgomery performed the surgery
Monday at HealthSouth Surgery Center in Dallas, and the Rangers
expect McLemore to begin rehabilitation this week. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rangers scheduled left-hander Scott Bailes to undergo
arthroscopic surgery Friday to repair the torn rotator cuff in his
left shoulder. Conway is scheduled to perform the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Left-hander Tony Fossas also plans to undergo arthroscopic
surgery within the next couple of weeks to repair torn cartilage in
his right knee.
</P>
</TEXT>
