<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1640 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-TEX     10-06 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES' LIGTENBERG ISN'T JUST COMIC RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The San Diego Padres closer is a Cy Young Award
candidate who saved 53 out of 54 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves closer is a former replacement player who was
acquired from the Minneapolis Loons for six dozen baseballs and two
dozen bats.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves look at second-year right-hander Kerry Ligtenberg
and don't see a disadvantage when he's matched against Padres
reliever Trevor Hoffman in the National League Championship Series,
which begins Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the story of the century for me,'' Braves manager Bobby
Cox said. ``He's a chemical engineer who came out of an independent
league and he's closing for a team that's won more games than any
other team the last seven or eight years. This guy is a pretty
well-kept secret in the league right now.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no secrets in the playoffs however. The assumption all
year with the Braves was that their bullpen would be their weak
spot in the postseason. But Ligtenberg has come close to matching
Hoffman's terrific numbers, even though he didn't become the closer
until June.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman led the league in save percentage, but Ligtenberg was
successful in 30 of 34 opportunities. Hoffman allowed 7.8
baserunners per nine innings, the best of any National League
reliever. Ligtenberg, who features a 94 mile-per-hour fastball and
above-average slider, was fifth best, allowing 9.2 baserunners per
nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done a great job,'' former Marlins manager Jim Leyland
said after watching Ligtenberg shut his team down last month.
``When you're saving games for the Atlanta Braves, you've got
pressure. Not only because you're saving the game, but because
you're saving it for a Cy Young winner every night. He has done
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves would be in deep trouble without Ligtenberg. Mark
Wohlers saved a club-record 39 games in 1996 and 33 more last
season, but injuries and a lack of control brought him down this
year. Two trips to the minor leagues failed to solve his problems,
which led to speculation the Braves would be in trouble during the
playoffs. When Wohlers was sent down, the reason listed was
``inability to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for me to say now that October isn't any different,
but every game matters in the postseason,'' said Ligtenberg, who
made two appearances in the playoffs last season. ``I don't get
rattled and I think I'm more focused at playoff time. I'm just kind
of proving my case that I can get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves weren't expecting Ligtenberg to be this good when
they first signed him. They were just hoping to get lucky in middle
relief when they signed him from the independent Prairie League in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   He was recommended by former Braves catcher Greg Olson, who was
managing the Loons at the time. There was actually no trade
involved, but the Braves sent Olson the badly needed equipment out
of gratitude for recommending Ligtenberg.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are not his first major-league organization.
Ligtenberg pitched in a couple of games as a replacement player for
the Seattle Mariners in spring training 1995 and, like Mets pitcher
Rick Reed, has been stuck with that label ever since. It keeps him
out of the Players Association and away from an extra $30,000 in
licensing money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making a big deal out of it,'' Ligtenberg said. ``They
have to do what they think is right. At the time I didn't know what
I was doing. I wasn't out to take anybody's job. I was fighting to
make an `A' ball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg hurt his shoulder in the Mariners camp and turned
down a high-paying job with 3M to keep pitching in the Prairie
League. His tenacity has been rewarded. So have the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll ever take this for granted,'' Ligtenberg
said. ``From where I was three or four years ago, this is about as
far away as you can get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
