<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS BUNCH KNOWS THEIR LINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The third- and fourth-line forwards of a hockey
team are kind of like the Jan Bradys of the hockey world.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Brady has the prettiest smile, the long blond hair, all
the attention.
</P>
<P>
   And Jan? She's Marcia's younger sister, always hidden in the
shadow.
</P>
<P>
   While third- and fourth-line players rarely get the glamorous
roles of a Mike Modano or Brett Hull, they are hardly the weak
sisters. They are the workhorses of the team, the muscle, the ones
who fans remember when they score a big goal in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The third and fourth line is where the Stars have worked hard
the past year to improve, adding, among others, Brian Skrudland,
Mike Keane, Brent Severyn and Jamie Wright _ not exactly Marcia
Bradys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has a No. 1 and No. 2 line, but what's going to win
you a Cup is your No. 3 and No. 4,'' said Mike Krushelnyski, an
assistant coach on Detroit's 1996-97 Stanley Cup-winning team and
Red Wings forward in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Stars general manager Bob Gainey: ``They're valuable
players. They're hard to find and hard to keep.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey trusts he has put the finishing touches on the Stars
third and fourth lines. And if you missed the transactions
involving these precious players, it's not hard to understand why.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``Golden'' precedes none of their nicknames, none of
their fathers were mega-NHL superstars, and none of them will score
anywhere near 50 goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars third- and fourth-line depth charges include a faceoff
master in Guy Carbonneau, experienced grinders like Keane,
Skrudland, Grant Marshall and Dave Reid, and a young, speedy rookie
in Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since our team has had a solid third and
fourth line like we do now,'' Modano said. ``Lines that contributes
on a consistent basis, every night, chipping in a goal or two on
the odd night that puts us over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   A third- or fourth-line player's job is very specialized, with
duties that include killing penalties, checking and fighting, all
while not being a defensive liability. The player must pair those
skills with hockey smarts and one or more of the following: size,
good hands or above-average skating ability, Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is where the GMs have their work cut out for them,''
Krushelnyski said. ``And it's not just going out and spending
money. It's finding the right role player to play the position.
It's a tactful chess game you have to meticulously plan out to put
the team together.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey began to execute his plan by acquiring Skrudland and
Keane at the trading deadline last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chance to add two experienced bodies, two players who
have playoff experience and some size,'' Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   Those two players mixed in nicely with young forwards Marshall
and Juha Lind. Add in veterans Carbonneau and Bob Bassen, and
sometimes Reid, and that made for a solid group of six.
</P>
<P>
   Against every team but Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Conference finals, the fourth-line heroes played
for the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't score, Grant Marshall didn't score and Bob Bassen
scored one goal,'' said Skrudland, then the fourth-line center.
``One goal from Grant, one goal from me, at some point, could have
changed the series.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's fourth line, which usually consisted of Kris Draper,
Martin Lapointe and Joey Kocur, combined for 14 goals in the
playoffs, including one game-winner from Lapointe against the Stars
in the six-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean the Stars third and fourth liners were incapable
of making a similar offensive contribution? Quite the opposite,
says Stars coach Ken Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities were there. The finish was not.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what aggravates Hitchcock the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have people getting opportunities offensively, they
have to bury it,'' Hitchcock said. ``They have to accept that
responsibility, and it doesn't matter if it's Brian Skrudland,
Brent Severyn or Grant Marshall. ... Those are the details we need
in this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey did a little more juggling in the offseason, subtracting
Lind and Bassen and adding Wright and Severyn. Wright brings speed
and a good touch while Severyn delivers size and muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just look at it as we're one of four lines that play,''
Marshall said. ``Modano's line can't play our role, and we can't
play their role. They're the No. 1 line for what they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're the No. 1 line for what we do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
