<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR'S ALFRED EARNS STARTING QUARTERBACK SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 12 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jermaine Alfred, who has come off the bench to trigger
fourth-quarter rallies in Baylor's past two games, will replace
Odell James as the Bears' starting quarterback in Saturday's game
against Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jermaine has played well and earned the right to start,''
Baylor coach Dave Roberts said Monday. ``But we'll keep playing
both quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred, a junior, passed for 225 yards and directed two
touchdown drives in the final 17 minutes of the Bears' 31-29 loss
to Texas Tech. A week earlier, he led Baylor (1-3, 0-2) to a
go-ahead touchdown in the fourth quarter of an eventual 18-16 loss
to No. 14 Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tech and Colorado are 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Against Tech, Alfred was involved in the game's most pivotal
play: a two-point conversion pass to wide receiver Derrius Thompson
with 1:10 remaining that did not count because game officials ruled
Alfred stepped out of bounds before releasing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Several Baylor players, including Alfred and Thompson, disagreed
with the call. Roberts declined comment Monday, but confirmed he
had reviewed the play and forwarded a report to the conference
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the mail,'' Roberts said. ``I can't comment on any of
that. We've done what we're supposed to do.'' Aggies lose RB Eric
Bernard, Texas A&AMP;M's third-team tailback, tore knee ligaments
during a non-contact drill Sunday night and will be lost for the
season, coach R.C. Slocum said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard, who missed the 1997 season because of reconstructive
knee surgery, will needs surgical repairs on the other knee, Slocum
said. A junior who rushed for 598 yards in 1996, Bernard carried
nine times for 40 yards (4.4 average) this season in relief of
Dante Hall and Sirr Parker. TV DECISION DELAYED
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive week, ABC officials have exercised
the right to wait until Sunday before selecting a Big 12 game to
telecast at 2:30 p.m. on Oct. 17, putting kickoff times for two
games in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Network officials said Monday they will select either Texas
Tech-Colorado or Oklahoma State-Kansas State as ABC's Oct. 17 game.
The unselected contest will begin at 11:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Oct. 17 Nebraska-Kansas game will begin at 6 p.m. as a Fox
Sports Southwest telecast. MISSOURI'S JONES QUESTIONABLE
</P>
<P>
   Missouri quarterback Corby Jones is questionable for Saturday's
game against Iowa State because of a sprained toe. Coach Larry
Smith said the injury caused excessive swelling after Saturday's
35-14 victory against Northwestern (La.) State and will keep Jones
out of practice until tomorrow, if not all week.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was ``concerned'' that Jones, a first-team
all-conference selection in 1997, would not be available when the
21st-ranked Tigers (3-1, 1-0) meet the Cyclones (2-3, 0-2). Jones'
replacement, if necessary, would be sophomore Ryan Douglass, son of
former Chicago Bears' quarterback Bobby Douglass. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Oklahoma State coach Bob Simmons, on the challenge of getting
his team to rebound emotionally from a last-second, 24-17 loss to
No. 2 Nebraska: ``I don't think it will be a problem. Our kids feel
good about what's going on. Good teams, in my opinion, tend to
bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes dismissed playing on artificial
surface as a reason why six players, including starting offensive
linemen Curtis Lowery (knee) and Steve McFadden (ankle), are not
expected to play against Oklahoma State: ``The surface had nothing
to do with that. Our guys just got hit hard. As big and fast as
guys are these days, you've got to be fortunate to dodge that
bullet for any length of time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Nebraska starting quarterback Bobby Newcombe is not at 100
percent and is considered ``a little questionable'' by coach Frank
Solich for Saturday's game at Texas A&AMP;M. Newcombe is expected to
see limited practice time this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
