<HEADLINE>
LANGENBRUNNER SIGNS; STARS HUMBLE LIGHTNING
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dallas Stars coach Ken Hitchcock wanted a dress
rehearsal for Saturday's opening night, so he sent out his best
lineup Monday night for a 7-2 preseason victory against the Tampa
Bay Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he'll be able to get even closer. The Stars yesterday
signed restricted free agent Jamie Langenbrunner to a two-year
contract for $1.8 million, giving Hitchcock access to every lineup
regular except injured centers Joe Nieuwendyk and Brian Skrudland.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner, 24, missed all of training camp while his agent
Steve Bartlett tried to hammer out a contract _ and the deal
finally came together yesterday. Langenbrunner will earn $750,000
this season, up from $300,000 last season, and will jump to $1.15
million next season.
</P>
<P>
   While the negotiations were at times difficult, Stars general
manager Bob Gainey said he was happy to have them completed before
the start of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of become the norm, there are still several other
players who aren't in camp throughout the league,'' he said. ``That
said, to have all our players available will be an advantage
against those teams that do not have theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner, 24, is a definite advantage. He was tied for
third in goal-scoring last season for the Stars with 23. The winger
added 29 assists for 59 points _ the most of any second-year player
in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   He also was selected to play for the United States Olympic Team
and had a goal and four assists in 16 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Skrudland hurt his knee in Monday night's game and could be
either ``day-to-day,'' Hitchcock said, or in need of arthroscopic
surgery and possibly out 10-14 days. If Skrudland can't play in
Saturday's season opener, Hitchcock said he expects to use
Langenbrunner as a center instead of a left wing. STRONG SHOWING
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull had his second two-goal game of the preseason and the
Stars' top line of Hull, Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen had three
goals and five assists for an eight-point night against the
Lightning. Hull finished with five goals and three assists in six
preseason games. Modano had three goals and six assists in seven
games. Lehtinen had three goals and four assists in seven games.
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ The Stars finished 5-2-1 in the preseason and outscored
opponents, 32-16.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have made available an additional 300 tickets for
Saturday's season opener against the Buffalo Sabres. Call
214-GO-STARS for information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stars defenseman Dan Keczmer is out two weeks with viral
meningitis. Hitchcock said yesterday he expected to keep only seven
defensemen instead of calling up a replacement. Hitchcock said the
Stars likely will use less than their 24 available healthy roster
spots.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Stars winger Benoit Hogue served as the Lightning
captain Monday night. Hogue, who signed with the Lightning as a
free agent, received a small cheer when he assisted on Tampa Bay's
second goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
