<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD REDISCOVERS THE HEREAFTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of scenes from the films
``One True Thing,'' ``What Dreams May Come'' and ``Meet Joe
Black.''
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Hollywood seems to be taking note of the fact that the century
is racing to its conclusion. And just like the Victorians at the
end of the 19th century, with their seances and their interest in
the occult, movie makers are preoccupied with some very strange
stuff.
 &HT;    Witness the current and future spate of movies dealing with
death, dying, angels, the afterlife, heaven and hell.
 &HT;    Just out is Robin Williams in ``What Dreams May Come,'' a
romantic drama complete with special effects, set in the afterlife.
Williams literally goes through hell to be reunited with his former
wife and soulmate (Annabella Sciorra).
 &HT;    He's in heaven after dying in a car crash. His wife, however, is
down below _ after killing herself from grief at losing her husband
and family. Robin makes the journey from paradise to the underworld
to rescue his true love.
 &HT;    In November, Brad Pitt plays the Grim Reaper himself in the very
offbeat ``Meet Joe Black,'' inspired by the l934 Frederic March
classic ``Death Takes a Holiday.'' Death assumes the face of the
recently killed Pitt, who while vacationing from his gruesome
duties falls madly in love with businessman Anthony Hopkins'
daughter (Claire Forlani) and discovers there's more to life than
death.
 &HT;    ``There was much talk of death on the set and how we would like
to die,'' recalls Hopkins, who last worked with Pitt in the movie
``Legends of the Fall.''
 &HT;    Pitt may seem rather unlikely casting for a fellow usually
depicted in a hooded robe carrying a scythe, but Hollywood seems to
have a penchant for turning death into a pretty face. Remember
Robert Redford as the unwelcome visitor to a very old lady played
by Gladys Cooper in an early episode of ``The Twilight Zone''?.
 &HT;    Director Martin Brest says they chose Pitt to avoid being
gruesome and heavy handed about the topic. ``I thought Brad had
that slightly otherworldly presence we needed,'' he told
Entertainment Weekly.
 &HT;    Nicole Kidman also takes a foray into the realm of the
supernatural, teaming up with Sandra Bullock in ``Practical
Magic,'' a spiritual tale about two women who happen to be New
England witches. The film, which opens Oct. 9, is based on Alice
Hoffman's novel.
 &HT;    Also upcoming (Nov. 6) is ``Jack Frost,'' with Michael Keaton as
a musician who dies in a Christmas car crash and comes back to life
... as a snowman. ``He's a funny, hip guy,'' says Keaton, ``who's
been transferred to a new body and finds cool things to do with
it.'' (That's cool as in snow, presumably). Keaton stepped into
this role after George Clooney, who took over from Keaton as
Batman, dropped out.
 &HT;    Earlier this year Nicholas Cage stepped out of the afterlife in
``City of Angels,'' as the angelic being who falls in love with
surgeon Meg Ryan and decides he wants to enjoy earthly joys with
her. He makes it back in the land of living _ just as Meg
unfortunately exits. The weepy romance was quite a hit among teens.
 &HT;    Woody Allen, for whom a preoccupation with dying is nothing new,
this past year gave us ``Deconstructing Harry,'' which included his
rather hilarious descent by elevator into hell, accompanied by Old
Nick himself, played by Billy Crystal.
 &HT;    Of course, Hollywood long ago learned that movies about dying
can be very profitable. Films like ``Ordinary People'' (1980),
``Terms of Endearment'' (1983) and ``Philadelphia'' (1993) all told
stories in which key characters died.
 &HT;    In the same vein, Meryl Streep plays a mother dying of cancer in
``One True Thing,'' based on Anna Quindlan's l995 novel. The
performance will certainly earn Streep another Oscar nomination for
best actress.
 &HT;    In the tearjerker ``Stepmom'' (opening in December), Susan
Sarandon is a wife and mother who discovers she's dying and
reluctantly coaches her ex's new wife Julia Roberts to step into
her shoes.
 &HT;    And in ``The Theory of Flight'' (opening, believe it or not, on
Christmas Day) Helena Bonham Carter is dying of a neurological
disease and must use a wheelchair. She wants to lose her virginity
before she dies _ and asks Kenneth Branagh to help her achieve her
goal. (This is the couple's first on screen pairing since their
offscreen romance went public.)
 &HT;    In ``Patch Adams,'' Robin Williams is back as a doctor who tries
to treat his terminally ill patients with humor, ``looking at death
lightheartedly,'' as the actor puts it. In l999 Williams will show
up in ``Jakob The Liar,'' this time a cheery story about death and
the Warsaw ghetto. ``Yeah--that was a nice double bill,'' he muses,
``to go from 'Dreams' to 'Jakob the Liar.'''
 &HT;    How are we expected to take all this dwelling on the dark side
without running from the theater in panic? Meryl Streep for one
thinks the answer is perfectly natural. ``We need to feel something
when we go to movies,'' she says. ``We need to cry ... It's OK.''
 &HT;    She cites ``Titanic'' as the ideal death movie. ``Leonardo
DiCaprio goes down in the depths and the kids cry and they put down
their money to go again and again.''
 c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.)  
