 CLUTTER INTO CASH  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this
week's LifeBeat lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By JULIE BAWDEN DAVIS 
 c.1998 JULIE BAWDEN DAVIS 
 World Rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drive down most residential streets on a Saturday morning and
you're likely to see perfectly ordinary people hawking lava lamps,
end tables, bicycles and books.
</P>
<P>
   Done well, a garage sale can rack up $500 to $1,300 in profits
over a weekend and just about anything can sell, says Peggy
Hitchcock of Lantana, Fla., author of ``The Garage Sale Handbook''
(Pilot Books, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman who held a garage sale in her upscale neighborhood
advertised a blue toilet,'' says Hitchcock. ``People came just to
see that blue toilet and someone bought it right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Much more than the unusual changes hands at garage sales,
though, says Hitchcock. ``Approach having a garage sale like you
would any other business transaction and you will be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The secrets to a profitable garage sale are simple, but
critical, says Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   First have enough merchandise to offer; at least 100 items are
needed to make a sale worthwhile, as about half of them will only
be worth $1 or less. If you don't have enough items on your own,
talk to friends and neighbors to see if they will donate things or
at least give them to you on consignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take some time cleaning items up and you'll easily double your
sales,'' says Hitchcock. ``No one wants to buy a mixer with pancake
batter on the side no matter how well it's priced.''
</P>
<P>
   Says 30-year veteran garage-saler, Yvonne Ray of Santa Ana,
Calif.: ``If I walk up to a garage sale and there's clothes laying
all over the ground, mud caked on the bicycles and dust on the
dishes, I just leave. Things need to be neat and clean.'' At her
most recent sale she earned over $700, not including the sale of a
car.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being clean, things should be well displayed. ``No one
wants to stoop down and rifle through boxes of junk,'' says
Hitchcock. ``Borrow card tables so that you can get things up off
the ground, or get sturdy boxes from the grocery store, which can
be taped together to create disposable tables. Don't dump clothes
in a box. Rig up a clothesline. The idea is to make things easy to
view.''
</P>
<P>
   Also provide shoppers with a way to test mechanical merchandise,
says Richard Harris, co-owner of Harris &AMP; Small Antiques in Mission
Viejo, Calif., who has gone garage-saling just about every weekend
for the last 20 years. He also recently held a garage sale where he
sold all but two items and made $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Run an extension cord out to the driveway so that people can
test things like radios and kitchen appliances, or provide
batteries,'' he says. ``Just telling people something works isn't
very effective, because they will tend to doubt you.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most challenging aspects of setting up a garage sale
is pricing the items. Although some people skip this step, most
experts advise against it. ``Many shoppers won't ask how much
something is,'' says Hitchcock. ``They'll just assume it's too
expensive and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray agrees. ``I won't buy anything unless it's marked, because I
don't like the fact that people could decide how much I should pay
by the car I'm driving or what I'm wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   When pricing items, remember your customers are thrifty souls in
search of the ultimate deal. ``The whole purpose of going to garage
sales is to find really great deals, and it can be addicting,''
says Ray. ``This past summer I wanted an iced tea maker, but I
didn't want to pay full price, so I looked at garage sales and
found one for $5.00, but I didn't stop there. I found two more at
other garages sales for the same price and ending up buying them
all and giving two away.''
</P>
<P>
   When pricing merchandise, Hitchcock suggests employing the 20
percent rule. ``If you bought an item like an electric knife for
$15 and it's brand new and never been used, then 20 percent of $15
is $3, she says. ``If it's still in the cellophane, you may be able
to go to $5, and if it's used, but still clean and in good shape,
then it will probably sell for $2. If you're not sure on some
items, look up what they would cost new in a catalogue.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20 percent rule doesn't work for all items, including
clothing, which should be priced very low, often for 50 cents to $1
or $2 a piece.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, too, that garage-salers like to bargain. ``If you want
$5 for something, ask $7,'' says Harris. ``Virtually no one will
want to give you what you ask, because they want to believe that
they're getting a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   When you price items, also think about how far you're willing to
go down in price, says Hitchcock. ``If someone says something isn't
worth $2 and they offer 25 cents, decide if you'll accept that,''
she says. ``Sometimes I suggest telling customers to come back
later and if the item is still there, you'll sell it to them for
the reduced price.''
</P>
<P>
   For a more expensive item, offer to take the person's number and
call if it doesn't sell.
</P>
<P>
   In order to attract a crowd to your sale, it's a good idea to
advertise in the local newspaper, says Hitchcock. When you
advertise, highlight items that people might find of interest such
as children's toys, baby items, kitchen appliances, furniture and
unusual, hard-to-find things. You can also advertise for free at
grocery stores. When possible, instead of using index cards, make
your own flier announcing the sale. If you must use cards, opt for
neon colored ones rather than white.
</P>
<P>
   Good signs placed within a mile radius of your home can also
make or break a garage sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better the sign, the easier it is to find the sale and the
more intrigued your customers will be,'' says Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Take some time making the signs, because they will serve as the
first impression you give potential customers. A brightly colored,
easy-to-read sign made on poster board with black magic marker is
much more impressive than a scribbled scrap of cardboard or a paper
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Rise early the day of the sale because serious garage-salers
will be out as soon as it's light, and the first two hours is when
you'll make most of your money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you say 8 a.m., people will pound on your door at 6,''
warns Harris. Also make sure there are at least two of you working,
so that one person can answer questions while the other collects
money. And have a lot of change on hand, because most people will
have $20 bills.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   (JULIE BAWDEN DAVIS is a free-lance writer based in Orange,
Calif.)
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT SELLS AT GARAGE SALES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those old knitting needles could be just what a veteran knitter
has been looking for. You'll be surprised at what people will snap
up, just remember that all items should be clean and in good shape.
Here's a short list of perennial favorites:
</P>
<P>
   _ Broken appliances (some shoppers will fix them, while others
</P>
<P>
   are looking for spare parts)
</P>
<P>
   _ Functional kitchen appliances
</P>
<P>
   _ Old radios and cameras
</P>
<P>
   _ Old diaries and pictures (intriguing to some shoppers, even if
</P>
<P>
   they don't know the people)
</P>
<P>
   _ Old books
</P>
<P>
   _ Craft items like yarn and knitting needles, hot glue guns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dishes, new and antique
</P>
<P>
   _ Children's toys
</P>
<P>
   _ Buttons
</P>
<P>
   _ Old plant pots
</P>
<P>
   _ Picture frames
</P>
<P>
   _ Well-priced furniture like beds, tables, chairs
</P>
<P>
   _ Old records
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
