<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1721 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEXUALITY-LIFEBEAT-NY     10-06 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXUALITY-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 HELPING YOUR KIDS COME TO TERMS WITH SEXUALITY  (This ``separate
buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By AVA L. SIEGLER 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kids and sex? You've got to be kidding, right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong! It takes a lot of years to develop a healthy attitude
about sex as well as a healthy sexual life. This process starts at
birth, so right from the beginning you need to help your child
build good feelings about the enjoyment he can get from his body.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we're not talking about sexual intercourse here. You
need a mature body (and, one hopes, a mature mind) to participate
in intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   But sexuality includes much more than just the sex act. It is
built upon all the kisses and caresses, sensuality and
satisfaction, and attachment and affection that you and your child
experience in your relationship with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see what's going on in your child's sexual development as
he matures, age by age.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Birth to 1 1/2 years &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Babies link pleasure with physical attention. All of the
sensitive physical attention you give to your little one (feeding
her, holding her, stroking her skin, washing her) helps her to
develop good feelings about her body and teaches her to associate
these good feelings with someone she loves.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that most of a baby's happiness and desire centers on
sucking, whether she is breast-fed or bottle-fed with formula.
(Many women report enjoyable sensual feelings when they
breast-feed. These feelings are completely normal and attest to the
fact that mothers and their children are connected through
pleasure.)
</P>
<P>
   Not all babies have an easy beginning. So don't be worried if
your little one is colicky and it takes some time for her
gastrointestinal system to settle down. As soon as she gets
comfortable, her pleasant feelings will grow and she'll begin to
make all of the right connections.
</P>
<P>
   And fathers, don't forget that by holding, caressing and
diapering your child you are strengthening her bond to you, as well
as your bond to her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1 1/2 to 3 years &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now he can use his hands to explore his own body and _ if he's
not given limits _ other people's bodies as well. Bottoms become
particularly fascinating to a toddler because toilet training is a
developmental goal and bottoms receive a lot of family attention.
</P>
<P>
   Kids this age are interested in all kinds of bodily functions.
Their explorations are a normal expression of their increased
intellectual curiosity and greater physical capabilities. So this
is the time to let your child know that he's in control of his body
and that it's OK to explore it.
</P>
<P>
   But you also need to begin to discuss some appropriate limits.
(``We call them private parts because we show and touch them only
when we're in private.'')
</P>
<P>
   It's important, also, to be matter-of- fact about the bodily
sensations you observe your toddler enjoying. (``I know it feels
good, but you can't touch yourself at the dinner table. That is
something you can do when you're alone.'')
</P>
<P>
   Too shocked or severe a reaction (``Stop it right now!'')
interferes with your toddler's ability to feel good about his body
and makes sexuality ``bad'' and guilt-ridden. On the other hand,
too indulgent a response or no response at all doesn't help your
child learn acceptable and civilized behavior.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3 to 6 years &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By now, your child has a fairly good idea about the anatomical
distinction between girls' and boys' bodies. Children from 3 to 6
years old often try to supplement their knowledge with mutual sex
play, so keep your eye on kids who disappear into a bathroom or
closet together on play-dates since they may be playing doctor.
</P>
<P>
   While this play is normal, children are frequently interested in
inserting a pencil or crayon into a vagina or rectum and can hurt
each other with their prying and poking.
</P>
<P>
   It's rarely the case that this kind of sex play is fully
consensual. Rather, one bolder, more curious or more aggressive
child often initiates the activity and/or dominates the other child
_ a potentially anxiety-producing scenario. If you catch your kids
``in the act,'' set a firm but matter-of-fact limit (``You can
pretend to be a doctor, but actually touching each others' private
parts is not allowed'').
</P>
<P>
   Preschoolers also become aware now that there is a certain kind
of relationship between their parents from which they are excluded,
and they are very curious about what this relationship entails.
Most children will raise questions on their own, but if your child
hasn't begun asking by age 7, a book can help you jump-start a
conversation. Try ``How Babies Are Made'' by Andrew Andry and
Steven Schepp (Little, Brown, 1984).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6 to 10 years &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the age of pals and best friends, a stage that serves as
a precursor to the more intimate puppylove relationships of the
preteen years and to the passions of adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes girls seem to become more ``girly'' and boys more
``boyish'' at this stage, as each gender begins to learn more about
social expectations and to adopt social roles.
</P>
<P>
   Identification with family members becomes more important, and
girls and boys this age are likely to show increased interest in
your work, your life when you were a child, and your family's
history. This helps them to develop a firmer sense of their own
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Because some anxieties are already beginning to build around
sexuality, sexual topics may inspire a lot of silliness, innuendo,
or even vulgarity from children this age. This can be unpleasant,
but it's pretty normal. Some 8- to 10-year-old girls pointedly
reject boys (``We hate boys'') and vice versa (``Girls are
stupid''), but other boys and girls seem to be comfortable with
opposite-sex friendships.
</P>
<P>
   Now is a good time to expand your discussion of sexual basics
with your child because he's likely to have been exposed through
friends and the media to information be doesn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AVA L. SIEGLER is a child psuchologist based in New York
City. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
