<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NAVAJO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLERMAN MYSTERY DOESN'T MATCH INTENSITY OF ORIGINAL NAVAJO
TALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
THE FIRST EAGLE 
Tony Hillerman (HarperCollins, $25) 
 
 By BETTY REID  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The First Eagle,'' Tony Hillerman's latest mystery novel,
doesn't fly.
</P>
<P>
   Fatal fleas, eagle poaching, a missing woman and murder are
blended in the mystery story that stretches from a place called
Yells Back Butte near Black Mesa, to Kaibeto, Cedar Ridge and
Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   They're familiar sites throughout the land where my relatives
have herded sheep for decades. I wanted to like this story.
</P>
<P>
   And the story line is interesting at times. Jim Chee, now acting
lieutenant with the Tuba City Police Department, seems to have a
perfect murder case. He nabs a Hopi eagle poacher hunched over the
body of a tribal police officer. The poacher's blood is mixed with
the officer's.
</P>
<P>
   The missing woman is Catherine Pollard, a ``flea catcher''
biologist with the Arizona Health Department who is collecting
bubonic plague-carrying fleas from desert rodents. She vanishes in
the area where Chee arrested the Hopi.
</P>
<P>
   As with Hillerman's ``Skinwalkers,'' the book failed to grab me
from the start.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to read ``Skinwalkers'' on a cold winter Fort Defiance
night in the late 1980s, ready for a good scare. For traditional
Navajos, skinwalkers are terrible creatures bent on harm. His book
should have kept me awake, jumping at noises in the night.
</P>
<P>
   It failed to turn my legs to jelly or send tingly goose bumps
down my spine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Eagle'' similarly falls short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I stopped reading ``The First Eagle'' at first, finding
it a slow and pondering story without enough ``whodunit'' intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   It reminded me of when I was an adolescent living near the
western edge of the Navajo Reservation. As a young shepherd, I
dreaded herding sheep through endless gnarled twists and turns of
plunging rocky canyons and washes. By the time I chased my mother's
sheep and goats home, my stiff legs ached.
</P>
<P>
   It took me a month to finish ``The First Eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, I give credit to Hillerman for heightening public
awareness of the Navajo people during the past two decades. Many of
his novels portray a humane account of the ``Dine,'' the people,
who thrive on a remote landscape with awesome scenery, wash-boarded
dirt roads and sometimes blinding windstorms.
</P>
<P>
   And it's noble of Hillerman to dedicate ``The First Eagle'' to
seven fallen Navajo police officers.
</P>
<P>
   But the book jumps around so much you sometimes feel you're
riding on one of those reservation roads.
</P>
<P>
   As a writer raised on a dose of traditional Navajo religion
south of Cedar Ridge and west of Black Mesa, the dark side of
Navajo belief was etched into my brain. Much of that was eclipsed
by a modern education, yet I'm always curious about English
descriptions of my childhood fears about werewolves and
skinwalkers.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of those fears are fairly rare _ the works of cultural
anthropologists and Hillerman's novels _ and often fail to capture
the essence of our beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I'm a closet Stephen King fan, but when I read about my
childhood fears, I expect it to draw a ``Yiya!'' out of me.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The First Eagle,'' a reference is made to the sighting of a
skinwalker that glints like a flashbulb during the day. We find out
later that it is the glare off a spacesuitlike protective cover
that flea catchers wear in the field.
</P>
<P>
   No ``Yiya'' there.
</P>
<P>
   I compare that to the bone-chilling stories from my aunt and
mother, who still tend sheep on the reservation.
</P>
<P>
   When they talk about skinwalkers in our native Navajo language,
we don't wait for the end before hunting down a medicine man to
restore harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Language, I believe, is key to writing bone-chilling Navajo
skinwalker stories. Hillerman just does not capture it in his books
and I'm not sure if any writer ever will. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Betty Reid can be reached at betty.reid(at)pni.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1782 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      10-06 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; AN AMERICAN KILLING &QL; 
 &UR; Mary-Ann Tirone Smith (Holt, $23)
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton and kinky sex co-exist in the first chapter of this
suspense novel, but they have nothing more in common than the man
who knew them both: womanizing Congressman Owen Allen Hall, who has
turned up dead under embarrassing circumstances. At his memorial
service, we meet Hall's former lover and our narrator, Denise
Burke, who is a bestselling true-crime writer and wife of one of
Clinton's close advisers. The book works backward from there, with
Denise telling the story of her relationship with Hall, which
begins when he asks her to look into a triple murder in his Rhode
Island hometown. The man convicted of the killings might be
innocent, Hall tells her, and Denise is off on an investigation
that will transform the image of a harmonious, racially diverse
community into one of violence, corruption and deceit. The plot is
sometimes too involved, and Denise has a tendency to be slow on the
uptake. But her narration is witty and appealing enough to carry
the day if Smith does the obvious and brings her back for a
sequel. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; CINDERELLA &AMP; COMPANY &QL; 
 &UR; Manuela Hoelterhoff (Knopf, $25)
</P>
<P>
   This is not a book of fiction, but it does have characters. One
is the sultry-eyed superstar you see on the cover. Another is the
author, whose unsparing, wickedly funny voice is a presence in
itself, delectable and not altogether unkind. She harbors, in fact,
a considerable amount of sympathy for the young opera singers of
today, who are judged as much for their looks and personality as
for the notes they sing. Cecilia Bartoli allowed Hoelterhoff to
follow her around through two seasons between ``Cenerentola'' in
Houston in 1995 and ``Cenerentola'' at the Metropolitan Opera in
1997. The result is this flamboyant behind-the-scenes look at a
competitive world of big money, big marketing, big egos and big
pressure that is often difficult for young singers to handle.
Hoelterhoff is irreverent about most of it _ she even includes the
``typical diva diet,'' which begins in the morning with half a
grapefruit and builds crescendolike to an entire Sara Lee
cheesecake eaten directly from the freezer at night. It's great fun
and would have been even better if it had an index so we'd have a
direct route to the gossip. Hoelterhoff won a Pulitzer Prize for
her opera reviews for the ``Wall Street Journal.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE POISONWOOD BIBLE &QL; 
 &UR; Barbara Kingsolver (HarperFlamingo, $26)
</P>
<P>
   Kingsolver's fans will be astonished by this, her biggest and
most ambitious novel, one that takes us far from the Southwestern
settings of her other books (``Pigs in Heaven,'' ``Animal Dreams'')
into the political and moral ramifications of the American presence
on another continent. It is 1959, and evangelical Baptist Nathan
Price has taken his family _ his wife and four daughters ranging
from 5 to 15 _ from their home in Georgia to the African Congo,
where they serve as missionaries in a village that does not welcome
their coming. Nathan's bold and irrational act is set against
political upheaval in the Congo, but he is so driven by
righteousness that he will not back down. His wife and daughters
have the grace to be less sure of what they've done, and it is
their voices that tell the story. Kingsolver does a masterful job
of moving from one daughter to another, establishing in their
narrations their differing temperaments, rivalries and reactions to
the village and its culture. But the best chapters belong to the
mother, Orleanna, who is vulnerable in her love for her daughters
and bears grief with breathtaking grace. As are all of Kingsolver's
novels, this one is thick with social conscience, perhaps too much
so in a few chapters when her characters seem like temporary props
in a retelling of the Congo's tragedy. Kingsolver would never
apologize for this, but it is not her strength. That lies in her
lovely renderings of universal experiences _ the daunting duties of
a mother to her children, the charged ambivalence between one
sibling and another, the faltering esteem between a husband and a
wife. It's not new territory for Kingsolver, but nowhere has she
portrayed it so well. She will read and discuss her book at 2 p.m.
Oct. 25 at Changing Hands Bookstore, 6430 S. McClintock Drive,
Tempe. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE NOT SO BIG HOUSE &QL; 
 &UR; Sarah Susanka (Taunton, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Susanka, an architect based in Minnesota, is here with a
soothing and persuasive message: Your house does not have to be big
to make you happy. It is possible, in fact, to be miserable in a
big house if it is full of wasted space and does not suit your
lifestyle. Spend your money on quality, not quantity, she says, and
build a home that accommodates your habits. How long has it been
since you used your formal dining room? Do you live in your living
room or in your family room? Why spend so much square footage on
rooms that see so little use? She suggests making a list of the
rooms in your house, their size and what happens in each, and then
ranking them from most-used to least-used. You'll probably find
many of the biggest rooms at the end of the list. And here's a
shocking suggestion: Cut back on bathrooms. They're expensive,
given the amount of time we spend in them each day. All of this, of
course, is especially appealing because Susanka is arguing that
less _ if it's well considered _ is more. And easier on the budget
too. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Correspondent Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1788 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOGA-HNS &LR;      10-06 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOGA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TAKES SOME EFFORT TO MAKE YOGA WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Relaxing isn't as easy as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Try sitting still for 10 minutes and emptying your mind. It's
tough. You'll find yourself twitching, itching and looking at the
clock.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I did two weeks ago at my first yoga class. I was so
impatient during the meditation that my instructor had to signal me
to lie down again. ``It does get easier,'' Lenore Reinhard said.
</P>
<P>
   She's been practicing yoga for five years and knows how
difficult it is to let go of stress and schedules in a busy life.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an adult, it takes so long to quiet the mind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yoga has long had the reputation of being a spiritual exercise,
a path to enlightenment, serenity and bliss.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's no longer so esoteric. Browse through the magazines
in the supermarket line or turn on ``The Rosie O'Donnell Show'' and
you'll see yoga being touted as an age-old solution to modern-day
problems and the key to good health and fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Even Oprah has demonstrated the postures of yoga on her show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It speaks to a need that has been overlooked,'' said Dr.
Jonathan Holt, an Albany psychiatrist who has been practicing yoga
for almost 25 years. ``If it's done correctly, it helps de-stress
the body and has beneficial effects on practically all the
systems.''
</P>
<P>
   He recommends it to his patients as part of a stress management
program.
</P>
<P>
   Stress has been linked to a host of health problems, including
heart attacks, high blood pressure and illness.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that yoga, with its focus on breathing and
meditation, does have immediate, measurable health benefits, such
as lowering blood pressure, heart rate and metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   The physical postures also are helpful in promoting strength and
endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yoga will give good flexibility, toning and make you feel very
rejuvenated,'' said Dr. Kumuda Reddy, a former anesthesiologist at
Albany Medical College.
</P>
<P>
   On a cautionary note, she warns against forcing the body into
certain yoga postures. ``You should never push yourself,'' she
said. ``The important thing is to listen to the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Reddy practices Maharishi Ayur-Veda, a holistic approach to
health care that integrates yoga into a daily regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the union of mind, body and spirit,'' she said. ``There
is a peacefulness that grows as one does yoga on a daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the key.
</P>
<P>
   Yoga requires a commitment to the moment, not what you did
during the day or have to do when you finish.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike an aerobics class, you won't get the full health benefits
if you let yourself be distracted by the pressures of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to just simply be there and let it happen,'' Reddy
said.
</P>
<P>
   For many of us, that's easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a very stress-ridden society,'' said Mehlli Bhagalia,
who teaches yoga at the Ayurveda Yoga Institute in Schenectady,
N.Y. ``Very few people are able to uncomplicate their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoga, however, seems like a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use it almost daily,'' Reinhard, 55, said. ``I certainly can
see that added flexibility and the strength, and you do get the
tone and definition.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Reinhard believes yoga has given her an
effective way of handling stress. In tense moments, she breathes a
little deeper and always feels a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very calming,'' Reinhard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
