<HEADLINE>
VIAGRA CRAZE PROMPTS NEW INTEREST IN SEXUAL DYSFUNCTION IN WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ All the talk about Viagra and male impotence may
be overshadowing the emerging reality that sexual dysfunction in
women appears to be more widespread and just as treatable.
</P>
<P>
   Once chalked up to psychological problems or dismissed as an
unavoidable result of menopause, female sexual dysfunction is
getting increased attention from the medical establishment.
Researchers are finding that it often has a physical basis, and
drug companies are right behind them, developing therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Some treatments, such as the use of testosterone for menopausal
women, have been around for years and were discussed Monday at the
American Society for Reproductive Medicine meeting in San
Francisco. Others are in development, based on the recent
recognition that obstruction of blood flow to the pelvic area may
be the root of some women's lack of sexual arousal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main question used to be `Does it hurt?' and `Can you do
it?''' said Jennifer Berman, a sex therapist at the Women's Sexual
Health Clinic at Boston University Medical Center. ``Now it's `Are
you enjoying it?' and `Are you reaching orgasm?' We're at the dawn
of a new era in female sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   A large national survey in 1992 found a third of women
respondents lacked interest in sex. Newer figures compiled by Yale
University found that 60 percent of menopausal women were
dissatisfied with their sexual functioning. Especially distressed
were women who were accustomed to having active, satisfying sex
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Many women who opt for hormone replacement therapy during and
after menopause receive only the female sex hormone estrogen. But
menopausal women also suffer diminished production of androgens
(male sex hormones) such as testosterone, known to play a key role
in sexual desire. Androgens are not routinely included in hormone
replacement therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria A. Bachmann, chief of obstetrics and gynecology at the
Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital in New Brunswick, N.J.,
said many of her patients had not wanted to take testosterone
because they were worried about masculinizing effects and did not
think their bodies produced it in the first place. Many women do
not realize that they normally have twice as much testosterone as
estrogen in their bloodstream, although still significantly less
than what is found in men.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that women who received estrogen and
testosterone reported feeling much better sexually than those who
received only estrogen. And because the dosages are low _ just
enough to replace the normal amount of testosterone lost with
menopause _ side effects are virtually nonexistent, according to
Morrie Gelfan, professor of obstetrics and gynecology at McGill
University in Montreal. He has been using androgens like
testosterone with his menopausal patients for nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Testosterone also could be given to younger women who take birth
control pills or have other conditions leading to lower-than-normal
levels of the sex hormone, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other scientists are looking into whether Viagra, the
male impotence pill, might also help with female arousal problems.
It works by allowing more blood to flow to the genital area, but
has been tested only in men.
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies have shown a link between hardening of the
arteries in female animals and inhibited sexual arousal. And many
women who want help have the same profile as men who seek treatment
for impotence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symptoms increase with risk factors like cardiovascular
disease, diabetes, obesity, smoking _ just the same as men's,''
said Laura Berman, Jennifer Berman's sister and a urologist at the
Women's Sexual Health Clinic in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At the clinic, more than 200 volunteers have signed up for the
first clinical trials of Viagra in women, she said. Coming up are
trials of other similar drugs administered either under the tongue,
or via topical treatments to the vaginal area. All are being
developed by drug companies because they have begun to see a large
potential market, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a significant problem that affects the quality of life of
many women,'' Jennifer Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   Among young women with no history of sexual abuse or
identifiable physical problems, the chief complaint is an inability
to climax, or a prolonged time to climax, she said. For those
women, there isn't much that medicine can offer now, nor any
promising treatments on the horizon, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Female sexual dysfunction was once considered the province of
psychology and attracted few medical researchers. But it has
recently blossomed enough to justify the first international
medical meeting on the subject later this month in Boston, Jennifer
Berman said. And another group is convening a task force to begin
to develop medical standards for treating, measuring and evaluating
women with sexual dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medical profession is just now getting on board with
this,'' Laura Berman said. ``In many ways, it's all brand new.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
