<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT WOMAN, LOST IN THE PRIME OF HER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ever since a tearful colleague phoned to tell me
that Caroline Drewes was dead, I've been hearing her gorgeous voice
in my head and seeing the honest-to-God light of vitality that
always surrounded her.
</P>
<P>
   That sound and vision do not jibe with a woman who goes out into
the setting sun to walk her dog and gets struck and killed by a car
_ which is what happened to Caroline in San Francisco on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When she retired from the San Francisco Examiner in March 1992,
I wrote in Caroline's commemorative goodbye issue that she was
``quite simply, my idol.'' That declaration was based on several
aspects of her existence, not the least of which were her voice and
her light.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline's voice was pitched just low enough to be sexy,
intriguing and confidential, but not so low as to hint of too much
of anything _ whiskey, smoke-filled rooms, long nights, loud fights
or reckless living. Nothing about Caroline was ever excessive. As
I've replayed her voice in my head _ she seems always to be asking
a question that begins with my name _ I've heard music. Sensual yet
controlled music, precise but with a sway. Intelligent but earthy
music, unfailingly elegant but filled with desire.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Drewes had a voice like a tango.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt that voice enhanced her already-keen abilities as an
interviewer. In the half-century that Caroline made her living as a
newspaper reporter (she took seven years off in the '40s to marry
and start a family), she interviewed everybody from Joe DiMaggio to
the Dalai Lama. They all trusted her and told her their secrets.
Somehow I believe they sensed that she would take care of their
words, wouldn't think of using them for cheap gain. They felt she
wouldn't betray them, and she never did.
</P>
<P>
   We who were fortunate enough to call Caroline ``colleague'' talk
about the ``poetry'' of her prose. (That we even use a term like
poetry in describing the stories of a daily journalist says as much
as anything about the special regard in which we held her work.)
Rereading some of my favorite pieces now, I think that Caroline
sounds like E.M. Forster at his very best: Straightforward, but
rich, evocative and wise.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sample from a story about a woman she met while living
in Vienna, a woman ``of reserve and an occasional disarming candor,
who always seemed hovering on the brink of something.'' It is
vintage Caroline: ``One late afternoon as a melancholy blue dusk
began to dim the great baroque city, at that hour when confidences
come unbidden, she related this vignette while we shared a glass of
wine and a conversation that had turned to love affairs: those we
remember with pleasure and no regrets, no pain. And the other
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, about Caroline's light.
</P>
<P>
   Some might toss it off as ``beauty,'' for Caroline was, most
assuredly, a knockout. Until the day she died, she had the power to
do something every woman dreams of, whether we admit it or not: She
could walk into a room and people's heads would turn in her
direction. All people's heads.
</P>
<P>
   Usually draped in long, clingy, feminine fabrics of subdued
color or tasteful print, she swung oh-so-gracefully when she
walked. I cannot remember her in a pair of pants or all black. Her
posture was superb, like that of a queen or princess. Except
Caroline would be fun royalty, like Audrey Hepburn in ``Roman
Holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   I once had dinner with a man who'd known Caroline since her
college years. He still called her by her childhood nickname,
Pommie. A big man, inclined toward cigars, brandy and all-men's
clubs, he recounted an evening, nearly five decades past, in which
a bunch of friends had gone skinny dipping in Lake Tahoe. With a
mesmerized, far-off look in his eyes, the man described following _
from a respectful 10 yards _ a naked and wet Caroline up a hill in
the moonlight. The reverence in his voice was of the quality most
of us reserve for the great pyramids or Renaissance art.
</P>
<P>
   She and her light had that effect on people. They will go on
having that effect. Caroline's brand of inner and exterior beauty,
her sophistication and impeccable taste, her pure heart and
insatiable curiosity about people and places, her passion for life
and her fierce loyalty to family and friends, was an exclusive.
I've never met anybody like her and I expect I never will.
</P>
<P>
   As my colleague and I were trying via telephone to comprehend
the news of Caroline's death, I said: ``Do you realize that we are
talking about an 81-year-old woman? Everything we are saying is
what you say when someone who's 30 gets taken out. We are talking
as though Caroline was cut down in the prime of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is exactly what happened. That's why none of
us who knew her can believe it quite yet. Until I no longer can
hear her voice or see her light, I simply refuse to believe it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
