<SLUG> BC-CRICKET-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S MARYLEBONE ADMITS WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Tradition, under siege in tradition-bound England like
never before, took another one on the chin last week when the
venerable Marylebone Cricket Club lifted its 211-year-old ban
against women.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists thundered, sniffed and ordered another gin and
tonic, lamenting that yet another institution that defined a
time-honored vision of Englishness had been consumed by what
conservatives here call the madness of political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   Most ordinary people, meanwhile, thought it was about time women
got in, or wondered why in the world anyone would want to join a
cricket club in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Marylebone, however, is not just any cricket club. It is the
guardian of cricket heritage around the world. It is to cricket
what Wimbledon is to tennis, what Cooperstown is to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to let women in ends a seven-year battle of the
sexes that was played out against the backdrop of Marylebone's
pristine pitch at Lord's Cricket Ground. Even Prime Minister Tony
Blair, always anxious to hype his Cool Britannia image, got
involved, urging the club to change its old fogey ways.
</P>
<P>
   Two previous attempts to admit women failed to get a two-thirds
majority of the club's 17,500 members _ average age 57 _ needed to
amend club rules.
</P>
<P>
   Although Monday's motion to let women in carried easily with
almost 70 percent voting in favor, club president Colin
Ingleby-Mackenzie diplomatically described the debate that preceded
it as ``acrimonious.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was Ingleby-Mackenzie's swan song. He retired the day
after succeeding in his campaign to get women in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great day for MCC and for cricket generally,'' he said.
``It's going to create a better atmosphere in the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ingleby-Mackenzie isn't exactly a model of political
correctness. In applauding the decision to end the all-male
bastion, he said, ``Women are a very fine species.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingleby-Mackenzie said there will be one concession to the
traditionalists: a small male-only bar at the club.
</P>
<P>
   Rachael Heyhoe Flint, the former England women's captain,
triggered the controversy in 1991 when she applied for membership.
After the vote, Heyhoe Flint cried tears of joy. Others were crying
in their beer, or, more precisely, gin, which is the spirit of
choice at MCC.
</P>
<P>
   As reporters clamored around Heyhoe Flint, a middle-aged man
walked by and mumbled, ``Life as we know it is now over.''
</P>
<P>
   MCC got religion in a hurry. In 1991, only 33 percent voted to
let women in. By last February, it was up to 56 percent. Faced with
the loss of corporate sponsorship and lottery funds, the club spent
more than $100,000 to convince its members that it was time for a
change.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rea, the club's marketing director, candidly admitted,
``No sponsors want to be involved with an organization whose image
is elitist, fuddy-duddy and old-fartish.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of history being made, the victory seemed a
rather hollow one. While as many as 10 honorary women members will
be admitted over the next few months, and up to 60 female
cricketeers let in over the next few years, the rest will have to
get on the waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   The average wait: 18 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
