<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODBYE-MIZRAHI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISAAC MIZRAHI SHUTS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     (-----They also have information on how to subscribe to ``HIGH
STYLE AND MORE,'' a complete lifestyle and entertainment package
composed of stories _ with accompanying B&AMP;W and color art _ from
numerous publications issued by Fairchild Publications.-----) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: One B&AMP;W photo of Isaac Mizrahi with supermodel Shalom
Harlow is available.)  
 &HT;    
 By MILES SOCHA with contributions from ANNE D'INNOCENZIO 
 c.1998 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Isaac Mizrahi dropped a fashion bombshell on Oct. 1:
He said his 10-year-old business is closing.
</P>
<P>
   Mizrahi, a designer whose ebullient personality matched his
colorful clothing, said his partnership with Chanel was being
dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   Chanel, which has backed the business since 1992, is said to
have become increasingly impatient with its mounting losses.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no spring 1999 Isaac Mizrahi Collection, and the
Isaac Mizrahi &AMP; Co. headquarters on Wooster Street in SoHo soon
will go dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little shocking, but that's life,'' an
uncharacteristically rueful Mizrahi told WWD just hours after he
broke the news to about 55 employees. ``It's all for the best. It's
a good decision, as painful as it was to make. I'm taking a break
and observing what fate has to offer me now. I feel very excited
about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Mizrahi said it was a ``joint decision'' with Chanel to shut
down his fashion business. He said initially he plans to
concentrate on a multitude of ``promising'' entertainment ventures,
including film production and screenwriting. He's working on a
movie optioned by Dreamworks based on his comic book, ``The
Adventures of Sandee the Supermodel.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also writing the third draft of a screenplay entitled
``Wild About Harry'' that has been optioned by Barry Sonnenfeld and
Disney; Mizrahi said he might star in it. He did not say
definitively if or when he would get back into the fashion
business.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was searching for new financial backers to relaunch
a fashion business, he said he was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to this point, my first commitment has been to fashion, but
now I don't know,'' he said, sitting at the desk where he has done
dozens of interviews and where he was filmed for the 1995 movie
``Unzipped'' that catapulted him to fashion fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always have a great love of fashion,'' he said. ``I
will always be a fashion designer, but I don't know what form it's
going to take. I'm really at this crossroads, and I'm going to
allow fate to take over. I can't fight fate. It's been the driving
force of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly as bewildered by his shocking announcement as the
fashion world, Mizrahi declined to predict what his future will
hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a psychic. I don't know what I'm going to come back
as,'' he said. ``I don't envision myself six months from now or six
years from now. I just do. I solve creative problems. Right now,
what I want to do has to be culturally sound, whatever I do next.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the shutdown comes less than nine months after Mizrahi
closed his two-year-old Isaac bridge line, a venture initially
heralded as an enormous growth opportunity for the brand.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, about 65 workers were laid off at Mizrahi's SoHo
headquarters and its warehouse in Secaucus, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Chanel said on Oct. 1 that it is withdrawing its financial
backing because the Mizrahi's business volume was not large enough
to warrant Chanel's stake, which is believed to be approximately 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dissolving the partnership,'' said Michael Rena,
executive vice president of Chanel Inc. ``The volume was not big
enough to make it interesting for us or him to continue. He doesn't
need us. He doesn't need backers to have the kind of
entrepreneurial business he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Chanel and Mizrahi declined to reveal Mizrahi's volume,
market sources said the business generated annual sales of roughly
$50 million before the Isaac bridge line was closed last year.
Isaac was believed to have accounted for less than half of the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Rena declined to say how much Chanel had invested in the Mizrahi
business in the last six years, but confirmed Chanel had ``lost
money'' on its overall investment.
</P>
<P>
   The Mizrahi business was profitable in the early years of the
partnership, he added, but it has lost money every year since the
launch of the bridge line in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Rena said the dissolution of the partnership, which also
involves several minority investors, will take several weeks to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the Isaac Mizrahi name is owned by the partnership,
but Rena said Chanel plans to divest itself of that property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not use his name,'' he said. ``I'm sure some
arrangement will be made so he's going to be able to use it. It's
all being sorted out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rena said Chanel had high hopes the Isaac bridge business would
pump up volume for the brand, but it did not achieve its goals.
</P>
<P>
   After Isaac was shut down, ``it was down to the collection line,
which is a fairly small business, and it didn't make sense for us
to go on,'' he added. ``It's really too small for a company like
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the designer said an Isaac Mizrahi fragrance
had been in development, but was stopped because Chanel did not
want to make the necessary investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't think the Isaac Mizrahi business was given a
fair shake,'' the source said. ``The clothes were great. The
personality was great. It's pitiful that one couldn't capitalize on
those assets and make it a viable company. The timing was not right
to support the company at a critical point.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Mizrahi's deepening interest in entertainment projects
was a distraction that irritated Chanel, Rena said the company
always understood Mizrahi had such leanings. ``They were part of
his mystique.''
</P>
<P>
   Mizrahi has been a darling of the media and the fashion press
ever since he burst onto the fashion scene as a precocious
26-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, he had been a student at Parsons, then worked at
Perry Ellis, Jeffrey Banks and Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   Famous for his theatrical, high-energy fashion shows and for
clothes as ebullient and colorful as his personality, Mizrahi
brought zing and glamour to fashion. His sense of humor and levity
was infectious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unzipped,'' a documentary, was probably the first fashion film
to become a mainstream hit, thanks to Mizrahi's razor-sharp wit and
campy humor.
</P>
<P>
   Mizrahi's interests in entertainment have intensified ever
since. He recently formed a new production company called Baby with
his friend and colleague Nina Santisi, who has been vice president
of public relations and advertising at his company since its
inception.
</P>
<P>
   Santisi was executive producer of _ and featured prominently in
_ ``Unzipped.''
</P>
<P>
   Mizrahi, who currently can be seen in the new Woody Allen film
``Celebrity,'' said on Oct. 1 that he has missed opportunities in
the entertainment field because of his commitments to the fashion
house. He said these included starring roles in motion pictures,
but declined to name them. He said he had been offered a cameo
appearance ``in a movie that has since become a major hit. It had
actresses I really would have loved to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mizrahi said he had to pass because the movie would have
required a commitment of three weeks to three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm just so open to any kind of offers,'' he said. ``As I
see my life, I can't imagine what it would have been like not to do
these projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was becoming tired of fashion, Mizrahi said he has
been ``more and more in love with it'' lately. ``The ironic thing
is, it was really working. This fall and this past spring,
everything was really working and really selling well. It's a
roller coaster of a business. Sometimes it stinks; sometimes it's
great. This past year has been a red-letter year.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did hint at some frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion is a very funny thing, because it has so much to do
with sales. In fact, it's a greater art form. It hits you right in
the face with the moment. I feel like it's influencing art so much.
I don't think you could have had Jeff Koons in the Fifties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now art is supposed to be so much about a reflection. Before
it was a prediction. Now fashion is a prediction, and art is a
reflection. That's a bold thing to say, but it's very, very true.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Rector, president of Isaac Mizrahi, said he would continue
to be employed by Mizrahi and Chanel to help wind down the
business. He said he and a small team of employees would remain
during the transition period.
</P>
<P>
   At present, Mizrahi has five licensing partners: Eyeota for
eyewear, FJ Benjamin Holdings Ltd. for handbags and leather
accessories, Lazare Kaplan for fine jewelry, Fairbrooke Enterprises
for coats and GFW Footwear for shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in conversations with the licensees regarding the
future of those businesses, and those plans will be announced when
they're finalized,'' Rector said.
</P>
<P>
   Retail executives said they were shocked at Mizrahi's news. For
the most part, buyers reported, the signature collection was doing
well.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, pointed out Mizrahi's creative designs might
have been a little too out of sync with what consumers really
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am totally surprised,'' said Kal Ruttenstein, senior vice
president of fashion direction at Bloomingdale's, noting the store
had just brought back the label for fall at its flagship, after a
hiatus of a few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a small parting of ways,'' he explained. ``A couple of
seasons ago, we moved the location, but it wasn't working. We
decided that until we came up with the right location, we would
take a little breather.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall, Bloomingdale's expanded Mizrahi's real estate to 700
square feet from 500 square feet, and moved it to a more visible
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Ruttenstein said the Mizrahi collection was doing well this
season, particularly the camel group of peajackets, long skirts and
cashmere sweaters. He added that Mizrahi's bridge label, which
closed last year, had done just ``OK.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a big mover and shaker in the industry,'' Ruttenstein
said. ``He brought back a fresh insouciance and a fresh, casual
elegance. He looked back to the movie stars, but he brought an
American contemporary feeling to the clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruttenstein said Bloomingdale's was the first store to buy
Mizrahi's collection when the designer started back in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember he had just left Perry Ellis, and he called me,''
he recalled. ``I went to see him. He did these velveteen powder
blue jump suits, and I immediately placed an order. We even
showcased the line in our windows. He was a big fan ever since. He
was one of the great showmen when it came to putting on a fashion
show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my lord, I can't believe it,'' said Joan Weinstein,
president of Chicago-based Ultimo, which carries the Mizrahi
merchandise in its three designer stores. ``I have to say that our
selection of (Mizrahi) has always done well,'' she added. ``We have
always had a consistent presence in the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Mizrahi's bestsellers this season have been sleeveless
cashmere pastel sweaters with scarves to match, inverted
front-pleated skirts and midcalf skirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a fabulous person,'' Weinstein said.``He used to make
personal appearances at the store about twice a year. Everyone
loved him. He stopped doing it last year.'' She added, ``Knowing
Isaac, he'll bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am totally shocked,'' said Joseph Boitano, executive vice
president at Bergdorf Goodman, which had sold the collection since
Mizrahi came on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The store devoted a 400-square-foot area to it. Boitano admitted
the store had some problems with the Isaac bridge line, but the
signature collection has done well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always had a nice business,'' he said. ``He had a great
following in the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergdorf Goodman has done especially well with Mizrahi's simple
short cocktail dresses this season. But one buyer from a designer
boutique, who wanted to remain anonymous, said her Mizrahi business
has been difficult in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did really well, but then business got tough,'' she said.
``I think what happened was he did what he wanted, and the
consumers just didn't get it. That was the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Another buyer, who also did not want to be named, said he had to
drop the line last year after poor sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very creative and had such a great personality,'' he
said. ``But his collection was too outside the box for our
consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Isaac danced to the beat of his own drummer,'' said Sherry
Cassin, executive fashion director at the Doneger Group, a buying
office here. ``He was clearly not for the masses. He was very
special and did his own thing. He never wanted to sell out to mass
commercialism, but that, I guess, may have not been a good
long-term decision in the end.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
