<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' EXAM DAY IS COMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big dog is coming Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Chiefs are five days away, but it is not too
early to say this. So let's say it again.
</P>
<P>
   The big dog is coming.
</P>
<P>
   There are certain games by which a team and a season are
measured in the NFL. The first has already come and gone for the
Patriots. It was Opening Day in Denver and it did not go well. Not
even as well as the final score (Broncos, 27-21) might lead you to
think.
</P>
<P>
   But that is history, as is Sunday's rather bizarre but oddly
impressive 30-27 victory over the previously undefeated New Orleans
Saints at the Superdome. Both are on the scrap heap and of no use
to the Patriots this morning or, more importantly, Sunday
afternoon, because a big dog is coming, and if you can't run with
the big dogs, then lie on the porch.
</P>
<P>
   That is the choice the Patriots face this week. Who are they
really? Are they elite or not yet complete? Are they among the top
four teams in the AFC or are they back in the pack, as they were a
year ago and proved it about this time of the season with losses to
Denver and Green Bay?
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots think they know the answer, and if they are
correct, the Chiefs are in trouble. But knowing the answer and
giving the right answer when your name is called are two different
things, as no talented team has proven more often than the Patriots
the past few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Drew Bledsoe has said quite rightly that his team
cannot consider itself among the elite until it beats the Denvers,
Green Bays, and yes, Kansas Citys. That is something these Patriots
have seldom done.
</P>
<P>
   So this is another chance to make a statement, because the team
that is coming to Foxborough is 4-1 and elite but also incomplete
itself. It has a defense that can squeeze the life out of your
offense and the breath out of your quarterback because it loves to
throw the latter on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, in the kind of rainstorm Noah must have been
anticipating, the Chiefs shut down Seattle's running game, limiting
Ricky Watters to 59 yards on 22 carries and forcing him to fumble
twice in the sloppy conditions. They also sacked the quarterback
four times.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, theirs is a defense that can do great damage to an
opponent and it will come after Bledsoe with one of the best rushes
in the league. It will come after him with a defense that has
allowed an average of only 128.8 passing yards and 12.6 points a
game. In other words, it will make life difficult not only on New
England's offense but also on its defense because that defense must
match play-for-play one of the soundest in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   Most critical is that while the Chiefs' defense is solid across
the board, the Patriots' remains flawed. Defensive coordinator
Steve Sidwell has done a masterful job the past two seasons of
disguising a glaring hole in his secondary, and all the talk about
the improvement of Chris Canty cannot mask the fact that if New
England's assortment of blitzes don't finish off the quarterback,
problems invaribly follow. Often big problems.
</P>
<P>
   Despite seven sacks against the Saints Sunday, New England's
rush got close without getting the quarterback far too often, and
when Danny Wuerffel escaped, he did serious damage. The Patriots
allowed a guy who is arm-challenged to pass for nearly 300 yards
and convert 9 of 18 third-down situations, including a
third-and-17, a third-and-14, a third-and-10, and a third-and-9.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the way an elite defense plays, and that is
certainly not all Canty's fault. But he is the cornerback teams are
aiming at, and all the mock flexing when he makes a sack cannot
alter that reality. Only tighter coverage can and this, it seems
clear, he cannot supply regardless of how many public pep talks
Pete Carroll aims in his direction.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints gashed New England several times on seam routes when
Canty trailed too far behind while the safeties were so concerned
with protecting deep that they didn't close down over the top,
leaving a huge gap in the middle of the defense. Hence tight end
Cam Cleeland ends up with eight catches and Andre Hastings with six
and an upset nearly ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City will surely try to exploit that, while Sidwell will
lecture on team defense and try to correct it. But no amount of
correction can help him if his gambling rushes don't finish off the
quarterback, because given reasonable time, guys like Andre Rison
and tight end Tony Gonzalez will do the same kind of damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rushed well and we crushed their run,'' said Sidwell,
putting the best face on things. ``Our problem was in coverage but
we also played well enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Saints that was true. It was not true against the
Broncos, however, as his defense was gashed for long receptions by
Ed McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have a powerful passing game, possibly an emerging
running game, and a ball-hawking defense that plays well together
and is scrappy. But they lack a game-breaking defender on which
opponents must concentrate. There is no Derrick Thomas here. No
Reggie White. No Deion Sanders. No John Randle. No Warren Sapp. No
Levon Kirkland.
</P>
<P>
   To survive without such a player makes a coach's life difficult
and a defense's precarious, especially when one glaring weakness
exists.
</P>
<P>
   Such a defense will be tested again Sunday. Sidwell's schemes
will be tested as well. Canty and the safeties will be tested most
of all. If their team is to run with the big dogs, they will have
to pass those tests because a lot of questions remain about these
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   They are the kind of questions that can be answered only in
games like this, when the big dogs are barking and you either bark
back or curl up on the porch and wait for them to pass by.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
