<HEADLINE>
INNS AT PEAK CAPACITY AS VISITORS HEAD NORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In Northern Vermont, where sugar maples, sumacs, birches, and
oaks are changing the lush green environs to scarlet, gold, violet,
and orange, La Toscana Country Inn in Stowe is booked solid until
late October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold out six months ago,'' said Tony DeVito, who owns the
small inn with his family. ``Foliage is our biggest time of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   He's had to turn away dozens of callers, some from as far away
as Italy, Germany, and England. And because of the big demand,
DeVito has to insist: pay upfront, no refunds, no cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they book I tell them it's not refundable,'' Devito said.
``It's feast or famine. Everybody wants the same 20 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout New England, where the variety of trees helps create
breathtaking scenes for a few precious weeks, many inns have had
their fall weekends booked for weeks, at a higher rate.
</P>
<P>
   And many innkeepers keep a strict &UR;  &LR; no-refund policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turn a lot of people away,'' said Cynthia Barber, the &UR;  &LR; owner
of the Smugglers' Notch Resort in Jeffersonville, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   She said sometimes callers want to pick the weekend where colors
are at 100 percent change, or ``peak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants peak and they will say, `Now when will that
be?' I give them a range. Sometimes they try to push you for a
date. One person said, `You haven't picked the date yet?'''
</P>
<P>
   Barber said she stresses to callers that the the foliage _
whether it be 30 percent or 80 percent at its peak, is beautiful
all season. And if it isn't peak in Jeffersonville, there's likely
an area not far away where you can see the colors at their peak.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, about 6.1 million people visited last year
during leaf-peeping season _ September, October, and November,
according to Wyndham Lewis, a spokesman for the state tourism
office.
</P>
<P>
   Boston hotels are also booked by those who make day trips up
north during the day and enjoy the city at night.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said that though the season started a little early _ with
oaks and hickory trees showing off red and purple tints _ the
season should extend throughout the next few weeks. Changes in the
leaves will start first in higher elevations and in northern parts
of the state, gradually changing in southern parts and on the Cape
and Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Hammerle, a housekeeper at the Birchwood Inn in Lenox, in
the Berkshires, said the leaves started to change colors a couple
of weeks earlier than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when the peak is going to be,'' she said. ``Our
Berkshire weather does what it wants.''
</P>
<P>
   In Northampton, where the rolling hills are still green, people
calling the The Autumn Inn are asking, ``When should I come?''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Pelis, the hotel's desk clerk, tells callers leaf peeping
is best around October and November, ``and, even then, it
depends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask when the peak season is, and we say we can't predict
that,'' Pelis said. ``We're not Mother Nature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
