<HEADLINE>
SPRINTER DREAMS OF OLYMPCI GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ She was talking with a common-cold accent. Her nasal
passages were feeling the kind of pressure Cheryl Taplin obviously
puts on herself.
</P>
<P>
   Taplin had just returned from the IAAF World Cup in
Johannesburg, South Africa. There, she captured first place in the
women's 400-meter relay, along with that annoying virus.
</P>
<P>
   The experience, though, was summed up with two letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' Taplin said, explaining her recent trip.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, that is exactly how Taplin portrayed her track career
last season. It was all right, nothing special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't run anything spectacular,'' Taplin said. ``I just
seemed to run well when I needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, timely hits are priceless. In basketball, timely
scores are astonishing. In the world of track and field, either you
are on time or you are not.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive Taplin if she is feeling a little off at the moment. Her
best time in the 100 meters this year is 11.15 seconds. She has run
22.79 in the 200. Those times in her premier events are below the
top 10 in the world, and Taplin is taking four weeks off to think
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can run a lot faster,'' said Taplin, a 1990 graduate of
Cleveland High School in Seattle. ``I've just got to put everything
together. I'm anxious to see what I'm going to be running next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Taplin expects vindication.
</P>
<P>
   She is a former gold-medal winner at the Goodwill Games and
track's World Cup. Taplin runs well enough to earn thousands of
dollars on the circuit and maintain Nike as her sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   However, Taplin will try hard to run better in 1999 than she did
in 1998 for one big reason: the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going to shoot for the 2000 Olympics, and so next season
will tell her a lot,'' said Donald Cufrie, Taplin's coach and
former 200 gold medalist in the 1972 Olympics. ``She has the
ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Taplin even walks into Azusa Pacific University _ a
southern California school where she trains in the offseason _ she
will have worked on the essentials. When she returned to Seattle
recently, Taplin did not bring any sweat suits or sprinter's garb.
She was attempting to re-group.
</P>
<P>
   Cufrie is helping Taplin to realize that running is more a test
of mental toughness than physical skill. Even though Taplin has
qualified for the finals of nearly every meet she has run the past
summer, her confidence has been shaky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going through a mental block. I was doubting myself,
which I had never done before,'' Taplin said. ``For some reason, I
was beating myself up before I ran a race. I had to put it behind
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Taplin said her ensuing workouts will be critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things she can add to her training,'' Cufrie
said. ``I am confident she will do what it takes. You never know
what can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Taplin has come a long way from when she won individual Class AA
state titles all four years at Cleveland and led the Eagles to the
team championship in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   She moved into high gear in college, helping Louisiana State to
an NCAA track and field championship in 1994. At LSU, Taplin was a
16-time All-American. Throughout her professional career, she has
ranked among the national leaders in the sprint events.
</P>
<P>
   Taplin has run with the world's best, including Marion Jones,
Gale Devers, Christie Gaines and Inga Miller _ her training
partner. Now, she believes, it is time to be placed among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I survived this year,'' Taplin said. ``I'm not going to put
too much pressure on myself, but I've got to mentally prepare.
(Next year) is a big year for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
