<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MUSEUMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON IS FULL OF GREAT LITTLE MUSEUMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For a quiet hour or so, for free and nearly alone, you
can pretend you're Frederick Law Olmsted, the famed landscape
architect who created New York's Central Park and Boston's Emerald
Necklace.
</P>
<P>
   You can sit in the rugged, gray and green sunken garden that he
built at his home in Brookline, or stand over the desk in his
office, which looks as if he had just gotten up, leaving a park
plan unrolled on the top, along with his drafting pens and an
ink-blotted cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Or instead of playing Olmsted, you could _ again, for free and
without the hint of a crowd _ wander through exhibits of
archeological artifacts, antique fire equipment, ship models,
historic scientific instruments, or New England antiquities _ each
time as if you were in your own personal museum.
</P>
<P>
   In and around Boston are some fine and often-crowded museums
that charge admission, including the Museum of Fine Arts, the
Museum of Science, the Fogg and Sackler museums at Harvard
University. But there are also dozens of interesting smaller
museums that cost nothing and are so underattended that visitors
often will find themselves alone, except for an unobtrusive guide.
</P>
<P>
   Among those worth a peek are the Com- &QC; 
 &UR; el0.5 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   monwealth Museum, the Boston Fire Museum, the gallery of the
Society for the Preservation of New England Antiquities, and
permanent collections at Harvard and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   The hidden treasure may be the Olmsted home and office on a
winding side street in Brookline, now a national historic site
owned and maintained _ cherished would not be too strong a word _
by the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday _ the Olmsted home is open to the public only
on Fridays, Saturdays, and Sundays _ Park Service Ranger C. Sue
Rigney led the morning's two visitors through the warren of rooms
where Olmsted and his landscape design firm drafted plans for
hundreds of parks and estates.
</P>
<P>
   Olmsted bought the old farmhouse in 1883 after he had been hired
to design the Emerald Necklace and immediately began adding rooms
in a somewhat haphazard fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The rustic feeling of the offices and workrooms, achieved by the
use of stained tongue-and-groove and ``washboard'' paneling, evokes
the natural-appearing landscapes that Olmsted and his firm were
creating.
</P>
<P>
   And surrounding the house is an Olmsted parkland on a small
scale. From a rugged sunken garden, a brief passage through a rock
garden leads onto a rolling lawn that suggests the spaciousness of
the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clearly loved this place,'' Rigney said.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service acquired the site, Rigney said, mainly to have
access to the hundreds of thousands of plans, drawings, and
photographs that constitute an irreplaceable resource for landscape
architects engaged in restoring Olmsted parklands.
</P>
<P>
   Weekdays, the site is open only for research. But Rigney said
the staff is always happy to pull out a plan for a park in a
visitor's hometown. ``We can almost always find a park or a
landscape that out-of-town visitors know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A more traditional museum _ but just as undervisited _ is the
Commonwealth Museum in the State Archives building, a granite
fortresslike building on Columbia Point in Dorchester standing
between the University of Massachusetts's Harbor Campus and the
John F. Kennedy Library.
</P>
<P>
   While the archives' major treasures _ including the royal
charter of Massachusetts Bay Colony and several Indian treaties _
are not on display, there is always an exhibit or two of historical
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the museum has an intriguing display of Big Dig
artifacts uncovered during construction of the new Central Artery.
Some came from a privy in the back lot of a late-17th-century house
on Cross Street in the North End. The house belonged to Katherine
Nanny Naylor, who supported herself as a seamstress after winning a
divorce _ rare for those days _ from an abusive husband. Thrown
into the privy _ and on display now _ were such items as a sewing
kit, pieces of fabric, and broken household utensils.
</P>
<P>
   The major exhibit, ``Toward a Better Life: Massachusetts Workers
and their Unions,'' chronicles the history of the labor movement in
the state, from the 1820s to the present, complete with the mockup
of a union hall, a mannequin dressed in a police uniform from the
time of the 1919 Boston Police strike, and a soundtrack of union
songs to accompany a video of workers on a picket line.
</P>
<P>
   Walking into the Boston Fire Museum on Congress Street downtown
takes a visitor into a working fire station when the firefighters
are out of sight upstairs in the dormitory, awaiting a call to
slide down the brass poles and jump onto the engines.
</P>
<P>
   The museum occupies a firehouse built in 1891 and home to two
engine companies until 1977. Behind the double overhead doors, two
deactivated engines are poised for a call that will never come
again for them. The cubicle where the station's dispatcher worked
stands as if he had just left it just for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is manned by knowledgeable _ and enthusiastic _
members of the Boston Sparks Association headed by Ted Gerber, a
fire buff since he served on a volunteer department while attending
the University of Massachusetts at Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked away in the basement of Harvard's Science Center is a
collection of historic scientific instruments. There is an
18th-century model of the solar system that curator William
Andrewes says is ``as beautiful in its design'' as it is
functional. But there is also a worn seat cushion, which was part
of an 1896 experiment in acoustical engineering conducted in
Harvard's Sanders Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   And along one of MIT's ``infinite corridors'' is a collection of
ship models, representing a small portion of the university's
extensive nautical collection, which also includes the plans and
designs of several thousand yachts and ships. Here, along with the
models of famed sailing ships like the Boston-built clipper Flying
Cloud and naval vessels from World War II, is the gleaming white
model of MIT alumnus William Koch's America3, which won the
America's Cup in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The tiniest of Boston's small and undervisited museums _ but as
interesting as any _ is the gallery operated by the Society for the
Preservation of New England Antiquities at its Bowdoin Square
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Through Oct. 9, an eclectic display shows samples of
18th-century wallpaper, photographs of a tennis match being played
in the 1880s on the grounds of a now-demolished mansion on
Dorchester's Bellevue Street, a Hoodsie lid with a picture of
actress Myrna Loy, and a 1945 Brownie uniform. Coming in November
will be an exhibit devoted to the region's shoe industry.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit area has been dubbed ``Waiting for a Gallery,''
reflecting the society's hopes that it will acquire a larger space
to house and display its collection of 100,000 objects and more
than a million documents, prints, and photographs that depict the
history and material culture of New England.
</P>
<P>
   There might even eventually be a small museum building, society
staffers hope _ but that probably wouldn't be free, or undervisited
either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
