<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-RELIEF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AID CREWS UNABLE TO SEND SUPPLIES TO DOMINICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ While many victims of Hurricane Georges in the
Dominican Republic live without shelter, wearing whatever was on
their backs when the storm struck, three sites in Massachusetts
fill with supplies collected by the local Dominican community _
medicines, canned goods, even 500 beds donated by a Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   But as of Monday, the piles of donations continued to rise, with
little immediate hope of reaching the hundreds of thousands of
victims in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   While organizers have gathered enough goods to fill more than a
dozen 45-foot-long containers, they've raised only $64,000. And the
donation of cargo space they had hoped would come from the US
government or a commercial airline have not materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, relief for hurricane victims in Puerto Rico speeds to
victims on federally funded planes, as mainland Americans rush to
help victims in the US territory President Clinton declared a
disaster area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very frustrated,'' said Carlos Veras, assistant to the
Dominican Consulate in Boston, and an organizer of the Dominican
relief effort. ``We're hoping to get the help of the US government,
which has already helped our country with relief equipment like
helicopters.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, only two containers of medicine and food have been
shipped by sea to the Dominican Republic from Massachusetts, thanks
to cargo space donated by a local shipping company. Several
containers at an Army base in Worcester wait for offical approval
before being flown to Santo Domingo. The rest of the goods wait in
a school in Lawrence and a warehouse in Boston's Hyde Park section.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, questions have been raised about the level of
organization among the Boston Dominican relief committee, as
community members grow increasingly frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all the merchandise, but we can't ship it,'' said
Maria Contreras, a committee member who has repeatedly questioned
Veras and the consulate about the delay. ``It's very painful for
us, because every time we talk to someone on the island, we know
the needs over there. And we have these things sitting here and
there's nothing we can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some volunteers, who asked that their names not be used, said
that they had been told by Veras's office that their donations had
been shipped when in fact they had not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say the consulate's office was not prepared,''
said Ramona Hernandez, a professor of Latin American studies at the
University of Massachusetts at Boston and author of several books
on Dominicans in America. ``Let's say they were caught up in the
tragedy and did not think about certain logistics instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Veras claimed relief efforts in New York City were having
similar problems, emphasizing the difference between Puerto Rican
and Dominican efforts. Organizers in New York, however, said they
have had no such problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard of any effort here that has had a hard time
shipping items,'' said Silvio Torres-Saillant, director of the
Dominican Studies Institute and City University of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sent seven containers, the size of a semi-truck,
already,'' added Gilsia Pujadas, human resources director of
Alianza Dominicana, one of several New York City agencies leading
relief efforts there. ``We'll be sending two more this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The apparent disparity between aid efforts for the Dominican
Republic and Puerto Rico may ultimately serve to highlight
longstanding tensions and resentments between the Latino ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the hurricane has brought the traditionally feuding
Dominicans and Puerto Ricans together in places such as New York
and Chicago, according to Torres-Saillant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have several big differences in Boston,'' he said. ``Here
in New York, you've had many different relief efforts, with many
non-governmental organizations involved. In Massachusetts, the
Dominican consulate has headed your efforts. No one from the
Dominican Republic trusts the government to get things done
efficiently....
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, here in New York you have Dominicans who have
acheived some level of economic and political power. In Boston
that's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York relief efforts were pushed through by assemblyman
Adriano Espaillat, the first Dominican American elected to the
state assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Massachusetts is home to the fourth-largest
Dominican-American population in the nation, Latinos in general
here have the highest poverty rates in the state.
</P>
<P>
   And Latinos in Massachusetts lack political clout. Veras said
his office has contacted several public officials, asking for their
assistance, but had gotten no reply yet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as Dominicans in Massachusetts argue among themselves
and with others, needs in the Dominican Republic remain accute,
said Maria del Carmen Luperon, an official with the Gordo de la
Semana Foundation in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need water,'' she said. ``We need medicine. We need food,
we need clothes, we need wheelchairs, walkers, we need beds. Here,
there is need for everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
