<HEADER>
A1832 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WVA-BIBLE-BOS &LR;      10-06 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WVA-BIBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITHFUL CONVERTED TO BIBLE CLASS FOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; UNION, W.Va. _ The Bible already had a place at James Monroe
High School. It nestled among the textbooks in Leah Comer's
backpack, available for comfort and guidance whenever the
pony-tailed senior had a spare moment.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't enough; Comer wanted her gilt-edged Bible to be
counted as one of those textbooks. So the preacher's daughter
rallied her fellow students in hope of joining a national trend
toward Bible-as-literature classes in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But when the county school board moved in August to make Comer's
dream a reality, it set off an unlikely revolt, in an unlikely
place, with unlikely players.
</P>
<P>
   Similar battles elsewhere have been marked by opposition from
big-city civil libertarians, First Amendment lawyers and committed
atheists. But here in this bucolic Appalachian town, the main
obstacles to teaching the Bible in public schools are some of the
Good Book's biggest boosters: four respected local clergy members
from three mainstream denominations.
</P>
<P>
   Among their chief concerns is the fear that teaching the Bible
as purely a literary gem _ severed, as constitutional practice
demands, from its full spiritual and religious context _ could
debase the meaning and power of its message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Scripture, in the wrong hands and read the wrong way, can
be used to justify slavery, male bigotry, all kinds of oppressive
acts,'' said the Rev. Charles Miller, a United Methodist minister
whose daughter attends the high school. ``And what happens if the
teacher is someone who sees the Bible as totally wrong? They might
be able to teach it as literature, but it wouldn't be the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, after having devoted their lives to spreading the Gospel,
the clergy members are hearing themselves being described by some
as ``agents of the devil'' and ``anti-Bible.'' One wonders if he
might lose his pulpit, and two others are concerned for their jobs
as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the broadest sense, their concerns are parallel to those of
ultra-Orthodox Jews who refuse to speak Hebrew in conversation,
saying it should be saved for prayer, and to some traditional
Catholics who prefer the Latin Mass to preserve the mystery of the
Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the clergy members say, they agree with
opponents who worry that a Bible class would unconstitutionally
promote one set of beliefs over others, isolating students of
different faiths and those with no faith. In this wellspring of
Christian Coalition strength, they fear that evangelical doctrine
will seep into classrooms _ the class probably would use the King
James Bible, the preferred text of fundamentalist Christians _ to
the exclusion of other Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   All those arguments are lost on Ed Pell, vice chairman of the
school board. Pell moved to create the class after reading a
student newspaper story about a survey by Comer that found
overwhelming student interest in a Bible-as-literature course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's well established that we can do this,'' said Pell, who
hopes the course can be offered as early as January. ``If you teach
it as history and literature, and you make it elective, it's not a
violation of the separation of church and state.''
</P>
<P>
   Pell is legally correct, but this is all a bit new for Monroe
County, a rural area with 12,000 residents, nearly all white and
Christian.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mountainous, beautiful county, tucked against the
Virginia border. Lacking coal, a rarity among West Virginia
counties, its economy is built on cattle, sheep and turkey farms;
its saltpeter mines served both sides during the Civil War.
Unemployment is low, and crime barely warrants counting.
</P>
<P>
   Though isolated, Monroe County is on the verge of joining an
accelerating number of school districts returning Bibles to their
classrooms, particularly in the South. No one keeps exact numbers,
but the National Council on Bible Curriculum in Public Schools
boasts that it has helped create classes in 26 states, involving
more than 75 school districts, said executive director Elizabeth
Ridenour.
</P>
<P>
   Some school districts hope it will be a salve, considering the
problem with school shootings nationwide. Others have sought a
return to the days when religion was the fourth ``R'' _ after
reading, writing and 'rithmetic.
</P>
<P>
   Although teacher-led prayer has been banned from public schools,
the Supreme Court welcomes the Bible, writing in 1963 that
``nothing we have said here indicates that ... study of the Bible
or of religion, when presented objectively as part of a secular
program of education, may not be effected consistently with the
First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick, however, is figuring out how to satisfy that
standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``A true Bible course that is constitutional and educational
would make sure that there are a number of different perspectives
on how to read the text,'' said Charles Haynes, senior First
Amendment scholar at the Freedom Forum in Arlington, Va. ``You can
teach Noah's ark, and should, but you'd have to say, according to
the liberal Protestant tradition, and the Roman Catholic tradition,
etc., this is how we understand the flood story.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the safest route is to focus on the Bible's literary
qualities. ``Biblical literacy is essential for becoming an
educated person. One can't read Lincoln or Washington or many other
American leaders without it,'' Haynes added.
</P>
<P>
   The Monroe County opponents recognize the literary merit, but
Miller and the others _ his wife, the Rev. Sharon Miller; Rev.
Mikel Pugh a Presbyterian; and Rev. Lynwood Wells, an Episcopalian
_ say the risks of misuse are too great. A student Bible club would
make more sense, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't like what's taught in a particular church, you
can go to a different church. But with one high school in the
county, there's nowhere else to go,'' said Pugh, who said he is
concerned about losing his job for speaking out against the class.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who retired last year but still serves as a fill-in, or
supply, priest, said he doubted it was possible to separate the
Bible's poetic qualities from the doctrine steeped in every line.
``You can't just say the words are beautiful. There is meaning
there, and it comes through. It needs to be interpreted through
faith,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The least strident is Sharon Miller, who said she sorely wants
students to know the gospel and wishes there was a way to reach
more of them. But, she said, it would be ``next to impossible'' to
find a teacher who could satisfy constitutional concerns about
keeping doctrine out of class.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Hansbarger, a school board member opposed to the class
who invited the ministers into the fray, said the effort is
misguided: ``Some people think putting in a Bible class will solve
all our discipline problems. That's not going to happen.'' But
Hansbarger is outnumbered; the four other board members favor the
class.
</P>
<P>
   Though they collectively pastor at 11 area churches, the
opponents are also a minority in a county with 70 or more active
churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bible should be taught anywhere, anytime, anyplace,'' said
the Rev. James C. Finley, pastor of Victory Pentecostal Church,
where Comer worships.
</P>
<P>
   As for the concerns of people with different beliefs, Finley is
blunt: ``I don't believe their doctrine, and I don't believe their
teaching. I don't care if theirs are taught. But I do believe our
Bible, our King James, should have a right to be taught in
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Comer, 17, says simply: ``I'm a Christian and I hate the fact
that the Bible is taken out of the schools. I thought if enough of
us could get together, we could get it back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the controversy has thus far been local _ confined mostly
to letters in an area newspaper, which editorialized against the
class _ the state chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union is
watching closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainstream religious leaders have been publicly silent but
privately supportive for a long time, so I am thrilled they have
decided to stand up against a dangerous incursion of religious
fanaticism into public life,'' said Hilary Chiz, executive director
of the West Virginia ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the class now rests with the school board and
Superintendent Lyn Guy, who supports the idea. She said she will
propose a curriculum by the end of the year, after studying a
neighboring county's 59-year-old Bible-in-schools program. If
Monroe County does go ahead, the cost _ estimated by Guy at just
$2,000 a year for one class daily _ would be paid by donations.
</P>
<P>
   As to why Monroe County has drawn opposition from ministers when
so many other districts have created Bible classes without fuss,
the superintendent said with a sigh: ``There's a long tradition and
history here of being quickly and vocally opposed. We're used to
it. I don't know if it's in the water, or what.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
