<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR'S CONNING OF THE JUDICIARY COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Kenneth Starr, rogue prosecutor, has now managed
to do to the House Judiciary Committee what he did to Attorney
General Janet Reno last January _ a classic con to avoid the
inspection of tainted evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months ago, Starr hoodwinked Reno with what we now know to
be at best spurious tape recordings into expanding his jurisdiction
to include a possible crime that, in fact, had not been committed,
on the basis of his probing of a similar possible crime that, in
fact, had also not been committed.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the sting was completed as Starr got the engine of
presidential impeachment _ just the third in our history _ running
on the basis of a ``referral'' and thousands of pages of grand jury
testimony and other documents, not one of which has been examined,
cross-examined, or otherwise subjected to anything remotely
resembling scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he seems to have told the committee things that are
demonstrably not true, especially about the infamous Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months ago, Starr conned the passive attorney general into
performing a rubber stamp role. Monday, he completed an astonishing
con that transformed the Judiciary Committee into a willing
transmission belt for Starr's highly argumentative submission.
</P>
<P>
   As of this morning, the committee has done nothing more than any
self-abusive citizen could have done over the last several weeks _
read a giant batch of material based on someone else's work.
</P>
<P>
   What both ends of the process have in common is Linda Tripp and
her tapes. Starr played a few snippets at the Justice Department in
January, he claims, not to get a soap opera about sex and lies
about sex going, but to launch a probe of a possibly imminent
effort to obstruct justice in Paula Jones's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   His alleged link was Monica Lewinsky's statements to her
presumed friend about Clinton confidant Vernon Jordan's effort to
get her to lie about her dalliances with the president in exchange
for a job in New York; and those taped snippets, Starr also
claimed, were ``similar'' to what he said was Jordan's involvement
in previous effort to find work for former Justice Department
higher-up and Clinton friend Webster Hubbell in alleged exchange
for his Whitewater silence.
</P>
<P>
   It was all, we now know, baloney. No evidence of any wrongdoing
has ever been presented about the Hubbell matter; Starr's
insinuations about Jordan in both instances turned out to be
unsupported smears, and so, therefore, even a perfunctory inquiry
by Reno would have given a thorough official reason to pause.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Henry Hyde's staff guy, David Schippers, put up a giant
smoke screen around his fellow prosecutor's conduct, essentially
rewriting the Starr referral's charges to make new-sounding
allegations (conspiracy, misprison of Lewinsky's felonies) that
have lower standards of proof and to make ``lying'' equally
culpable with ``perjury'' as an impeachable high crime or
misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   As Starr did, Schippers presented a pure prosecutor's brief that
consistently omitted or hid exculpatory testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, he ignored the patent untruths in Starr's referral to
the effect that his involvement in the Lewinsky case began with
Tripp's call to his office on Jan. 12 and a subsequent visit. But
from several sources, and most recently a detailed account last
weekend in The New York Times, there is information that
Tripp-Starr contacts began at least a week before that _ more than
enough time to prepare a strategy to snare the president in perjury
in his Paula Jones case deposition.
</P>
<P>
   And there is evidence that contact between Tripp and the Jones
camp went back at least another two months.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of an ordinary person, prepackaged evidence and
entrapment are real defenses and often get a case tossed out; in
this case, that would be a legitimate result even before we get to
questions of fact, credibility of witnesses, or whether certain
conduct comes near standards for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   That is why independent-minded Judiciary Committee Democrats
like Bill Delahunt of Massachusetts were opposed to the route
insisted upon by the GOP majority Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt, a veteran prosecutor himself, felt that to avoid being
a rubber stamp, his colleagues had to conduct at least a
preliminary investigation to see if Starr's referral was sufficient
for a full-blown inquiry _ in short, to see if probable cause
really exists.
</P>
<P>
   By not doing so, Delahunt said it had turned the independent
counsel statute into an automatic trigger and the Congress into a
rubber stamp.
</P>
<P>
   He was absolutely right, just as Janet Reno was turned into a
robot last January by Starr, and on the basis initially of the
same, tainted evidence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
