<HEADER>
A1838 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN07-COX     10-06 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The restroom watch
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have spent a lot of time hovering outside men's restrooms. No,
this isn't a confession. It's a fact of life for any mother of
small boys.
</P>
<P>
   When my sons were infants, I thought the day would never come
when they'd be able to go to the restroom by themselves when we
were out in public.
</P>
<P>
   The years of diaper changing at the mall and potty training take
their toll. Potty training, of course, merits its own column.
Several of them.
</P>
<P>
   I'll admit right up front, I bribed my toddlers with M&AMP;Ms. Every
time they successfully accomplished their mission, they got five
M&AMP;Ms and I got five handfuls. We all grew from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Once the children are potty trained, however, we moms still have
a grace period when they usually will concede to accompany us to
the women's restroom _ that is, unless they have older brothers who
promptly inform them they're going into a ``La-a-dies Bathroom!
Eeewww!''
</P>
<P>
   That usually elicits a wail of anguish from the younger brother,
although he has no idea why. It just seems to be the expected
response. The mother then has to resort to dragging her youngster
into the facility.
</P>
<P>
   This routine helps moms become expert at creating a scene. We
get so used to it, we no longer notice the outraged looks of
bystanders. You think you can do better, buster? Here, be my guest.
</P>
<P>
   The day does come, though, when it just doesn't seem appropriate
to take the little tyke into the women's restroom. Not that you
mind, but he certainly does. A lot. So, fearing we're about to do
permanent psychological damage, we take the plunge and begin
hovering.
</P>
<P>
   We do not, however, send our sons into this potential minefield
without detailed instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you go in there and find an empty stall. Be sure it's
empty. Do NOT crawl under the door. Make sure there's paper in
there if you have to do Number 2. Don't put anything else into the
potty. Give me that G.I. Joe. Flush when you're done. Give me that
other G.I. Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember to wash your hands. Don't talk to anybody. Don't look
at anybody. If anybody looks at you, scream for Mommy. Then come
RIGHT back out here. I'll be waiting right here. If you need me,
just holler. OK? ``
</P>
<P>
   Nearly overwhelmed by the responsibility suddenly cast upon him,
the little fellow manfully hitches his britches and ventures in.
</P>
<P>
   That's when we hover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you all right in there?'' we call in through the door.
</P>
<P>
   No answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you OK?'' we holler again.
</P>
<P>
   No answer.
</P>
<P>
   Passersby stare at us as we stand shouting into the doorway of
the men's bathroom. We glare back at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you finished yet?'' we call in.
</P>
<P>
   At just this moment, a burly man walks out the door. ``Yeah,
lady, I am. Happy?''
</P>
<P>
   Then comes that moment of truth when we can bear the anxiety no
longer. Do we cover our eyes, open the door just a crack and call
his name? Do we ask a male store clerk to go in and check on him?
The seconds drag on like hours.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, out walks the little guy, toilet paper stuck to his
shoe, the waist of his shorts folded twice over, his hands dripping
wet, and a big smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it Mommy, all by myself!''
</P>
<P>
   You smile encouragement even though you know otherwise. No, son,
you didn't. You had moment-by-moment verbal instructions. Never
mind that I was ready to call in the National Guard, not to mention
your platoon of G.I. Joes.
</P>
<P>
   We survived it, though. With any luck, it'll be another 30
minutes before you have to go again. Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for
the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald. She can be reached online at
VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-10-01-98 1212E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
