<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MELLENCAMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNREPENTANT ROOTS-ROCKER MELLENCAMP BACK TO BASICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' says John Mellencamp. ``People who love rock
'n' roll are kind of like smokers. It's a case of, `Hey, you guys
go smoke outside, will you? We don't want you in here.''' He has a
point, since rock 'n' roll has lost commercial ground to other
forms of popular music such as rap, techno, and pop in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock 'n' roll is just another music now,'' he adds with a
sigh. ``When we were kids, it was the music.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mellencamp, of course, it still is the music. He's back to
affirm that on his new album, ``John Mellencamp,'' which hits the
stores today. It's his first disc for Columbia Records after 20
years with PolyGram _ and it marks a return to hard-hitting,
guitar-dominated roots-rock, after a trendy, techno-dabbling side
trip on his last album, ``Mr. Happy-Go-Lucky,'' in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If you liked his popular '80s albums ``Scarecrow'' and ``The
Lonesome Jubilee,'' then you'll like this new one, which not only
rocks, but reflects the honesty that is at the root of Mellencamp's
best music. It also reflects the blessing of just being able to
make music at all, since Mellencamp has recovered from the heart
attack he suffered a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us be grateful for what you've got,'' he sings in the
closing tune, ``Days of Farewell.'' That makes a nice book-end to
the first track on the record, ``Your Life is Now,'' which
declares, ``Lift your head up above the crowd/Your father's days
are lost to you/This is your time here to do what you will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp, now 46, is doing quite well, thank you. ``I'm
happier and more content than I've ever been,'' says the Indiana
native. ``I don't get bored or lonely these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he feels a new lease on life thanks to his switch to
Columbia Records, whose president, Tommy Mottola, managed
Mellencamp's career back in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were inspired by the new record label,'' Mellencamp admits.
``I also owe a great deal of thanks to PolyGram for letting me
out,'' he adds, though somewhat sarcastically, since he feels
PolyGram was more interested in supporting the teen-idol group
Hanson than in promoting his records.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mellencamp, formerly one of rock's angry young lions,
is more sanguine and accepting on his new record, which is another
of its strengths. ``I'm not the young kid that I used to be,'' he
sings on the percussive ``I'm Not Running Anymore.'' He knows his
place and limits, which many veteran rockers aren't always willing
to acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's stopped his social commentary, mind you. In fact,
there's a lot of it on the new record. The song ``Eden Is Burning''
is a metaphor for a failing love affair, but also for societal
decay. The hard-rocking ``Fruit Trader'' points up the futility of
some '90s cynics: ``Ain't got no morals/Ain't got no politics/Ain't
go no particular point of view,'' he sings, mimicking them. But,
without sounding preachy, the rejuvenated Mellencamp concludes with
the verse, ``Better let a little bit of this goodness get in.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the new Mellencamp is facing the millennium with a
positive attitude. In the funky ``Summer of Love,'' which has a
recitative, Tom Waits-style vocal, he even notes, ``It's the summer
of love/Leastways, I'm hopin' it is.'' Never for a moment do you
doubt him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
