<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON POLS JUST WANNA HAVE FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans can't agree on whether President
Clinton should be impeached, but there is one subject on which the
leaders of both parties are in perpetual harmony: that campaign
finance is a game whose rules were made to be broken.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of rules were broken, or at least bent, during the 1996
election, a depressing spectacle that gets the ``Frontline''
treatment this week on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   You should watch ``Washington's Other Scandal'' if you care
about democracy, though you should probably avoid it if you care
about preserving any illusion that democracy is on the level in our
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Though a bipartisan stench emanated from the '96 campaign, at
$2.2 billion the most expensive in history, there is little doubt
whom ``Frontline'' considers the Miscreant-in-Chief. Host Bill
Moyers puts the case succinctly: ``In 1996, a `For Sale' sign was
hung on the White House.'' Indeed, despite his periodic prating
about campaign finance reform, such niceties did not get in
Clinton's way as he geared up for reelection.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising stories can be confusing and labyrinthine, and are
usually not long on visuals. But this ``Frontline'' largely
achieves the elusive goal of clarity because it makes copious use
of White House videos of the notorious fund-raising ``coffees'' and
Clinton dinners with fat-cat contributors.
</P>
<P>
   So again we see our president doing some slick talking on
videotape, but this time it's to boast to some assembled moneybags
of the ``brilliant thing'' they are helping to finance. What
Clinton was so proud of, Moyers says, was an end run around
campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton agreed to accept public money and the spending
limits thereby required, his campaign also orchestrated, with the
Democratic National Committee, an effort to raise millions of
dollars of so-called ``soft money'' _ money used to pay for
``issues ads'' that amounted to thinly disguised Clinton campaign
ads. Soft money can't legally be used to promote a specific
candidate, and some have charged that Clinton and perhaps Vice
President Gore both knowingly flouted that rule.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tells donors on one videotape that ``it means that we
can finance this campaign in 1995, so I don't have to worry about
it in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor were matters any more fragrant over on the Republican side.
According to ``Frontline,'' the GOP employed ``shells and shams''
to conceal the identity of rich donors who secretly gave tens of
millions of dollars to Republican candidates. The money funded
attack ads on Democratic rivals.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Senate launched its investigative hearings, both
parties had so much to hide that the hearings turned into ``a
mutual protection racket,'' Moyers says, with senators determined
to cover up the ``sordid truth'' of what happened in 1996.
Eventually, Senate Republicans killed a campaign-finance reform
bill that would have eliminated soft money from campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics will see this as politics-as-usual, and maybe they're
right. But ``Frontline'' reminds us that politics-as-usual carries
a price by examining what happened to a poverty-stricken Oklahoma
Indian tribe that got caught up in the Washington money game.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to get any action in Washington on their bid to regain
land taken by the federal government, the Cheyenne-Arapaho tribe
scraped together its meager savings and gave almost $100,000 to the
Democratic National Committee. Lo and behold, tribal leaders were
then invited to a White House lunch with Clinton. Soon enough, a
Washington lobbying firm descended on the tribe, demanding tens of
thousands more dollars to further grease the skids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cheyenne-Arapaho still do not have their land,'' Moyers
says. ``What they do have is an understanding of the rules in
Washington's greed-driven game.'' And so, thanks to ``Frontline,''
do the rest of us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1852 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-06 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAGAMIX MAY BE IN BREEDER'S MIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sagamix, an undefeated 3-year-old, won the $1.2 million Prix de
l'Arc de Triomphe at Longchamp in Paris Sunday and may come to the
Breeders' Cup at Churchill Downs Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Owned by Jean-Luc Lagardere, trained by Andre Fabre, and ridden
by Olivier Peslier, Sagamix ran his record to 4 for 4 with a wide
rally in deep stretch, catching the fine filly Leggera and Richard
Quinn at the wire to win by a neck. The time for the 1 1/2-mile
race over soft going was 2:34 2/5 and, at 2-1, Sagamix was one of
the favorites in the 14-horse field. It was a milestone victory for
both Fabre, who saddled his fifth Arc winner (Trampolino, '87;
Subotica, '92; Carnegie, '94, and Peintre Celebre, '97), and
Peslier, who won his third straight Arc (Hellissio in '96 and
Peintre Celebre).
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be the fifth time I've trained the winner, but every
time is something special, really great,'' said Fabre. ``I could
see from Sagamix's beautiful action that he was going well as they
ran downhill and I was always confident that he would catch
Leggara. The soft ground didn't matter, as Sagamix goes well on any
ground. This is a great achievement for Monsieur Lagardere as he
bred Sagamix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wonderful,'' said Peslier. ``There was a big question
mark early in the straight because Sagamix is a lazy horse and I
was pushing and pushing him. But he fought all the way, and, when I
smaked him, he ran on.''
</P>
<P>
   The $2 million Breeders' Cup Turf is enriched when the winner of
the Arc, Europe's greatest race, comes to challenge the best in
North America and there is a 50-50 chance that will happen this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for France,'' said Lagardere, president of
GALOP, the ruling body of French racing. ``The horse is still
undefeated, and you can't get any better than that. Andre told me
before the race that this was his best horse. We may run him in
either the Breeders' Cup or the Japan Cup. But this is a very
emotional occasion and we never make hasty decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A broadcast for fans
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk Downs opened its gates at 9:15 a.m. Sunday and offered
simulcasting wagering on the Arc, and three stakes that followed on
the undercard, at the request of its most ardent patrons. About 300
devotees were on hand for the Arc, which carried a 9:50 a.m. post,
and a total of $7,132 was wagered on the four races from Longchamp.
``We consider these simulcasts more of a service to our customers
than anthing else,'' said Suffolk publicist T.D. Thornton.
``Bringing in racing from Europe at 9:50 a.m. on an NFL Sunday is
hardly a big money-maker. But enough fans follow the worldwide
racing scene that we though it would be a good idea to follow
through on their requests to show the Arc.'' ... Pat Day, a true
gentleman and one of the top ambassadors for racing, was unable to
ride Keene Dancer in the Virginia Derby at Colonial Downs Saturday
after he was denied a Virginia permit because of a technicality
stemming from a 1975 conviction for marijuana possession in
Chicago. Day has long since had a religious conversion, about which
he speaks openly and often. Trainer David Carroll scratched Keene
Dancer from the race in protest. ``Pat's turned his life around and
he's a spokesman of the highest order in racing,'' said Carroll.
``If God can forgive you, how come the state of Virginia can't? I
think it's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away looks ready
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away continues to look sharp training for Saturday's $1
million Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont. Certain to be Horse of the
Year, Skip Away will be seeking his third straight Jockey Club
victory, and he showed he is ready with a five-furlong drill in
1:00 2/5 under Jerry Bailey Sunday. ``The work was just fine, and
he came out of it beautifully,'' said trainer Sonny Hine. ``Jerry
told me after the work that Skip Away is ready and everything is
perfect. We're really glad that Gentlemen (who ran second to Skip
Away in the Woodward at Belmont Sept. 19) is in because he'll keep
Skippy on his toes. You can't let a horse like Gentlemen get an
edge on you, and you can't take him lightly. But the better the
competition Skippy has to go against, the better he is.'' ...
Coronado's Quest, the 3-year-old who won the Haskell and Travers
but was run off his feet by Skip Away when fifth and last in the
Woodward, worked five furlongs in 1:01 4/5 at Belmont Sunday.
Coronado's Quest will be retired to stud after one more race,
either the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic or the $300,000 Cigar
Mile at Aqueduct Nov. 28. Frankly, the later spot would make more
sense as a showcase for a triumphant curtain call, since Skip Away
is going to the Classic. ... Free House, fourth in the Woodward,
has been working well since returning to California, and went five
furlongs in :58 4/5 at Santa Anita last Friday. ``He looked very
good and he did it easily,'' said trainer Paco Gonzalez. Free
House, who just had a bad day when the second choice in the
Woodward, will start next in the Goodwood Handicap at Santa Anita
Oct. 17 ... Richard Mandella, who trains Gentlemen, hopes to have
his other two crack handicap horses, Malek and Puerto Madero, back
in training within five weeks. Malek, who won the Santa Anita
Handciap, has been out with an ankle problem since finishing fourth
in the Dubai World Cup, won by Silver Charm, March 28. Puerto
Madero, who finished second to Skip Away in the Massachusetts
Handicap at Suffolk, has been sidelined with strained back muscles
since finishing sixth in the Pacific Classic, won by Free House, at
Del Mar Aug. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
