<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX MANAGER STANDS BY HIS PLAYOFF MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jimy Williams's plans for the immediate future?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to dinner in about 10 minutes,'' said the Red Sox
manager, who stopped by Fenway Park early Monday morning and said
Monday night by phone that he planned to spend a few more days in
the Boston area before heading home to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   One thing he won't do, Williams said, is dwell on the deciding
Game 4 of the Division Series, a 2-1 loss to the Cleveland Indians
in which he brought in closer Tom Gordon to start the eighth, only
to have the Indians score both of their runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, when asked if he'd replayed the game, one in
which he was villified in advance for starting Pete Schourek, only
to have the lefty deliver 5 1/3 scoreless innings. ``I have no
reason to.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he'd gotten it right the first time, he said: ``In my
estimation, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   On two occasions during the regular season, Williams had used
Gordon to record six outs, though this was the first time all year
he'd started the eighth inning. On both of those occasions, he
recorded a save, but Saturday night, Gordon blew a save for the
first time since April 14, ending a string of 43 consecutive saves.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had been on the bench in Atlanta as the Braves'
third-base coach in Game 4 of the 1996 World Series, when Braves
manager Bobby Cox brought in closer Mark Wohlers for the first time
to start the eighth inning. Wohlers gave up a three-run home run to
Jim Leyritz that is widely credited for swinging that Series in the
Yankees' favor.
</P>
<P>
   Williams noted the Red Sox outscored the Indians in the series
(20-18), outhit them (.252 to .206) and outpitched them (4.63 to
5.00).
</P>
<P>
   ``Errors? I don't think we made one (they didn't), and yet we
lost the series, three games to one,'' Williams said. ``Timely
hitting, timely pitching came into play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last part of our lineup didn't hit at an inopportune time,
but basically they hit all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he spoke briefly with Mo Vaughn after the final
game. ``Just for a second,'' he said, ``to compliment him on the
year he had. I look forward to seeing him in Fort Myers. If I
didn't say it loud enough, I said it to myself. He's an integral
part of this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to having him on the Red Sox next spring,
but the organization has to handle that. I'm sure they'll handle it
the best way they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams echoed the comments of CEO John Harrington, who said
the team plans to seek a top-line starting pitcher in the
off-season. ``A lot depends on who you're talking about, who's
available?'' he said. ``Do you get that pitcher from your system,
in a trade, as a free agent? Those clubs that have good starters,
like we do, aren't going to give any up.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams defended left fielder Troy O'Leary, who hit just .238
after the All-Star break, .218 on the road, and was just 1 for 16
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the kid had a good year,'' Williams said. ``He had some
big hits for us. He really played well defensively. I think it
helped him that he played right field last year, had to roam those
big spaces, because he became a very good left-fielder in Fenway
Park. He was consistent all year long, and hit his home runs (23).
</P>
<P>
   ``The last part of the lineup just didn't hit in the playoffs,
that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he hopes that center-fielder Darren Lewis elects
to return next season. Because he played at least 100 games, Lewis'
contract stipulated that he has the right to declare free agency,
rather than accept the club option for a modest $1 million next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him back, very much so,'' Williams said. ``You really
can't say enough about him. He was a tremendous asset, and what an
outstanding person this guy is.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams hinted that the Red Sox might be in the market for a
right fielder, rather than go with the platoon of Darren Bragg and
Damon Buford, though he said that ``if we were to saddle up
tomorrow, I'd utilize their skills the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox right fielders batted a combined .297 last season, which
ranked third in the league, but their home runs (13) ranked last in
the league and their RBIs (74) were more than just one team, the
expansion Devil Rays (65).
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there an absolute way to have a perfect team?'' Williams
said. ``Maybe we could have Nomar (Garciaparra) play right field.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams praised his young catching tandem of Scott Hatteberg
and Jason Varitek (``People don't talk about what they gave to this
team, with their combined three years of experience'') and said he
liked rookies Donnie Sadler and Trot Nixon, though he expects
second baseman Jeff Frye to reclaim his position.
</P>
<P>
   Among the young pitchers, he talked of the great improvement
shown by Derek Lowe, whom he believes has found his niche as a
reliever. ``I really believe that's his forte with the club as we
speak.''
</P>
<P>
   His coaches have yet to be rehired, but Williams said he doesn't
anticipate any changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a group of kids that really wanted to do something,''
he said. ``And they seemed to be more focused as the season went
on. It was very easy for them to come play every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to do the best we could to play them all. They all
got in there, they all had their opportunity to do something. Every
one of them had at least one day in the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, under the harvest moon, there was no lineup card to be
filled out. It was time to go to dinner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
