<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OFFENSE WELL-CONNECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The Patriots need to solve their third-down
problems on defense in a hurry. The Kansas City Chiefs, a team
chosen by many to be the AFC representative in the Super Bowl, will
be in town this Sunday. It will be the biggest game for the
Patriots since Denver on Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chiefs, likewise, have to be a bit worried about the
Patriots' offense. The Ernie Zampese system has taken hold quite
nicely, despite four turnovers by Drew Bledsoe in Sunday's victory
over New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Bledsoe will not be doing that every week. He had
some bad luck, with a ball deflected at the line of scrimmage being
intercepted by a lineman. And most of the time, Ben Coates will
catch the ball that went right between his hands into the arms of a
defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Four very good things happened with the Patriots offense Sunday,
after a bye week to boot.
</P>
<P>
   1. Bledsoe overcame his mistakes and led the team downfield for
a win.
</P>
<P>
   2. Rookie Robert Edwards ran with authority and is quickly
shaking the first-year nerves.
</P>
<P>
   3. The offensive line and fullback Tony Carter were able to
run-block very well.
</P>
<P>
   4. Coates resurfaced with seven receptions after being a virtual
nonfactor in the first three weeks, missing one game because of
ankle injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best we've felt about our offense,'' said coach
Pete Carroll. ``Ernie was really free-wheeling out there, calling a
lot of different types of plays. I thought the guys really
responded well and we were moving the ball in the air and on the
ground against a very good defensive team. It was just great to see
how we came out of the bye week with so much fire. I was worried
about that. But we wanted this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates, who would have been a big star in the silent movie
industry, is beginning to do his talking on the field, where he's
always done it. During the bye week, the Patriots staff realized
that it wasn't using one of the greatest tight ends of all time in
the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben was hurt in Denver and then couldn't play against
Indianapolis,'' said Carroll. ``We really weren't even planning for
him to be back for Tennessee, but he was. This was the first week
that Ben was really a part of our game plan after the first week.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bledsoe, who has thrown 37 touchdown passes to Coates in
their five-plus years together, had been looking away from him.
Reportedly, Coates wondered what was going on, but attention
quickly was refocused on him. He has shaken off several personal
problems and is again a force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so much respect for that man,'' said Shawn Jefferson.
``All that he's had to overcome. But if anyone can overcome it,
it's Ben Coates. He's amazing. After he hurt both ankles in Denver,
he insisted on going out on a pass play just so he could be a
decoy. That enabled me to go out there and catch a long pass in the
game. That showed me right there what Ben would do to help win a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the old Coates traits reappeared. He fought off
linebackers and safeties by swatting at them throughout the game.
Nobody has been beaten up more in his career than Coates, who
usually dishes it back out.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints were trying to hammer him, but Coates got the best of
the battles.Bledsoe's first pass of the game was an 11-yarder that
Coates muscled forward another 4 yards. Three of his catches were
on third down, helping drives continue. He gained 78 yards on the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards gained more than 90 yards for the second straight game
(22 carries for 97 yards). The Patriots did different things with
their run blocking, including running to the left side more.
</P>
<P>
   Center Dave Wohlabaugh did a fine job on Saints nose tackle
La'Roi Glover and was especially effective on a first-quarter play
when he had to take on two blitzing Saints and warded them off long
enough for Bledsoe to complete a fourth-down pass to Terry Glenn
for a first down.
</P>
<P>
   Pass protection was good, as well, as the line and fullback Tony
Carter did a nice job picking up blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the best front we've played,'' said Carroll.
``Wohlabaugh did a nice job up front and our guards did a nice job.
It's really coming together with the pass and the run. We're
picking up blitzes, and the team we're about to play blitzes at
least 30 times a game. We beat the blitz very well, especially when
Drew hit Terry on the fourth-down play with a full blitz coming.
Teams have got to be saying, `Should we be doing this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe completed 60 percent of his passes (21 of 35) for 317
yards. He said the offense seemed able to move downfield with ease,
but mistakes prohibited him from putting away the game earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've been accused of not being fiery,'' said Bledsoe,
``but I think one of my strengths as a quarterback is that whether
things are going well or bad, one of my strengths as a quarterback
is being able to keep a level head.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe continues to spread the ball; seven players had
receptions. One of them wasn't Jefferson, who has caught only five
passes this season, though for a 25.6-yard average. Bledsoe is
going to whoever appears to be hot and whoever appears to be open.
</P>
<P>
   This offense appears ready to handle whatever the Chiefs throw
their way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
