<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-GIRARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIDENCE SUGGESTS THAT YOUNG GIRARD COULD HELP BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jonathan Girard is a native of Quebec, he's 18 years old, he's a
defenseman, and he's quiet and shy _ all of which could be said
about Ray Bourque when he broke into the NHL in 1979. Girard has
been impressive in Bruins training camp and could be on the team
when the season opens Saturday at the FleetCenter against the St.
Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Girard's offensive talent is something the Bruins lacked on the
blue line last season, and that is part of the reason why the club
is weighing whether to keep him in Boston or send him back to his
junior team. He can play nine NHL games before his contract would
kick in and give him credit for one year of pro experience.
</P>
<P>
   He played six of the nine exhibition games, including the final
one at the FleetCenter against the Rangers last Saturday. Girard,
who was selected with Boston's first pick in the June draft (second
round, No. 48 overall), has shown significant flash for someone
with so little seasoning. He was on the right point for the Bruins'
five-on-three power play with Bourque Saturday. And he learned some
tough lessons. At one point early in the second period, he got
picked by Wayne Gretzky, though he recovered nicely.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand, a kid that age coming up is a little
bit intimidated,'' said coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   On the power play, said Burns, ``He's got everybody in the
building except me yelling at him to shoot the puck. He's got Wayne
Gretzky on the ice, he's got Ray Bourque playing beside him, he's
got Mike Richter in net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a kid who has never played in front of more than 3,000
people in his life. All of a sudden he's playing an NHL game
against Gretzky and Adam Graves and Brian Leetch and everyone is
yelling and screaming at him to `Shoot, shoot, shoot.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He conducted himself well. He has to work on his defensive end
a little bit more, be a little bit stronger, but those things are
coming. He's a prize kid and we're certainly glad he's part of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   One factor that will affect his status (he is not eligible to go
to the AHL) is whether the Bruins come to terms with free agent
Kyle McLaren. Boston is thin at forward but has a glut of blue
liners. However, few are of the offensive variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very young, but we just don't have that accomplishment on
the blue line on the power play that he brings,'' said
president/general manager Harry Sinden. ``We're going to have to
see how much the coach thinks he needs that. With (Dave) Ellett and
(Darren) Van Impe, we tried it last year and it was OK but it's not
of the caliber we need.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid can move the puck really good. I wouldn't say he has
made the team yet. It depends what happens with McLaren. But he's
got an awful lot of Brian Leetch in him. Ray needs that along the
blue line with him. I can see he's very vulnerable to defensive
problems. But he is a smart kid and he'll probably overcome them
once he gets playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, who converses with Girard in their native French,
thinks Girard has good instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, he sees the ice really well,'' said Bourque. ``He
moves it good. I tell him to try not to do too much, just keep it
real simple. A couple of times he might try a pass here or there.
Whenever he does something like that, I try to remind him sometimes
you've got to put it off the glass or hard around the boards. The
nice pass isn't always going to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think he's handled himself really well. I like that
whenever he does make a mistake, he doesn't get flustered. He'll
try a pass he feels he can make on the very next shift. It's a
matter of getting used to being pressured a little quicker than
you're used to. That's the big thing any young guy coming in has to
adjust to, and that takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   When Girard was picked clean by Gretzky, Bourque was impressed
that the kid didn't lose his cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things still happen to me,'' he said. ``You're going to
get picked by guys like that but he caught up to him. He can skate
and can recover really well. He's very talented and has good
composure for an 18-year-old. You don't see too many 18-year-old
defensemen handle the puck like he does from back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens, Bourque has enjoyed taking the
youngster under his wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak to him in French but he doesn't say much, even in
French,'' said Bourque. ``I think I said a little more than he did.
That's the way he is. My nephew played with him last year and said
he's a very quiet kid. He just goes about his business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
