<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A HAMBURGER WAR YOU'LL RELISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are you ready for a Hamburg war?
</P>
<P>
   A while back, we reported on the claim that America's favorite
sandwich, the hamburger, originated in Hamburg, Germany, where it
was known as the Hamburg steak _ a name that was shortened to
``hamburger'' in the United States. But there is another claimant
to the birth of the burger: the village of Hamburg, N.Y. Here, as
forwarded by Mayor John S. Thomas, is the Hamburg, N.Y., version of
how the burger came to be:
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1885 and the place was the Hamburg Fair (now the
site of the Erie County Fair). Frank Menches, a concessionaire, and
his brother Charles brought their new gasoline stove to the fair to
cook their specialty, a pork sausage sandwich. Alas, the local meat
market had run out of pork sausage, so Frank came back with five
pounds of chopped beef. He got the stove going while his brother
formed the beef into patties. When the first patty came off the
grill, the brothers tried it and decided it didn't taste zesty
enough. So they went wild and sprinkled a little light brown sugar
into a frying patty, and the result was a scrumptious hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the village calls itself Birthplace of the Hamburger
and holds a Burgerfest the third Saturday of each July, an event
that's always well done. What's more, the Chamber of Commerce uses
this snappy slogan: ``We're on a Roll.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the Hamburg, Germany, story? ``Well, I guess the
war is on now!'' says Mayor Thomas. He's not kidding: Some say
hamburgers were on the menu at Delmonico's restaurant in New York
as early as 1836. Others maintain a little eatery in New Haven
called Louie's Lunch was responsible for the invention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; And as for frankfurters...: &LR;  In 1852, the Frankfurt, Germany,
butchers' guild created a long, thin sausage and named it
``frankfurter'' in honor of their town. Then, in 1906, Harry Mosley
Stevens, who operated the New York Giants' refreshments concession,
decided to add the frankfurter, which had been nicknamed the
``dachsund sausage,'' to his menu. He instructed his vendors to
yell, ``Get your dachsund sausages while they're red hot!'' A
cartoonist lampooned the item by depicting vendors selling real
dachshunds in a roll, yelling ``Get your hot dogs!'' And the name
stuck. (With thanks to Mike Schuster of Foxborough, who cites
Mailbits.com, which in turn cites three sources. Nonetheless, we'll
probably hear from the mayor of Frankfort, Ky.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  What is the largest country in size in South
America? Wait a minute, that's too easy. What is the second-largest
country? No, that's still to easy. What is the third-largest
country?
</P>
<P>
   (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  There is a baker/cafe on Prince Edward Island, Canada,
called Knead the Dough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``How were these magnificent structures finished in
time? In the sixth century, a deadline meant that if you didn't
finish the work in time, you were dead.'' _ tour guide in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Today's fractured English lesson: &LR;  From a welcoming brochure at a
beach resort on Margarita Island, Venezuela: ``The identification
bracelette that has been put on your wrist is the only visible sign
that will difference the contrated service you adquired. ... The
Hotel reserves the right to offer the service to those who do not
attend the Internal Regulations and good manners.'' (With thanks to
Julie Martin of Stow, Mass., who is no fan of Margarita Island.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Freebie: &LR;  Autumn is a wonderful time to visit New Hampshire, and
after a couple of recent visits, we can vouch for that. For a
215-page guidebook, with lodging and dining information included,
call 800-FUN-IN-NH, ext., 100, or visit www.visitnh.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; It's contest time: &LR;  Travelers who book a Fall Weekender package at
participating Holiday Inns through Nov. 15 and pay with an American
Express card not only get discounted rates that include breakfast:
They also get to participate in the Stay, Play &AMP; Win scratch-card
game. All players win something, and prizes include free Holiday
Inn stays and American Express Cheques worth $25-$100. Players also
get a chance for a trip to New York City that includes all expenses
plus $2,000 for shopping, $500 for food, and a visit to the set of
TV's ``Good Morning America.'' That would be a good morning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Prayer and prettiness: &LR;  South Korea has more than 11,000 Buddhist
temples. Many are nestled in the mountains, so in fall they are
surrounded by colorful autumn leaves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; New travel products: &LR;  Travelers who monitor their blood pressure
may have a friend in the Omron Wrist Blood Pressure Monitor. It
weighs a mere 8 ounces, fits any wrist from 5 1/4 inches to 7 3/4
inches, is easily packed for travel, inflates to the proper
pressure automatically, and uses ``fuzzy logic'' for accuracy. The
suggested price: $99. For more information, call 800-634-4350 or
visit www.omron.com/ohi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Are you lonesome tonight? &LR;  The state of North Dakota gets 2.9
million visitors a year, the least of any state. According to The
New York Times, the outlet malls in Freeport, Maine, get more
visitors per year than North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Mailbag: &LR;  To our recent list of low-cost New York City attractions,
George W. Duffy of Seabrook, N.H., adds the Staten Island Ferry.
``Great trip: marvelous vistas, big ships and tugs and barges to
see, fresh air and (hopefully) sunshine. Get off at St. George's,
make a U-turn, and catch the next boat back to the Battery.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Closed for repairs: &LR;  St. Louis's biggest tourist attraction, the
Gateway Arch, will be closed at least a month after a small
electrical fire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  Peru is the third-largest country in South
America. (Brazil is the largest and Argentina is second-largest.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
