<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN FACE BARRIERS WHEN SEEKING OVERSEAS JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jan Ledbetter asked officials at a large Midwestern
manufacturing firm to consider her for an overseas assignment, they
didn't mince words. They refused outright.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `We aren't comfortable sending a woman to South
America or Asia because of cultural issues,''' recalls Ledbetter,
43. ``The other concern was my husband. He was working, so the
company felt he wouldn't want to travel. I told them my husband was
looking forward to coming with me, but it didn't make any
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, a decade later, women continue to have difficulty
landing overseas assignments, says Lynn O'Brien Hallstein, a
communications professor at Babson College in Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In research published this year, Hallstein reports that the
biggest barrier women face when applying for foreign assignments is
the gender bias of male managers who believe American women cannot
be successful in cultures where gender roles are more traditional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assumption is that American women will be treated like the
women in the host country,'' says Hallstein. ``The truth is
American women are often treated as a third sex, and are given a
lot more leeway than the women in the host country.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, female executives still lag their male counterparts
when it comes to foreign assignments, reports New York-based
Windham International. The company, which helps new expatriates and
their families settle abroad, notes in a 1998 survey of 45 large
firms that only 15 percent routinely tap women for overseas
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, however, female expatriates said they had few, if
any, problems on the job and were often welcomed by their host
countries.
</P>
<P>
   But old ideas die hard. With lingering stereotypes of women
playing a submissive or limited role in some societies and their
workplaces, &UR;  &LR;  companies are still more likely to choose a male for
assignments in Asia, Africa, Latin America, or the Middle East for
fear their female emissary's gender will get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Dolins, cofounder of Windham International, says that when
her firm began polling companies about female expatriates five
years ago, ``everyone predicted that by the year 2000 women would
be 20 percent of all those sent on international assignments. But
the truth is, the female expatriate population has grown only 5
percent since 1992 and it was just 10 percent then.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hallstein, 83 percent of all women who were
assigned to international jobs in 1997 got them through their own
initiative. She maintains that female executives who take the
following steps are more likely to land a foreign assignment than
those who simply wait for their employer:
</P>
<P>
   _First, initiate a discussion about your interest in
international assignments as early as your initial interview with
the firm.
</P>
<P>
   _Educate your employer about the strategic advantages women
bring to overseas assignments. ``If you do not do this, the company
will operate from its own gender filters and may not consider
you,'' says Hallstein.
</P>
<P>
   _Find out the company's specific concerns about sending women
abroad before you make a serious pitch for a position. This will
allow you to respond appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   _Encourage employers to think about good predictors of success.
Point out that such assignments require people who can tolerate
ambiguity and change and who are flexible, are sensitive to
cross-cultural issues, and are capable of building strong bonds.
</P>
<P>
   _Point out that with international assignments, gender is only
one of many variables that can influence the quality of work. In
fact, your female characteristics and style might actually be
highly valued abroad.
</P>
<P>
   _Some companies have made significant headway in this area. Find
out who they are, gather statistics about the number of women they
have sent abroad, and present this to your firm as part of your
campaign to encourage your employer or supervisor to consider women
for these jobs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis is a Boston Globe staff member. She can be
reached at The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107, or by e-mail at
work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
