<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS DEALS SEEN AS UNLIKELY TO AFFECT HUDSON PCB CLEANUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Two historic agreements to clean up industrial
PCB contamination in Massachusetts waterways are unlikely to have
much impact on the cleanup of the Hudson River, business and
environmental officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very different rivers, different facts, there is
different science, there is different laws,'' said David Warshaw,
spokesman for the General Electric Co. at its headquarters in
Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 24, the Environmental Protection Agency and GE
announced a $150 million agreement to remove PCBs from the
Housatonic River and contaminated areas of Pittsfield. One week
later, the agency announced a $120 million plan to dredge New
Bedford Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   But interviews with officials in the New York office of the EPA,
GE officials and Hudson River environmental advocates suggest that
these recent accords won't alter how _ or if _ the EPA and GE
settle their differences over whether to dredge the Hudson to
remove PCBs. The Hudson's ecosystem and the laws that will guide
any cleanup of its waters are different than the Housatonic's. Both
rivers, however, were legally polluted for years by GE discharges
of PCBs, an industrial insulator used to make transformers and
capacitors.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Housatonic, most of the Hudson River, from Fort
Edward to Manhattan, is a federal Superfund site, which gives the
EPA greater power to enforce any PCB cleanup decision it reaches.
The Pittsfield agreement gives GE the option of challenging EPA's
proposed remedy in court. The company has no similar option for the
Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, GE and the EPA say the Hudson's environmental
issues do not compare with either the Housatonic's or the harbor's.
PCB levels in New Bedford, for instance, are among the highest in
the nation, making dredging a necessity. For the Hudson, GE claims
dredging would only stir up long-buried PCBs, which the EPA
considers a probable human carcinogen.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in Pittsfield, the Housatonic runs weakly and is
almost shallow enough to wade across, lessening any potential
damage from dredging, Warshaw said. By contrast, the Hudson is a
much deeper, rapidly flowing river.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials agree. Dick Stapleton, a spokesman for EPA's
Region 2 office in New York City, said the Pittsfield deal won't
affect the agency's work in the Hudson River because it wasn't a
final settlement as much as ``an agreement to try to come to an
agreement,'' Stapleton said. ``There's no deal yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists in New York have cautiously embraced the
Pittsfield agreement but say the Hudson's future won't be affected
by it. Cara Lee of Scenic Hudson, an advocacy group in
Poughkeepsie, warned against drawing any precedents from what GE
hammered out with EPA's Region 1 office in Pittsfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's seen the fine print on this settlement,'' she said.
``It's hard for me to see how that will affect the Hudson decision
in the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   Some EPA officials, in fact, expressed dismay at the Pittsfield
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the most profitable company in the United States, and
EPA is picking up part of the tab,'' said an EPA staff person
familiar with the Hudson PCB assessment project. ``Why is EPA using
taxpayer money to help out GE? We're really troubled by that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
