<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLIAGE, FESTIVALS   ABOUND IN WESTERN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If all goes well, next week should be prime time for foliage
viewing in many places throughout New England.
</P>
<P>
   The best, and easiest, foliage route west of Boston is Route 2,
especially after you pass Fitchburg. Pick the route up at Route 128
and go west, leaf peepers. Beginning in Lincoln, you'll find
farmstands filled with the harvest, good places to get your
Halloween pumpkins. Once beyond Acton and Route 27, there's not
another traffic light for some 70 miles. The only problem at this
time of year is the traffic, which can be quite heavy.
</P>
<P>
   The rewards, though, in beauty and festivities, are worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield will hold its annual Fall Festival on the Common on
Oct. 10 from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. The festival will feature crafts,
food, sidewalk sales, magic shows, goat petting, live music from
jazz and bluegrass to a world beat, and there will be cow milking _
unfortunately, Betsy, the cow, has another commitment this year,
and she will be replaced by Victoria, a brown Swiss who just loves
being milked, and just happens to be available. It's a fun time.
For more information, call 413-774-2791.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield, at the junction of Route 2 and Interstate 91, is a
good jumping-off place for the Mohawk Trail (Route 2 beyond
Greenfield), where the scenery gets even more magnificent. All
along this route you'll find apple farms, pumpkins, cider, and
more. There will be yard sales galore as well as many other local
fests.
</P>
<P>
   From Greenfield, you can take the relaxed Route 10 to Deerfield
and tour Historic Deerfield, a village from the past (its main
street has been described as one of the most beautiful in the
country). Historic Deerfield has many homes from the early 1700s to
tour (the town was the western frontier in colonial days), and a
grand and brand new museum filled with artifacts from the past.
</P>
<P>
   Continue down Route 10 and you come to what has become the
second-most-popular attraction in New England _ the Yankee Candle
flagship store. It has to be seen to be believed. Besides candles,
old cars, and a Bavarian Christmas village, there's also a nice
restaurant, Chandlers, where you can dine by _ you guessed it _
candlelight.
</P>
<P>
   Take Interstate I-91 down to Northampton and you can catch the
Paradise City Arts Festival, Oct. 10-12. More than 200 artists and
designers from 42 states will be participating, making this a
festival not to be missed. There will be an emphasis on custom
furniture and home furnishings, large-scale sculpture and
functional pieces for the garden, and museum-quality collectible
work in all media. The festival also offers great food, jazz,
children's entertainment, and demonstrations. Northampton is known
for its restaurants and art. The festival is $7 for adults. For
information, call 413-586-6324. Northampton also is easily reached
via the Mass. Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   For those continuing on Route 2, the rewards are grand. You
could drive to the top of Mount Greylock, the state's hightest peak
at 3,491 feet. Mount Greylock is celebrating its 100th birthday as
a state reservation this year. Then continue on to Williamstown to
view the art of the Clark Art Institute, one of the country's
finest museums _ it even has some Monets. To get maps for driving
tours, events, lodging, and more in the Berkshires, call
800-237-5747 or on the Web at www.berkshires.org.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of traveling Route 2 is that you can dart off in many
directions, traveling on quieter roads, and return in a new
direction, almost without a map.
</P>
<P>
   While this routing encompasses only a small part of New England,
you can be sure no matter where you travel next weekend in the
region's southern parts, you'll be treated to good to great color.
Check out the foliage hot lines for the latest color; some states
also offer events to add to the trip.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who can't hit the road, the Vermont Chamber of
Commerce Web site is featuring a ``leaf cam.'' Just click on the
site and watch as a photo comes up showing a beautiful wooded scene
from Huntington in north-central Vermont. The camera stays focused
on the scene throughout foliage season and is updated every three
hours. To view, go to www.vtchamber.com. The leaf cam runs from 8
a.m. to 5 p.m., and retains the clearest photo until the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foliage events
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire is packed with happenings for foliage season.
Here's a sampling of events around Columbus Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Oct 10-11: 18th Annual Gunstock Octoberfest, Gilford. Live
entertainment, music, and dancing. Plenty of German food and beer
for sale. Children's activities during the day. Call Gunstock at
603-293-4341.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 10 and 17: Shaker Music and Dance, Canterbury. Call
Canterbury Shaker Village for tickets at 603-783-9511.
</P>
<P>
   Until Oct.12: Autumn 1998 Nature Cruises on Squam Lake,
Holderness. These tours are presented by the Science Center of New
Hampshire. View the foliage from the lake while also taking in the
other natural wonders. Reservations are required. Call
603-968-7194.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 17, Inherit New Hampshire will present its Fall Tour. In
the late 1800s, a highly cultured group of writers and artisans
sought the clean air and refreshing spirit of New Hampshire's
Connecticut River, settling especially in the towns of Plainfield
and Cornish. For them, the pleasant countryside and the grand views
of Mount Ascutney were a source of both personal relaxation and
professional inspiration for their work. There will be a tour of
Saint-Gaudens National Historic Site in Cornish beginning at 10
a.m. followed by lectures. For more information, call 603-224-2281.
</P>
<P>
   You might also want to check out this exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   A new exhibit, ``All my Wareing Apparill: The Production,
Consumption, and the Culture of Women's Clothing in Revolutionary
Exeter,'' has opened at the American Independence Museum in Exeter.
The exhibit runs through the end of this year and takes a look at
women as producers and consumers of clothing goods and accessories.
For more information, call 603-772-2622.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foliage hot lines
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vermont _ 802-828-3239
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire _ 800-258-3608 or 800-262-6660
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts _ 800-447-MASS, ext. 300
</P>
<P>
   Maine _ 888-MAINE-45
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut _ 800-282-6863, ext. 88
</P>
<P>
   New York _ 800-CALL-NYS.
</P>
<P>
   For nationwide foliage updates from the US Forest Service, call
800-354-4595.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane update
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For travelers heading for the Caribbean, the news is mostly
good. Hurricane Georges spared many islands, and most of the ones
hit by the storm are either back in business or almost ready to
accept bookings again. Puerto Rico is reporting that all services
are either back or will be so this week. Only a couple of resorts
on the island are still closed. For information on the island, call
888-858-9582.
</P>
<P>
   The US Virgin Islands also report minimal effects from the storm
and that most resorts are open. The Ritz-Carlton St. Thomas is open
but not accepting reservations for a couple of weeks while it
cleans up the property.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines and cruise ships are again calling on Puerto Rico and
the Virgin Islands. Resorts on the British Virgins reported no
structural damage and are open.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Caribbean Tourism Organization, the Dominican
Republic reports hotels in Puerto Plata are fully operational, and
in Santo Domingo, hotels received minor damage. In other areas, the
effects of the hurricane are still being evaluated, with many
resorts closed.
</P>
<P>
   St. Kitts and Nevis suffered extensive damage, and a state of
emergency is still in place.
</P>
<P>
   Islands with no damage to tourism facilities include St. Martin,
Guadeloupe, Anguilla, and St. Lucia.
</P>
<P>
   Islands unaffected by the hurricane include Aruba, Bonaire,
Curacao, Martinique, Turks &AMP; Caicos, Barbados, Jamaica, Cayman
Islands, Grenada, and Trinidad and Tobago.
</P>
<P>
   Information was supplied by tourism boards, including the
Caribbean Tourism Organization. For more information, call the CTO
at 212-635-9530.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Washington fun
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 10, you can travel around the president's neighborhood
on a specially issued passport to view homes and offices not
normally opened to the public. The 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. tour is
centered around the annual Salute the Square open house. All events
are free and around Lafayette Square. For information, call Decatur
House at 202-842-0917.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Oct. 10-12 is the annual Taste of DC festival when 40 of
the city's top restaurants offer samplings of their foods. There
will be entertainment, and crafts. For information, call
202-724-5430.
</P>
</TEXT>
