<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1911 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-FOLIAGE-ART-BO     10-06 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FOLIAGE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND'S NOT-SO-COLORFUL PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWBURY, N.H. _ Northern New England is swathed in autumn finery
_ arresting reds and vibrant oranges. And it is easy to believe,
looking at these forests, that foliage season has been exactly this
magnificent since the Pilgrims landed at Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   But these hills were not always so glorious.
</P>
<P>
   Foliage season as we know it, with scores of maple trees leading
the annual charge into colorful glory, is a relatively new
phenomenon, according to Dave Anderson, a naturalist and educator
with the Society for the Protection of New Hampshire Forests.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Cogbill, a historical ecologist based in Vermont, says
the foliage picture now is much different from the one early New
England settlers saw.
</P>
<P>
   Cogbill, who is researching the makeup of the pre-European
settlement forest in New England, said that when the first settlers
gazed out over the hills in autumn, they did not see what we see
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was more conifer, more dark green, no really blazing
oranges,'' said Cogbill.
</P>
<P>
   But the European settlers did not tread lightly on the forests
of the New World. And it was their actions _ and the continued
actions of their descendants _ that inadvertently made foliage
season what it is today.
</P>
<P>
   First, they cut down nearly all the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Clearing for agriculture and wholesale cutting of spruce for
timber denuded as much as 85 percent of New England by the
mid-1800s, said Jim Hornbeck, a research forester at the
Northeastern Research Station of the US Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can assume that after the Civil War, foliage was not
great,'' said Anderson, making his way along a wooded trail at the
John Hay Forest Reservation in Newbury, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 675 acres on the Hay Reservation were once farmland.
Now the area is nearly all forested _ a classic New England
combination of pine, hemlock, beech, maple, birch, oak, poplar, and
ash.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson explained that after the first great cutting, as farms
were abandoned and clear-cuts reverted to forest, what came back
was a combination of green conifers and foliage-producing
hardwoods. Old fields went to pine, with an understory of hardwood
growth.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a second great cutting of pine, sparked by the
Industrial Revolution, that Anderson said made today's foliage what
it is. Anderson refers to this second harvest of pine as ``The
Boxboard Boom'' _ a massive harvest of pine for making packing
crates and other material needed by New England's mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``That released, in many cases, the hardwood forest we know
today,'' Anderson said. ``The Boxboard Boom begat the foliage.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, said Hornbeck, New England is back to being about 85
percent forested.
</P>
<P>
   One of Cogbill's field studies tells the tale. Using colonial
land survey records, Cogbill has determined that a plot of land in
Woodstock, N.H., in 1794 was comprised of 38 percent spruce, 32
percent beech, 22 percent birch, 8 percent fir, and not a trace of
maple.
</P>
<P>
   A nearby plot today, at the same elevation and close to the same
spot, boasts 16 percent sugar maple, 11 percent beech, 31 percent
yellow birch, 4 percent ash, 5 percent fir, and 13 percent spruce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spruce is gone,'' said Cogbill. ``Sugar maple has come on like
gangbusters.''
</P>
<P>
   Red maple _ also called swamp or white maple _ has also come on
strong. While sugar maple turns predominantly orange and yellow, it
is red maple that produces the arresting crimsons so prized by
leaf-peepers.
</P>
<P>
   Since red maple is of little timber value, Anderson said, it is
often left standing when other trees around it are harvested.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire alone, said Anderson, red maple has increased
by 500 percent since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   According to the US Forest Service, red maple and sugar maple
now account for a large percentage of all trees on forested land in
New England. The two species account for 28 percent of the trees in
Massachusetts, 31 percent in Connecticut, 18 percent in Maine, 25
percent each in Rhode Island and New Hampshire, and 31 percent in
Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want color,'' said Anderson, ``maple's the poster
child.''
</P>
<P>
   And, said Anderson, current trends in timber harvesting _ and
the aging of foliage-producing hardwoods _ means the fall colors
will just keep getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continuing harvest of our big pines and the aging of our
forest gives way to hardwoods,'' said Anderson. ``A lumberman's
concern, but a foliage aficionado's dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
