<P>
   &UR; Clinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Democratic leaders struggle to
maintain unity in opposition to the Republican resolution for an
impeachment inquiry. By Lizette Alvarez and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHARGES (Washington) _ The version of Starr's report
provided by David Schipper, the Republican counsel on the House
Judiciary Committee, served one purpose: choosing charges easier to
prove than Starr's, but with potentially less gravity. By Alison
Mitchell and Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   ICKES-TEAMSTERS (Washington) _ The House Education and Workforce
Committee turns up new documents that provide more details of
Harold Ickes efforts on behalf of the Teamsters. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other Washington &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ With a deadline three days away,
Congress is moving ahead on appropriations bills. Looking at what
is in each of the unfinished measures. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-MILITARY (Washington) _ Defense Secretary Cohen and the
Joint Chiefs' Gen. Shelton go before Congress again to discuss the
budget. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RACE (Washington) _ With both President Clinton and his
advisory board on race having recommended sharp increases in
programs to enforce anti-discrimination laws, civil rights groups
are expressing disappointment that Congress has approved only
modest increases for agencies like the EEOC. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DEBARTOLO-BRIBE (Baton Rouge, La.) _ Eddie Debartolo, whose
family owns the San Francisco 49ers, agrees to plead guilty and pay
a large fine in exchange for testifying against Louisiana's former
governor Edwin W. Edwards after a long investigation of riverboat
casino licensing. DeBartolo will agree to testify that he paid
$400,000 to Edwards to get the last riverboat gambling license in
the state. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFING (Undated) _ Shorts on politics. By B.
Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
