   LEPEN-HOLOCAUST (Paris) _ The European Parliament lifts the
immunity of the French rightist leader Le Pen, meaning he may face
trial in Germany for remarks belittling Holocaust. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:20 p.m., the Dow industrial average was
up 21 points and the Nasdaq index down 4 points. Elsewhere, prices
rose 0.6 percent in Tokyo, while the Hong Kong market was closed
for a holiday. They gained 4 percent in Frankfurt, 4.5 1 percent in
London, 6.2 percent in Brazil and 2.7 percent in Mexico. On the
American debt market, the long bond was down 1 5/32 point at
midday, with the yield at 4.79 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate:
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ A detailed look at credit market
developments. By Robert Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT (Undated) _ Developments in the rescue plan
for Long-Term Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIED-PENN (Undated) _ The Pennsylvania House of
Representatives is expected to vote today on legislation that would
probably kill Allied Signal's proposed takeover of AMP. By Sharon
R. King.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-IBM (Frankfurt, Germany) _ IBM and France Telecom will
develop a successor to Minitel, the French system that was a
pioneer in online commerce but that has been largely overtaken by
the Internet. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   GM-REORG (Detroit ) _ More about General Motors' decision to
combine its domestic and international automotive operations. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The weekly business travel column.
By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro) _ Developments on the Brazilian
economic front. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-RAILS (Tokyo) _ A bill that is likely to lead to a
showdown between the Japanese government and foreign investors is
nearing approval in the Diet. At issue are the government's plans
to shift $1.3 billion in debt to the seven railway companies that
were formed when the national railroad system was privatized more
than a decade ago. The presidents of the seven companies have vowed
to fight the measure, contending that it violates their
shareholders' rights by illegally changing the terms of the
privatization. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
