<SLUG> BC-SCOTT-RITTER-INTERVIEW-EXCLUSIVE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW IRAQ IS HIDING ITS WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By DAVID MAKOVSKY  
 c.1998 Ha'aretz  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (NOTE: In this exclusive interview, former U.N. arms inspector
Scott Ritter tells Ha'aretz, the Israeli newspaper, that the U.N.
inspectors had broken Iraq's code for hiding missiles _ and then
inspections were stopped.)
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Scott Ritter knows Iraq pretty well by now. A veteran
arms inspector for the U.N. Special Commission charged with
tracking Iraq's arsenal of weapons of mass destruction, Ritter, who
recently resigned his post, was intimately involved in the U.N.
effort to keep Saddam Hussein honest.
</P>
<P>
   Over an extended period, Ritter and other inspectors worked to
break the code Saddam was using to issue instructions involving the
movement of weapons Iraq wanted to keep hidden from inspectors.
Well into this year, the cat-and-mouse game being played in Iraq
made regular headlines around the world.
</P>
<P>
   What few know is that the U.N. inspectors, with Israeli help,
eventually broke the Iraqi code and were on the verge of a major
breakthrough in uncovering concealed weaponry. Then this summer the
inspections were halted. That's when Ritter quit his job _ out of
pure frustration, he says.
</P>
<P>
   In this conversation with David Makovsky, correspondent for
Ha'aretz, Ritter reveals how weapons were being moved around in
Iraq and what role Israel played in helping the inspections team.
He also reveals his own personal disillusionment with the United
States for what he characterizes as its lack of support for the
inspections program.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAVID MAKOVSKY: How did Iraq conceal weapons from UNSCOM?
</P>
<P>
   SCOTT RITTER: In April 1991, Saddam Hussein issued a
presidential directive ordering that Iraq lie to the Special
Commission (UNSCOM) and to the IAEA (International Atomic Energy
Agency), (and that Iraq) would keep (its mass destruction)
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1991, the materials that were kept were turned over under
instruction of the president to the Special Security Organization
(SSO) and Special Republican Guard (SRG). These are presidential
security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How big is this special organization?
</P>
<P>
   A: The SSO is one of the most secretive organizations in Iraq.
It probably numbers around 5,000 people. The SRG is the military
arm that had four brigades, around 15 battalions, and is about the
size of a division _ maybe 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was the special organization set up for this purpose of
concealment?
</P>
<P>
   A: The special organization was set up to protect the president
of Iraq. Back in the 1980s this special security organization also
had a responsibility for protecting Iraq's weapons. ... So they
have been linked from the very beginning with these weapons, but
today they have the responsibility of hiding them from the Special
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is their job basically to conduct one big shell game?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's right, it's a shell game. Now what you're getting to
is the problem I faced. We were beating our heads against the wall
going after the shell game. We're playing their game. I said to
(then) chairman (of UNSCOM, Rolf Ekeus, that) rather than going
after the shells, let's go after the man moving the shells.
</P>
<P>
   One reason why I went to Israel and started working with the
Israelis is because I believe that the methodologies that Israel
uses to hunt down terrorists are the same methodologies we needed
to use to go after the weapons of mass destruction. So I asked
Israel to help the commission formulate analytical models,
analytical techniques and to advise on operational issues.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was that?
</P>
<P>
   A: I first approached (Israel) in 1994. We started working in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was it helpful?
</P>
<P>
   A: I can honestly say that if it weren't for Israel, the Special
Commission would not have been able to carry out the
anti-concealment effort.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was Israel's unique contribution?
</P>
<P>
   A: I can just say Israel had a good reputation of being
innovative, of being capable, of being good. And we approached
Israel due to all those factors. It's Tel Aviv that can be hit by
these missiles, not New York City, and we were actually, frankly
speaking, a little dismayed with the lack of intensity, the lack of
enthusiasm, that emanated from Washington on this issue. The U.S.
treated it more as an academic exercise and I thought Israel
treated it as it is _ a matter of life and death. So we came to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were your trips and cooperation with Israel authorized by the
head of UNSCOM? Was it also approved by the U.S.?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ekeus started this, yes. It was all authorized by Ekeus. It
was a totally authorized thing and it was approved by the U.S.
government. Every aspect was approved by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who ran the Iraqi concealment program?
</P>
<P>
   A: Abed Hamed Mahmoud, the presidential secretary. He is
probably the most powerful man in Iraq after the president. He is
Saddam's bodyguard, confidant, right-hand man. Qusay Hussein
(Saddam's son) cannot go to the president without going through
Abed Hamed Mahmoud. He is the gatekeeper. He is the man responsible
for coordinating the national security policy of Iraq. He's the
secret power in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   He runs what's called the joint committee, (which) coordinates
all the national security. ... He's the one who brings people in
and gives them concealment tasks. He's the one who (manages) the
concealment operation center that monitors all the stuff that is
moved around Iraq. Abed uses the special security organization
[SSO] as the tool for concealment.
</P>
<P>
   I can name officers within the special security organization who
did concealment, and I can tell (the UNSCOM) chairman, how, when,
where and why specific acts of concealment took place. That's how
good we got. I can't say how we did it. But I can say how good we
got. So we started with nothing and in the end we were down to
where we knew when, where, how, why, who and what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why the frustration. It was not a single source of
information. We used everything that we had available to us. And
that's why what happened in July and August (when the U.S. halted
inspections) was so frustrating. Because now that we have
identified how they're doing it, and now that we get the kind of
information we need on the timely basis we need, we're inside their
decision-making cycle. We're reacting before Iraq can react.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You really could get the information before they move the
shell?
</P>
<P>
   A: Before they move the shell. And I got stuck. That's why I was
so mad. Because I finally came up with the solution. I broke the
code. We untied the Gordian knot. We figured it out. We had the
problem solved and now we just need to go do the job. It took us
three years, but we solved the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. didn't let us. Not only didn't they let us, they
won't let us _ because to go do it ratchets it up to the ultimate
level of confrontation. Because there's no way Iraq will allow us
to inspect the people who need to be inspected. We're talking about
the people closest to Saddam Hussein. We're talking about the
security forces, the personal security forces of Saddam; we're
talking about the family of Saddam. These are the people doing
concealment.
</P>
<P>
   It basically works like a mafia organization. When you organize
crime (or set up a) terrorist organization, you have cells. And in
order to become a cell leader, you have to be trusted by the
family, so you have to be very close to the family. So the people
being selected are direct blood relatives of Saddam. There are
primarily Tikritis (people from Saddam's hometown) or there are
alliances of marriage to other tribes, like the Alduries.
</P>
<P>
   People of this nature are also close to Saddam. Abed is the one
who says I can trust this man or I can't. Abott does the
interviews. That's all compartmentalized. (Even) if you get one
cell, you don't what the other guy is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Now the cells can rely on a larger infrastructure, the Special
Security Organization, the Special Republican Guard. These elite
organizations are populated by people loyal to Saddam. Now they
don't have a mission per se of concealment, but if you need a
truck, you can go to that Special Republican Guard and vehicle
resources. If you need 15-man working party, you can go to that
Special Republican Guard unit and get 15 soldiers to do something
for you.
</P>
<P>
   So you have the resources of the SSO and SRG at your disposal if
you want to hide these weapons. You're given vehicles, you're given
money, you're given a safe house. You're given the responsibility
to go out and find a location to hide this stuff. ... You go to
your uncle who has a farm in Samara, and you say on that farm, 'I
need to use that shed. I can't tell you what for, it's a family
business.'
</P>
<P>
   Thirty days later, they leave and he has a soldier on his team.
He asks: 'Do you have a relative near here?' They go to the cousin
and say, 'We need to use your farm and hide stuff on your farm.'
And that's how they move stuff around.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many people do you think are involved?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think we are talking about hundreds of people involved. It
is probably several cells doing chemicals, several cells doing
ballistic missiles, several cells doing biological (components),
and a cell doing nuclear (devices). You might be talking 50, 60
sites in Iraq at any one time with all that. Then you have the
groups responsible for monitoring ... personnel. Then you have a
group responsible for monitoring UNSCOM _ trying to collect
intelligence on what UNSCOM is doing. And Iraq has this regime of
terror and control. ... They can tap into any resource in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Israel help crack the code of concealment?
</P>
<P>
   A: We used the methodology that Israel was considered to be the
best at in the world. We cracked the code, not Israel. Israel was
not in the lead on this, but I can say that UNSCOM could not have
solved this problem without the help of Israel. It's absolutely
essential. We could not have done what we did. We couldn't even
come close without the help of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   I was in charge when I went to Israel. Israel responded. My
requirements and my tasking came from the executive chairman.
Israel did not control the Special Commission. Israel didn't want
to control the Special Commission. Israel was a fair player on all
of this. It was extremely responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you say how many times you were in Israel?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was there a lot. From 1994 until 1998 I was there a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you comment on the FBI investigation into your links with
Israel?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's the most outrageous that I ever encountered with the
U.S. government. I was sent to the Special Commission by the U.S.
government to work for the executive chairman. Those are my orders.
So I did that. I was told that strength of the Special Commission
would be in its independence, that the Special Commission could not
be seen as a tool of any country and that I have to help make the
Special Commission independent. I did that. I succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, we needed some new methodologies that we weren't
getting from the United States, so we went to Israel. I went to the
executive chairman (Ekeus) and we raised the issue of approaching
Israel, and he approved.
</P>
<P>
   I have to say that as an American citizen, I went to the U.S.
government and told them that I was doing this and they didn't stop
me. When the relationship really began in earnest starting in July
of '95, everything I did in Israel was approved by the executive
chairman. Everything we did was consistent with the mandate given
by the Security Council. And everything I did was made known to and
approved by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Every step of the way?
</P>
<P>
   A: Every step of the way. Now they didn't agree with a lot of
what I did. They didn't agree at all. They didn't like the idea of
UNSCOM becoming this independent, nor UNSCOM having a capable
partner like Israel supporting us. They weren't happy with this at
all. They tried to stop it every step of the way. But I kept them
informed. I had their approval and everything was approved by the
executive chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was it the CIA that instigated the FBI investigation?
</P>
<P>
   A: The bottom line is that it was the CIA that raised the
concerns. They said that the relationship that Israel and Ritter
had could be an espionage relationship. Even though they knew all
the facts and they approved everything. They turned it over to the
FBI and the FBI ran with it and then it became sort of a
self-continuing effort. Every time I went to Israel, the pile got
thicker. Every time I did my job, the FBI just collected more data,
saying its espionage. It was terrible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did the FBI investigation become known to you?
</P>
<P>
   A: I knew in January, February 1997 that the U.S. had a concern
about the nature of the work and I worked very closely with the
government to try and talk about what their concern was. And it
came down to basically bureaucratic jealousy. You know, I have a
better relationship with the Israelis than they do. They are not in
control. They lost control.
</P>
<P>
   I'm an American. Israel can't have an intelligence relationship
with an American that is not controlled by the U.S. These are their
concerns. I said basically if that's it, then tough luck. Because,
you sent me here to work. You told me to be independent. I'm doing
what you told me to do, and I'm succeeding. So unless you give me a
direct order to stop, and always I'm an American, you give me a
direct order, you say stop, I will stop today. You ask me a
question, I will answer it. I'm not hiding anything from them. But
they never said stop.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can you say about the Israeli officials you met?
</P>
<P>
   A: First is the professionalism. The people I dealt with were
dedicated, professional, smart. When you go down to Washington you
are overwhelmed with the 9 to 5 mentality. There wasn't this 9 to 5
mentality. This was national security. Plus they think out of the
box.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does that mean 'to think out of the box?'
</P>
<P>
   A: In America, you have rules. We're going to address this
problem. Let's read the rules here. They say we can think this, we
cannot do this. That's how we are going to solve this. That's how
we're going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis are: `What's another way of looking at this? How
else can we do this? Let's think of alternatives here. Is there
another way we can solve this problem?' The Israelis were
innovative and courageous in terms of putting forward ideas. They
were not afraid to have an idea shot down. Again, professional. A
level of trust developed.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis looked at me and didn't see a United Nations
official, or an American. It's all professional. It's somebody whom
they can respect, whom can they can work with. That's what
impressed me about them. And the fact that they were always
sympathetic with the cause.
</P>
<P>
   I never once felt when I was over there that I was somehow
imposing on them or somehow inconveniencing them. When I was over
there, we were a team. We were all going for the same cause. We
were working really hard. They are good people.
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1409EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1945 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREUD-CORRECT-WHEN-NY     10-06 2516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREUD-CORRECT-WHEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT FREUD GOT RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By KEN ADELMAN  
 FROM: Washingtonian Magazine  
 &HT;    The 20th century opened with Sigmund Freud publishing ``The
Interpretation of Dreams'' and closes with Freud so controversial
that not long ago the Library of Congress postponed an exhibit on
him. In October the library again hopes to display its large
collection of original Freud works.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, psychiatrists such as Sandra Gail Hershberg practice
Freud's craft and use his techniques.
 &HT;    Born and raised in the Bronx, N.Y., Dr. Hershberg graduated from
New York University and Yale Medical School. After an internship in
pediatrics at the University Hospitals of Cleveland and a residency
in general psychiatry at Mount Sinai Hospital in New York, she
completed a fellowship in child and adolescent psychiatry. She is a
graduate of the Washington Psychoanalytic Institute.
 &HT;    Hershberg specializes in child and adolescent psychiatry, the
psychology of female development, and the psychological dimensions
of medical illness. She lives in Bethesda with her husband, a
physician, and their two adolescent daughters. She enjoys reading
fiction, antiquing, watching old movies and biking.
 &HT;    In her office, lined with Freud's complete works and featuring a
couch, we discussed what she's learned.
 -0 
 &HT;    KEN ADELMAN: What makes Freud so incendiary a century after he
started writing?
 &HT;    DR. SANDRA GAIL HERSHBERG: Three things come to mind. People
today often view psychoanalysis negatively _ as a luxury treatment
that takes a long time and is very expensive. So it's thought that
Freud's method doesn't work any longer. At least, that it's been
surpassed by medication, group therapy, family counseling, or other
techniques. I've found that's wrong.
 &HT;    The psychoanalytic method is alive and well. To me it's an
exciting and meaningful treatment. But it's no quick fix. People
now seek to do everything faster and faster. Western Union's been
replaced by the Internet. So many people no longer have the
patience for psychoanalysis they once did.
 &HT;    Second is this big category summarized as comprising ``women.''
The way Freud viewed women _ as having inferior superegos and penis
envy and all that _ opened him to harsh criticism. I'm with the
critics here. I don't agree with Freud much on this score. Some of
what he said on women has some relevance. But there are much more
complex and productive ways of looking at women and gender than
what he presented.
 &HT;    Third is Freud's treatment of sexual seduction and abuse as a
type of fantasy. He initially did think there was real sexual
abuse, but then switched when he attributed patient accounts to
subconscious fantasies.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What did Freud get right?
 &HT;    A: When considering Freud in his own times _ he was a pioneer,
there was no one before him; he used his cases and his
self-analysis as data _ I'm impressed at how much Freud got right.
Every brilliant individual who makes discoveries makes errors along
the way. Freud made many important contributions.
 &HT;    First and foremost was the nature of the inner life, the
significance and meaning of the unconscious. Freud pioneered the
use of free association. Through his analyses of others and
self-analysis, Freud delineated the concept of psychosexual
development, the child's progression through various developmental
stages.
 &HT;    Unconscious motivation was and is an enormous discovery. It
permeates our lives and culture. Fantasy and creativity are central
to modern life. The fact that we never fully know our less rational
motivation is a staggering insight. Freud developed all that.
 &HT;    Moreover, Freud showed greatness in his willingness to revise
his theories based on new clinical information. He was thus
open-minded in an honest, scientific way. Freud got carried away by
his ideas and his narcissism in deciding to psychoanalyze his
daughter Anna. His putting his daughter on the couch and hearing
her innermost thoughts and fantasies in that way breached an
important boundary.
 &HT;    Clearly Anna Freud identified with her father through her
trailblazing work with children and her defining contributions in
the field of child development and child psychoanalysis.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Was Freud an attack on free will?
 &HT;    A: I don't see it that way. Not at all. Because of unconscious
factors, we make choices on the basis of more than rational free
will. That's true. But Freud's thrust makes one freer, not less
free. For people truly suffering _ as his patients did, as many of
my patients do, and as all of us do from time to time throughout
our lives _ Freud showed us a technique to better understand and
treat conflicts that result in feelings of shame, disgust, guilt,
etc.
 &HT;    Freud frees us by enabling us to be aware of inner connections
and see deeper motivations. That's at least been my experience with
patients. Once they're able to peer into their innermost feelings,
memories, fantasies, they can then make real choices. Freud knew
psychology and biology went together. As a trained neurologist, he
always searched for the biological basis of psychology. The concept
of mind versus brain interested him deeply.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Why should someone choose psychoanalysis over drugs, a
family-systems approach, group therapy or yoga?
 &HT;    A: Pharmacotherapy helps with symptom relief. Drugs can
accompany psychoanalysis or another therapy for someone who's
extremely depressed or with a manic-depressive disorder.
Psychoanalysis works best with patients who suffer from traumas or
other early experiences they haven't integrated well.
 &HT;    It opens up an opportunity to be in a safe situation with
someone committed to exploring such experiences in depth. This
enables the patient to transform internal representations and thus
to act and feel better. They can be freer.
 &HT;    Granted, other therapies do that too. But to me psychoanalysis
provides that help in a deeper and broader way than the other
approaches. It opens a greater sense of meaning and knowing one's
internal motivations.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Do you still use a couch?
 &HT;    A: Yes. I usually sit behind the patient, out of view _ like
Freud. The patient's usually lying down.
 &HT;    Q: What's your average length of treating one patient?
 &HT;    A: More than two years and up to 10 or 12 years _ or more. It
really depends.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: How did you feel as a patient?
 &HT;    A: Undergoing psychoanalysis was an essential part of my
professional training. It had a very important, even dramatic,
impact upon my life and it made me more aware of what the process
is like for the patient. That made me a better analyst because I
both knew myself better and knew what this process was like on the
other side of the couch.
 &HT;    Psychoanalysis made me much more aware of who I am as a person _
what interests me, how I pursue creative interests, act as a
parent, and what I carry from my own childhood which then gets
aroused in me as an adult. Knowing all this, and these responses,
makes me freer to act _ more of being my own person.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Being a parent, I wonder if Freud really blamed neuroses
almost entirely on the mother.
 &HT;    A: Mothers do have a tough time and a tough job. By emphasizing
the importance of early childhood experiences, Freud did put
mothers at the center of traumas and such early episodes. But
remember that in cases like little Hans, Freud focused on the
father as well. I don't see it as being hard on mothers so much as
trying to understand the nature of the conflict in front of him.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Which groups get maddest at Freud?
 &HT;    A: We've all gotten mad at Freud. But too many have treated
Freud as the last word. They expect too much of him. No one gets it
all right. Certainly Freud didn't. By focusing on so many
cornerstones of the theory of the mind, development, and
psychopathology, Freud opened the door for others to modify and
change the theory. I think that even he would embrace that view. He
did change his theories when shown contrary evidence.
 &HT;    Remember, Freud was a man of his time. He was limited by the
milieu and context in which he worked. The field was brand new
then. There wasn't much to go on. Some of Freud's blind spots
reflect that. Many times he went beyond these constraints and made
enduring insights. And that's why he's still prized, and praised.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: You've lectured on creativity?
 &HT;    A: Freud wrote a lot on the subject. His office was full of art
pieces, mostly antiquities. Freud read constantly on art and had
many artistic friends. In a paper analyzing Dostoyevski, Freud
said, ``Before the problem of the creative artist, an analyst must
alas lay down his arms. '' Freud thus recognized that he was at a
loss when analyzing creativity. But then, as on most topics, he
proceed to say a lot on the topic.
 &HT;    Freud writes beautifully. I hope the Library of Congress exhibit
and the resulting conferences will prompt more people to read what
Freud actually wrote, rather than what other people have written
about Freud. Works like ``The Psychopathology of Everyday Life,''
``The Interpretation of Dreams'' and ``Civilization and Its
Discontents'' are accessible to the average person.
 &HT;    One of my favorite essays of Freud's was ``Creative Writers and
Daydreaming. '' There he says, ``The child's best loved and most
intense occupation is with his play or games. Might we not say that
every child at play behaves like a creative writer in that he
creates a world of his own, or rather rearranges the thing of his
world in a new way which pleases him?''
 &HT;    While a child takes play seriously, Freud pointed out that he
``distinguishes it quite well from reality.'' Freud concludes:
``The creative writer does the same as the child's play. He creates
a world of fantasy which he takes very seriously _ that which he
invests with large amounts of emotion, while separating it sharply
from reality.''
 &HT;    Freud goes on in this vein of comparing play and creative
writing. It's a very lovely essay.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What makes creativity?
 &HT;    A: Many artists had an early appreciation of the sensual world.
Sometimes even an early trauma. Edgar Allen Poe's mother died when
he was quite young. Poe saw her body then in all its horror. That
description appears in some of his later stories. Magritte's mother
jumped off a bridge and drowned. You can see that sense of time
standing still and unreal nature in his work.
 &HT;    Many creative people were ill or had a lot of time to
themselves. They then became more aware of their own thinking and
fantasies _ their inner workings. For those of us less gifted, we
must find a way to bring out the creativity within us. I see
psychoanalysis as a very creative act. In that space between me and
a patient, something exceptional happens.
 &HT;    I take in a vast range of images, fantasies and feelings from an
analysis, and I respond on a similar level. It's a most exciting
and creative endeavor. I'm very privileged to be able to help
people in need, to free them from symptomatic behavior.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: How can we increase our creativity?
 &HT;    A: Give yourself time every day when you're not busy with
something else. Allow your thoughts then to flow out. When Freud
was very young, he'd place a blank sheet of paper in front of
himself every day, just to see what would come up. That was a way
to expand his creativity.
 &HT;    You can see how he was always interested in learning about
himself. This led him into the unconscious, being able to connect
with inner thoughts and emotions. That's what creativity's all
about and what psychoanalysis is about.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: You've also lectured on eating disorders. Is that an
upper-class, female adolescent disease?
 &HT;    A: Basically. It's not only teen-agers but young adult women as
well. I've treated so many that it appears to me like a societal
disease.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What causes it?
 &HT;    A: It involves a girl coming to terms with her body, with sexual
feelings, and relationships with each of her parents, particularly
with her mother. She must develop a sense of herself with
confidence _ just who she is in the world. While this sounds like
the adolescent struggle in general, some women are of a
perfectionist bent and more preoccupied with their bodies. They
have more eating disorders than others. But adolescent boys
body-build and strut around. They too fixate on their bodies.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: So why don't they have eating disorders?
 &HT;    A: The incidence of eating disorders in boys is on the rise;
however, our culture emphasizes beauty mostly in the female body.
Look at our advertisements. Girls must look a certain way, wear
makeup, watch every ounce of fat. There's a different emphasis on
the female body for the girl, and for her mother and father, which
is generally less pronounced in boys.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: You've studied women who have careers. Give us lessons
learned there.
 &HT;    A: The opportunities to be fulfilled by one's work are ever
increasing in our society. That's so wonderful. Not that women get
compensated equally for their work _ they don't yet _ but they can
fulfill such ambitions more easily nowadays. That's important. For
working mothers, it's essential to keep open all lines of
communication.
 &HT;    From professional experience I've learned that sometimes my kids
need more of me. Sometimes they need less of me. Occasionally they
don't need me at all, for a while.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Is the incidence of mothers with careers increasing?
 &HT;    A: Yes, but we should look at how the whole family functions in
that household. The real problem arises when one parent becomes so
absorbed that he or she doesn't realize what's missing in the
family.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What have you learned from Freud?
 &HT;    A: The main thing is the primacy of one's inner life. That
determines so much of how we think and behave. As an analyst, I'm
very grateful to Freud for his methodology, which is very much a
part of my way of working and helping others.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What are the main lessons of life?
 &HT;    A: Psychological health is based on the capacities to love, to
work, and to play, as Freud indicated. To be able to maintain a
balance of those abilities makes for a satisfying and fulfilling
life.
 &HT;     c.1998 Washingtonian Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ken Adelman is national editor of Washingtonian Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
