 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: So why don't they have eating disorders?
 &HT;    A: The incidence of eating disorders in boys is on the rise;
however, our culture emphasizes beauty mostly in the female body.
Look at our advertisements. Girls must look a certain way, wear
makeup, watch every ounce of fat. There's a different emphasis on
the female body for the girl, and for her mother and father, which
is generally less pronounced in boys.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: You've studied women who have careers. Give us lessons
learned there.
 &HT;    A: The opportunities to be fulfilled by one's work are ever
increasing in our society. That's so wonderful. Not that women get
compensated equally for their work _ they don't yet _ but they can
fulfill such ambitions more easily nowadays. That's important. For
working mothers, it's essential to keep open all lines of
communication.
 &HT;    From professional experience I've learned that sometimes my kids
need more of me. Sometimes they need less of me. Occasionally they
don't need me at all, for a while.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Is the incidence of mothers with careers increasing?
 &HT;    A: Yes, but we should look at how the whole family functions in
that household. The real problem arises when one parent becomes so
absorbed that he or she doesn't realize what's missing in the
family.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What have you learned from Freud?
 &HT;    A: The main thing is the primacy of one's inner life. That
determines so much of how we think and behave. As an analyst, I'm
very grateful to Freud for his methodology, which is very much a
part of my way of working and helping others.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What are the main lessons of life?
 &HT;    A: Psychological health is based on the capacities to love, to
work, and to play, as Freud indicated. To be able to maintain a
balance of those abilities makes for a satisfying and fulfilling
life.
 &HT;     c.1998 Washingtonian Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ken Adelman is national editor of Washingtonian Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
