<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1947 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIAM-WELD-PROFILE-     10-06 2702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAM-WELD-PROFILE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A WILLIAM WELD KIND OF THING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By FRANK BRUNI  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    It starts the moment Bill Weld steps from the car and seems as
if it will never stop: the craned necks, the raised thumbs, the
exuberant hellos.
 &HT;    As he makes his way into and then through Fenway Park, there is
a new fan at every step, another outstretched hand at every turn.
 &HT;    On this mid-July night in the heart of Boston, the approbation
is as thick as the humidity. ``Can I get a picture of you with my
nephew?'' asks one man, maneuvering the little boy into position.
 &HT;    Weld obliges with a hand around the boy's back, a well-practiced
smile and a wry apology.
 &HT;    ``Sorry about the extra poundage,'' he quips, his free hand
straying toward a belly that's only a tad larger than it used to
be.
 &HT;    There is another man who regales Weld with praise for his six
and a half years as governor of Massachusetts, another who vows
eternal political allegiance to him, yet another who simply wants
to chew the fat.
 &HT;    Finally, Weld reaches his destination: a swath of seats where
more than a dozen colleagues from the blue-chip law firm where he
now works are ensconced, frothy beers in hand, for a ties-off,
wing-tips-unlaced outing.
 &HT;    He takes his seat and looks toward home plate, a white speck,
almost invisible from this remote section deep behind right field.
Strangely, Weld has run a gantlet of adoration to end up far, far
away from the action.
 &HT;    ``Governor Weld,'' shouts a voice from three rows behind him,
``what are you doing all the way back here?''
 &HT;    ``These are the best seats I could get,'' Weld quips. ``When
you're out, you're out.''
 &HT;    Just two years ago, Weld was very much in. He was a popular
second-term Republican governor in a heavily Democratic state. He
had presided over, and certainly contributed to, the state's
transition from economic bust to boom. Pundits touted his brand of
fiscal conservatism and social liberalism as a New Age model, and
Democratic peers emulated it. Journalists anointed him a
presidential possibility.
 &HT;    Then he made one of the most abrupt, astonishing U-turns in
recent political history. Brashly tempting electoral fate, he
challenged John Kerry, a popular Democratic incumbent, for one of
Massachusetts' two seats in the U.S. Senate.
 &HT;    It was a questionable decision, ending in defeat, that Weld
followed with another, more quixotic quest: to become the U.S.
ambassador to Mexico, a post that Jesse Helms, the
ultraconservative Republican chairman of the Senate's Foreign
Relations Committee, almost immediately vowed to deny him. Weld
left office to devote himself to the fight for confirmation. Once
again, he lost.
 &HT;    Now comes another surprise, of an entirely different sort. This
month, Simon &AMP; Schuster published Weld's first novel, ``Mackerel by
Moonlight,'' a political, picaresque tale seasoned generously with
his trademark droll humor. Although Weld is not the first
politician to try his hand at fiction, the book remains an unusual
endeavor, the latest curve ball in a career that has recently been
rife with them.
 &HT;    And it draws renewed attention to a question that has perplexed
observers for some time now: How did William F. Weld, 53, a onetime
golden boy, get from there to here?
 &HT;    One of the most frequently offered answers has to do with Weld's
status as a pro-choice, gay-friendly libertarian in a Republican
Party that does not easily accommodate such thinking. Or, Weld's
exile is chalked up to a few bad decisions.
 &HT;    But the truth is more complicated, and has at least as much to
do with who Weld is on the inside as the world outside him. As
reflected in both the substance and tone of ``Mackerel by
Moonlight,'' which is more ``Primary Colors'' than ``Profiles in
Courage,'' this is a man who has always favored irony over
earnestness, who seems at least as interested in private amusement
as in public service and whose itchy mind demands new adventures in
rapid succession. This is a man, in other words, almost
spectacularly ill suited to the stratagems, tedium and patience
required for sustained political glory.
 &HT;    ``Bill Weld is a guy who likes the bold stroke,'' says Ray
Howell, who worked on Weld's gubernatorial campaigns. ``He likes to
throw the Hail Mary pass. Grinding it out is not something that
appeals to him. Unfortunately, I think grinding it out is often the
successful route for elective politics.''
 -0- 
 &HT;    ``Mackerel by Moonlight'' introduces Terry Mullally, who is both
like and unlike Weld. While Weld grew up on 600 acres on Long
Island and followed his forebears' leather-soled footsteps to
Harvard, Mullally comes of age in Brooklyn and gets his degree from
a city university.
 &HT;    Like Weld, Mullally first makes his name tackling corruption as
a federal prosecutor and ends up in Boston. Unlike Weld, he is a
Democrat, and the elective office he seeks is district attorney.
 &HT;    As the novel tracks Mullally's meteoric rise and all the debris
that falls to earth along the way, it eventually becomes a whodunit
about two mysterious deaths. The title alludes to a pungent
put-down of a successful politician, and of politics itself. Like a
rotting mackerel in the moonlight, the saying goes, it shines and
it stinks.
 &HT;    Jaunty and clever, the book nonetheless seems the byproduct less
of Weld's literary talents than of his name recognition, a more
respectable relative of ``Embrace the Serpent,'' the bizarrely
titled and quizzically received international thriller co-written
by Marilyn Quayle, and ``Murder at City Hall,'' a mystery
co-written by Ed Koch that also left many critics scratching their
heads, if not holding their noses.
 &HT;    It underlines the way in which political celebrity seems to be a
flexible currency that puts Susan Molinari in the anchor chair of a
TV news program and Donna Shalala in milk advertisements.
 &HT;    But ``Mackerel by Moonlight'' is most interesting for what it
says about Weld himself. He began writing it in January 1997,
shortly after his failed Senate bid, when he was still governor
and, according to friends, beset less by disappointment than by
disinterest in the familiar tasks at hand.
 &HT;    His account of its genesis and rapid completion betrays not only
his quicksilver mind but also his elite cultural bearings,
intellectual vanity and ``look, Ma, no hands'' style.
 &HT;    He says the book was born one night as he sat in front of a
blazing fire in his three-story, seven-bedroom house in Cambridge,
reading a description of the way F. Scott Fitzgerald wrote ``The
Last Tycoon'' from an outline. ``I thought, Gosh, it must be easy
to write a book from an outline,'' Weld recalls. So he tried one.
``It took me 15 to 20 minutes.''
 &HT;    He then dictated the narrative onto tapes for his secretary to
transcribe, devoting one day every weekend to the task and
finishing the first draft in eight weeks. His muses, he says,
included Thomas Mann and Graham Greene. As he refined the novel
over subsequent drafts, he kept a careful record of each version,
``just in case some jaundiced observer should suggest there must
have been a ghostwriter somewhere.''
 &HT;    The result offers no life lessons and suggests no particular
conviction, a charge that Weld's political critics have often
levied against him. As the protagonist caroms through a weightless
adventure that clocks in under 250 pages, his emotions remain
inscrutable and his demeanor aloof, very much like his author's.
 &HT;    ``I still have nothing to say,'' Weld explains one afternoon in
his Boston office, referring to a remark he once made about being
intrigued by the idea of writing a novel, but not being able to
identify a message he wanted to get across. ``I'm the guy who hates
politicians who preach at you.''
 &HT;    The next day, the subject recurs as he, his wife, Susan
Roosevelt Weld, and one of his five children, Mary, sit on their
vast, well-shaded lawn.
 &HT;    Susan says she did not actually crack the book but had Mary read
it to her as they drove from Cambridge to New Haven, where Mary
attends Yale. The two-hour drive proved ample time.
 &HT;    ``It's a bagatelle,'' Weld confirms.
 &HT;    ``Large print,'' his wife chimes in.
 &HT;    ``Generous margins,'' Weld adds.
 &HT;    The exchange captures Weld's charm: his occasionally
self-effacing humor, his banter. But it also suggests the lack of
gravitas that made his political career so offbeat and unlikely,
and arguably curtailed it.
 &HT;    Mary Weld, enjoying tiny spoonfuls of brownie batter
interspersed with mincing sips from a quart of milk, weighs in with
her own appraisal. ``I'm glad it has no moral,'' she says. ``A
moral would be pompous.''
 -0- 
 &HT;    Weld's tenure as governor from 1991 to 1997 was so successful
that observers often forget how improbably he squeaked into office,
and how much his personal wealth and fortunate circumstances
mattered.
 &HT;    Back in 1990, when he first ran, he was a leaden public speaker.
He had never held any elective office, and while his experience as
a high-ranking member of the U.S. Justice Department in the 1980s
gave him law-enforcement credentials, he was untested on other
issues. At their convention, state Republicans endorsed his rival
in the primary, Steven Pierce.
 &HT;    Howell remembers, ``I couldn't get reporters to come to a
campaign event if I promised that Bill Weld would be biting off the
heads of chickens.''
 &HT;    But Weld pumped about $1 million of his own money into his
primary campaign, handily outspending Pierce. And primary voters
gambled that Weld's liberal social views _ arising from his
distaste for bigotry or any other limit to individual expression
and potential _ gave him a better chance against the eventual
Democratic nominee than Pierce had.
 &HT;    Weld won the primary and then, in the general election,
capitalized on voters' exasperation with the state's economic woes
and their willingness to try a change from decades of Democratic
leadership. He narrowly defeated a weak opponent, John R. Silber.
 &HT;    This was not the triumph of a man with a potent sense of calling
or long history of political involvement. Although his years as a
classics major and law student at Harvard coincided with the
activism of the late 1960s, Weld was largely unmoved by it.
 &HT;    He approached the job of governing with a similar insouciance,
keeping bankers' hours and seldom missing his thrice-weekly
appointments on the squash court. Once, after signing a bill to
protect waterways, he dove, fully clothed, into the Charles River.
Visitors to his office spotted a stuffed armadillo near his desk.
``I like creatures who are slow and stupid,'' Weld explained.
 &HT;    For Massachusetts voters, Weld's levity and sublime confidence
was a welcome relief after Gov. Michael Dukakis' severe
prognostications. Moreover, he got the job done. Leading the
national charge to trim welfare programs and generally rein in
government spending, he reduced taxes while finding ample money for
education and the environment.
 &HT;    All the while, he had the cooperation of a Legislature still
controlled by Democrats. In 1994, he was re-elected with a
staggering 71 percent of the vote. But aides said he was bored and
had limited interest in serving out a second term.
 &HT;    So he set his sights on the Senate, then the ambassadorship,
which dovetailed with his curiosity about international affairs.
Aides advised him that if he were looking toward the presidency,
such a job change and gambit were madness. Weld ignored them.
 &HT;    ``He's not ambitious in the way most politicians are,'' explains
Marty Linsky, his chief secretary from 1992 to 1995. ``The stuff
that most politicians care about it not important to him. He wants
to have a good time. He wants to have fun. He wants to be engaged
all the time, but his definition of engagement is different from
most people's, like sitting at the end of a dock in the Adirondacks
reading Greek.''
 -0- 
 &HT;    The Welds seem to have their own obscure sources of amusement.
While others regarded the war of words between Weld and Helms last
summer as a stomach-churning embarrassment for the Republican
Party, the Welds pronounce it a grand diversion.
 &HT;    As Weld tells it, he ran into Helms months later and told the
senator that he wanted to buy him dinner, because Helms was the
reason he was working as a high-priced lawyer and could afford to.
When Helms responded that he usually ate at home, Weld turned to a
companion and exulted, ``Senator Helms has just invited me to his
house for dinner!''
 &HT;    Weld guffaws at the memory. ``Senator Helms was waving his arms,
'No, no, no,''' Weld says. So there was never a trip to Helms's
house, for dinner or anything else. ``No jammy party,'' Weld sighs.
 &HT;    Although he assumes that what he calls the ``apostasy'' of his
liberal social views helped fuel Helms' opposition to him, he
steadfastly refuses to bash either Helms or the religious right.
That would imply that they rattled him, and it's not at all clear
that that's possible.
 &HT;    Besides, Weld says that he's happy now _ that there's more
``intellectual content'' in his current legal work advising venture
capitalists and private equity firms than there was in his second
term as governor.
 &HT;    And he has already finished the first draft of a sequel to
``Mackerel by Moonlight.'' It took him seven days instead of eight.
 &HT;    Beyond that, he is maddeningly hazy about his future, quite
possibly because he is waiting to feel the next tickle of his
fancy. Friends say he once eyed the presidency and probably, at
some level, still does. When questioned directly, Weld gives
answers that seem deliberately opaque.
 &HT;    The year 2000, he says, is out, but if the Democrats win again
and there is no plausible Republican challenger with moderate
social views in 2004, ``it's not so clear I'll be free to cultivate
my own garden.''
 &HT;    But by forcing a confrontation with his own party for a
dubiously prominent position in a Democratic administration, he
came across as disloyal, to the point where a shot at the
presidency seems impossible, and a Republican president might be
disinclined to consider him for the kinds of Cabinet posts he once
discussed with President Clinton's advisers.
 &HT;    ``Politically,'' said Greg Mueller, a Republican political
consultant, ``he's in no man's land.''
 &HT;    Even if he weren't, it's doubtful that Weld could ever muster
the conventional sincerity for the ultimate political prize.
 &HT;    ``Bill Weld is the mirror opposite of Bill Clinton,'' says
Stuart Stevens, a Republican media consultant. ``Clinton tries to
become you. He's like some sci-fi creature who wraps around you and
sucks out your energy. Weld is a guy who knows who he is and is
very comfortable with himself. He doesn't take himself that
seriously.''
 &HT;    At the end of the game in Fenway, which the Boston Red Sox win,
Weld is briefly elated, then instantly intent on finding a route
over the Charles, and into Cambridge, that circumvents traffic. His
demeanor is rapt as he barks out directions _ left, right, faster,
slower _ that brilliantly do the trick. He's home in a flash.
 &HT;    It's not much of a journey, or much of an accomplishment, but it
seems to give him great pleasure. He walks off into the night with
a bounce in his step.
 &HT;     c.1998 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Frank Bruni is a Metro reporter for The New York Times.) &LR;
</P>
