<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-THERAPISTS-CLINTON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE SEX THERAPISTS SAY ABOUT CLINTON-LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By REBECCA JOHNSON  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    It may not feel like it now, but some day America may look back
on the Starr report as a publishing event as significant as the
Kinsey report was in its day.
 &HT;    True, it is a crudely sketched morality play, but it has given
the American public and the descendants of Kinsey _ the sex-advice
columnists, the researchers and the therapists whose job it is to
explain us to ourselves _ an unprecedented opportunity to examine
our attitudes about sex.
 &HT;    In the same way that a traumatic life event propels someone into
therapy, where he discovers much of what he believed true to be
false, the scandal has exposed the steady undercurrent of sexual
hypocrisy running through many marriages.
 &HT;    Politicians (other than Dan Burton, Helen Chenoweth and Henry
Hyde, of course) may be shocked, shocked to learn that people have
sex out of marriage, but they shouldn't be.
 &HT;    Studies of married people's sexual habits show again and again
that adultery is quite common. According to the 1992 Janus Report,
two out of three married men, and one out of three married women
have had an extramarital encounter _ figures that are backed up by
Kinsey and other national sex surveys.
 &HT;    The experts say the reasons are obvious. Sex may get deeper,
more emotional, more spiritual and certainly more convenient with
the person you wake up to every morning, but it does not get
hotter.
 &HT;    According to Judith Seifer, a therapist, sex-advice columnist
and past president of the American Association of Sex Educators,
Counselors and Therapists, ``Sexual boredom is the most pandemic
dysfunction in this country. Think of sex as an appetite. Now think
about having to eat the exact same meal every day for the rest of
your life _ of course you'd get bored.''
 &HT;    Judy Kuriansky, who has dispensed love and sex advice for 18
years as ``Dr. Judy'' on her nationally syndicated radio call-in
show, says, ``'How do I keep the passion in my marriage alive?' is
by far the most common question I hear.''
 &HT;    Throw in the biologists who correlate a need for novel sex with
the presence of testosterone and the outlook for long-term monogamy
in any marriage is dim. Turn on the talk shows, read the
editorials, listen to the radio and you hear a lot of outrage. How
could he? But if sexual boredom is as rampant as everyone says, how
could he not? Indeed, some columnists think this could be an
excellent moment for America to rethink its sexual paradigm.
 &HT;    Perhaps every age gets the advice it deserves. Once, the market
was cornered by Ann Landers and Abigail Van Buren. The Iowa-born,
kindly, aphoristic twin sisters imprinted generations of Americans
with the kind of values that promised to make the center hold:
marriage, monogamy and the like. But the center did not hold.
 &HT;    Divorce rates soared. AIDS spread. Jerry Springer beat Oprah in
the ratings, and then came the Clinton scandal _ the public
response to which suggests that Americans are a lot less prudish
than they perhaps used to be.
 &HT;    With changing times came changing advice _ meaner, funnier, more
frank. And of all the new Miss Lonelyhearts to be found on cable or
the Internet or in the alternative press, none is blunter or more
libertine than a syndicated columnist whose name _ real name _ is
Dan Savage.
 &HT;    To one reader who wrote: ``I am an androgynous spirit. Sex to me
means spirituality, tenderness, kindness, loving another human
being as myself. ... Call me a freak, but that's my libido,''
Savage replied: ``Your 'libido' sounds really evolved. You, on the
other hand, sound like a drip.''
 &HT;    Savage says that the mess this country has made over the
Lewinsky affair can be traced directly back to our wrongheaded
thinking about love, sex, marriage and monogamy.
 &HT;    ``The sexual model that straight people have created doesn't
really work,'' he says. ``All it does is force people to lie.''
Savage, who is gay and whose collection of weekly columns, ``Savage
Love: Straight Answers From America's Most Popular Sex Columnist,''
was just published, says that to gay people monogamy is not a
monolithic all-or-nothing concept, and he thinks the rest of the
world could learn from that model.
 &HT;    ``In this society, we view monogamy like we view virginity,'' he
says, ``one incident and it's over, the relationship is destroyed _
but we should view monogamy like we view sobriety. You're sober.
You might get completely drunk one night, but you can get sober
again. You can get monogamous again.''
 &HT;    Indeed, Savage thinks our pity for Hillary Clinton is misplaced.
``We don't know what Bill and Hillary's agreement is,'' he says,
``and we will never know. She might not like sex. I don't feel
sorry for her. She's grown-up. She's smart. They have some sort of
arrangement, and who are we to say whether it's good or bad? I
think they are more mature about sex, like they are about drugs,
than they can let on.''
 &HT;    You would be hard pressed, however, to find a mainstream
sex-advice columnist who embraces adultery as an antidote to sexual
boredom. Not even James Petersen, a senior editor at Playboy who
wrote the magazine's advice column for 20 years. ``We don't endorse
it,'' Petersen says, ``but we accept that it's part of human
nature.''
 &HT;    In this era of neo-Darwinian sociobiology, some of the morally
conservative advice dispensers have even tried to apply scientific
principles to adultery. ``It's a medical fact that monogamy and
intimacy are what make people happy,'' says Drew Pinsky, M.D., aka
``Dr. Drew,'' co-host of MTV's ``Love Line,'' a nightly call-in
love-and-sex advice show that pairs Pinsky with a comedian
sidekick.
 &HT;    Says Seifer: ``I don't know if monogamy is a natural way to
live. It's a product of social organization, but it's essential for
the way our society is organized, both emotionally and for the
passage of property. In my practice I rarely find people who have
had affairs say they would do it again.''
 &HT;    What sex therapists do suggest, almost universally, is that
couples ``work at it'' when the passion goes. But the standard
resuscitation techniques advocated _ massage, videos, romantic
getaways and, who can forget, ``Meet your husband at the door
wrapped in Saran Wrap'' _ can be more deadly than the boredom.
 &HT;    And if the fireworks fail to ignite, then what? ``My advice is
always, 'Challenge the relationship,''' Petersen says. ``'Bring out
the whips and chains and if that doesn't work, leave.'''
 &HT;    Savage, on the other hand, thinks that as a culture we oversell
the importance of sex in a long-term relationship.
 &HT;    ``The way we talk about sex destroys a lot of perfectly decent
relationships,'' he says. ``Read Cosmo magazine, listen to Jenny
Jones. The whole culture reinforces these infantile ideas about
sex. You have to burn with sexual passion for your husband for 60
years or your relationship is over.''
 &HT;    We are, he says, ''laying down the dialogue that destroys these
relationships. When we talk about trying to bring the divorce rate
down, maybe we should do it by creating a society where we don't
insist a relationship is over when the sexual passion is gone. I
know gay couples who have been together for 35 years. They have
separate bedrooms. Sometimes they sleep together and sometimes they
sleep with other people, but they're a great couple. Who are we to
say: 'You're busted! You're not a couple anymore because you're not
having sex'?''
 &HT;    As the advice dispensers explain, for Hillary Clinton's
generation, the kind of behavior Lewinsky exhibited to snag the
president's attention reads as slutty and even unbalanced. But
women Lewinsky's age were weaned on the postfeminist notion that
``slut'' is a sexist term, a mixed message that encourages men to
compartmentalize what they need from women: one for companionship,
another for sex.
 &HT;    The Monica Lewinskys of the world grew up believing ``nice
girls'' do _ her therapist actually wrote a book with that title.
``Girls like Monica learned their sexuality from Madonna,''
Petersen says. ``They bought their underwear from Victoria's Secret
catalogues. Flashing it is nothing to them. It's the sort of thing
you might see in a Sprite ad.'' And one thing ``nice girls'' do in
the 1990s is oral sex.
 &HT;    The generation gap on this issue is startling. In a nationwide
study released in 1994 _ The Social Organization of Sexuality _
21.1 percent of women ages 25 to 29 said they found giving oral sex
``very appealing,'' but only 7.2 percent of women ages 50 to 54
said the same. Some women much older than that don't even know what
it means.
 &HT;    I was watching CNN with my 92-year-old grandmother, a lady if
there ever was one, on the day that Lewinsky testified before
Starr. She turned to me after the phrase ``oral sex'' had been
mentioned for the hundredth time and said, ``I guess that means she
stimulated him with her imagination.''
 &HT;    Society, of course, did not go from thinking oral sex was
perverted to embracing it in one great leap.
 &HT;    Attitudes changed incrementally beginning as far back as the
turn of the century with Havelock Ellis, moving forward to Alfred
Kinsey in the '40s and Masters and Johnson in the '60s. They also
occasionally go backward, as in the moral conservatism of ``Dr.
Laura'' Schlessinger, the radio personality.
 &HT;    It was, however, people like Xaviera Hollander, aka ``the Happy
Hooker,'' who has written an advice column for Penthouse magazine
since 1972, and Ruth Westheimer in the '80s, who first talked about
sex in everyday, sometimes salacious terms, who made dialogue about
sex truly accessible to the public.
 &HT;    ``Dr. Ruth was this tiny woman who said 'penis' with a German
accent and a giggle,'' Seifer says, ``and that's who we were
willing to hear about sex from.''
 &HT;    And now a growing number are willing to hear about it from
Savage. He draws letters from men and women, straight, gay and
bisexual _ all of whom want to hear what a rude anything-goes
columnist has to say about their sex lives. He explains his slow
convergence with the mainstream this way: ``The gay response to
AIDS forced everybody to start talking about what they were
physically doing in bed. It forced the newspapers to write honestly
about sex.''
 &HT;    At the same time, experts say, the generation of young
heterosexuals who grew up with the specter of AIDS has pushed the
envelope of what's considered kinky. In analyzing the results of
Playboy's college sex surveys, even Petersen was surprised by what
young people do these days.
 &HT;    ``They had to redefine safe sex, so they ended up doing things
it took me 20 years to do,'' he says. ``You name it, they've done
it _ whips, chains, Wesson oil, making videos.''
 &HT;    People who find Clinton's sexual behavior debauched are,
according to some therapists, buying into the idea that anything
other than missionary-position sex is shameful. And that, they say,
is where sexual dysfunction begins.
 &HT;    ``All sex is about power,'' says Allison Glock, the sex-advice
columnist for GQ magazine. ``Ultimately, someone is on top and
someone is on bottom.''
 &HT;    When clients go to Seifer complaining that sex is boring, she
says it is usually because of fear and shame that they have
absorbed from some source, often religion. You lose your
self-consciousness in sex by either feeling totally loved and
accepted, or not really caring what the other person thinks. It's
why so many men prefer to indulge their more far-out or just plain
selfish fantasies with prostitutes instead of their wives.
 &HT;    ``I think Hillary could be a powerful sexual partner,'' Petersen
says, ``but I don't think the president can see it. It's too much
like being in bed with your law partner for him.''
 &HT;    In the end, it is impossible to know how the scandal will affect
the future of sex relations in America. Petersen calls it the
``last chapter of the sexual revolution,'' but says that maybe it
will be good for us. As he says, scandals have a way of dragging
important issues into the public _ Anita Hill gave us sexual
harassment; perhaps this will give us honesty in relationships.
 &HT;    As Seifer says, ``Most people find it easier to have sex than
talk about it.''
 &HT;    Indeed the nation has clearly been traumatized by the endless
parsing of the sexual relationship between the president and
Lewinsky. In his own way, Savage draws a conclusion: ``If we were
all honest about our sex lives,'' he says, ``the republic would
crumble. This just confirms that people have a right and a
responsibility to lie about it.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Rebecca Johnson  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Rebecca Johnson is a contributing editor at Vogue magazine.) &LR;
