<SLUG> BC-MUTUAL-FUNDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVERAGE MUTUAL FUND INVESTING SLID 15 PERCENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter where they turned, investors who put their money in
stock mutual funds couldn't escape the turmoil in financial markets
over the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   The average fund investing in U.S. stocks slid 15 percent, the
worst quarterly showing for stock funds in eight years, according
to Lipper Analytical Services in New York, which tracks fund
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Gains earlier this year lessened the pain somewhat. Stock funds
have fallen an average 6.4 percent for the 12 months ended Sept.
30.
</P>
<P>
   Losses were even worse for those who invested in funds putting
their money in smaller companies _ where the typical fund was off
21 percent in the quarter and 20.6 percent for the year _ or
international funds, where losses averaged 16.2 percent in the
quarter and 10.7 percent for the year ended in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of your investors have just given up the ghost,'' said
money manager Gerald Perritt, editor of The Mutual Fund Letter in
Largo, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The one safe haven that investors found was in bond funds. The
average domestic long-term bond fund was up an average 1.4 percent
in the quarter and an average 7.2 percent in the year ended in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a flight to certainty in an uncertain time,'' said Rob
Schumacher, chief investment strategist at the Van Kampen Focus
Portfolios in Chicago, a mutual fund. ``I'm not going to make any
money on a 4.29 percent treasury, but I know it's going to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The poor showing by stock funds in the quarter showed that
investors couldn't depend on the stock-picking skills of portfolio
managers to shield them from the market rout.
</P>
<P>
   The losses were less in funds where the money is automatically
allocated into a portfolio that matches the benchmark Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index. These index funds fell an average of 10
percent in the quarter, 33 percent less than the typical U.S.
equity fund, and chalked up an average gain of 8.5 percent in the
year ended in September.
</P>
<P>
   It was a case of big stocks performing better than small stocks
because the S&AMP;P index is dominated by large companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest stocks held up better,'' said Scott Cooley, a fund
analyst at Morningstar in Chicago, a fund research firm. ``Active
managers tend to pick mostly smaller companies.''
</P>
<P>
   And small stocks got killed in the quarter, even though analysts
were predicting a revival from a previous downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Small-capitalization funds swooned an average 21.5 percent in
the quarter and an average 20.6 percent in the year ended in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``There continues to be a penalty for investing in companies
with market capitalization below the largest,'' said A. Michael
Lipper, president of Lipper Analytical.
</P>
<P>
   But then, small stocks tend to do worse than large stocks in
market downfalls, Cooley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, when the market turns down, small caps get hit
worse,'' he said. ``They tend to be a little more volatile.''
</P>
<P>
   The much touted technique of investment diversification failed
investors in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   International funds tanked an average 16.2 percent in the third
quarter and an average 10.7 percent in the year ended in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some real carnage in this stock market and the
more diversified you've been across stocks, probably the worse your
portfolio performance,'' Perritt said.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian financial crisis, which has spread to Russia and Latin
America, decimated stocks in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   European Region funds were down an average 17.3 percent in the
third quarter but were up an average 3.4 percent for the year ended
in September.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese funds dropped an average 9.4 percent in the quarter,
but they suffered severely in the long term, skidding a whopping
23.3 percent for the year ended in September.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging markets funds, which invest in companies in developing
countries, took an especially huge hit, the victim of the global
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Those funds dived an average 23.6 percent in the quarter and an
average 46.5 percent in the year ended in September.
</P>
<P>
   Latin American funds plummeted an average 29.4 percent in the
quarter and lost more than half their value _ an average 50.2
percent _ in the year ended in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-term declines in Latin American funds and emerging
markets funds are approaching depression levels,'' Lipper said.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles facing funds investing in emerging markets haunted
financial services funds as well.
</P>
<P>
   Those funds, which were last year's leaders, dived an average
19.2 percent in the quarter but were off only an average 1.7
percent in the year ended in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decline is significant because the prior gains in
financial stocks have been driving some general equity performance
for some time,'' Lipper said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' fear of bad times came out in the performance of gold
funds, which rose an average 4.3 percent in the quarter and led all
stock funds for the first time since the first quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gold funds were spurred on by an extraordinary 42.93 percent
gain in September,'' Lipper said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors flee to gold in turbulent economic and political times
because they perceive it as a store of value.
</P>
<P>
   Gold funds' gain came at a price, with an awful 33.4 percent
decline for the 12 months ended in September.
</P>
<P>
   Lipper was cautiously optimistic that stocks are due for a
comeback. He titled his fund report, ``First the Valley, then the
Rally.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock funds have fallen more than 10 percent in 12 quarters
since the beginning of 1960, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In nine of those 12 periods, general equity posted a positive
return in the following quarter,'' Lipper said.
</P>
<P>
   However, stock funds are now up an annualized 13.7 percent in
the last five years, closer to the 35-year rate of 12.1 percent, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary risk is that after many years of above-average
gains, we may be due for year of below-average gains,'' Lipper
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
