<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORIAMOS-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORN-FLAKY GIRL: TORI AMOS ON HER GAME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE CRAWFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With Tori Amos, you either get it, or you don't.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, she has a gorgeous voice, clear and supple. On
the other, she spends so much time in the upper ranges that it's
almost impossible to understand the lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, a good many of those lyrics are just plain
goofy anyway. On the other hand, she has a way of connecting raw
emotions to her words in such a way as to create something of an
epiphany, especially with female fans.
</P>
<P>
   Count me, a guy, among those who don't get it. But that doesn't
mean I can't appreciate the kind of performance Amos delivered
Saturday night at the Cynthia Woods Mitchell Pavilion north of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Her mix of performance art, high classical/jazz inflected
compositions, and bombastic rock 'n' roll doesn't always translate
on her recordings. But in the live setting, with room to cavort and
project her expansive and playfully coy stage presence, she comes
across as a true rock goddess.
</P>
<P>
   The constant cascade of high-pitched screams from the decidedly
distaff audience affirmed that point.
</P>
<P>
   The best moments of the show came with Amos' more controlled,
conventional songs, especially on ``Spark,'' ``Playboy Mommy''
(both from her latest work, ``from the choirgirl hotel'') and
``Cornflake Girl.'' These songs find Amos laying down a solid
repeating piano hook and hanging exotic rhythms and other
instrumentation on the foundation. The result is a hypnotic musical
crescendo.
</P>
<P>
   Other moments weren't so stellar. More than a few of Amos'
compositions fall in a rote quiet-crashing-quiet again format, with
tempo and chord changes thrown in seemingly at random intervals.
After about five or six of these compositions in the same vein,
they become a headache.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Amos was otherwise on her game Saturday,
particularly on a couple of lovely, grim songs performed solo
(especially the powerfully melodramatic ``God''). And she ended her
main set with one of the most thrilling examples of over-the-top
Baroque musical theater I've experienced, the swirling, menacing
``The Waitress.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish trio the Devlins opened the show with a satisfyingly
downcast batch of well-constructed guitar-pop songs. The Devlins'
tunes are a swirling mix of folk and Southern jangle-rock coupled
with somber, love-lost lyrics sung by charismatic (and exceedingly
polite) frontman/guitarist Colin Devlin.
</P>
<P>
   His remarkably clear and supple voice translated well into the
live setting, soaring above the band's crystalline compositions.
With numerous critical plaudits for their latest album,
``Waiting,'' the Devlins are definitely a band to watch. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Crawford is a free-lance writer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
