<HEADER>
A1972 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THIRDEYE-MUSIC-REVIEW     10-06 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIRDEYE-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK GROUP EYES BLIND AMBITION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Third Eye Blind lead singer Stephan Jenkins snickered
like a smart-aleck school boy who had just pulled the wool over the
principal's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dirty, filthy song,'' he told the sell-out crowd _
many of them school kids themselves _ Friday night at the Woodlands
Pavilion. ``That means that all of you must be dirty, filthy,
too!''
</P>
<P>
   The band then kicked into Third Eye Blind's breakthrough hit
``Semi-Charmed Life,'' a disjointed little tale of sex, drugs and
rock 'n' roll disguised by a maddeningly catchy ``doot doot doot''
chorus.
</P>
<P>
   You get the sense that Jenkins imagines himself a rock frontman
and songwriter in the tradition of the Who, the Clash and U2 _
big-statement bands that weren't ashamed to admit their own
ambitions. And after a decade of tortured grunge rockers trying to
reconcile punk ideals with pop megastardom, Jenkins' charismatic
cockiness comes across as a refreshing contrast.
</P>
<P>
   If only he and his band could do more to justify that ambition.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``Semi-Charmed Life,'' Third Eye Blind's
self-titled debut album has spawned a slew of modern rock radio
hits _ ``How's It Going to Be,'' ``Graduate,'' ``Jumper.'' At a
time when modern rock is desperately seeking a new direction to
take the place of faded flannel, these songs present a commercially
palatable alternative to wimpy folk-pop on the one hand and
metallic shock-rock on the other.
</P>
<P>
   The band performed on a stage designed to resemble the
dilapidated warehouse nightclubs where Third Eye Blind came up
playing in San Francisco. The show opened with the musicians
silhouetted behind a heavy curtain, like shadows from a bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins sang one song seated in an overstuffed chair, and
another skipping around with his arms in the air. An unplugged
segment found all four members huddled together strumming acoustic
instruments. On the radio hits, the audience sang along in almost
ritualistic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   While Jenkins is the group's visual focal point, guitarist Kevin
Cadogan is most responsible for Third Eye Blind's chunky
instrumental sound. Bassist Arion Salazar and drummer Brad
Hargreaves bring a semi-anonymous professionalism to the rhythm
section.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins nodded to his classic rock inspirations by tagging a
verse of the Who's ``Baba O'Reilly'' on to the end of ``How's It
Going to Be.'' He also made a sincere but lame attempt to
reinterpret Ice Cube's rap ``It Was a Good Day'' as a rock song.
The encore, introduced by Cadogan as ``the first song I ever
learned to play on guitar,'' was U2's ``I Will Follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Twenty years from now, some young guitar player might
say the same thing about Third Eye Blind's ``Semi-Charmed Life.''
But I doot-doot doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   Eve 6 opened the show with a set of songs from its self-titled
debut album, including the No. 1 modern rock hit ``Inside Out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern California trio was signed to a recording contract
while still in high school, with an unusual stipulation of ``no
diploma, no deal.'' Once bassist/vocalist Max Collins and guitarist
Jon Siebels graduated, they hooked up with drummer Tony Fagenson
(son of noted producer/bassist Don Was) and set to work on their
debut album.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a charmed life; Eve 6 played with the same spirit at
the Woodlands Pavilion they might have brought a post-game backyard
beer bash, only tighter. And they did it without snickering. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
