<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ TIRANA, Albania _ Humanitarian aid groups are
meeting here on Tuesday to come up with a plan on housing the tens
of thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees from fighting in
Yugoslavia's neighboring Kosovo province as the region's brutal
winter approaches. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NORFOLK _ NORFOLK, England _ When a resident of Norfolk,
England, complained that her town was boring, her life quickly
became more interesting than she might have hoped. She got death
threats and is now under police protection. (Campbell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SENATE _ WASHINGTON _ With midterm elections less than four
weeks away, both parties are bracing for the possibility of a sharp
shift of power in the Senate, one that could determine the fate of
Bill Clinton's presidency. If Republicans gain five seats for a
total of 60 senators, Democrats would no longer be able to delay
legislation with a filibuster, or win compromises by threatening
one. (Shepard, Cox News Service 550&AMP;add).
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-BARBOUR _ Former Republican National Chairman Haley
Barbour offers advice about how Democrats should campaign this
fall. (Barbour 200).
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-MORRIS _ Dick Morris, a former pollster for President
Clinton, offers advice about how Republicans should campaign this
fall. (Morris 200).
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-DATA _ For a graphic, the latest polling data on nine
battleground races.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-POLITICS _ WASHINGTON _ America Online, the nation's
most popular online service, unveils a new site for political
information Tuesday. As midterm elections near and the nation
prepares for an early start of the 2000 presidential race, the
Internet is offering much more _ and more sophisticated _ political
information than ever before. An overview. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-DATA _ A political junkie's tour of the top Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   SELFTAX _ WASHINGTON _Two tax law experts say the Atlanta-based
Southeastern Legal Foundation may have violated its tax-exempt
status with a fund-raising appeal that was too closely allied with
the Republican party. The 22-year-old public interest law firm has
recently raised its profile by challenging in federal court the
Clinton administration's plans to use statistical sampling to get a
more accurate count of minorities in the 2000 census. But a letter
from Amos McMullian, a foundation board member and chief executive
of a south Georgia baking company, soliciting money for the lawsuit
may have crossed the line that keeps charities out of political
activities, the tax experts said. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)..
</P>
<P>
   STARR _ At 9:15 a.m., the grand jury, investigating the
allegations regarding President Clinton and former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky, hears new testimony. Meanwhile the
Republicans on the Judiciary Committee meet. (Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GOPADS _ WASHINGTON _ Far outspending their Democratic
counterparts, the Republican House leadership is launching a $7
million family-friendly TV ad campaign in more than 50
congressional districts. The cost of this one project equals the
entire issues ad budget of the Democratic House campaign committee.
Yet Democrats say their candidates will have enough money to
compete in the Nov. 3 midterm elections. A look at the amount spent
in Georgia. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NET-POLITICS _ WASHINGTON _ America Online, the nation's most
popular online service, unveils a new site for political
information Tuesday. As midterm elections near and the nation
prepares for an early start of the 2000 presidential race, the
Internet is offering much more _ and more sophisticated _ political
information than ever before. An overview. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-DATA _ A political junkie's tour of the top Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JEWEL-THIEF _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sentencing today for jewel
thief Alvaro Valdez and his fence, Barry Marshall. They are accused
of stealing jewelry worth millions from heiress Kathleen Ford's
home in Palm Beach. (Ellicott, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   CERABINO-CATS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Local news column on the
wild cats at the Flagler Museum in Palm Beach. (Cerabino, Palm
Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   DIVERSITY _ Ford Foundation releases nationwide poll (with
samples in Georgia and five other states) on key issues relating to
diversity in higher education, including effects of academic
standards of courses in diveristy, diversity in student body, role
of diversity education in preparing students to enter the
workforce. Among participants in the Atlanta release are William
Chace, Emory president, Walter Massey, Morehouse College president,
and MLK III, president of the SCLC. (Suggs, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   STAMPS _ It's taken Atlantan Milton Murray nearly three decades
to convince postal officials to honor philanthropists with a stamp.
But today (Oct. 7) a new 32 cent stamp will be released at a
ceremony at the Atlanta Mariott Marquis. The presentation is part
of this year's annual symposium on ``planned giving''. (Henry,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8-10. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving in (l) Lifestyle category.
</P>
<P>
   UT-PRESIDENT-SPEAKS _ UT President Larry Faulkner gives his
first major campuswide address today on the ``State of the
University.'' The speech follows a symposium at which faculty,
staff and students discuss what they want to UT to be like two
decades from now. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   GARWOOD-IRRIGATION _ Austin and other cities near the Colorado
River will not need to search for new sources of water until 2090
if state regulators approve a $75 million purchase of water rights
today. The Garwood Irrigation Co., which serves rice farmers near
the Gulf of Mexico, has agreed to sell its considerable water
rights to the Lower Colorado River Authorityfor the highest price
in Texas history. Before the LCRA can begin closing the deal, the
sale needs approval from the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission _ and that could come at this morning's commission
meeting. (Lindell, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTNING-STRIKE _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ James Zimmerman could
still feel the twitch in his right side, as though someone were
jolting him with electrical bolts. The feeling is the reminder of
that moment on Tuesday that Zimmerman became one with some 100,000
volts of electricity and lived to tell the tale to an audience who
could no more identify with it than they could describe the dark
side of the moon. (Harmon, The Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
