<HEADER>
A1988 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-VIOLENCE-HNS &LR;      10-06 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SUGGESTS SAME-SEX VIOLENCE ON RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The number of domestic violence cases among
same-sex couples surged both nationwide due largely to increased
reporting of abusive situations, according to a report released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The second annual survey by the National Coalition of
Anti-Violence Programs also found that while community outreach and
services have improved greatly, police response to same-sex
domestic violence is sometimes misguided.
</P>
<P>
   Based on reporting from the coalition's member organizations in
12 cities, including in San Francisco, the survey found a 41
percent increase last year in gay, lesbian, bisexual and
transgender victims of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, reported cases surged by 67 percent from 1996
to 1997, accounting for 27 percent of all cases in the national
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We attribute that not to the magnitude of the problem, but
rather, increased information and services have translated into
people in our community being willing to seek assistance for
domestic violence,'' said Greg Merrill, director of client and
advocacy services for Community United Against Violence. ``The real
change is people are coming forward.''
</P>
<P>
   There was not a big gender gap: male victims accounted for 52
percent of cases and female victims 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another conclusion of the report was that restraining orders
provide the best legal remedy to abuse victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our clients indicate to us after they've gotten a
restraining order, the person leaves them alone because they
realize there are going to be sanctions against them if they
continue,'' Merrill said.
</P>
<P>
   Restraining orders are also invaluable in summoning the police
in an emergency situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see some homophobia, but mostly what we see is an inability
(by the police) to detect who they should arrest,'' Merrill said.
``Some police officers think, if it's two men or two women, it's a
fair fight and they shouldn't get involved. Or they arrest the
bigger one or the one who is, quote unquote, the more masculine
one.''
</P>
<P>
   In one extreme case in San Francisco, officers handcuffed the
victim to his batterer and put them in the same jail cell, Merrill
said. With a restraining order, it is immediately obvious to the
police who the aggressor is, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The violence survey was far from scientific: it depended on
self-reporting from member organizations in 12 cities. Those
organizations serve less than 20 percent of the U.S. population.
Those groups with the largest staff and funding _ in San Francisco,
Los Angeles and New York _ reported the highest number of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a review of past studies and their own experience,
victim advocates say that domestic violence is just as prevalent in
gay relationships as in straight ones. They also have seen no
difference in the frequency, severity or patterns of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But because most services are geared toward heterosexual
couples, it is difficult for male victims and female batterers to
get counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Many gays and lesbians accept the widely held belief that
domestic violence occurs only in heterosexual relationships,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, seven states exclude people in same-sex
relationships from getting restraining orders: Arizona, Montana,
Louisiana, South Carolina, Virginia, New York and Delaware.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
