<SLUG> BC-TECH-JOBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH JOB GROWTH SPREADS BEYOND SAN JOSE, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While the San Jose area remains far and away
California's undisputed high-tech employment center, San Francisco,
Sacramento, Fresno and the Vallejo-Napa region are quickly becoming
``cybercities.''
</P>
<P>
   A report released Monday by the American Electronics Association
indicates the state's high-tech industry has moved well beyond
Silicon Valley, so that it is no longer ``a geographical state but
a state of mind,'' AEA spokesman John Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Using the most recently available data from the Bureau of Labor
Statistics, the report shows the San Jose metropolitan area
employed 221,000 high-tech workers in 1996, representing nearly
one-third of the 724,000 high-tech jobs in California. The average
annual wage for technology workers in Silicon Valley was $72,000,
57 percent more than wages in the private sector as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   The second-largest metropolitan area in total high-tech
employment was Los Angeles, with 147,000 jobs and an annual wage of
$51,000; followed by 81,000 in Orange County, 53,000 in Oakland and
52,000 in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles was the state's largest high-tech employer in a
number of key industry segments, including consumer electronics,
defense electronics and information services, the ``California
Cybercities'' report found.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said the real-time 1998 employment figures are most likely
up from the 1996 data despite recent or planned layoffs in the
semiconductor and semiconductor equipment sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs in software ``are still going gangbusters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the job growth beyond Silicon Valley _ and the
positive economic ripple effect it creates in other regions _ that
is the centerpiece of the AEA report.
</P>
<P>
   Today's electronics and information technology companies have
created thousands of new jobs with rapid employment growth between
1990 and 1996 in emerging high-tech metropolitan areas. During that
period, the number of jobs were up 56 percent in Sacramento,
followed by Fresno (54 percent), Vallejo-Napa (46 percent), San
Francisco (37 percent) and Santa Cruz (28 percent).
</P>
<P>
   After the San Jose/Silicon Valley average high-tech wage high of
$72,000, San Francisco was No. 2 at $66,000. The average in Santa
Cruz was $61,000, followed by $57,000 in Oakland and $55,000 in
Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that high-tech employment in Northern California
totaled 377,000, just ahead of Southern California at 313,000.
</P>
<P>
   It also found that one of every four jobs in Silicon Valley is
in high tech. Statewide, there was a 12 percent increase in
high-tech jobs _ from 197,000 in 1990 to 221,300 in 1996. Average
annual wages increased 29 percent in the same period _ from $55,600
in 1990 to $71,900 in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
