<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW THE DEMOCRATS CAN WIN
 &HT;    With SENATE and SENATE-MORRIS.
 &HT;    By HALEY BARBOUR
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many experts are predicting a record low turnout in
November, so these elections will be decided by who actually votes.
The Democrat strategy, therefore, will be aimed at inflaming and
turning out the liberal base Democrat vote, while secondarily
trying to convince swing votes that Republicans in Congress have
accomplished nothing because of their determination to ``get
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat message will attempt to achieve both goals
simultaneously. They will lament the impeachment process as
partisan and political, while doing everything they can to make it
as rancorous and partisan as possible. On legislation, they will
stall, complain and blame.
</P>
<P>
   The union bosses will try to turn out the Democrat base vote.
While polling shows Republican voters are more likely to turn out
than Democrats, unions will try to overcome this GOP advantage with
untold millions for phone banks, direct mail, paid organizers and
Election Day ``street money.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Big Labor will be liberal groups, ranging from trial
lawyers to radical environmentalists, from pro-abortion
associations to ethnic political organizations. The Left's goal is
to transform the disgust and disillusionment felt by Democrats
toward Clinton's conduct into anger toward Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Haley Barbour was chairman of the Republican Party from January
1993 to January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
