A2031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-MORRIS07-COX     10-06 0240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-MORRIS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW THE REPUBLICANS CAN WIN
 &HT;    With SENATE and SENATE-BARBOUR.
 &HT;    By DICK MORRIS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican candidates should let the Earth move
under their feet
</P>
<P>
   without trying to help it along. The Clinton impeachment
proceedings will energize the GOP base and will provide both lift
and loft for Republican candidates all by itself. Any candidate who
tries to help it along by addressing the issue directly will look
too partisan and will seem to be exploiting a national agony for
political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   GOP candidates should take advantage of the hidden weakness in
Clinton's armor _ the fact that he doesn't have an agenda. He has
done what he came to do, and doesn't have much left for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans should wage largely positive campaigns highlighting
their own issue proposals. They should focus on how they would
address traditionally Democratic problems like education,
environment, child care, the concerns of the elderly and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Such a strategy has three advantages: it co-opts Democratic
issues; it shows a positive reason to vote Republican, and it
subtly emphasizes that Clinton can't get anything passed even if he
wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Morris was a pollster and political adviser to President
Clinton until August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
