NYT-10-06-98 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2033 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE07-COX     10-06 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELECTION'S CENTERPIECE IS STRUGGLE FOR SENATE
 &HT;    560&AMP;add. With SENATE-MORRIS, SENATE-BARBOUR and SENATE-DATA.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With midterm elections less than four weeks away,
both parties are bracing for the possibility of a sharp shift of
power in the Senate, one that could determine the fate of Bill
Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans gain five seats for a total of 60 senators,
Democrats would no longer be able to delay legislation with a
filibuster, or win compromises by threatening one.
</P>
<P>
   Such a gain would also leave the president little room to wiggle
out of an impeachment noose.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely the GOP can raise their Senate number to 67, the
two-thirds required by the Constitution to convict an impeached
president. But a filibuster-proof Senate will embolden Republicans
_ and perhaps even Democrats who fear for the future of their party
_ to remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   That means Clinton's fate rests with voters in nine battleground
states where the Senate races are ``in play'': California,
Colorado, Kentucky, Nevada, New York, North Carolina, South
Carolina, Washington and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome in each state could come down to which party gets
their supporters to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic turnout tends to lag behind that of Republicans in
midterm elections. A recent Gallup poll found 73 percent of
Republicans are extremely or very likely to vote in November,
compared with 63 percent of Democrats. Other polls have had similar
results.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ``can't wait to get to the voting booth to send a
message to Clinton,'' said Glen Bolger, a Republican pollster with
Public Opinion Strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Clinton's sex-and-veracity scandal is putting
extra pressure on the president's party to turn out its voters.
``Democrats have to concentrate on winning the 'ground' war versus
winning the 'air' war,'' said Fred Yang, a Democratic pollster with
Garin-Hart-Yang.
</P>
<P>
   Few candidates are openly raising the scandal as a campaign
issue in the battleground states. National Journal, an influential
magazine on politics and public policy, recently found campaign
advertising in this year's election overwhelmingly oriented to
issues, not Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``it's definitely an environment that can't hurt us,''
said Mike Russell, spokesman for the National Republican Senatorial
Committee (NRSC), a party organization that provides money and
advice to GOP Senate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four Senate seats are on the line this year, most of them
held by Republicans. But Democrats are bucking historic trends that
favor the opposition party in a president's sixth year in office.
Even the popular Ronald Reagan lost eight Senate seats in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The political math in the Senate is undoubtedly in the GOP's
favor. The equation begins with 55 for the GOP. Add Republican
gains in Ohio, where popular Gov. George Voinovich, a Republican,
is leading comfortably in the race to succeed retiring Sen. John
Glenn, and in Illinois, where Democratic incumbent Carol
Moseley-Braun is badly trailing GOP right-winger Peter Fitzgerald.
Then subtract the Republican-held open seat in Indiana, where the
popular Democratic Gov. Evan Bayh is expected to take back the seat
his father, Birch Bayh, lost in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   That would give the Republicans 56 seats. If the parties hold
their seats in other states, the GOP could gain a filibuster-proof
Senate majority by winning just four of these nine close races:
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add that follows could run along
with SENATE-DATA graphics material.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  California, where Democratic incumbent Barbara Boxer, one of
the Senate's most liberal members, is neck-and-neck with State
Treasurer Matt Fong, a Reaganite advocate of supply-side economics
and opponent of abortion who has chided his opponent for not being
more critical of Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Colorado, where Democrat-turned-Republican Ben Nighthorse
Campbell is being challenged by former Colorado first lady Dottie
Lamm. Campbell's opposition to gun controls has become a hot issue
because of recent violence in Denver schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kentucky, pitting Republican Rep. Jim Bunning, a former major
league baseball star who has built a near-perfect conservative
voting record during six terms in Congress, against Democratic Rep.
Scotty Baesler, a tobacco grower and former college basketball star
with a moderate record in three terms in Congress. They are vying
for the seat of retiring four-term Democrat Wendell Ford.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nevada, where two-term Democratic incumbent Harry Reid is
being challenged by Rep. John Ensign. The mild-mannered Reid, who
tried to be a peacemaker between the administration and Western
ranchers in a fight over grazing fees, has built a
moderate-to-liberal record in the Senate. Ensign, with family ties
to the state's hotel and gambling industries, was part of the 1994
Republican class that came to power with House Speaker Newt
Gingrich's ``Contract With America.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New York, where Republican incumbent Alfonse D'Amato is
seeking a fourth term in a mostly Democratic state. His challenger
is Charles Schumer, a nine-term House member who has been a staunch
critic of Gingrich and the National Rifle Association. D'Amato is
wily, a brilliant tactician and a master of New York's
tabloid-and-TV culture. But Schumer is his match at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  North Carolina, where 70-year-old Republican incumbent Lauch
Faircloth, who frequently attacked First Lady Hillary Clinton
during Whitewater hearings, faces 45-year-old trial lawyer John
Edwards, a telegenic political newcomer who is running as a
Washington outsider.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  South Carolina, where veteran Democratic incumbent Fritz
Hollings is facing his toughest challenge in a state that is as
solidly Republican as any in the country. His challenger is
three-term Rep. Bob Inglis, who, as a member of the House Judiciary
Committee, has been highly critical of the president's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Washington, pitting Patty Murray, the ``mom in tennis shoes,''
whose surprise election in 1992 heralded the ``year of the woman''
in American politics, against Rep. Linda Smith, one of the leading
voices in the Republican's revolutionary freshman class of 1994.
This race, more than any other, could turn on voters' attitudes
about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wisconsin, where freshman Democratic incumbent Russell
Feingold faces a challenge from Rep. Mark Neumann, another member
of the GOP class of 1994. Feingold is best known for his
co-sponsorship of campaign finance reform measures, while Neumann
has shown unusual zeal in cutting government spending, even at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
