<SLUG> BC-LIVING-COLUMN-HAHN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EACH RAY COUNTS BEFORE DAYLIGHT FADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With less than three weeks to go before our return to
standard time, I'm trying desperately to save some daylight. But
most days lately seem to end with a race between the stock market
and actual daylight, trying to see which one can close down faster.
</P>
<P>
   After carping that I'd used my hammock on only three brief
occasions this summer, I took a colleague's advice and stretched
out to enjoy one of our last sunny afternoons on the back deck.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone rang five times in 90 minutes, and I hung the darn
hammock and the phone back on the wall. With daylight and dry
weather vanishing, the 10 gallons of deck sealer probably won't be
applied until the next clear warm day . . . next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Daylight-saving time seems like a good idea to kids who want
summer days to last longer, and to middle-age columnists who can't
seem to read all the newspapers out on the porch swing before the
sun goes down. When I was a kid, during World War II,
daylight-saving time went all year. And some cities and states
continued to shift back and forth onto daylight-saving time in the
summer even though the railroads operated on their own clock, which
created a lot of problems.
</P>
<P>
   The passage of time, whether 24 hours or a phase of your life,
is a matter of perspective. The rest of the world is worried about
whether their computers will make it into the next millennium. I'm
trying not to worry about making it through the La Ni &UR; gftilde &LR; na
winter.
</P>
<P>
   With the warm, dry summer, I finally have managed to grow some
ripe red tomatoes. But I barely have enough time to pick and eat
them. I would seize the day, except that most of it seems already
to have flown while I am bent down tying my shoes. And if I stop to
smell the roses, sometimes I forget where I was going.
</P>
<P>
   I was poring through Sunday's paper for the best prices on snow
tires and discovered that Gene Autry and Roddy McDowall had died.
And I wondered if there was any point in getting a 70,000-mile
warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of you, I have that ``organ donor'' thing on my
driver's license, but if they parted me out tomorrow, there
wouldn't be a whole lot anyone could use again.
</P>
<P>
   This is a state of mind, this realization that the autumn of
your life is not a long-play CD. As you get older, everything seems
to be on fast forward. Everything, that is, except you.
</P>
<P>
   By what might generously be termed the far side of middle age,
most folks should learn to take things a bit slower. And some
things actually seem better when slowed down. Of course, you know
that I am referring here to hot showers and teeth-flossing.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the past several years have I truly appreciated what my
late father used to say about how a certain biological function was
a sure sign of a good day. Parents _ most usually mothers _ have a
way of bringing up certain subjects in everyday conversation as
though everyone subscribes to the importance of bran cereal and
prunes. But it's taken me this long to appreciate that my dad was
right.
</P>
<P>
   Fading daylight-saving time and creeping middle age alter your
perspective as well as affect your eyesight. Not only do street
signs and road maps become more difficult to read, but police
officers, doctors and movie stars all appear to have just graduated
from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Car and real estate salesmen look incredulous when you tell them
that the vehicle they're trying to sell you costs more than your
first house, or that the house they're trying to peddle costs more
than you could pay in your lifetime. Like, who cares about that
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes time to readjust the clock to standard time, I
remember the old adage about ``spring ahead and fall behind,'' and
I'm happy it's fall because I don't think I've got the oomph to
spring anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hahn is a P-I staff columnist. He can be reached at
206-448-8317 or e-mail him at jonhahn(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
