<P>
   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SF-NORTH-BEACH (San Francisco) _ North Beach is a gentle old
Italian neighborhood that ambles up the hill from the Bay in the
shade of Telegraph Hill. Only 30 years ago the small streets were
lined with butchers who made their own sausage and its bakeries
supplied every Italian restaurant in town. But by the early '80s it
was impossible to go into any of the neighborhood places without
being bombarded by a standard lament: The neighborhood was
disappearing. Storefronts stood empty, one by one the restaurants
started to close, and even the cafes seemed sad. The people who
loved North Beach began to anticipate its demise. And then,
something remarkable happened: North Beach reinvented itself
through food. By Ruth Reichl.
</P>
<P>
   OFF-THE-MENU (Undated) _ When Michael Eisner, the chairman of
Disney, goes to La Grenouille, he doesn't look at the menu. Doesn't
have to. The chef, Daniel Orr, designs a meal just for him. And
when Ronald O. Perelman, the chairman of Revlon, dines at Harry
Cipriani he almost always has roasted halibut served with a slab of
tomato, capers and oregano. It is prepared for him alone. At the
same restaurant, Oscar de la Renta, the clothing designer, orders
riso alla valenziana every single time he comes. Never mind that it
doesn't happen to be on the menu. In fact, that may be the point,
as some restaurant observers believe: treat the royalty royally and
they will return time and again, adding a less than subtle glitz to
the restaurant's cachet. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: On one level, it is
absurd, even insulting, to try to reduce an entire cuisine to a few
ingredients. But, in fact, so many of the world's exciting cuisines
do have signature combinations and flavors. With just a handful of
Thai ingredients, nearly all of which are available in most
supermarkets, dishes found in the typical neighborhood Thai
restaurant can be duplicated or improved upon. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
