<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      10-06 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPRECIATING A ROYAL BIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 This is the last of eight columns by Charlie Palmer, chef and owner
of Aureole in Manhattan. Judith Choate collaborated. Next week: the
first of eight columns by Francois Payard, the chef and owner of
Payard Patisserie in Manhattan.  
 By CHARLIE PALMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Unlike most of today's outdoorsmen, my dad hunted and
fished for sustenance rather than sport. As soon as we were old
enough, my brothers and I joined him in the fields and forests of
upstate New York, bringing home deer, rabbit, pheasant, partridge
and a host of other game birds.
</P>
<P>
   But it was only years later, as I trained to become a chef, that
I learned truly to appreciate the complex flavor of game. And now,
as it becomes more widely available in the market, game is becoming
more popular among home cooks who aren't living as close to the
land as I once did.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most game animals are raised on farms or in game
preserves. It's true: farm-raised game and game birds do not have
the subtlety of flavor of those taken in the wild. But they do have
some advantages: they have a more assertive flavor than more
familiar poultry, they are lean and they allow the cook to prepare
game throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   At the table, pheasant has a long history as the king of game
birds, notably in classic French preparations like braised pheasant
with wild mushrooms. Like all royalty, though, it requires careful
handling.
</P>
<P>
   Pheasant, particularly the breast, quickly loses moisture when
it is roasted. Instead, I like to give it a quick searing at high
heat, which seals in the juices and creates a crisp crust.
</P>
<P>
   Muted, earthy kale and cabbage make a fine complement in flavor
and texture. When they are young and tender, these hardy greens
make splendid foils for delicate game. To add a little
sophistication, I finish the dish with a subtle pan sauce of sweet
sherry and pungent shallots infused with thyme, citrus and mint.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the dish is a balance of the straightforward and the
sophisticated, delicate and hearty: humble greens and royal bird. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PHEASANT BREAST WITH HARDY GREENS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   \ cup plus 3 tablespoons shelled pistachios
</P>
<P>
   { pound fresh kale
</P>
<P>
   6 boneless pheasant breasts, with skin
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons corn oil
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 cup rich chicken stock or low-sodium canned broth
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 pound savoy cabbage, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 sprigs fresh thyme, for garnish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Spread pistachios on baking
sheet, and bake until slightly crisp and brown, about 5 minutes.
Set aside. Bring large pot of water to boil. Add kale, and blanch
for 10 seconds. Drain immediately, rinse with cold water, and drain
again. Set aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Season pheasant breasts with salt and pepper to taste. In
large saute pan over medium heat, heat corn oil, and add breasts
with skin sides down. Sear until a crisp, golden crust forms, 6 to
7 minutes. Turn, and sear the other side for 4 to 5 more minutes.
Remove breasts to warm platter, and cover lightly with foil to keep
warm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Return saute pan to medium heat. Add 3 tablespoons minced
shallots and the minced thyme. Saute until shallots are softened,
about 2 minutes. Add sherry, and stir to deglaze pan. Raise heat to
medium-high, and simmer until sherry is slightly reduced, about 3
minutes. Stir in chicken stock, reduce heat to low, and simmer for
4 minutes. Whisk in 4 tablespoons butter, a tablespoon at a time,
until smooth sauce forms. Adjust salt and pepper to taste, and keep
warm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. In large saute pan over medium heat, melt remaining 2
tablespoons butter. Add remaining 2 tablespoons shallots, and saute
until they soften, about 2 minutes. Add cabbage, kale and salt and
pepper to taste. Reduce heat to low, and saute until greens are
wilted and well coated with butter. Add \ cup pistachios, and toss
to mix. Remove from heat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, place an equal amount of greens in center of each
of six warm dinner plates. Place pheasant breast on top of each
plate of greens. Drizzle pan sauce over pheasant and around edge of
plate. Sprinkle each plate with some of remaining pistachios. Stick
thyme sprig into each pheasant breast, and serve immediately. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1551EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
