<SLUG> BC-PAC-BELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC BELL FACES UPHILL BATTLE TO ADD LONG-DISTANCE SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pacific Bell should not yet be entitled to offer
long-distance service because the company has made little progress
in proving it has opened its local network to competitors, state
regulators said.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released late Monday, the state Public Utilities
Commission said Pacific Bell has met only four of 14 federally
mandated requirements to become a long-distance player.
</P>
<P>
   The report is considered crucial to the company's chances of
cracking the long-distance market. The PUC gathers next month to
vote on whether to recommend Pacific Bell as a long-distance
carrier, and if it votes no, it is unlikely that the Federal
Communications Commission would approve the company's entry into
the long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   In July, after the PUC's initial review of Pacific Bell's
long-distance application, the commission stated that the company
had only satisfied three of the 14 criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (report) paints a very dismal picture of Pacific's
repeated efforts to keep out competition,'' said Charles Carbone,
telephone analyst at Utility Consumers Action Network, a watchdog
group in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But Pacific Bell has said repeatedly it has opened its local
phone market to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Blase, the company's regulatory vice president, issued this
statement: ``We were disappointed that the (PUC) staff report did
not reflect today's highly competitive market and the significant
progress that Pacific Bell has made to open the door to full
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission has concluded that Pacific Bell has met the
following conditions established by the federal Telecommunications
Act of 1996: It has given competitors access to phone poles and
cables; has provided competitors access to groups of phone numbers;
has allowed customers to use their existing phone numbers if they
transfer service to another phone carrier; and has developed resale
contracts in which competitors can achieve sufficient rates of
return on phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC report asserts that competitors aren't going after
residential customers because Pacific Bell has made it difficult
for challengers to get access to customers, Carbone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pacific is proactively keeping competitors out of the
residential market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell, which is owned by SBC Communications Inc. in San
Antonio, stood by its claim that its competitors are more
interested in serving big businesses than consumers.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 5, the PUC is scheduled to vote on whether Pacific Bell
should be allowed to offer long-distance service. Should the PUC
not give the company the go-ahead for long-distance service, the
company can reapply.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no regional Bell operating company has been allowed to
offer long-distance service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
