<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are considering
for Page 1, Wednesday, Oct. 7. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
paryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Democratic leaders struggle to
maintain unity in opposition to the Republican resolution for an
impeachment inquiry. By Lizette Alvarez and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHARGES (Washington) _ The version of Starr's report
provided by David Schipper, the Republican counsel on the House
Judiciary Committee, served one purpose: choosing charges easier to
prove than Starr's, but with potentially less gravity. By Alison
Mitchell and Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ With a deadline three days away,
Congress is moving ahead on appropriations bills. Looking at what
is in each of the unfinished measures. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHIEFOFSTAFF (Washington) _ The new White House chief of
staff is likely to be John Podesta, a wiry, wry devotee of the
X-Files and conspiracy theories who has been at the center of the
White House conspiracy alleged by Ken Starr. In turning to him
rather than to an outside heavyweight like George Mitchell, Clinton
will be picking a longtime damage-control expert with ties to the
Hill who is widely respected, if also feared, within the White
House. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CRISES (Washington) _ President Clinton is confronting a
severe global economic crisis and the worst domestic political
crisis of his career simultaneously. The world's top economic
policymakers are meeting in Washington as Congress weighs the
president's fate. So far, the American economy has not been
substantially affected by the chaos in Europe, Asia and Latin
America, and Clinton's political prospects may hinge on whether he
can construct a firewall around the domestic economy. How are the
two parallel crises affecting each other and what do the finance
ministers and central bankers have to say about Clinton's ability
to manage the two problems? By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DEBARTOLO-BRIBE (Baton Rouge, La.) _ Eddie Debartolo, whose
family owns the San Francisco 49ers, agrees to plead guilty and pay
a large fine in exchange for testifying against Louisiana's former
governor Edwin W. Edwards after a long investigation of riverboat
casino licensing. DeBartolo will agree to testify that he paid
$400,000 to Edwards to get the last riverboat gambling license in
the state. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Belgrade) _ U.S. envoy Holbrooke visits the
province of Kosovo and then returns to Belgrade for more talks with
Yugoslav President Milosevic. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Kosovo and the Primakov Effect:
Reflecting a harsher line under its new prime minister, Russia vows
to veto any U.N. plan for military action in Kosovo. By Celestine
Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Richard Butler, the top U.N.
weapons inspector, gives his semi-annual report, and the
International Atomic Energy Agency its annual report on Iraqi
compliance. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-CLINTON (Washington) _ Developments at the IMF-World Bank
meeting: Clinton speaks again, saying it's time for ``urgent
steps'' to stop the global economic crisis from spreading. By David
E. Sanger.
</P>
