<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2256 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR-CONTROVERSY-HNS     10-06 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-CONTROVERSY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSY OVER SCOPE, COST OF STARR INVESTIGATION COULD MEAN END
OF INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN DRAKE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the House of Representatives begins taking
action on Kenneth Starr's impeachment recommendations, the
controversy over the scope and cost of his investigation could mean
the end of the independent counsel law, at least in its present
form. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; After taking over the investigation of the president from
Robert Fiske in 1994, Starr has looked into a number of matters,
including Whitewater, the White House travel office firings,
unauthorized use of FBI files, and the president's affair with
Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office last week estimated the total cost
of the investigation at about $40 million, second only to Lawrence
Walsh's six-year, $47.4 million review of the Iran-Contra scandal
during the Reagan administration. Starr's share of those costs was
pegged at $33.5 million through March 31 of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of an independent counsel investigation almost always
means it will be expensive and time-consuming because the subjects
are such powerful and well-protected government officials,
according to several former special prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not surprising that it costs a lot to investigate people
who are bound and determined to fight the investigation at every
turn,'' said Joseph diGenova, who investigated a State Department
search for Clinton's passport file before his November 1992
election. ``This is what the independent counsel law envisioned,''
he contended.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't helped, diGenova said, that Starr has ``been met by
one of the most massive obstructions and delay tactics I've ever
seen.'' He contended that the administration's tactics were
primarily responsible for the length of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, who also faced considerable stonewalling from Reagan
officials and had to deal with the additional burden of an
investigation that dealt with highly classified information, said
Starr has not even hit ``the end of his road yet,'' in terms of
investigation costs, and will probably spend at least another $5
million or $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   He listed several challenges that cause high-priced
investigations: the independent counsel and staff must start from
scratch, as opposed to normal prosecutors who have a wealth of
files and information on their subjects; the prominence and
position of the investigation's target brings a great deal of
intense and formidable opposition; and the investigation's
directive generally requires every avenue of criminal possibility
to be explored.
</P>
<P>
   The high cost can be deceptive as well, according to Dan
Pearson, who investigated Commerce Secretary Ron Brown until his
death in a plane crash in Bosnia in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsels often use agents from other areas of the
government, such as the FBI or Internal Revenue Service. They are
paid through the special prosecutor's budget, but in the end it is
still the federal government paying their salary, Pearson said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Trout, who worked with Pearson on the Brown
investigation, had a more critical view Starr's probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the sense they've got to go down every rabbit hole
without necessarily exercising the sort of judgments prosecutors
normally routinely exercise in evaluating what leads they ought to
investigate,'' Trout said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether the blame for the length and cost of the
investigation lies with Clinton or Starr, there likely will be no
Office of Independent Counsel by this time next year if
congressional sentiment remains intact.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy generated by Starr's investigation and the fact
that both parties have now seen administrations of their own under
the relentless scrutiny of independent counsels could mean that the
Ethics in Government Act, originally passed in 1978 in the wake of
the Watergate scandal, will not be renewed by Congress next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh would rather the statute be revised, with two major
changes.
</P>
<P>
   An Independent Counsel only should investigate matters related
to criminal misconduct in the course of official government duties,
and should only investigate those in the offices of the president,
vice president or attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of criminal acts prior to office, such as
Whitewater, or civil misconduct, such as the Paula Jones sexual
harassment suit, should have their statute of limitations extended,
Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   That way, a president can deal with the business of the country
while in office and face prosecution once he's out, when it doesn't
matter to the functioning of the nation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   DiGenova sees no such room in the political process for an
independent counsel, and Trout calls it ``a fourth branch of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Office of the Independent Counsel may pay an
even higher cost than its current tab of hundreds of million of
dollars for almost two-dozen investigations over the last 20
years. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
