<HEADLINE>
TAKE THE YANKEES, JERSEY: DOM'S HAS MOVED TO SOHO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af) 
By FLORENCE FABRICANT  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The creaky wooden floors and the array of sausages
and salamis hanging over the meat counter make Dom's look as if it
had been in SoHo for 100 years. But the store, one of the few
places in New York that make their own cured meat products, is a
newcomer, having moved from Union City, N.J., to 202 Lafayette
Street (Broome Street) earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Neapolitan-style sopressata, the meaty little cacciatorini
(available plain or marinated in olive oil) and the Genoa-style
salami are especially good. The salamis, available sweet and hot,
are mildly salted and very meaty.
</P>
<P>
   It is essential to slice them _ or have them sliced _ paper thin
or they will be chewy. There is also an excellent cotechino garlic
sausage to stew with lentils. The sausage products are mostly $6.99
to $10.99 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, non-Italian sausages including boudin,
merguez and chorizo will be available. The store also sells meats:
leg of lamb is $4.99 a pound, short ribs of beef are $2.99 a pound
and Black Angus strip loin steaks are $7.99 a pound. The store
carries produce as well, along with cheeses, breads, some seafood
and packaged Italian products. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grace's Marketplace, 1237 Third Avenue (71st Street), has
expanded and for the first time is selling fresh meat and seafood
in a sparkling new tiled area. In addition to run-of-the-steer
steaks, the meat department carries buffalo strip steaks, $23.99 a
pound; Argentine beef fillets, $13.99 a pound, and, soon, Kobe
beef.
</P>
<P>
   Sal Salpietro, the manager of the seafood department, says he
plans to concentrate on European varieties like whole branzino,
$9.99 a pound, and Italian scampi, $25 a pound. Norwegian salmon
fillets will be $13.99 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of the store have been reorganized, allowing for a
larger cheese department near the front and a produce section that
is 50 percent bigger and has more organic items. More checkout
counters now line the 71st Street side.
</P>
<P>
   The prepared food area has also been dressed up. The smoked fish
counter is larger, and among the unusual items it now carries are
big fresh duck eggs, 99 cents each. And there will be an espresso
bar for a snack on the spot, just to the left of the entrance. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dinner tables in American homes are being set with glasses for
wine or beer at a slowly increasing rate. Eating Patterns in
America, an annual survey conducted by the NPD Group, a market
research company in Port Washington, N.Y., showed that for the
first time, alcoholic beverages, primarily wine and beer, were
served with dinner slightly more often than coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol was served in 3.5 percent of homes, barely inching ahead
of coffee, at 3.4 percent. In 1990, alcohol was on the table in 2.5
percent of homes surveyed, and coffee in 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Balzer, a vice president of the company, predicted that
alcohol consumption at dinner would keep rising because of
publicity about the health benefits of moderate alcohol
consumption. People 45 and older are the ones drinking more, with
17 percent of them consuming alcohol with dinner at least once in
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, based on diaries kept for two weeks in 2,000 homes
nationwide, lasted a year, ending in February 1998. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Bonte's pastry shop has been a delicious destination on
the Upper East Side for 25 years. But the lease for the shop, at
1316 Third Avenue (75th Street), expires this month. Bonte said
that the landlord wanted to increase his annual rent from $87,000
to $145,000, and that he had offered $144,000 but had heard nothing
back. The building's owner, Jaminco Management of Glen Rock, N.J.,
refused to comment. Bonte said he was determined to stay open at
least until the year-end holidays. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Community Research Initiative on AIDS will benefit from an
evening of browsing Chelsea art galleries, sipping Lillet aperitifs
and nibbling neighborhood-restaurant interpretations of artworks
Thursday from 6 to 9 p.m. Tickets, $30, from (212) 924-3934 or at
the Lillet Gallery, 531 West 21st Street, Thursday night. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate and more chocolate at the Culinary Institute of
America in Hyde Park, N.Y., on Sunday from 1 to 5:30 p.m. will
benefit the Junior League of Poughkeepsie. Tastings and cooking
demonstrations cost $20, $10 for those 4 to 12: (914) 471-5330. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Would-be romantics take note. Rick Moonen, the chef of Oceana,
will teach how to prepare dinner for a date on Oct. 14 at the
Culinary Loft, 515 Broadway (Spring Street). Chivas Regal is
sponsoring the 6 to 9 p.m. class to benefit Share Our Strength,
which supports groups that feed the needy. Tickets, $75: (877)
244-8277 (toll-free). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tastes of the food of Brooklyn, from Gage &AMP; Tollner crab cakes
to Junior's cheesecake, will be offered on Oct. 15 from 6:30 to
8:30 p.m. at Brooklyn Eats, an event in the New York Marriott
Brooklyn, 333 Adams Street (Tillery Street). Tickets, benefiting
the Brooklyn Chamber of Commerce, are $50 in advance, $75 at the
door. For $75 in advance ($100 at the door), admission will start
at 5 p.m. Reservations: (212) 239-6200.
</P>
</TEXT>
