<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATH RELIES HEAVILY ON DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A recommendation on checking the NFL standings:
Don't undertake this activity without the help of Dramamine. You're
bound to get a little dizzy when you see ``New Orleans _ 3-1'' in
black and white.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco 49ers are sharing the top spot in the NFC West
with the New Orleans Saints. The Atlanta Falcons are up there, too.
Things are getting cramped, and the Niners have to be wondering
what happened to the league's zoning laws. Or the loitering
statutes, which might be more applicable.
</P>
<P>
   The Niners should be able to shoo the Saints away this weekend,
when the two co-leaders meet in the Superdome. But could it be that
the Saints really belong where they are, that in the NFL of 1998,
they're above the pitiful average?
</P>
<P>
   There are crazier truths out there. Consider some of Sunday's
winners at quarterback: Bubby Brister, Donald Hollas and Jason
Garrett, in place of John Elway, Jeff George and Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make your eyes cross and then you turn on the
television Monday night, and there's Randall Cunningham, the
Minnesota Vikings' cryogenically preserved backup, frolicking at
Lambeau Field, having his name held up alongside Joe Montana's.
</P>
<P>
   What does it all mean? Two things, only one of which is
guaranteed to hold up. Minnesota is really, really good (no
guarantee). The NFC East really, really isn't (or your money back).
</P>
<P>
   While the Saints are sneaking into a gated community, the entire
NFC East, once the province of kings, has become a slum.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when the Cowboys, Giants and Washington Redskins were
handing off Super Bowl appearances every year, as if the whole NFC
race were their own relay? When they wore one another out and
elevated one another at the same time? When only the Cardinals were
a breather, because they also had to get past a tough Philadelphia
team with a young nimble quarterback named Cunningham who was
supposed to be the next great one, maybe the new Montana, but it
never worked out?
</P>
<P>
   Well, now here's what it's all come to: The Dallas Cowboys lead
the division because somebody has to be in first place. How did
Garrett win on Sunday? He faced Washington and the esteemed
signal-caller Trent Green, who is cheating destiny by not toting a
clipboard. And he faced coach Norv Turner, who is cheating destiny
by not working for someone else. Neither he nor the Bears' Dave
Wannstedt should ever have left his job as Jimmy Johnson's
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile against the Philadelphia Eagles, the Denver Broncos
could afford to shelve a battered John Elway and start Brister,
plus let Terrell Davis cool his smoking feet after just one half.
They still beat the winless Eagles by almost four touchdowns,
42-16.
</P>
<P>
   Hollas' victim was the Arizona Cardinals, whose last-minute
clock management rivaled that of the folks overseeing the 1972
Olympic basketball final between the Soviets and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But this was probably destiny. The Oakland Raiders, you see, own
the NFC East. All three of their wins have come against that
division (Giants, Cowboys, Cardinals.) They still have Washington
on the schedule, which assures Oakland of matching last year's four
wins. Given that the Indianapolis Colts head to Oakland this
weekend, it's a reasonable bet that the Raiders will top their 1997
win total.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pity that they can't simply switch divisions. Theirs,
once again, is a minefield. If Denver can dominate without Brister,
and if Kansas City can beat a good Seattle team behind Rich Gannon,
who keeps turning up behind center the way your mother's leftover
casserole used to pop up on the dinner table ... well, then either
the AFC West is brimming with talent or every starting quarterback
in the league needs to take a pay cut because the job just isn't
that important.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that division is simple and true to form. Its NFC
counterpart is confounding, living in an altered state. A few more
games could sort everything out, returning the division to its
natural order, with the Niners looking down at everyone, or more
devastatingly, just dismissing them.
</P>
<P>
   But the Niners' 26-21 loss in Buffalo will linger in the air for
a while. It was impossible to watch that game, with its
league-record-tying 22 penalties, and not wonder: Who are these
guys?
</P>
<P>
   It was also impossible not to think later on: If they can play
that badly, historically so _ if they can give away 178 yards in
penalties, if the offense can been so unstable that Steve Young
lined up behind a guard on one play, threw a shovel pass that
looked like a jump ball on another and capped it all off with a
throw that hit a member of the Bills' secondary in the back _ if
they can do all of that and still almost win the game, then what
would they have done to the Bills on a good day?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a lot of that depends on how good or bad the Bills
really are. Either way, the 49ers may end up being grateful to
them, for exposing every weakness, for introducing them to a
passionate Great Lakes audience a month before their game in Green
Bay and for not smacking Steve Young's head against the artificial
turf any more than necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Smith showed the 49ers a lot on Sunday, roaring off the
defensive line and past the underwhelming Jamie Brown. But even as
he displayed his moves, Smith revealed his class. He had a couple
of clear shots at the quarterback, but he never went for the
maiming blow. A dirtier player would have seen a chance to end
Young's season and taken it.
</P>
<P>
   But the quarterback stayed healthy and now he is preparing to
play on Sunday, his 37th birthday. He will play the Saints, the 3-1
Saints, division-leading New Orleans _ and isn't that enough to
make us all think we're seeing stars?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
