u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POTATO-FAMINE-HNS &LR;      10-06 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTATO-FAMINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS PROD SCHOOLS TO DEVELOP LESSONS ON IRISH POTATO FAMINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE HUREWITZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Concerned that New York public schools were
ignoring a mandate to teach the Irish potato famine as a human
rights issue, legislators have ordered the state Education
Department to develop a curriculum for teachers to use.
</P>
<P>
   The order comes in the wake of a controversial amendment in 1996
that added instruction about the famine to a law requiring courses
examining genocide, slavery and the Holocaust. Critics said such a
mandate would politicize the issue by blaming the English for
intentionally causing the crop failure.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the legislation believe educators are dragging
their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the legislation, there had been no discernible change in
what was being taught,'' said Joseph Crowley, the Queens Democrat
who was a prime sponsor of the measure. ``We were meeting with some
opposition from the state Education Department, inasmuch as they
believed they were in compliance with the law by simply developing
and issuing to school districts a bibliography of materials
concerning the famine.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowley said the academic establishment was using a loophole in
the legislation to evade the spirit of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lo and behold, we had mandated something for which there was
no curriculum to be disseminated,'' Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Dolan, chairman of the board of trustees of the Irish
American Heritage Museum, said it was more than an oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to avoid it ever happening is don't fund it,''
said Dolan, who was present when the mandate was signed.
</P>
<P>
   To remedy the situation, Crowley and supporters met with
legislative leaders and Gov. George Pataki and secured a quiet
victory.
</P>
<P>
   In the final weeks of this spring's legislative session, with
little notice and no debate, Pataki added $200,000 to develop study
guidelines and resource materials.
</P>
<P>
   George Gregory, supervising the project for the Education
Department, said his team has solicited proposals from academic
institutions and groups like the Irish American Heritage Museum.
The award will go to a group of institutions that must complete its
work by June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed curriculum will be reviewed for accuracy and
fairness by an advisory committee of scholars whose precise
composition has yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Their focus is a period between 1845 and 1850 during which more
than 1 million people died in Ireland and 2.5 million plus were
forced to flee, Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley contends that old textbooks give the subject scant
attention, or treat it simply as a natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   It's Crowley's view that the English government was responsible
_ at the least through neglect, at worst through food-export
policies aimed at decimating the Irish population.
</P>
<P>
   Others describe the events as an unavoidable result of a potato
blight that afflicted other populations in Europe and which Britain
tried to alleviate with foreign grain purchases only to run into
distribution and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many historical perspectives, and I'm not a
historian. I have my own personal views on it,'' Crowley said.
``That's not the issue. The issue is what was being taught was
lacking. And it had a significant impact historically on the state
of New York because an overwhelming majority of those people who
were forced to leave that country came to this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory said the Legislature's action has been helpful and
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have surveyed their constituency and determined there is
a need,'' Gregory said. ``They teach about the Holocaust. They
teach about slavery. This is another case study that students can
learn about in the area of human rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
