<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-BITS&AMP;BYTES-NYT &LR;      10-06 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BITS&AMP;BYTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE INTERNET, ADVICE CAN BE SLOW IN COMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By S.A. BELZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In theory, the Internet should be a first-rate place to get
answers to urgent cooking or nutrition questions. But is it? The
following question was sent to four Web sites that invite questions
for their resident authorities:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to bake an apple pie for the holidays. Which apples
will stay crispest and juiciest through the baking? Do I have to
prepare the apples in any way, by cooking them first, for
instance?''
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Goldman at Baker Boulanger (www.betterbaking.com) wrote
back by e-mail within a couple of hours: ``I always use a
combination of apples. Yellow delicious keep their shape (but
little flavor). McIntosh and Cortland (mushier but great flavor).
Granny Smith (stays crisp). Never liked Granny Smith for baking at
all, but everyone swears by them. Mostly yellow delicious and
anything sweet and tart.'' Her advice on preparation was simply
``core, peel and slice,'' no cooking.
</P>
<P>
   To ask a question at Ms. Goldman's site, click on RSVP (``You
ask, we answer''). A search of previous questions she was asked
will probably bring a list of recipes to the screen. Search for
``strudel,'' for instance, and the tempting recipe choices include
Romanian strudel made with Turkish delight and a ``mile high''
apple-and-raisin strudel cake for Thanksgiving dessert.
</P>
<P>
   The Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, N.Y.,
participates in www.digitalchef.com. To ask questions, click on Ask
Digital Chef. Karen (just Karen) responded after two business days:
``I've always found that Granny Smith apples are the best to use
for baking. They keep their shape, don't get mushy and have great
sweet and tart flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   This seems to be a site for questions you couldn't ask a friend
without risk of humiliation. For instance: ``What is a `solimmier'?
I don't know if I'm spelling it correctly.'' The chef was very
understanding in explaining what a sommelier is.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two weeks, Tina Ujlaki, the food editor of Food &AMP;
Wine Magazine(www.foodwinemag.com), answered on the site: ``The
best apples to use in making pies, if you can find them, are some
less common firm varieties that hold their shape when baked.'' For
example, Arkansas Black, Braeburn, Cox's Orange Pippin, Jonathan,
Northern Spy and Rhode Island Greening. If those aren't at your
market, she will allow Golden Delicious or Granny Smiths, and Romes
before McIntosh.
</P>
<P>
   She, too, advises peel, core and slice and adds these tips:
``Tossing the just-sliced apples with fresh lemon juice will
inhibit browning. Many bakers add sugar and spices for flavor and a
little flour as well to thicken the juices as the pie cooks.''
</P>
<P>
   From www.iVillage.com, which calls itself ``The Women's
Network,'' an acknowledgment that the question was received came
almost immediately by e-mail (with an invitation to join
iVillage.com). But nearly two weeks later the answer had still not
followed either by e-mail or at the site. Three experts on food and
nutrition are said to be there waiting to help. (Click on Experts
Center and then Food.)
</P>
<P>
   The best advice, then, on food advice from the Internet (except
perhaps for Ms. Goldman's site) is: Don't preheat the oven while
waiting for an answer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Need to spell creme froide de concombres, creme bavaroise or
creme patissiere?
</P>
<P>
   You do if you write menus or edit cookbooks and the food pages
of newspapers or magazines. Arno Schmidt, a former Waldorf-Astoria
executive chef (who has a computer programmer son), offers help
with Menuspell, a diskette containing 26,000 menu terms. They are
broken into 10 categories, like French, German, English, Bordeaux,
Burgundy and beer.
</P>
<P>
   The diskette is in the bookstores of Johnson &AMP; Wales University
and the Culinary Institute of America (on whose board Schmidt is an
emeritus member). ``Chefs love it,'' Schmidt said, not
surprisingly. But whether or not editors will is another question.
</P>
<P>
   Spot checking shows that the lists are not uniformly
alphabetized internally; for instance, the list of agnello (lamb)
dishes in the Italian section. This may not be crucial because it
is best to use a search or find command and give a reliable
fragment (like ``bav'' to find bavaroise), rather than, say, to
scroll and scroll.
</P>
<P>
   An editor will search in vain for kabocha, delicata and turban
squash. But care has been taken here (for example, the foreign
terms on the English list have accents). Editors should find
Menuspell, despite some inconsistencies, a useful supplement to
their shelf of reference books.
</P>
<P>
   The diskette comes in MS Word and Macintosh versions and costs
$54.95, plus $3.50 for shipping, from (800) 787-1455. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sallie Motch got into steady brownie baking when her very good
friend developed a sweeter and sweeter tooth during a course of
chemotherapy. Now, she is baking brownies to order in her kitchen,
selling them on the Web at www.salliesbrownies.com and giving part
of the proceeds to a dozen good causes.
</P>
<P>
   She offers 10 varieties, from chocolate fudge to bittersweet
cherry kirsch. Ms. Motch uses Ghirardelli chocolate, Madagascar
vanilla, fresh eggs and butter and no preservatives.
</P>
<P>
   For a product uninterested in a shelf life, that means
indulgence must be swift and decisive. Which isn't difficult: the
chocolate fudge brownie is richly chocolaty without being cloyingly
sweet. (Yes, refrigeration is possible.)
</P>
<P>
   Each two-pound, 8-by-8-inch pan of uncut homemade brownies costs
$20, excluding shipping, with $1 going to a Hudson Valley, wildlife
or animal-care organization (the buyer chooses from a list on the
Web site, and the choices change four times a year). Design your
own brownie and Ms. Motch will bake it for you for $35, with $5
going to a nonprofit organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
