<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2288 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OFF-THE-MENU-ART-3TAK     10-06 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFF-THE-MENU-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF-THE-MENU DINING: CHEF, DARLING, PEEL ME A GRAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Michael Eisner, the chairman of Disney, goes to
La Grenouille, he doesn't look at the menu. Doesn't have to. The
chef, Daniel Orr, designs a meal for him that is, unlike almost
everything else on the menu, fat free.
</P>
<P>
   And when Ronald Perelman, the chairman of Revlon, dines at Harry
Cipriani, he almost always has roasted halibut served with a slab
of tomato, capers and oregano. It is prepared for him alone.
</P>
<P>
   At the same restaurant, Oscar de la Renta, the clothing
designer, orders riso alla valenziana, a rice dish with saffron and
shrimp, every single time. Never mind that it doesn't happen to be
on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that may be the point, as some restaurant observers
believe: Treat the royalty royally and they will return time and
again, adding a less than subtle glitz to the restaurant's cachet.
Just think of Le Cirque 2000, which often feels like a celebrity
cafeteria. The Maccioni family learned this trick long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, food isn't everything. Some affluent diners
apparently go to a restaurant more to soak up the ambiance _ or
perhaps for the sake of their guests _ than for their own gustatory
needs: One publisher, for instance, has been known to have a lunch
at the Four Seasons that consisted of a plain baked potato and
nothing else. It might well be the most expensive baked potato in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   That off-the-menu request is not a phenomenon either welcomed or
admired by some chefs _ who, of course, pride themselves on their
carefully designed menus _ or by some customers, who find it
boorish. Daniel Boulud, for instance, is responsive to the unusual
requests of his true regulars _ the people who, he says, treat his
restaurant like an extension of home. (He has even made what he
calls a ``golf club salad'' filled with raw vegetables for a couple
who come every week.)
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't tolerate such requests from newcomers. ``We don't
want to build a relationship with a customer who doesn't appreciate
our food in the first place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some restaurateurs are even less tolerant. ``People don't come
to Savoy so we can be their personal caterer,'' said Peter Hoffman,
the owner of the SoHo restaurant. ``We don't promote that, and our
customers aren't those kinds of people. They're not the finicky,
limited palate kind of people.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bill Blass, the designer, who admits to making modest
off-the-menu requests, finds that the increasing desire for
pampering by some diners can reach the point where it's offensive
and pretentious. ``You're in the hands of people who know what
they're doing,'' he said. ``You put yourself in their hands.
Otherwise stay home and boil an egg.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, when you enter a restaurant of any reputation
these days, it's a pretty good bet that some of the diners aren't
eating anything you've learned about from the menu or the waiter.
Michael Batterberry, a food historian and the editor of Food Arts
magazine, said that today's special treatment in restaurants is
rooted in practices of the past, when to bring in business, chefs
would create and name dishes for a celebrity. Peach Melba, for
instance, was named for Nellie Melba, the legendary soprano, and so
was Melba toast. Now it's individual treatment that does the trick
_ or maybe we just have too many celebrities today for the name
game.
</P>
<P>
   Fame isn't a prerequisite for privilege. Just establish yourself
as a regular.
</P>
<P>
   If you do so at Montrachet, the restaurant will add your name to
a file listing foods you like and dislike. ``For instance,'' said
Eric Rota, the maitre d'hotel there: ``Mrs. Simon is coming
tomorrow, and we know she loves lobster. So we will send her an
hors d'oeuvre of lobster.''
</P>
<P>
   To speed up acceptance, it may be a good idea to say the word
``truffles'' or ``foie gras'' every time your waiter passes to make
sure it sinks in.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of dishes are kept on hand only for these regulars. Like
the Basque lobster salad at Gertrude's. So many regular customers
have asked for it since it was taken off the menu that the chef now
keeps poached lobsters in the refrigerator. (As a new customer
though, I ran into determined resistance and discovered I had to be
extremely insistent with the waiter to get it.)
</P>
<P>
   At Manducatis in Long Island City, Queens, regular customers
know to ask for the pappardelle alla nonna, a hearty dish of pasta
with cannellini beans and tomato. But dining off the menu at the
restaurant goes beyond asking for specific dishes. ``We have a lot
of what we call suggestion people,'' said Anthony Cerbone, the
manager. ``They don't even look at the menu.''
</P>
<P>
   La Grenouille, which has been open for 36 years, has built up a
hefty repertory of classics. Though many of the Careme-style dishes
are down and have been discreetly removed from the menu, they are
not yet out. Longtime customers still hanker for roasted oysters
with champagne sauce, poularde pochee, a poached chicken served
with horseradish and vegetables, and even calves' brains. So Orr,
the chef, makes sure they get them.
</P>
<P>
   Some requests are not so lofty.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Green, a voice-over specialist and regular at Chianti, worked
over the waiters and the chef at the restaurant so much, that they
now keep a container of ``Eddie's dressing'' in the refrigerator at
all times _ a honey mustard concoction that is used just for his
salads. It's official: Green has gained a toehold into the world of
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Benjamin Jr., a portfolio manager at a New York investment
bank, who dines frequently at Oceana, has his own way of finagling
dishes not on the menu. ``First of all, you have to be real low
key,'' he said. ``You have to ask in a very subtle way with a
smile. Tell them the restaurant is the best and that this is the
only place you can get it. You have to make them feel special.''
</P>
<P>
   He is sure it helps to ask someone at the management or
ownership level. ``If you get an ordinary waiter or waitress, let
me tell you, what do they have to gain?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has worked for him. The cooks at Oceana serve
Benjamin his beloved salmonburgers, which are not on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``They only make them for me,'' he said. ``I'm the king.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   It takes some clout, or some nerve, to ask for a dish not on the
menu, which is why most New York restaurantgoers will never eat the
roasted oysters with Champagne sauce at La Grenouille (an old-time
classic). Or the pappardelle with white beans and tomato at
Manducatis (you have to know about it to ask for it). Or the Basque
lobster salad at Gertrude's (a favorite with the regulars).
</P>
<P>
   But you can make them all at home, no request required.
</P>
<P>
   LOBSTER SALAD BASQUE STYLE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Gertrude's
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   16 quail eggs
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt or kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   4 lobsters, about 1 pound each
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons duck fat, or butter
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces Bayonne ham, cut in strips 1/4 inch thick by 1/4 inch
wide
</P>
<P>
   2 red bell peppers, halved, seeded and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 green bell peppers, halved, seeded and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 Spanish onion, halved and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   6 tomatoes, peeled, seeded and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Spanish piments d'espelettes powder (see note) or 1
teaspoon minced fresh jalapeno pepper
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sherry wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 handfuls mesclun greens
</P>
<P>
   4 fresh basil leaves, torn into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   1. Fill a medium pan with water, and bring to a boil. Add the
quail eggs, and simmer for 1 1/2 minutes. Transfer the eggs to a
bowl of ice water to stop the cooking. When cool, peel. Cover, and
refrigerate until needed.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring a large pot of water to a boil, and add about 2
teaspoons of salt. Add lobsters, and cook for 12 minutes. Remove
from water, and allow to cool completely. Pull off the tails, and
remove the meat from the shells; reserve the remainder of the
lobster for another use. Cover, and refrigerate the meat from the
tails until needed.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stew the peppers. In a large saute pan over medium-low heat,
heat the duck fat, and add the ham. Saute until lightly browned, 3
to 4 minutes. Add red bell pepper, green bell pepper, onion and
garlic, and saute until slightly softened, about 5 minutes. Add
tomatoes and thyme. Cover, and cook for 30 minutes, stirring at
times. Add water if needed; there should be a few tablespoons of
liquid. Add piments d'espelettes powder or jalapeno, and salt and
pepper. Saute for 1 minute. Remove from heat. Allow to cool
completely, then cover, and refrigerate until chilled, at least 1
hour.
</P>
<P>
   4. For the dressing, combine 2 tablespoons of pepper stewing
liquid, tomato paste, vinegar, salt and pepper in a small bowl.
Slowly whisk in oil. In a large bowl, combine mesclun greens and
basil. Add 2 tablespoons of dressing, and toss to coat the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, spoon about 1 1/2 tablespoons of stewed peppers in
the center of each of four plates. Lean a lobster tail on the
peppers, and spoon remaining dressing on the meat. Place a handful
of greens closely around and partly on the lobster. Place 4 quail
eggs on the outer edges of the plate, and drizzle the remaining
dressing around the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Piments d'espelettes powder may be ordered from S.O.S.
Chefs of New York, (212) 826-6514; 4 ounces, $8.50.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED MALPECQUE OYSTERS WITH CHAMPAGNE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from La Grenouille
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt
</P>
<P>
   2 medium leeks, white and light green parts only, very thinly
sliced
</P>
<P>
   24 Malpecque or other meaty oysters, scrubbed well
</P>
<P>
   4 shallots, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   5 black peppercorns, crushed
</P>
<P>
   6 mushrooms, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 cup brut Champagne or sparkling wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fish stock or clam juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks.
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Add 1 teaspoon of salt
and the leeks. Blanch the leeks until tender, 3 to 4 minutes.
Drain, then rinse with very cold water, then drain again. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Open the oysters, and remove them from their shells,
reserving all their liquid. Set aside the bottom cuplike portion of
each shell, and discard the flat top.
</P>
<P>
   3. To make the sauce, combine the oysters and their liquid in a
medium saute pan. Place over medium-high heat until the edges of
the oysters begin to curl, 1 to 2 minutes; do not overcook. Using a
slotted spoon, transfer the oysters to a small bowl. Continue to
cook the oyster liquid until it has been reduced to 1 or 2
tablespoons. Remove the liquid from the heat, and set it aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a medium saucepan, combine shallots, garlic, peppercorns,
mushrooms, thyme, bay leaf, Champagne, fish stock and reduced
oyster liquid. Place the saucepan over medium heat, and bring to a
boil. Reduce heat to medium-low, and simmer until reduced and
thickened enough to coat the back of a spoon, 15 or 20 minutes. Add
the cream, and bring back to a boil. Reduce heat to low, and simmer
until the sauce is again reduced by half, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   5. Pour the sauce through a fine strainer into a bowl; discard
the solids. Add lemon juice, and salt and pepper to taste. Place
the egg yolks in a medium bowl. While whisking vigorously, add
about 1/2 cup of the sauce to the yolks. Pour the yolk mixture back
into the bowl of sauce, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   6. Heat oven to 500 degrees. Place oyster shells on a cookie
sheet, and place one oyster in each shell. Divide the leeks equally
over the oysters, and season with salt and pepper to taste. Divide
the sauce equally among the shells, pouring it over the leeks.
Roast the oysters until hot and browned on top, 8 to 10 minutes. If
the oysters are hot but not browned, they may be placed under a hot
broiler for 1 minute. Serve six oysters to a person on oyster
plates or on flat plates, using seaweed, rock salt or watercress to
steady them.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   PAPPARDELLE WITH WHITE BEANS AND TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Manducatis
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 1/2 hours, plus overnight soaking of beans
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (1 pound) dried cannellini beans
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 ripe tomatoes, cut into quarters
</P>
<P>
   5 large basil leaves, torn into large pieces
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pappardelle
</P>
<P>
   Crushed red pepper flakes.
</P>
<P>
   1. Rinse the beans, and place in a large bowl with 6 cups of
water. Soak them overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. Drain the beans, place in a large pot, and cover with 6 cups
of cold water. Bring to a boil over high heat, then reduce heat,
and simmer until tender, about 1 1/2 to 2 hours. Drain, and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bring a large pot of water to a boil for the pasta. In a
large saute pan over medium-low heat, combine oil and garlic. Saute
the garlic until golden but not browned, 1 to 2 minutes. Add
tomatoes and basil, reduce heat to low, and saute until the
tomatoes are slightly softened, about 2 to 3 minutes. Add the
beans, and stir to combine. Season to taste with salt and pepper.
Remove from heat, and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cook the pasta in boiling water until al dente, about 8 to 11
minutes. Drain well. Add the bean mixture to the pasta, and toss to
combine well. Season to taste with salt, pepper and crushed red
pepper. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   RICE PILAF VALENZIANA
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Harry Cipriani
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, halved and seeded
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, peeled and halved
</P>
<P>
   2 cups short-grain rice, preferably carnaroli, vialone nano or
Arborio
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, peeled and lightly crushed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound shiitake mushrooms, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound medium shrimp, shelled, deveined and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brandy
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup canned crushed tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of powdered saffron
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat a broiler with a rack 3 inches from the heating element.
Place the pepper halves, cut side down, on a baking sheet, and
broil until the entire pepper surface is blackened. Put the pepper
into a small paper bag, and fold the top to seal. Leave the peppers
in the bag until cool, 20 to 30 minutes. Peel the peppers, and cut
into 1/2 inch dice. Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat the oven to 350 degrees. In a medium saucepan, bring the
chicken broth to a boil; then, reduce the heat to low and keep the
broth at a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large casserole or Dutch oven over medium heat, melt the
butter. Add onion, and saute until the surface is slightly softened
but not browned, about 4 minutes. Add rice, and stir for about 2
minutes. Add the simmering broth, and salt to taste. Raise the heat
to bring to a boil, then remove from heat. Cover the pan with a
sheet of foil, and top with the lid. Place in the oven, and bake
for 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. While the rice is baking, place a large saute pan over medium
heat, and add olive oil. Add garlic, saute for 30 seconds, then
remove and discard it. Add mushrooms, and saute until they are
lightly browned and the liquid has evaporated, about 4 minutes. Add
shrimp and reserved red bell pepper. Saute to sear the shrimp,
about 2 minutes. Stir in parsley. Add brandy, and carefully light
with a match. Swirl the pan until the flames die out. Add crushed
tomatoes, curry, saffron, cayenne and black pepper to taste. Season
to taste with salt. Saute for 1 minute more.
</P>
<P>
   5. Add the mushroom mixture to the pan of baked rice, and toss
to combine well. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
