<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- ENERGY. Clinton administration officials and Bay
Area congressional delegations reacted differently to the passage
of a $291 billion energy and water spending bill -- $500 million of
which will go the Bay Area. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO -- SANDCREEK. President Clinton is signing into law a
bill by Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., that authorizes
funds to find the actual site of the Sand Creek Massacre to
purchase the land as a National Park. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   -- SKAGGS/SCHAEFER. Working on project. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   IDAHO -- AGRICULTURE. The Senate passed a massive agriculture
spending bill, which includes the Republicans' $4 billion emergency
aid package for farmers -- $3 billion short of the Democratic
version. President Clinton has threatened to veto the bill, which
already passed in the House, because he said it does not do enough
to help farmers in trouble. Brown
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS -- BRIEFS. Column for Sunday. (Working.) Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- LAT-WAHOO2. Rest easy Tribe fans. Chief Wahoo is back.
The cardboard poster of the Cleveland Indians mascot stolen from
outside Rep. Steven C. LaTourette's office late last week was
returned Tuesday. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   -- ECONOMY-ASIA. As one of the top 20 states exporting to Asia,
Ohio is feeling the effects of the Asian financial crisis. Ohio's
exports to Asia declined 21 percent in the first quarter of this
year compared to the first quarter of 1997, according to statistics
released Tuesday by the Treasury Department. Will include some
area-specific information. (Possible.) Hurt
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- DIVERS. A strong majority of Pennsylvanians say
that increasing diversity in higher education is helpful in healing
racial and ethnic differences, according to a national poll
released Tuesday. The vocal opposition to affirmative action
programs are just a vocal minority in Pennsylvania, according to
one administrator at the state's largest university, Penn State.
Butler
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA -- SRS. Department of Energy worker retraining
and education programs spurred by downsizing at the Savannah River
Site produced nearly 5,000 jobs between 1993 and 1997, more than at
any other DOE facility, according to a new independent analysis.
(Working.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- HOUSING. The Department of Housing and Urban
Development awarded an $800,000 grant to the Community Development
Corporation (CDC) in Brownsville. The CDC will use the money to
construct new homes and rehabilitate some older homes in four rural
areas. Brown
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- CHILDCARE. Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., pushed his child
care bill before a Senate committee Tuesday, but the measure is
most likely doomed with Congress ending its session this week.
Berman
</P>
<P>
   -- SENSENBRENNER. Some consider Rep. Jim Sensenbrenner, R-Wis.,
a gruff man who can't get along with opponents, but the science
community praises his ability to bridge gaps between Democrats and
Republicans on the House Science Committee that he chairs.
(Working.) Marlin
</P>
<P>
   -- BUSINESS. A final compromise could be worked out this week on
a bill that would allow many restaurants to play music without
having to pay licensing fees. Proposed by Rep. Jim Sensenbrenner,
D-Wis., the bill passed the House over the opposition of both the
House Judiciary chair and chair of the Intellectual Property
Subcommittee. (Working.) Marlin
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
