<HEADLINE>
A HOME THAT'S TRULY LIVED IN CAN BE A GENUINE WORK OF ART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They have lovely works of art at the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   There are beautiful paintings, specimens, and unusual objects on
display throughout the building. Many people travel great distances
to view their latest exhibit. It's well worth the trip. As a child,
one of my favorite pastimes was visiting museums like the Amon
Carter Museum and the Fort Worth Museum of Science and History.
Yes, I was a strange kid.
</P>
<P>
   I carried my love for museums from my parents' home right into
my own home today.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know exactly how it happened. It must have started
normally enough, probably with comfortable furnishings purchased
more for their practicality and durability than their aesthetic
value. But a couple of episodes of Martha Stewart and a few
articles in some decorating magazines changed all of that.
</P>
<P>
   Before I knew it, I had started buying frames that cost more
than the pictures inside them. We had white chairs in the dining
room. The rug was a work of art. The magazines _ the socially
conscious and incredibly boring magazines _ were arranged
symmetrically on the fingerprint-free table. I was warning my
children not to use the ``good'' soap or the ``good'' towels in the
``good'' bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I had to take my shoes off just to walk into my own
house. I don't even have to remove my shoes at the Kimbell, and
they've got Cezanne and Matisse in there.
</P>
<P>
   We had a dining room that we hardly ever dined in because we
were afraid we might stain the white chairs. And we had a living
room that absolutely no one lived in.
</P>
<P>
   Like a museum, our house was on display.
</P>
<P>
   People have a certain way of behaving in museums. But what's
appropriate for a museum is not appropriate for a home. Homes are
for living, lounging, loving and laughing.
</P>
<P>
   If the pictures, chairs, towels, and pretty dishes aren't for
your family, then who are they for? And why? That's what I asked
myself one day when I found myself becoming angry because I had
discovered dirt on one of the ``good'' towels.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't like the answer I gave myself.
</P>
<P>
   So now, we burn the candles. We use the soap. And we drink tap
water out of the long-stemmed glasses. Life is too short. The only
thing irreplaceable in my home is my family.
</P>
<P>
   You know, I still love to visit museums. I just don't want to
live in one.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
