A2407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      10-06 0167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RED WITH BODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miguel Torres Mas La Plana 1994 Penedes, Spain. About $35.
</P>
<P>
   When this wine, which is 100 percent cabernet sauvignon, was
introduced in 1970, it was known as Gran Coronas Black Label. It
was created by Miguel Torres Jr., who joined the family business in
the early 1960s and introduced French grape varieties to the
Penedes region, southwest of Barcelona. The cabernet vines were
planted in the Milmanda Vineyard in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1980s, the wine was rich and tannic, apparently
too much so for the Spanish market. Even though the wine was
immensely popular elsewhere, its style was softened to conform more
to that of most Spanish reds.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, it reverted somewhat to the earlier
versions, with more structure. This 1994 embodies the best of both
styles: rich, opaque and intensely flavored. It would be just right
for Thanksgiving; it will also last for 15 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
