<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1007-     10-06 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1007-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HUMANITARIAN GROUPS FIGHTING TIME, WINTER TO SAVE KOSOVO
REFUGEES
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trim.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Determined government and humanitarian
agencies are struggling to provide food and shelter, before winter
sets in, to more than 20,000 refugees who have fled to Albania to
escape the violence of neighboring Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Already a poor country with a fragile government, Albania is
straining under the weight of caring for the refugees, and
officials here express deep concern about the future if the crisis
in Kosovo persists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes this difficult country even more difficult to
govern,'' said Daan Everts, the ambassador here for the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, aid groups, including the Red Cross an Catholic
Relief Fund, met with representatives of Western governments and
Albanian officials to take an account of the situation and plot the
next steps in coping with the refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
   NATO airstrikes, meanwhile, moved closer to reality as U.S.
envoy Richard Holbrooke met with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic for a second day on Tuesday in Belgrade and warned him
against failing to show the West he really means to end his harsh
crackdown in Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, speaking in Washington, said Holbrooke was
telling Milosevic that NATO is prepared to act if he fails to honor
U.N. resolutions ordering him to withdraw from areas of conflict
and allow a political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are high,'' Clinton said. ``The time is now to end
the violence in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   No halt to the violence, many fear will only exacerbate the
refugee problem -- particularly as winter looms.
</P>
<P>
   Preparations are being made for as many as 20,000 additional
refugees but officials here worry about the country's capacity to
handle such an influx. ``This is an emergency plan, and we hope
this will remain on paper,'' said Tauland Dedja, the Albanian
government official coordinating refugee efforts. ``If we had such
a number there would be tremendous problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the government pledges not to close the border
with Kosovo, where an estimated 250,000 more refugees have been
displaced by the seven-month struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are our countrymen,'' Dedja said. ``Only destiny put a
border between us. To close the border would be unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, which is about 90 percent ethnic Albanian, is a province
of Serbia, one of the two remaining republics of Yugoslavia. Kosovo
was largely self governing before 1989, when Milosevic placed the
region under direct Serb rule.
</P>
<P>
   Since February fierce fighting between the Kosovo Liberation
Army, which seeks independence from Serbia, and Serb police and
military forces has emptied dozens of villages. Many refugees say
they will not return home until their safety can be assured.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 20,000 refugees already in Albania, nearly half are women
and about 7,500 are children aged 14 years or younger, according to
the United Nations High Commission for Refugees. More than 3,400
are under 6 years old, and 1,265 are over 60. About a quarter have
significant health problems.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,600 school children between 7 to 15 years of age have
been admitted into Albanian schools, and the government has given
them free school books.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the refugees stayed with Albanian families, but over
the months this arrangement has become untenable, officials said.
Consequently, warehouses, old barracks and dormitories are being
improved to provide housing. Additionally, the government has
pledged to provide land where aid groups intend to build a compound
of prefabricated buildings for the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   However, the process has been slowed by a number of problems,
including security and complicated legal issues related to
ownership of many of the buildings, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim begins here.)
</P>
<P>
   Efforts also have been hampered by turmoil within the Albanian
government. The impoverished former Communist country has endured
months of political conflict that last month erupted into street
violence in the capital. In an attempt to ease tensions, Prime
Minister Fatos Nano resigned last week. He was replaced by Pandeli
Majko, a 30-year-old official in Nano's ruling Socialist Party.
Even so, there are fears that tensions could escalate into civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee situation here is potentially a destabilizing force
for the frail Albanian government, Everts said. Many refugees have
expressed unhappiness with the relative moderate stance of the
Albanian government toward Kosovo and have added to the civil
unrest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis also has diverted the government's attention and
resources, while contributing to the lawlessness in the
northeastern region where the only clear authority is heavily armed
clans, Everts said.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict with Serb forces has stimulated the illegal arms
trade in the region, making it even more difficult for the
government to regain control, he said. An estimated 3,000 refugees
are in the Tropoja district, the heart of a region of near anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign aid workers have been pulled out of the area because of
harassment by the clans, who apparently view the workers as
profitable prey, said Ilir Gjoni, an official with the U.N. refugee
commission. ``We're operating in very difficult circumstances ,''
Gjoni said. ``There have been thefts, lootings of our warehouses,
life threats, cars stolen, and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, because the poor conditions in Albania are well-known
in Kosovo, officials assume -- and hope -- that few remaining
refugees will cross the border. Additionally, Kosovar rebels eager
to preserve the ethnic Albanian majority are blocking a mass
exodus, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the challenges, authorities believe they will be able to
shelter the refugees through the winter if the numbers remain
stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this will be determined by the scale of conflict in
Kosovo,'' Dedja said. ``The conflict will determine whether the
number of refugees in Albania will increase or whether it will slow
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far nobody has been left out on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
