<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2420 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-PORNOGRAPHY     10-06 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-PORNOGRAPHY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STARR REPORT: AS AMERICAN AS APPLE PIE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JUDITH A. HUNTER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The word ``unprecedented'' keeps turning up in the media's
analysis of the Clinton/Lewinsky saga. Particularly perplexing to
many analysts has been the popularity of the Starr Report, in both
printed and on-line forms, despite the fact that most Americans
have told pollsters they don't want to see President Clinton
removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits have been unable to reconcile these facts, which seem to
point to opposite conclusions. What they don't realize is that the
Starr Report is actually only the latest example of an American
fondness for what could be termed ``political pornography.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nineteenth century the American public showed a
remarkable appetite for publications that were, for their time,
graphically sexual, as long as these works made at least a pretense
of being related to an important issue of the day.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there was an entire genre of books that purported
to be exposes written by wives who had escaped from polygamy in the
Mormon territory of Utah (Utah's admission as a state was denied
until 1896, after the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints
formally renounced polygamy).
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans sincerely believed that what the Mormons called
``plural marriage'' was a danger to the nation; in fact, in the
1860 Republican platform the young party referred to polygamy and
slavery in the same sentence as evils to oppose, ``twin relics of
barbarism.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet no one remembers the early Republicans for their stand
against Mormon marriage practices; we remember them for their stand
against the extension of slavery. And, in truth, Republicans of the
time spent the preponderance of their energies on the slavery
issue, despite what their platform said.
</P>
<P>
   Polygamy simply didn't seem to be as important an issue. But you
would never know that from the number of anti-Mormon books and
pamphlets produced and consumed in the nineteenth century.
</P>
<P>
   One prominent example was ``Wife No. 19,'' whose author claimed
to be ``Ann Eliza Young, Brigham Young's Apostate Wife.'' Among the
many tales she told about life in Utah, she often stressed how the
Saints were fond of marrying more than one female from the same
family. (It is true that Mormons believed taking ``sister wives''
who were truly sisters might lessen some of the tensions inherent
in a polygamous household.)
</P>
<P>
   As an example of an ``incestuous intermarriage'' she told of a
widowed mother who remarried, with the understanding that her two
daughters would also wed her husband when they were old enough.
``The little girls knew of the arrangement, and used to talk very
openly of 'marrying Pa,' and in very much the same way they would
speak of their intention to take tea with a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The author also insisted that very young girls were forced into
marriage, saying her father had to begin turning down marriage
proposals for her once she reached the age of 12.
</P>
<P>
   Yet polygamy, incest, and underage marriage were not the only
avid interests of nineteenth-century readers. Anti-Mormon stories
were a variation on even more popular anti-Catholic works, whose
sordid details found large audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Awful Disclosures'' of a woman who claimed to be a former
nun and called herself ``Maria Monk'' was a runaway bestseller when
it first appeared in 1836. (It was the best-selling book in
American history before Harriet Beecher Stowe's ``Uncle Tom's
Cabin,'' published in 1853, finally overtook that distinction.)
Monk inspired scores of imitators, whose stories were eagerly
bought long after the specific ``facts'' of Monk's tale were
exposed as frauds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Awful Disclosures'' remained the model for Monk's
imitators. The book spun lurid tales of convents being attached to
priests' quarters by underground tunnels, of mother superiors
ordering nuns to ``obey the priests in all things,'' and of the
cold-blooded murder of newborns produced by the illicit unions
which seemed to be the whole purpose of convents. Monk even claimed
to have been raped by clergymen the day she took her vows as a nun.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of this sort of work sought to inspire Americans
to join a political crusade, the nativist movement, which opposed
the influence of immigrants who were arriving in port cities in
numbers they found alarming.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these immigrants were Catholic, and that was a
frightening thing to many native-born Protestants, especially since
the official pronouncements of the papacy, embroiled in the
political upheavals of Europe, seemed so at odds with American
values. (For instance, one pope of the early nineteenth century
referred to liberty of conscience as ``that most pestilential
error.'')
</P>
<P>
   The consumers of anti-Catholic material, however, did not rise
up and make nativism the controlling political force of the day.
How many current Americans have ever even heard of the Know
Nothings, the short-lived national nativist party?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the current threshold for titillation is exponentially
higher than it was 100 or 150 years ago. Today's eager audience for
``respectable pornography,'' salacious material with a political
veneer, needs more graphic, explicit detail. But the Starr Report
does have precedents in American culture. Give something salacious
the fig leaf of political significance (e.g., egregious
presidential misconduct) and Americans have always consumed it
lustily, whether it be the report of an independent counsel or the
purported memoirs of escaped nuns or Mormon wives.
</P>
<P>
   But the past demonstrates that whatever the public's appetite
for such pornography, it doesn't necessarily produce the expected
political response.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Judith A. Hunter, who has a Ph.D. in American history from Yale
University, is a Research Scholar at the State University of New
York at Geneseo.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
