u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-POLL-PA     10-06 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-POLL-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  PENNSYLVANIANS BACK DIVERSITY, AFFIRMATIVE ATION
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Ellen Butler
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct. 6. -- A majority of people in Pennsylvania and
the nation support increased diversity on college campuses, despite
contentious debates about affirmative action, according to a
national poll released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   College administrators and other diversity advocates claimed
that the affirmative action debate has been dominated by a small
faction of the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime around 2035, 50 percent of all Americans will be made
up of what today we call minorities,'' William Gray, III, president
and CEO of the United Negro College Fund, said at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this study says to me is that Americans may be way ahead
of their political, economic and social leaders in understanding
that reality,'' said Gray, the former congressman from
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that 71 percent of people in the nation and 64
percent from Pennsylvania said diversity in education on college
campuses helps bring society together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to hear the vocal minority speaking out against
diversity,'' said Edwin Escalet, Penn State's University Park
Campus director of minority admissions and community affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Students, however, are increasingly interested in attending
diverse colleges, whether they are diverse in terms of gender, race
or ethnicity, Escalet said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, a first-of-its-kind national poll examining the
public's attitudes toward diversity in higher education, was part
of the Ford Foundation's Campus Diversity Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are the result of a telephone poll of 2,011
registered voters conducted between July 14 and August 4. The poll
has a margin of error of plus or minus 2.2 percent. The
Pennsylvania results are part of a 200-person sample.
</P>
<P>
   Practical concerns like communication at work were a prime
factor in the public's attitudes toward diversity, said Daniel
Yankelovich, chairman of DYG, Inc., the group that conducted the
poll.
</P>
<P>
   Of respondents to the study, 96 percent of Pennsylvanians said
in the future people will need to get along with people who are not
like them. And 88 percent said the global economy makes it more
important than ever for everyone to understand people who are
different from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public feels the purpose of higher education is to acquire
job and job-related skills,'' Yankelovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, of The College Fund, described diversity in colleges and
in the curriculum as America's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about who we are going to become and how we will become
what we will be,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents to the survey not only responded to questions about
encouraging diversity in admissions, but in the curriculum.
Fifty-three percent of those polled in Pennsylvania said every
college student should have to study different cultures in order to
graduate. That percentage was higher than in states with
increasingly diverse populations such as California, where less
than half, 49 percent, said students should have to study different
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   At Penn State, students are required to take three
diversity-focused classes. The administration encourages faculty
members to incorporate diversity by giving them time off and extra
money to develop the courses in their free time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a lot easier to keep these initiatives because the
students support them,'' Escalet said.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
