<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2485 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-ROBERT-BERDAHL-COX     10-06 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-ROBERT-BERDAHL-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Funding battles threaten schools
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Ann Roser
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ America's premier public universities,
including Texas' two flagships, are in peril because of a
``relentless barrage of criticism,'' regional politics and intense
competition for state money, former University of Texas President
Robert Berdahl said in a speech Monday at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a subtle but a dangerous effort to weaken flagship
campuses,'' said Berdahl, who now heads the University of
California at Berkeley _ considered the flagship of U.S. public
universities. ``No one will admit that it is happening, but it is.
Texas is not unique in this.''
</P>
<P>
   UT, which last year launched a campaign to raise $1 billion by
2004, hopes to persuade potential donors that Texas benefits
economically from having a comprehensive research university
powered by strong faculty and students. UT, along with Texas A&AMP;M,
also must convince the Legislature to sustain them as flagships in
the face of criticism and complaints of elitism, Berdahl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing, of course, kills private fund-raising for public
universities faster than the belief that the state will withdraw
funds if private donors are willing to add them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Berdahl's remarks on ``The Future of Flagship Institutions''
were made before a crowd of several hundred attending an academic
convocation to honor 125 Texas A&AMP;M faculty and staff for their
achievements. A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen, who became friends with
Berdahl during Berdahl's 4 1/2-year tenure at UT, said the topic
was intended to open the debate on flagships in Texas. It is an
issue California has successfully confronted by creating a system
that provides access and academic excellence to all, Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   When Berdahl, 61, left UT 16 months ago, he cited inadequate
state aid to higher education as the main reason. Some lawmakers
had said they did not see a need to pour more resources into UT and
Texas A&AMP;M at ``the expense of'' other Texas universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my first years here, the regional universities launched
an assault on graduate education, ostensibly in the name of
undergraduate education, that moved resources from College Station
and Austin elsewhere,'' Berdahl said. Regional universities
``persuaded their representatives that the distribution of
resources is unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the primary beneficiaries of the state's Permanent
University Fund, UT and Texas A&AMP;M continue to be challenged by
other state schools that want a share of the historic endowment.
Some state lawmakers, including state Rep. Rob Junell, D-San
Angelo, chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, have said
those schools have a point.
</P>
<P>
   Berdahl revealed that an appearance before Junell's committee
persuaded him in February 1997 to become a candidate for the
Berkeley job after turning down an interview three months earlier.
It was the same week he learned UT would not get a share of $600
million in recommended construction money because the
appropriations committee believed UT could raise the money
privately.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature last year substantially boosted aid to higher
education in Texas, but it provides just 25 percent of the UT
System's overall budget. The rest comes primarily from tuition,
donations and revenues from UT System hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The Permanent University Fund ``was a whipping boy of sorts
during each of the three legislative sessions I was in Austin,''
Berdahl told the audience. ``I actually came to see the PUF as a
political handicap for UT.''
</P>
<P>
   When the better funded Berkeley campus beckoned, Berdahl said it
was hard to resist. California has made a strong commitment to
financing higher education over four decades, guided by a master
plan created in 1959, and now boasts eight flagships. Texas could
use at least one or two more flagships, Berdahl said, but not until
it adequately finances the two it has.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that if Texas fails to protect and promote UT and A&AMP;M,
the best students will leave for better schools out of state, and
``we will all be the poorer for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Higher education critics have long complained that research
universities shortchange undergraduates by corralling them into
huge classes and giving them graduate students as instructors.
Lawmakers have been sensitive to those critics and have targeted
elementary and secondary education for higher chunks of state aid.
</P>
<P>
   While some criticisms are valid, including inattention to
undergraduate education, Berdahl said, flagship universities ``are
the envy of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Roser writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
