<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Oct. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Saturday night to Monday night, 48 inches of snow
accumulated at the town of Galena in the Black Hills of South
Dakota as a potent winter-like low pressure system forged across
the northern Rockies and northern Plains. Wednesday, the center of
the weakening low will move into the Canadian province of Ontario.
Nonetheless, the system will leave a legacy of showers and
thunderstorms over parts of the eastern half of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate to locally heavy rains will douse parts of the eastern
Great Lakes region as moist air streaming north from the Gulf of
Mexico is lifted by a slow-moving cold front attached to the
Ontario low. Rainfalls in excess of an inch are possible from
eastern Michigan to northern Kentucky. The heavy rainfall will
shift eastward to western New York and Pennsylvania on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms marking the cold front
will extend southward to the central Gulf States. Brief downpours
are possible. Some storms may contain gusty winds, but the risk of
severe weather will be limited by the lack of energetic jet stream
winds that could augment the lifting of low-level moist air.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, partial to full sunshine will bathe eastern New
England as an area of high pressure retreating slowly east shields
the region from inclement weather developing along and west of the
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, moderate rains will develop over west-facing slopes
of the Cascades as moist Pacific winds blowing from the southwest
are forced to rapidly ascend the sloping terrain. Rainfalls of an
inch are possible in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Winter Closes In
</P>
<P>
   Winter has begun to close in, launching a seasonal assault on
two fronts. On the northern front, winter has gained a foothold on
northern Alaska, where splotches of light snow fell Tuesday with
temperatures hovering in the 20s and 30s. Winter also attacks from
above, slowly descending earthward as it wages war with fading
warmth in the upper atmosphere. Tuesday, between 8 and 12 inches of
snow blanketed the mountains of southeast Wyoming, while, to the
east over the lofty Black Hills of South Dakota, heavy snow was
whipped into a blizzard frenzy by winds gusting to 60 mph.
</P>
</TEXT>
