<HEADLINE>
`RECIPES 1-2-3 MENU COOKBOOK': DAILY MENUS, LESS SHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New Yorkers like to brag that you can get absolutely
any ingredient in the city. I think this is probably true. I've
tracked down fresh curry leaves, a tropical fruit called a genep
and soft wheat berries with almost no effort. What they don't tell
you is that these ingredients are never all in one place. In a
year's time, not once have I been able to buy everything for a
recipe-testing session in one store. Instead, I run all over the
city and am usually exhausted before I even begin cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Rozanne Gold, who lives in New York City, responded to this
tedious aspect of cooking with her first book, ``Recipes 1-2-3''
(Viking, 1996), in which no recipe had more than three ingredients,
not including salt and pepper. With fewer ingredients, shopping
becomes less painful, and cooking times and techniques tend to be
simpler.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gold's second book, ``Recipes 1-2-3 Menu Cookbook'' (Little,
Brown, $25), follows the same set of rules, but this time the
recipes are grouped into menus for morning, noon and night.
Arranged this way, a menu of four dishes, for instance, has a
maximum of 12 ingredients. Which isn't bad when you consider how
many you have to hunt down for your average salsa.
</P>
<P>
   She is a clever cook. She doesn't allow a recipe for poached
prunes with cardamom yogurt to rest as is. She has you reduce the
prune poaching liquid to make an intense sauce. And she doesn't cut
corners. In the same recipe she instructs you to strain the yogurt,
making it much denser and creamier and markedly improving a simple
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some recipes inevitably suffer as a result of the
three-ingredient rule. I made the menu called ``a dinner of
aromatics,'' which included a warm goat cheese and fresh mint
salad, Bombay leg of lamb with yogurt and lime, curried couscous
with currants and chilled sliced oranges with rose water and dates.
The lamb was delicious, though my guests could have lived without
the sauce, which tasted fine but had curdled. (More explicit
instructions, about not letting it boil, for example, might have
helped prevent this.)
</P>
<P>
   But the couscous, which worked perfectly and was extremely
fragrant, could have been so much better with a little butter. In
fact, it was: I tried it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   It made me wonder whether the dishes I tried were good, or just
good for dishes containing three ingredients. Would it be better to
go all out on one dish and round out the menu with things like
bread, salad and a cheese course? I'm torn on this point, but not
on another: Ms. Gold's approach is so well executed and so many of
the dishes impress upon you the power of wholesome, quality
ingredients that it is far better than any cookbook promoting easy
cooking that I've tried.
</P>
<P>
   BOMBAY LEG OF LAMB WITH YOGURT AND LIME
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Recipes 1-2-3 Menu Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes, plus 6 to 8 hours' marinating
</P>
<P>
   1 2-pound boned leg of lamb, butterflied
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain low-fat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 large limes
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon kosher salt.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large nonreactive bowl, combine lamb and yogurt. Grate
zest of 1 lime, and squeeze the juice of 2 limes (you will have
approximately 1/4 cup). Add to bowl with freshly ground black
pepper and the salt. Mix well so that lamb is thoroughly coated
with yogurt marinade. Cover, and refrigerate for 6 to 8 hours. Turn
once or twice during the marinating period.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat the broiler. Remove lamb from the marinade. Place
lamb in a heavy baking pan. Place marinade in a small pot.
</P>
<P>
   3. Broil lamb on each side for 6 to 8 minutes. It should be 150
degrees on a meat thermometer for rare; 160 degrees for
medium-rare. Meanwhile, warm marinade over low heat, whisking
constantly; do not let boil. Remove lamb from oven. Let rest 5
minutes. Slice thinly, and serve with marinade (if curdled, pour
through a fine strainer).
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
