<HEADLINE>
BILL MAHER AND THE PROS AND CONS OF A SCANDAL  
 BROUHAHA OVER LINCOLN WHITE HOUSE SITCOM  
 STAR SEARCH FOR ANOTHER `60 MINUTES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: bylines at end of articles)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're doing a show called ``Politically Incorrect,'' it has
to help when a political scandal is dominating the news, right?
</P>
<P>
   The star of the ABC show of that name, Bill Maher, is not
totally convinced. ``I'm sure it's been good for the show, because
it's something anyone can weigh in on,'' Maher said. ``You don't
have to explain the issue, and frequently people are passionate
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The downside: ``People are sick of it. They want it to end, and
they kind of blame the messenger a little bit. You're talking about
it so you're part of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Maher himself is sick of talking about the travails of
President Clinton. ``It's fascinating; I never get sick of it,'' he
said during an interview at the studios of the Comedy Central
program ``The Daily Show,'' where he was a guest this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, derisively, that it's all about whether Clinton
gets to keep his job,'' he continued. ``I think that's right. It's
really important that he keep his job to prove this kind of attack
can't succeed. That you can't just say, `OK, we've got a lot of
money, a lot of lawyers and we'll find something and we'll get you
out of there.' That's treason. That's like a coup. That's like a
fourth branch of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Maher makes no pretense at being objective on the subject.
``It's obvious I'm backing Clinton on this one,'' he said, ``though
I have been tough on him on a lot of things in the past.'' That
only makes it harder to balance the show every night, he said,
because in Hollywood, where ``Politically Incorrect'' is taped,
celebrities who don't come down on Clinton's side are a rare
species.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the celebrities say get out of his sex life,'' he said,
``because celebrities know what it's like to have their privacy
invaded. And they're all liberals anyway. Once you get past Pat
Boone and Charlton Heston, there's not a lot of conservative
celebrities. They're worth their weight in gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Maher said he usually tries to steer the conversation into new
areas, like the night he argued that Clinton's responses in the
grand jury could be seen as an act of civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   His search for new angles on the story has extended to his
nightly monologue, he said, where he has pushed his writers to
steer clear of all the obvious jokes. ``I see the same kind of
jokes from other people,'' he said. ``I try to do jokes with some
point of view. I don't like neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   One recent example Maher cited: `'I've never seen a story that
turned so many cliches on their head. Because this really IS about
dirty laundry, and they really DID make a federal case out of
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   White House Farce
</P>
<P>
   A group that included the Rev. Jesse Jackson gathered as planned
Monday for a protest rally urging the cancellation of UPN's new
sitcom ``The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer,'' but the more
effective protest was a silent one. Viewers stayed away in droves.
</P>
<P>
   The comedy, a farce set in the Lincoln White House and centering
on an aristocratic black Englishman who has mistakenly become
Abraham Lincoln's butler, made its debut Monday night at 9. But it
drew only 2.06 million viewers, with a Nielsen rating of 1.6 (each
rating point represents 994,000 homes).
</P>
<P>
   At 7 that morning, Jackson (who was in Los Angeles to attend the
funeral of former Mayor Tom Bradley later that day) and about 200
others gathered outside Paramount Studios to complain that
``Desmond Pfeiffer'' made light of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   UPN president Dean Valentine has said that the show has nothing
to do with slavery other than being set in the Civil War period. He
also has said that the protesters will not determine the show's
fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the American public tells us they hate the show,''
Valentine said, ``it'll come off, just like any other network
show.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   `60 Minutes' More
</P>
<P>
   Because ``60 Minutes'' is the grand old monarch of all network
news magazines, the growing pains of its offspring have been
matters of great curiosity in the press.
</P>
<P>
   Just about any serious television news correspondent not already
locked into a dream job has seen his or her name tossed out as a
candidate for a correspondent's job on ``60 Minutes II,'' which is
to take a midweek time slot on CBS early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the span of one week, from last week to this, Chris
Wallace of ABC News (whose father, Mike Wallace, is one of the
originals on the original ``60 Minutes''), has gone from being
labeled can't miss to dismissed as out of the running. (The truth,
as of Tuesday, remained somewhere in between.)
</P>
<P>
   Still considered front-runners are three CBS veterans _ Dan
Rather, Bob Simon and Vicki Mabrey _ and one from well outside the
bloodlines, PBS's Charlie Rose. Reached Tuesday, Rose said: ``This
is going to happen, and I'm so excited.'' He said he would be a
contributor rather than a full-time correspondent because he will
keep his own weeknight interview program on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   With all that said, CBS spokeswoman Sandy Genelius had the
following comment Tuesday: ``Not a single correspondent agreement
has been signed yet.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
