<SLUG> BC-TALKIN-RADIO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INGELS A KIEV SURVIVOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Raspy-voiced funnyman Marty Ingels is at his
happiest in restaurants, so it makes sense that his show will move
to one in the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   Ingels, whose popular hourlong call-in program can be heard at 7
p.m. Monday through Thursday on Glendale talk radio KIEV-AM (870),
will broadcast from a specially built studio at the soon-to-open
Legacy eatery on Sunset Boulevard starting in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk to Marty'' features celebrity and listener chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the pendulum is turning away from the shock-jock
thing,'' Ingels said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Married to actress Shirley Jones for 21 years, comedian-producer
Ingels caught the radio bug when onetime ``Partridge Family'' child
actor turned Chicago nighttime talk host Danny Bonaduce invited him
on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Ingels eventually filled in for Bonaduce for two weeks and then
went looking for a station to hire him. Nobody bit, so Ingels
bought time on KIEV in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most natural thing,'' he said. ``I realized this
was my place.''
</P>
<P>
   When new owner Salem Communications took over KIEV and fired
many longtime staffers, Ingels was put on contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty's humorous, yet intelligent and sensitive format seems
to be the perfect balance to the solid issues-oriented lineup
already in place,'' said Salem vice president Dave Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ingels says his own career ``has had more dips and
turns than the Matterhorn. But I'm really old-fashioned, and I
believe in restraint and responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Guests on ``Talk to Marty'' have included Charlton Heston, Red
Buttons, Shecky Greene, Gloria Allred, Phyllis Diller and others.
</P>
<P>
   HUMBLE HARVE RETURNS: Longtime disc jockey Humble Harve returns
to oldies radio KRLA-AM (1110) this weekend to launch a new doo-wop
show.
</P>
<P>
   Harve, born Harvey Miller, has worked at many of the area's top
stations, most recently country radio KZLA-FM (93.9) on weekends.
He worked at KRLA throughout the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Harve's new ``Doo-Wop Heaven'' can be heard on KRLA at 10 a.m.
Saturday and noon Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE OF KFI HOSTS: You're invited to watch talk radio KFI-AM
(640) afternoon team John and Ken debate morning man Bill Handel on
the Clinton-Lewinsky mess at the Museum of Television and Radio
(465 N. Beverly Drive, Beverly Hills) from 5 to 7 p.m. Friday.
Parking is available in the museum garage or nearby lots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
