<HEADER>
A2541 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVIL-TV-LADN     10-06 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVIL-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT HALF BAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Unusual forces fighting evil are the new arrivals
on Wednesday nights.
</P>
<P>
   The WB offers up ``Charmed,'' which focuses on three good
witches fighting evil and also marks the reunion of Shannen Doherty
and Aaron Spelling.
</P>
<P>
   UPN will debut ``Seven Days,'' in which an alcoholic mental
patient saves the world. &QL; 
CHARMED &QC;
</P>
<P>
   If ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' wasn't enough for you, the WB
has upped the ante threefold with ``Charmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not one, not two, but three attractive young women will try to
rid the world of warlocks the way Buffy tries to exterminate
vampires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charmed'' is the story of the three Halliwell sisters _ Prue
(Shannen Doherty), Phoebe (Alyssa Milano) and Piper (Holly Marie
Combs) _ who are an excellent cast of those who cast spells.
</P>
<P>
   They are brought together after the death of their mother and
spend their days bickering with each other in the creepy San
Francisco Victorian fixer-upper their mother left them.
</P>
<P>
   One of the sisters, while snooping around the attic, happens
upon ``The Book of Shadows.'' In it she discovers that she and her
sisters are witches and each has a specific power.
</P>
<P>
   Prue can move objects, Phoebe can see the future, and Piper can
stop time. They also find that when they chant in unison _ ``The
power of three will set us free'' _ they are an unstoppable force.
</P>
<P>
   This show is not nearly as campy as ``Buffy,'' but its special
effects are wonderful, and it just might find its audience on the
television schedule. It is certainly distinctive and plays right to
the crowds that have flocked to see such movies as ``Scream'' and
``I Know What You Did Last Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Having hit teen drama ``Dawson's Creek'' as its lead-in won't
hurt ``Charmed'' any, either.
</P>
<P>
   THE SHOW: ``Charmed.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT: &UR; : &LR;  Three good witches fight bad witches in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   THE STARS: Shannen Doherty, Holly Marie Combs, Alyssa Milano,
T.W. King.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE &UR; : &LR;  The WB (Channel 5).
</P>
<P>
   WHEN &UR; : &LR;  9 p.m. Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating &UR; : &LR;  2 { Stars.
</P>
<P>
   SEVEN DAYS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Frank Parker (Jonathan LaPaglia) is a belligerent alcoholic who
resides in the CIA mental hospital. He is also the best man to do a
difficult and dangerous job, as he is highly intelligent and
performs even better under duress.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA offers Parker a trade-off: He will be released from the
mental hospital if he agrees to join their covert operation.
</P>
<P>
   The president, vice president and the speaker of the House have
been killed by a terrorist, and the country needs a quick fix. The
CIA wants to send Parker on an experimental time machine to go back
in time seven days and alter history.
</P>
<P>
   Parker accepts the mission and saves the world. But everything
he does, including making a seemingly harmless bet on a basketball
game, will affect history.
</P>
<P>
   The first episode of the show is a two-hour movie, which is not
always the best indicator of the future of a series, but the
presentation was slick and the story compelling. Once you get past
the time travel and Parker's past, it requires no unbelievable
leaps. There are enough light moments to keep you glued, and
LaPaglia is outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   THE SHOW: ``Seven Days.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT: A science-fiction thriller about a covert military unit
with a top-secret operation that allows one person to go back in
time seven days to prevent present-day catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
   THEN STARS: Jonathan LaPaglia, Don Franklin, Norman Lloyd,
Justina Vail, Nick Searcy, Alan Scarfe, Sam Whipple.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: UPN (Channel 13).
</P>
<P>
   WHEN: 8 p.m. Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating &UR; : &LR;  3 { Stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
