<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2550 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-CLUBS-COX     10-06 2334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-CLUBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many investors trying to take advantage of any bargains they can
find
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell and Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How low can the stock market go?
</P>
<P>
   That's a frequently asked question when stocks are falling. But
it's a question that doesn't seem to preoccupy the members of
Georgia's 1,016 investment clubs affiliated with the National
Association of Investors.
</P>
<P>
   They know that ultimately it is individual stocks that determine
the market, not vice versa. Individual stocks can rise in a bear
market and fall in a bull market.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, investment clubs hew to a simple strategy: Pick
solid companies, invest in them regularly, and don't try to jump in
and out on every bit of news.
</P>
<P>
   With many stocks now off peak prices, clubs are readying their
shopping lists. Members of four clubs, who have shared their
strategies with Cox writers Hank Ezell and Robert Luke over the
past two years, met again Sept. 11 to discuss their latest moves.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What are your members saying about the market? Are they
nervous?
</P>
<P>
   Billy Williams, 60, of Best Buy Investment Club, is a retired
transportation engineer: Most of them are not. They think this is a
good opportunity to buy good stocks at a good price.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Werner, 45, of the Women's Investment Society for
Education, helps form other clubs: We just had a meeting. There was
almost jubilance. There were no sad faces, no panicky questions. As
our treasurer said, `Gee, stocks have gone on sale.'
</P>
<P>
   The biggest dilemma of the night was that we don't have enough
money to do what we want to do. It all had to do with what should
we buy and how should we buy it. Should we spread the money around
through DRIP (dividend reinvestment) programs? Should we buy more
(oil services giant) Schlumberger to take advantage of the price
right now? Should we save our money until next month, to see if we
can buy some of these great companies that are on our shopping
list?
</P>
<P>
   Q:So what did you decide?
</P>
<P>
   Werner: We decided, after much discussion, to buy 65 shares of
(specialty chemicals maker) RPM.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Any particular reason for adding that stock to your portfolio?
</P>
<P>
   Werner: I think it was because we had just studied RPM. We liked
it in July at $16, but we didn't have enough money to buy (steel
maker) Nucor and RPM. We bought Nucor then. Now, all of a sudden,
RPM was at $14, paying a 3.3 percent dividend yield. We decided
we'd take advantage of this low price now.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Any tips for finding bargains?
</P>
<P>
   Larry Reno, 52, of Mutual Investors of Atlanta, is comptroller
of the Army's Second Recruiting Brigade: Develop a watch list. You
identify good companies that are outside your buy range. When it
hits that buy range, start buying.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Commit all your money at once?
</P>
<P>
   Reno: Normally not. What we like to do is get 10 or 15 shares,
get into the DRIP program if it's available. You get the advantage
of dollar-cost averaging. You may reduce the commissions. If the
market goes down, you could pick up additional shares at even
better prices.
</P>
<P>
   Clair Redmond, 51, of Buckhead Investment Club, is a Forest
Service economist: Investment clubs usually don't have enough money
to buy a big stake. You start off small.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Is there a sense that the bargains are just beginning to
emerge, or is there an urgency to buy, and buy now?
</P>
<P>
   Werner: We may have the market come down a little bit more. You
still have several Dow (Jones industrial average) stocks like
General Electric selling at a price-to-earnings multiple of
28-plus. Merck is selling at over 28, Johnson &AMP; Johnson is selling
at a P/E of over 28, and you have Wal-Mart selling at a P/E of 34.
</P>
<P>
   These companies have good growth, but I don't think any of them
have growth that's over 20 percent that would justify the high P/E
multiples.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond: There's got to be some corrections in those big stocks
before this is all over with.
</P>
<P>
   Williams: The market is where it was last October. That's not
big enough of a pullback, in my opinion. Most stocks, even at
today's prices, are too high.
</P>
<P>
   Q:So will they go lower if the economy continues to slow?
</P>
<P>
   Williams: Yes. Definitely that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Werner: But I think there are some attractive buys out there
now. They might get more attractive, but you don't time the market.
If the stocks meet your criteria, as far as being a good solid
company at a reasonable price, go ahead and buy.
</P>
<P>
   If the market pulls them down further, that's when you use the
dividend reinvestment programs and dollar-cost average over time.
We're not buying stocks today for tomorrow or next year or even
three years from now. We're buying companies, not stocks, and for
the long term.
</P>
<P>
   Q:But isn't there a tendency on the part of investors to avoid
putting more money into stocks in which they have a loss, at least
on paper?
</P>
<P>
   Werner: Yes. It's really difficult for new clubs and new
investors to put more money into something that's declining. Their
faith is shaken.
</P>
<P>
   With our club, Century Telephone did nothing for two years after
we bought it. Earnings kept going up, the price kept going down or
staying the same, and the P/E ratio kept getting smaller.
</P>
<P>
   There was no bad news for this company, except the negative
outlook for the industry it's in. Several times the question came
up whether we should add to Century Telephone. But we were
reluctant to do so because the stock hadn't performed.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in six months time, it doubled in value.
</P>
<P>
   Q:So is there a lesson to be learned?
</P>
<P>
   Werner: I believe the lesson is that just because a stock
doesn't do anything over a short period of time, it doesn't mean
that the value won't be recognized at some point in the future.
</P>
<P>
   So if you've done your homework, and the company is
fundamentally strong, you need to have the faith and courage to add
to your holdings while the price is attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Is that what you did with Norrell?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. We added to our holdings last summer, near its
high, right before the stock plunged on an earnings warning. After
a slight rebound, we added once again. Now, the market has taken
the stock price a lot lower. The decision at the last meeting was
to hold and not buy more.
</P>
<P>
   I might add that at the current price of $14, P/E of 15, and
projected growth rate of 15 percent to 20 percent, Norrell appears
to be an excellent buy for the long term. However, it is a
small-cap company, with only 19 million shares outstanding, which
may not make it appropriate for all clubs or investors.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Why is that?
</P>
<P>
   Werner: It may be inappropriate because of the illiquidity of
the stock, which makes it a lot more volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Any other bargains out there?
</P>
<P>
   Redmond: We like (insurer) AFLAC (which derives most of its
revenues and profits in Japan). It's got a P/E of about 18.5 now.
It had been really high until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Isn't that because of Japan's economic problems?
</P>
<P>
   Williams: The problem with AFLAC is not the Japanese economy.
They have a lock on cancer insurance there, and the Japanese are
not giving up their insurance. The problem is the currency
fluctuations, which is making their earnings a lot lower than they
should be. But they are pushing their business in the United
States, and their growth here is up about 30 percent this year.
They're doing very well in the United States. Their cream comes
from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Aren't a lot of companies facing pressure on their earnings
because of economic turmoil overseas? Doesn't that hurt their stock
prices?
</P>
<P>
   Williams: I had a college professor who told me, ``Only be
concerned about the things you can control.'' I can't control the
world economy, I can't control politics. I can control what good
companies I buy and how long I hold on to them. That's all I can
do.
</P>
<P>
   Werner: I have been reading that McDonald's has been over in
Southeast Asia buying properties cheap. Royal Dutch Petroleum has
been down in South America, buying stuff cheap. (Automotive parts
maker) Dana Corp. was in Europe three years ago buying companies
cheap. So some of these companies are taking advantage of the world
doom and gloom, and it's going to set them up to be better,
stronger companies in the future. Even Anheuser-Busch and Coca-Cola
are taking advantage of the bad situation in other countries.
They're buying things cheap. You just have to understand that if
you have well-managed, financially strong companies, with a
long-term outlook, the sun will rise again.
</P>
<P>
   Q:OK, any other potential bargains?
</P>
<P>
   Redmond: If you're a contrarian, Citicorp is another good stock.
It has dropped 50 percent in price this year because it has so much
exposure to the Asian situation and uncertainties with the merger
with Travelers Group. It's got a P/E of about 10, and the P/E has
been as high as 16 or 17. It's going to be a while before they
bounce back, because of the Asian difficulties. That's something
that's five years out, if you want to start accumulating shares
now.
</P>
<P>
   Williams: One company we like is Fiserv. It's pulled back quite
a bit. They do the backroom service for banks and set up systems
for banks. They're super at it. Part of their growth has been by
acquisition, which will continue. But even without that they could
probably maintain 15 or 16 percent growth. With acquisitions,
they're growing about 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Another one I like is (medical products maker) Stryker. It's
back in the buy range. It's dropped down from $48 to around $30 or
$32. Fantastic company.
</P>
<P>
   Werner: Stryker is buying Pfizer's Howmedica orthopedics unit
for $1.9 billion, and the stock took a pretty good dip after that
was announced. This is a company that for years has had 20 percent
growth and a dynamic CEO that drills into his employees this 20
percent growth.
</P>
<P>
   I called the company and said I'm a long-term investor. But I
want to understand how much of a detour the company is taking (with
the Howmedica acquisition) and how long it's going to take to get
back to that 20 percent earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   The company told me that probably over the next year they will
be below 10 percent growth as they digest this acquisition. They
should get back to 20 percent growth in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This acquisition is going to make them a bigger, stronger,
dominant company. It will have about 15 percent of the worldwide
market for devices to repair injured joints and bones.
</P>
<P>
   What I'm trying to say is that you take advantage of the
short-term problems and be patient for the long-term payoff. There
are reasons it's down, and the market in general is not helping.
But if you do the research, you can be a lot more comfortable
sitting on a stock that may be depressed a while.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Let's turn to some hometown companies. What are your thoughts
about Home Depot, which some of you have?
</P>
<P>
   Williams: I love it. It's back in our buy range. The outlook is
fantastic. Lowe's is really not hurting at all. In fact I think
Lowe's is helping them, because it's making them get a little bit
more aggressive on what they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What about Coca-Cola?
</P>
<P>
   Williams: Coca-Cola is a fantastic company. I bought some last
week at $62, but I'll buy more when it's down below $58.
</P>
<P>
   Reno: I continue to buy shares for my wife. Matter of fact, she
came into a chunk of money and we bought more than our usual $100 a
month. But, yes, I'm still buying. I think it's getting better
every day as it comes down.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond: We discussed buying Coke at our last meeting, but
Disney won out because we hadn't purchased it for years and it was
more attractively priced, in our view.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Any others you like?
</P>
<P>
   Williams: Synovus Financial is one we haven't discussed that I
really like. It's really high right now, but it might come down.
It's a fantastic company, especially with the (bank card processor)
Total System Services kick to it. They own 80 percent of that.
</P>
<P>
   Werner: I follow Synovus for our club. Even though it's come
down from $25 to $18, I personally think it's overvalued. It has a
P/E of 29. It's high for a bank stock, even taking into
consideration Total System.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Did you sell any stocks?
</P>
<P>
   Reno: We had a member cash out at our last meeting, so we had to
sell some stocks. We eliminated our position in (filter maker) Pall
and (electronic chip maker) Atmel.
</P>
<P>
   We had Pall, I think, about 18 months. It didn't meet our
anticipation. Earnings have been going down rather than up. They
just reported for the fiscal year, and they're down again. We just
felt like we could do better elsewhere. I think we broke pretty
close to even, but we took a loss in Atmel. We sold (at) between
$10 and $11. We bought it at $38.
</P>
<P>
   We also sold Motorola the previous month. We were cleaning
house.
</P>
<P>
   Williams: That's something we need to do from time to time. But
most people sell the good stocks. You ought to get rid of your bad
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Reno: We had a lengthy discussion on that. Get rid of your dogs.
With a portfolio of 10 stocks, you're going to have one or two
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Any closing thoughts?
</P>
<P>
   Williams: It's a good time to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond: The last time we had a market downturn like this, in
1987, people were getting ready to jump off buildings. But those
who held off and didn't sell, they were back to normal within a
year. It may take a year for this market to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Reno: In '87, when it made the dive, I put some money in, and
I'm proud I did. I'm hoping that in the year 2003, when I look back
on '98, I can be real proud of it as well.
</P>
<P>
   Werner: The stock market has been my passion. I saw a chart in
Forbes that went back to 1801. And doggone it _ from 1801 to 1998 _
although there were a lot of ups and downs, the long-term trend for
stocks has always been up.
</P>
<P>
   How to get started
</P>
<P>
   Want to start or join an investment club?
</P>
<P>
   Contact the NAIC at 248-583-6242. The Internet address is
http://www.better-investing.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
