<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2552 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN-HNS     10-06 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS SEEK CLINTON COMPROMISE TO FUND GOVERNMENT, AVOID
SHUTDOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders said Tuesday that Congress would
not be able to finish work on all appropriations bills by its
scheduled adjournment deadline of Friday and asked President
Clinton to negotiate a compromise package that would fund the
government well into next year.
</P>
<P>
   But while extending the hand of compromise, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., accused President Clinton and
Democratic lawmakers of conspiring to force a government shutdown
to divert public attention from the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reaching out to try to get some discussion with them as
to what they want (in the 1999 spending measures),'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said GOP leaders are ``concerned about a domestic `Wag
the Dog' scenario in which Clinton would veto a number of spending
bills this week and force a government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   The reference to the movie in which a president stages a phony
war to distract attention from sexual misbehavior drew a sharp
response from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Press Secretary Joe Lockhart denied that there are any ``secret
plans'' to close government operations. He said Lott and other
Republican leaders should ``stop worrying about the politics and
start worrying about the job they were sent here to do and get the
work done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been in session now for nine months,'' Lockhart added.
``We're now six days late (for the 1999 fiscal year that began on
Oct. 1).''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his concerns, Lott said he was hopeful that White House
officials would meet with congressional leaders as early as today
to work out the details of rolling at least five of the 13 major
appropriations measures into one omnibus bill. He acknowledged that
packaging whatever the Republican-controlled Congress fails to pass
before Friday into one big measure is the only way to avoid an
interruption in government services and allow members time to
campaign for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers realized several weeks ago that they would not be able
to complete work on the major spending bills by Oct. 1, and adopted
a temporary funding measure that expires at midnight Friday. If
lawmakers fail to reach agreement with the White House on remaining
spending matters by then, they may have to pass another stopgap
measure until compromise agreements can be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Congress will complete work by Friday on no more than
eight of the 13 bills needed to fund government operations. That
would leave five that would have to be combined. But many of those,
covering everything from foreign operations, labor and commerce to
education, contain funding levels and amendments that have been the
source of disagreements between Clinton and the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Clinton wants $14 billion included in the State
Department spending bill to help shore up the International
Monetary Fund. But conservative Republicans, led by House Majority
Leader Dick Armey of Irving, are against it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also wants money to hire 100,000 new teachers and build
more schools, and wants to eliminate what he considers a number of
anti-environmental provisions in the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem we have is the president, as usual, and the
Democrats, want to spend more money,'' Lott said. He added that a
meeting with administration officials would try to focus on where
the ``major heartburn'' problems are with remaining legislation.
</P>
<P>
   With the clock ticking down, both sides appeared willing to
abandon a number of controversial positions to avoid a budget
stalemate like the one that forced partial government shutdowns in
1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Armey, for instance, announced that GOP conservatives had
dropped their insistence that school vouchers be included in the
District of Columbia funding measure that would allow parents to
send their children to private schools. Clinton had threatened to
veto the bill if the voucher program remained in it.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate side, meanwhile, Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., signaled that Democrats were ready to negotiate as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``With time running out, we realize that we're not going to get
everything we want,'' he said. ``But we want a lot more than the
Republicans are offering.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Congress has completed work on six of the 13
appropriations measures. But the $60 billion farm bill approved by
the Senate Tuesday could be headed for a veto because it falls $3
billion short of the $7 billion Clinton requested for emergency
relief to farmers and ranchers hit by drought and floods. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
