<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2551 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-ECONOMY-COX     10-06 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-ECONOMY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wobbly world threatens to unseat U.S. economy
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's interest rate cut as the third quarter
came to an end was a clear sign policy-makers think the world's
economic problems are a threat to the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   The cut of a quarter of a percentage point in the federal funds
rate was about as small a change as the Fed could make. But it
symbolized Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan's intention to prevent a
recession, which some analysts had begun to fear.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan had warned the Senate Budget Committee in advance of
the Fed's policy meeting on Tuesday about the danger of
``deteriorating foreign economies and their spillover to domestic
markets ...''
</P>
<P>
   And clearly, the bailout of the huge Long-Term Capital
Management hedge fund showed the depth of the Fed's concern about
how vulnerable U.S. financial institutions might be.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's rate cut, designed to stimulate the economy, was the
first rate change in almost a year and a half, and a dramatic
switch from the Fed's usual policy of guarding against inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan and others have argued that inflation is in no
danger of becoming a problem in an environment of global deflation
and slower U.S. growth. In short, encouraging growth has replaced
fighting inflation as the Fed's strategic objective.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is expected to make additional rate cuts if necessary to
maintain the economy's growth and hold off the foreign threat.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the Fed was too cautious in cutting rates on
the first go-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point there is no commodity inflation whatsoever.
However, there is labor market inflation, and there's nothing that
is easing that off,'' said Georgia State University economist
Donald Ratajczak.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so we we're starting to see some accelerating prices in
the service sector even as we're seeing deceleration or actual
declines in prices on commodities,'' he said. ``I think they (the
Fed) should have been more aggressive, but I understand their
reasoning.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed aimed chiefly at boosting the economy, analysts
said Greenspan and company were also concerned about the economic
impact of the stock market sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of household wealth due to declining stock prices has
been estimated as high as $1.5 trillion since the sell-off started
on July 17 _ when the benchmark Dow Jones industrial average peaked
at 9,337.97.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of loss that threatens to weaken consumer
spending, forcing people to curb their spendthrift habits, analysts
fear.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the economy is that a drastic cut in consumer
spending has not yet occurred. If anything, the consumer is still
driving the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems in Asia, Russia and Latin America, coupled with
the prospect of further stock market losses, are expected to put
pressure on the economy over the next 12 to 18 months despite
interest rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, analysts say that the trade, investment and other
financial links now connecting world economies are what caused the
stock market sell-off and the U.S. economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary problem is not the market downturn itself, but the
world financial crisis that triggered the slide,'' said David A.
Wyss, Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI chief economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian economies are showing few signs of recovery, and in
fact are tumbling deeper into recession. The Asian flu is also
showing signs of infecting South America,'' said Wyss.
</P>
<P>
   While the Russian crisis is not directly connected to Asia, he
said it reflects and reinforces the increasing investor wariness of
all emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the world's economic problems are affected
primarily by Japan's reluctance to go through with promised
financial reforms. A Japanese rescue would go a long way toward
curing Asia's problems, it is thought.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's foot-dragging has led in turn to growing concern that
China, which still promises to hold the line on its currency, may
yield next year and devalue the yuan to protect its producers.
</P>
<P>
   That would set off another series of currency devaluations not
only in Asia, but very likely in Latin America, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, of course, is not so much an economic threat _ its
economy is about the size of Denmark's _ but its problems are
emblematic of the difficulty that once centrally planned countries
have had in adopting market capitalism. Their cultures have no
experience with it.
</P>
<P>
   All of these trends threaten to converge some time in the future
as an economic problem that may be too big for the United States to
handle.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the nation shows signs of ``moderate'' growth, the
New York Federal Reserve District has already reported that
``significant segments of its economy were slowing,'' and the
Dallas district showed decelerating manufacturing growth in August.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term interest rates, which are market-related and affect
bond yields, already are at historic lows. The 30-year Treasury
yield has moved below 5 percent, due in part to demand for bonds
from foreign investors looking for a safe haven. The demand that
drove prices higher pushed yields lower.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Fed's rate cut at the end of September, and the
prospect of further rate cuts, drove bond prices even higher and,
therefore, yields lower.
</P>
<P>
   The economy could get some help from a rebounding economy,
according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody knows what the market is likely to do. The outlook
greatly depends on what kind of third-quarter corporate earnings
reports are released during October.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations are not very optimistic, although first- and
second-quarter profits turned out better than predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The strong U.S. dollar has hurt profit growth so far this year,
but it has also helped the economy to retain at least a part of a
``just right'' aura _ in the form of minimal inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Economists look for consumer price increases to remain in the 2
percent to 3 percent range in the next 18 months, thanks in part to
the cheap Asian imports the dollar makes possible.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts contend that foreign economies may get so weak
that the problem will shift from inflation to deflation.
</P>
<P>
   But without dismissing it as impossible, most mainstream
analysts doubt prices will get that weak.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, analysts see even more events that could have an
impact on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   One is the European Union's currency that is scheduled to go
into effect Jan. 1, creating another enormous and competitive
market.
</P>
<P>
   And while the prospect of a presidential impeachment is still up
in the air, analysts believe the long-range implication of future
congressional and White House economic policy may be decided by the
outcome, at least in part.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the Year 2000 problem. Analysts are greatly
divided over what is likely to happen when 2000 arrives, with
computers misinterpreting dates ending in two zeroes.
</P>
<P>
   But with the next millennium just 15 months away, its one of
those economic problems that seems certain to get increasing
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
