<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-EURO-COX     10-06 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-EURO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Switch to euro considered good for U.S. investors
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lot of computer code to fix, and if the job isn't done
on time unconverted software could plague or even shut down banking
systems and stock trading. No, it's not the year 2000 problem. It's
the euro conversion scheduled to kick off Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   On that date, 11 countries _ France, Italy, Germany, Austria,
Belgium, Finland, Ireland, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Spain and
Portugal _ will begin to phase out their native currencies in favor
of the euro. It's part of the final phase of the European Monetary
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Four other countries in the union _ Great Britain, Sweden,
Denmark and Greece _ haven't opted to phase out their traditional
currencies, but the euro will be legal tender in those nations as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, many experts were saying the euro introduction
would create a crunch like that posed by millennial date foul-ups.
Now, in many quarters, the worries seem to have been displaced by
euphoria about the new era.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the message for investors seems to be: Prepare for
short-term technological disruptions of the European financial
system. But over the longer term, the euro will provide a strong
backing for investments.
</P>
<P>
   That means it will make more sense for U.S. investors to buy
European stocks, bonds and real estate than it does now because the
euro is expected to be strong currency. In a recent cover article,
The European, a weekly business magazine, trumpets, ``European
stock markets will benefit from a wave of risk-averse money which
has to find a home.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the euro also should mean U.S. investors _ and
U.S. companies _ will be better protected against currency
fluctuations in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But first there's the conversion to make, and if things go wrong
at the outset, European stocks and bonds could take a fall,
offering temporary bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts, such as Capers Jones, chief scientist at Artemis
Management Systems of Boulder, Colo., continue to expect trouble.
Jones believes only 55 percent of European companies, and most of
the governments, won't be ready. He estimates delays in the
conversion will last for three to nine months and that computer
disruptions could cost $1 billion per day.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph A. Whitt Jr., an economist with the Federal Reserve Bank
of Atlanta, is among those with a positive view about the
conversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hassle for banks and other companies that have to
convert their financial records, but in a sense it's just taking
their old numbers and dividing them into a new number that
represents the euro,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The countries that adapt the euro will give up control of their
monetary policy _ the ability to expand or contract their supply of
money, a tool most governments consider a vital instrument of
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Control will pass into the hands of the European Central Bank in
Brussels. The other central banks will remain in operation but
without their monetary teeth.
</P>
<P>
   In return for that loss of control, the participating nations
can expect to benefit from a strong, stable currency. The European
Central Bank will be managed in spirit, in not in fact, by
Germany's inflation-fighting central bank, the Bundesbank.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the euro is expected to threaten the dollar
both as the currency of choice in foreign exchange transactions and
as the preferred currency backing for investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The euro is going to become a major global currency as long at
they hold the union together,'' said Mark Gargano, managing
director of currency derivatives at First Union.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
