<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Enough already! After self-pity, life's looking up
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When bad things like an automobile accident happen to bumbling,
well-meaning but clumsy people like me, the first step, according
to my raising, is to say your prayers and promise to try harder and
do better in the future.
</P>
<P>
   You also get specific. I'll never say anything mean about
anybody, I vowed (and I do enjoy nipping at other people when I get
a chance).
</P>
<P>
   I'll start doing all the things I dread and avoid. And I did. I
went home and cleaned out the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   I'll hire that nice cleaning lady I heard about and keep an
impeccably tidy house. (She came and looked around and departed
looking defeated. There are some places a respectable cleaning lady
wouldn't touch with a 10-foot pole.) So I washed dishes, the ones I
had hidden from her, and made beds and finally got in one of them,
pulled up the cover and, to quote a Jewish mother I met, I said
``Enough, already!''
</P>
<P>
   You can be upbeat and striving for just so long. Then your
bruises begin to hurt almost more than your conscience, which was
mortally offended that my good car, bought through the courtesy of
friends, sat in a garage with the ultimate bad word against its
name: ``Totaled.''
</P>
<P>
   I, too, am totaled, I thought. My arms hurt; my legs hurt;
there's a pain somewhere in back and ribs. Here I sit in a cold,
dirty cabin without wheels to take me to the world out there beyond
the paved road. Totaled is the word for me.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, woe, woe is me. And then I heard the rain on the tin roof,
and I thought, if you have gratitude in your heart for anything,
now's the time to recognize it. Rain on the tin roof, who has
anything better? So I lit the fire in the fireplace and pulled up a
wool throw. (A legacy from my late friend, Faith Brunson. And the
friendship of people like Faith suddenly made me ashamed of my
self-pitying slump.)
</P>
<P>
   And then I went to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   When I awoke, the sun was shining. It was suddenly a summer day,
except for the dogwood trees in the back yard, which are turning
gold and red.
</P>
<P>
   My granddaughter Betsy and her little friend, Alex, arrived with
nutty muffins and stayed to show me a dance they are practicing.
Tib, my big granddaughter, called to see if I needed a ride. My
biggest grandson, John, called to offer me a ride to look at rental
cars, strongly recommending that I go for a Mack truck. My other
grown-up grandson, Bird, called to make a date for car-looking and
to say comforting words about other people who have survived dumb
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The inference, of course, is I'm not the only one. Or as Snoopy,
the wise hound in ``Peanuts'' put it, when Charlie Brown read him
an item about National Dog Day, ``I am not unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the world looked good to me. Driving to town had a
fresh feeling about it. I hadn't done it for a long time, it seemed
to me, although it was only two days. I was glad to be at work and
to find two gifts of the season _ a jar of muscadine jelly and a
diminutive pot of yellow chrysanthemums.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know where all those bruises went, and I don't ask. I
picked up a little black book put out by NationsBank. It's called
``The Book of Excellence,'' and it opened to words of instruction:
``Look at life through the windshield, not through the rear view
mirror.'' And one that's hard to follow: ``It is important that you
like yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
