<HEADER>
A2561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DAWSON-COX     10-06 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DAWSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dawson is back_ with hormones raging in full force
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C._Here is where to catch the buzz on ``Dawson's
Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   In high school hallways, students are anticipating tonight's
second-season premiere on WB. The adolescent soap opera, featuring
the tangled love lives and improbable philosophizing of four
good-looking kids, all 16-going-on-30, quickly became the No. 1
show among teen girls on any network last season.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, fans chatter with obsessive zeal about each
episode.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can catch the real buzz, the annoying attack of countless
insects on a muggy, buggy day on the set of ``Dawson's Creek.''
Near a reedy marsh, in what serves as Dawson Leery's back yard, the
gnats and mosquitoes are as thick as adolescent longing. Crew
members spray themselves with bug repellent and occasionally slap a
bare arm as the pouty-mouthed Jen (Michelle Williams) tells
ever-so-earnest Dawson (James Van Der Beek): ``You are so on the
rebound, Dawson.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dawson's Creek'' sets are closed, of course, both the
houses that double for Dawson's and Jen's, and the soundstages at
Wilmington's Screen Gems Studio, previously home to ``Matlock'' and
movies like ``Billy Bathgate'' and ``Blue Velvet,'' now housing the
interiors of Dawson's house.
</P>
<P>
   Everything's up to date in Dawson's bedroom. An aspiring
filmmaker and Steven Spielberg wannabe, the TV character has
plastered his walls with Spielberg movie posters, even the bad ones
(``Hook''). Last year, the ``Dawson'' folks had to beg Spielberg's
company for permission to use the posters. For this new season,
Spielberg gladly sent a one-sheet of ``Saving Private Ryan'' to
hang above Dawson's bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's Creek'' had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the show arrived with its target audience almost from
the moment it debuted in January. Boosted by a canny saturation
marketing campaign by WB, the show had enormous word-of-mouth among
teens even before it debuted. They even knew it was created by the
jalapeno-hot screenwriter Kevin Williamson, who'd written
``Scream'' and ``I Know What You Did Last Summer,'' and who based
Dawson on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nielsen ratings are small by ``ER'' standards,
``Dawson'' is a hit with more than teen girls. In Atlanta, where
ratings are more than twice as high as the national average, it
sometimes beat ``Ally McBeal'' and ``Frasier'' last season. The
cast appeared on TV Guide covers and in a special J. Crew catalog.
This season, the WB moved it to 8 p.m. ET Wednesdays in an attempt
to knock off ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' (although the two won't go
head-to-head until Oct. 21 because of baseball playoffs).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' says Van Der Beek of the media swirl, the
magazine covers, the fandom. One Wilmington teen was hired to be an
extra and fainted dead away at her first sight of Van Der Beek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very dehumanizing actually,'' he says. ``You cease to be
a human being. All of a sudden, you're a novelty item.''
</P>
<P>
   But the four young stars _ in addition to Van Der Beek and
Williams, there's Joshua Jackson as Pacey and Katie Holmes as Joey,
both long-time buds of Dawson _ agree that filming in bucolic
Wilimington, an entire country and several attitude zones away from
Los Angeles, has kept them steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. is a wonderful city and it has so much to offer, but it's
almost too much,'' says Holmes, sitting on a bug-free screened
porch on the set, a copy of ``Pride and Prejudice'' on a table in
front of her. ``Everything's about the business. To be able to
concentrate solely on what we're doing and not be exposed to all
the temptations, life is a little more simple here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. is the epicenter of hype,'' says Williams, who's only 18
but speaks in a soft, slightly bruised manner that makes her seem
older. ``But it's really hard to pick up and move your life to a
town you might not normally pick.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Josh, the most aptly named of the four _ Josh
Jackson. As Pacey, he's the comic spice in their stew of teen
angst. As Josh, he bounds around the set with more energy than his
huge black dog, Simba (which he pronounces Shoom-ba).
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels kind of chilly out here,'' he announces loudly to no
one, strolling through Dawson's back yard on a hot, humid day. Over
the next few hours, as soon as director Joe Napolitano yells
``Cut!,'' Jackson acts as if that's his cue to cut loose: a few
lines of ``I Feel Pretty'' from ``West Side Story,'' followed by
``I Just Wanna Fly'' and ``Rock On.'' To round off the off-screen
performance, he gives Holmes a long, tight bear-hug, then walks
away whistling ``Raindrops Keep Fallin' On My Head.''
</P>
<P>
   He does, however, keep his pants on. One of Jackson's set stunts
is to ``hang a moon'' at other cast members, something he says he
hasn't done so far this season. To which Van Der Beek replies with
a cryptic smile and a raised eyebrow, ``Has he not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to keep the mood on the set as light as possible,''
says Jackson. ``There's no need for it to be somber all the time.
We're here to do a job, but it's a pleasurable job.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also some new faces hanging out in Wilmington these
days. Monica Keena, who appeared as sassy trouble-maker Abby in one
episode last season, is now a regular. And Meredith Monroe and Kerr
Smith are joining the cast as Andie and Jack McPhee, brother and
sister who move to Capeside, Mass., the show's fictional setting.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson describes Andie as ``over-achieving and slightly
anxious,'' and says she and Pacey will be very romantically
involved. Katie Holmes, whose Joey will be paired up with Jack
(much to Dawson's chagrin), describes Jack as ``kind of aloof, a
little shy, and you don't quite understand what he's about for
awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Williamson and the show's producers realized ``Dawson'' couldn't
keep going just on last season's love triangle among Dawson, Joey
and Jen; hence the new blood. Also on tap this season:
</P>
<P>
   -- Jen will return to her bad-girl ways, says Williams, of being
promiscuous and self-destructive. As an actress, ``it's the stuff I
wait and long for.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Dawson will win a film festival award, his first step toward
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   -- A big homecoming dance will feature swing dancing similiar to
the popular ``Jump, Jive and Wail'' Gap TV ads. A bunch of
Wilmington high school dancers spent several days learning and
filming the intricate dance steps.
</P>
<P>
   The first two months have not been a total tap-dance on the
``Dawson'' set, though. Hurricane Bonnie swept through North
Carolina and knocked out production for four days; the shooting
schedule is so tight they're only now catching up.
</P>
<P>
   And Williamson's film career kept him away for more than a
month, causing the show to suffer a bit, according to Williams and
Van Der Beek. The creator finally flew to Wimington in September to
meet with the cast and crew and help map a strategy, before heading
back to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any show has growing pains,'' says Van Der Beek, at 21 the
elder of the main cast. ``I think it ended up being a little more
vague than we wanted it to be. The episodes are actually a lot
stronger than we were afraid. They're fine, they're just not a cut
above.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a long day of filming, Van Der Beek sits in a
trailer. His hair is held back off his square-jawed face by several
large white plastic hairclips, making him look anything but the
teen idol, and he looks back on an amazing recent run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's surprised me how quickly everything happened, how I went
from looking for an agent to turning down films in a year and half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from college (Drew University in Madison, N.J.), being
an English major, I auditioned for this show on this tiny little
network, and I got it. I got a pilot. But then of all the pilots
they make, this one actually got picked up. That doesn't happen
very often. But then to be on a show that has this much buzz, I
struck gold. It's like a one in a million shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's Creek''
</P>
<P>
   8 EDT tonight on WB
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
