<HEADER>
A2563 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER07-COX     10-06 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Only time will tell if latest UPN offering will be successful
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A big, old-fashioned thriller-adventure with hokey dialogue,
ticking digital readouts, political assassinations and more gun
battles and blow-'em-up scenes than a summerfull of Jerry
Bruckheimer pocorn flicks? Sign us up, says UPN, as long as it's
about time travel.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, ``Seven Days'' (8 EDT tonight on UPN), which is loaded
with preposterous doo-dah but works just fine as neat-o mindless
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Our hero is Frank Parker (Jonathan LaPaglia of ``New York
Undercover''), an ex-CIA op who's shut up in a mental hospital,
then is recruited for a secret project called Operation Back-Step.
Is Parker really nuts? ``I'm not crazy enough to get involved in an
operation you want a crazy man for,'' he says, just before he signs
up.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that while Parker was squirreled away, Russian
terrorists killed the U.S. president, vice president, speaker of
the house and the Russian president for good measure. Why? Who
cares? All we care about is the big spherical machine at a secret
military base in Nevada that can send Parker back in time seven
days to thwart the assassinations.
</P>
<P>
   Why can Back-Step only send one man back in time for only seven
days? Who cares? All Parker cares about is changing history to save
his young son's life (he was killed in the attack); getting down a
bet on a basketball game where he already knows the outcome; and
making time with the babe-ski Russian defector scientist (Justina
Vail) who's part of the time-travel team.
</P>
<P>
   How can ``Seven Days'' be a long-running series when all it can
do, according to tonight's two-hour pilot, is send Parker back in
time one week, over and over and over?
</P>
<P>
   UPN had better care. It doesn't look like a premise with much
long-range promise. So for now, enjoy the corny but engaging pilot.
As for the future, only time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   ``Charmed'' is a bad stupid show
</P>
<P>
   It's not like there's never been a successful stupid show. The
key may be those stupid shows that don't realize they are stupid.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Charmed'' (9 EDT tonight on WB) and its trio of
sisters-turned-witches fits the bill. It's real stupid _ but it's
no ``Charlie's Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannen Doherty, Alyssa Milano and Holly Marie Combs portray
``we sisters three'' who live together in a big old house in San
Francisco, change their low-cut blouses every few minutes and end
up discovering they're good little witches with special powers. One
can see the future. One can freeze-frame aggressive boyfriends and
really bad dudes. And one can make things move with her mind.
</P>
<P>
   What they're destined to do is slay evil warlocks (there's
millions of 'em out there in all shapes and forms, we're told). And
on ``Charmed,'' our girls do this with far less aplomb than Buffy,
who so gloriously kicks vampire butt every Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good stupid show here. It's just not there yet.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
