<HEADER>
A2566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESCAPE-SAILBOAT-2NDTA     10-06 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCAPE-SAILBOAT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: from capsizing. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beginners, not surprisingly, love the Escape. ``It's not very
tippy, and sure enough, it is easy to learn,'' said Kathryn Tarsa,
a 40-something newcomer to sailing who bought an Escape with her
husband, John, last year to sail near their home in Duxbury, Mass.
``The video showed exactly how to do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some longtime seafarers see the attraction of the boat. Si
Kamen, 78, is an experienced sailor who owns a larger boat, but he
keeps an Escape at the dock behind his home in Bel Marin Keys,
Calif., because it is so quick to set up. ``It performs pretty
well,'' he said. Best of all, ``you unroll the sail and you're off,
in two minutes.'' He adds, though, that he would like more leg
room.
</P>
<P>
   Reviews of the Escape sailboats by the sailing establishment
have been mixed, with some deriding them as plastic pool toys and
others praising any product that can bring fresh faces to the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   The Escape ``is sort of a crossover boat between your typical
beach toy and your real boat,'' said Robert Perry, a naval
architect and columnist for Sailing magazine, who keeps an Escape
at his beachfront home near Seattle. ``I sail the 11.5-footer onto
the beach full bore. It's supremely designed for that use.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Colgate, president of the Offshore Sailing School, a chain
based in Fort Myers, Fla., has bought four Escapes for his
children's classes, but he said he did not believe the boat was a
significant advance over the classic Sunfish, the quintessential
beach boat that was introduced 45 years ago and is the all-time
best-selling sailboat.
</P>
<P>
   In their heyday, about 10,000 to 15,000 Sunfishes, which were
not much more than a sail attached to a shallow-hulled board wide
enough for one or two people to sit on, were sold annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the hype is far beyond what it delivers,'' Colgate
said of the Escape. ``Once you learn to sail the Escape, which
takes maybe an hour, where do you go from there? Then you need to
get into something with more challenge.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One thing that irks Colgate, not surprisingly, is the assertion
that the Escape eliminates the need for sailing lessons. It is an
assertion aggressively promoted by Johnstone, whose name means
something in the sailboat industry. Twenty years ago, his father
and uncle founded Jboats, a successful maker of racing sailboats in
Newport, R.I. After graduating from college, Johnstone joined the
company alongside several siblings and cousins, but his strong
opinions soon brought him a polite invitation to leave, he says.
</P>
<P>
   So he formed a partnership, with North Sails, the leading maker
of high-performance sails, and Gary Jobson, a former America's Cup
skipper, to buy the Sunfish and Laser brands from a struggling
manufacturer. Although they succeeded in reviving these two
venerable designs, naming their company Sunfish Laser Inc.,
Johnstone said they were dismayed to discover virtually all of
their sales were to longtime sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a new outlet, they conceived the Escape, which was
introduced in April 1996. Once the new design seemed to attract
interest, they sold Sunfish Laser last year to Vanguard Sailboats
Inc., a leading maker of small racing boats, also based in
Portsmouth. Escape now offers four hull sizes, and two kinds of
rigs. It has also recently branched out to offer plastic canoes.
</P>
<P>
   While sailing traditionalists frown on plastic, regarding it as
an inferior material, it is rapidly gaining acceptance at the low
end of the boating market. Vanguard now offers a plastic boat, the
Pico, at $2,095; a plastic trimaran, the Windrider, from Wilderness
Systems has also been a strong seller at $3,350. (A trimaran is
similar to a catamaran, but has three parallel hulls instead of
two.) The Hobie Cat Co. actually introduced the first rotomolded
plastic boat, a 13-foot catamaran called the Wave, in October 1994.
At $3,595, it is now the company's best-selling boat.
</P>
<P>
   But many industry longtimers question the material's longevity.
A short life span could be a plus for the industry, though, if it
encourages people to replace their boats more frequently. Because
fiberglass stands up so well, companies like Sunfish Laser and
Hobie have had to compete with their own products on the used
market, where boats can be had for a few hundred dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Johnstone readily concedes that rotomolded plastic becomes
brittle with prolonged exposure to sunlight, and he estimates the
life of an Escape from as little as 5 years if left outside in the
Caribbean, to 15 years, sailed seasonally in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of having to deal with used Sunfish 45 years after
they were built,'' he said, ``we'll have to deal with Escapes for
15 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
