<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-FLOODS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH TOLL RISES IN AFTERMATH OF FLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
 - take 1 of 2-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS and GLENN E. RICE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The death toll from flash floods rose to
seven Monday _ with two more missing _ as authorities began
assessing the devastation left by one of the worst floods in Kansas
City's history.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the area, heartrending stories surfaced as witnesses
told of using ropes, garden hoses _ anything they could find _ in
desperate attempts to pluck terrified victims from the raging
waters. Two of the victims were on their cellular phones calling
for help when they were swept away.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy rain, as much as 7.7 inches in some areas, deluged
streets and businesses, closed highways and knocked out power.
</P>
<P>
   Destruction was widespread. Southwest Boulevard was swamped by
as much as 5 feet of water. Damage to the American Royal Building
could exceed $2.5 million. Brush Creek, at the top of its banks,
swept three cars off the Prospect Avenue bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross teams found waterlogged cars that had been tossed like
toys, dozens of basements filled with water and many homes with
structural damage, some with portions of their foundations washed
away.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Emanuel Cleaver estimated the damage in Kansas City to be
in the millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss of life we take very seriously,'' Cleaver said at a
news conference Monday afternoon. He said the city had documented
at least two dozen successful rescues.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also visited another hard-hit area, the Village Green
Apartments, 1500 E. 46th St., near the Country Club Plaza. More
than 100 units were damaged. Cars plastered with mud were stacked
two and three deep.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver said city officials would meet to discuss the
possibility of applying for federal disaster aid.
</P>
<P>
   The flood claimed victims throughout the area, five of them at
the Prospect Avenue bridge over Brush Creek. Those found:
</P>
<P>
   - Orlando Hudson, 27, of Kansas City, who had gone in search of
cough medicine and candles. His car stalled on the Prospect Avenue
bridge over Brush Creek and was swept away. He had a wife and two
children, ages 3 and 1 week.
</P>
<P>
   - Bonita L. Black, 43, of Kansas City, whose car was swept into
Brush Creek at the Prospect Avenue bridge.
</P>
<P>
   - Azalech Zewuda, 57, of Overland Park, Kan., whose body was
found late Sunday in the tennis court area of the Carriage Club at
5301 State Line Road.
</P>
<P>
   - John W. Parmerlee, 8, who drowned when the runoff from a cove
leading to Lake Jacomo overflowed behind his house in Blue Springs,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   - Walter Nott, 83, of Overland Park, whose car stalled at 103rd
and Connell streets. Witnesses said he tried to get out but was
swept away by rushing water.
</P>
<P>
   - Kenny W. Tucker Jr., 27, of Lenexa, Kan., who was found about
a half-mile from his car, which was in Mill Creek.
</P>
<P>
   - An unidentified body was found in Brush Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Those still missing:
</P>
<P>
   - Rushonda Talifero, 25, of Kansas City, who called her mother
on a cellular phone from the Prospect Avenue bridge and said her
Ford Explorer was going into Brush Creek.
</P>
<P>
   - Edna McNeal, 44, of Grandview, Mo., who was a passenger of
Talifero's.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, emergency sewer crews worked throughout the day
Monday, responding to reports of flooded basements at more than 70
homes. Flooding and electrical outages also shut down storm and
wastewater pump stations at Kemper Arena, on State Line Road and on
83rd Street early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Crews from the Water Services Department erected 83 high-water
barricades early Monday to block motorists from 36 flooded
intersections.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the flooding occurred simply because the stormwater
system was overwhelmed. Some areas received rainfall of 7 inches in
an hour and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kansas City sewer system isn't designed to handle this
much water,'' said spokeswoman Nancy Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Rick Brisbin said the Fire Department responded to about
50 reports Sunday night of persons trapped by water. About 35 of
the calls required the Fire Department's assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going into areas where we typically respond to high
water,'' Brisbin said. ``But there are an awful lot of places we
responded to where we never had high water before.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the storm's intensity was second only to the
flood of 1977, when up to 16 inches of rain fell on the area in a
24-hour period, sending Brush Creek out of its banks and inundating
many Country Club Plaza businesses.
</P>
<P>
   That flood, which killed 25, displaced thousands and caused
nearly $100 million in damage. It was one of the worst natural
disasters in the area's history, and some of its victims were
missing for days.
</P>
<P>
   While more rain is expected, the worst may be over,
meteorologists said. The National Weather Service predicted light
showers for today and Wednesday, but said the moisture should not
cause more flooding. Partly cloudy skies the remainder of the week
should allow the area to begin drying out.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Frevert, deputy public works director, said the city still
was assessing damage to the Prospect Avenue bridge late Monday
afternoon. Because of lingering high water, engineers could not
make a complete assessment of the damaged southeast corner of the
structure, Frevert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bridge will be closed for some time until we can assess
the damage and determine how much of it we can reopen,'' Frevert
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Wolf, public works director, said the damage at the Prospect
bridge was similar to that in the 1977 flood. The bridge is not
part of the Brush Creek flood-control project, but Wolf said the
city needed to consider adding it.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson's family said the bridge should be raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could save other people's lives,'' said Dorothy Hudson, his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   City crews also worked on a collapsed section of Brush Creek
Boulevard between Woodland Avenue and Bruce R. Watkins Drive.
Frevert said nearby concrete channel protection had collapsed,
causing soil under the roadway to erode. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
