</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-FLOODS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH TOLL RISES IN AFTERMATH OF FLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
 - take 2 of 2-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS and GLENN E. RICE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PICKUP AFTER ``ROADWAY TO ERODE.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffic for about three blocks of Brush Creek Boulevard has been
restricted to the two westbound lanes, one way in each direction.
</P>
<P>
   Frevert also said that crews would continue cleaning Southwest
Boulevard, with the street scheduled for reopening about 8 p.m.
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Police and firefighters were credited with saving many lives,
and bystanders rescued stranded motorists. Some attempts, however,
were fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   LaKeisha Johnson and several friends were on their way to
Skateland in Grandview around 8 p.m. when they saw water rise along
Prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone yelled, `It's a car over the guardrail and bridge!' &UR; ''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Passers-by grabbed ropes and garden hoses and tossed them to
persons in the vehicles. Authorities said one man thought about
diving into the water, but the currents were too strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water was cascading off the bridge like a waterfall,'' said
Clovis Hampton, who lives nearby on 45th Street and Chestnut
Avenue. ``I had seen it flood down here before, but never like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   About 9 p.m. Sunday, flash flooding collapsed a portion of a
bridge at Prospect Avenue and Brush Creek Boulevard, pushing two
cars carrying at least five persons into the creek.
</P>
<P>
   Currents were too strong for firefighters to ford the creek,
said Fire Department spokesman Brad Humston. Nearly 175
firefighters helped in the rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of two persons were pulled from Brush Creek around 2
a.m. Monday, as emergency crews spent the day searching along the
banks of the creek.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Howard, a diver with Recovery Inc., Underwater Rescue and
Recovery, based in Lee's Summit, said the water in Brush Creek was
moving about 7 knots, compared with the Missouri River, which
travels at 3 knots.
</P>
<P>
   As the water began to recede shortly after 4 p.m. Monday,
firefighters and police searching the banks of Brush Creek
discovered another victim.
</P>
<P>
   Covered with mud, the body was discovered about three blocks
away, face down in a muddy area in the middle of the creek just
west of Benton Boulevard. Underwater Rescue and Recovery teams
pulled the body to shore.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, a tow-truck driver pulled a white Ford
Explorer from the murky water just east of Prospect Avenue. No one
was found inside the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Searchers combed the creek throughout the evening for two
missing persons.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities on Monday expressed frustration that many drivers
failed to heed flash flood warnings. Several of the areas where
people drowned, particularly along Brush Creek, have been problem
spots for years.
</P>
<P>
   Humston said the city did not have enough barricades to block
off every area that floods.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency officials said people must rely on common sense and be
especially careful at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think they realize how deep the water is,
especially when they can't see,'' said Julie Llorente, Kansas
City's emergency preparedness coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about sirens, but we definitely don't want to use
those for flooding, because most people, when they hear a siren,
they're going to go to their basement, which is the last place you
want to be.'' &QL; 
Flood control
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps of Engineers spent Monday monitoring
flood-control projects across the area and checking for signs of
potential flooding.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting assessing the damage, Michael Bart, chief of
planning and hydrology for the corps, showed officials a film he
took of the flooding Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brush Creek came close to coming out of its banks,'' Bart
said. ``It had its problems. But the project appeared to do its
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bart said Indian Creek and the Blue River also were high, as was
the Kansas River.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the respite in the weather Monday, Col. George H. Hazel,
district engineer for the Corps of Engineers, said he was concerned
that more flooding might develop in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned about the lower reaches of the Missouri
River,'' Hazel said.
</P>
<P>
   Communities along the river were taking heed Monday. In
Jefferson City, the National Weather Service forecast that the
Missouri River would crest Thursday at 35.9 feet _ just two feet
lower than the highest crest of the flood of 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
