</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-DINNER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY TALKS ABOUT HEALTH CARE, WORLD FINANCIAL CRISIS, AND HIS
BASKETBALL CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. JOSEPH, Mo. _ He talked about health-care policy, and he
talked about the international financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Bradley, the former National Basketball Association
star who served as a U.S. senator from New Jersey for 18 years,
knew what his audience really wanted to know Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John Havlicek was the toughest guy I ever guarded,''
Bradley said about the former Boston Celtics great Monday night at
Missouri Western State College's Convocation Dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, no one in the crowd of 300 asked Bradley about
the best player he ever guarded during his pro career with the New
York Knicks. Bradley just threw out the answer as a quip because he
is asked that question so often.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the crowd asked him about another pressing matter
either, and the question hung in the air like a crucial shot in a
tie game with no time remaining: Is Bradley, who retired from the
Senate in 1997, running for president in 2000?
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, at a news conference, Bradley said what every
likely candidate says about such things: He's weighing the decision
carefully. He'll decide by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   But judge Bradley not by what he says, but by his actions _ such
as his frantic, fast-break-like schedule in the Kansas City area
Tuesday. Following the college's annual convocation Tuesday
morning, Bradley was to hit the campaign trail _ not for himself,
but for several fellow Democrats in tight races.
</P>
<P>
   Those candidates include incumbent state Sen. Sidney Johnson of
Agency, Mo., who was to meet Bradley at a Northland nursing home.
At an education rally in Lee's Summit, Mo., Bradley was to stand
beside state Senate contender Pat Starke.
</P>
<P>
   He'll was to cross the state line into Kansas to appear with
Dennis Moore, the Third District congressional candidate. In a
meeting at the Kansas City Club, the two were to discuss crime.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Bradley is acting an awful lot like a presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   During his ranging, 45-minute question-and-answer session Monday
night, Bradley mixed stories from his days in sports with his views
on current affairs _ a combination that proved highly appealing
judging by the audience's rapt attention.
</P>
<P>
   He was highly critical of the flat tax, the dramatically
simplified income-tax system touted by some members of both
parties. Calling it a ``rhetorical device'' invented by those
frustrated with the Internal Revenue Service, the former senator
said the plan would result in higher taxes for the middle class and
lower taxes for the rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upon closer evaluation, people would find the flat tax
wanting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about athletes he admired, such as Dick Fosbury, who
reinvented the way to perform the high jump. He defined courage by
telling a story about another Celtics great, Larry Bird, who
retired just days before he was eligible for millions in an
automatic contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't play, I'm not taking the money,'' Bradley quoted
Bird as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the worldwide monetary crisis, Bradley criticized
the Clinton administration for failing to act more quickly on bold
solutions, such as Bradley's call for an international commission
similar to the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission to oversee
stock and monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would use any so-called budget surplus money to save
Social Security unless the Federal Reserve Board fails to cut
interest rates further. If the board does not act, Bradley would
use the surplus to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was asked about Dennis Rodman, the controversial Chicago
Bulls' forward known for his rebounding and flamboyant lifestyle.
Calling Rodman a hustler, Bradley said, ``I only want to see Dennis
on the court, and I don't want to see him off it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
