<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2588 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOUNTY-AWARD-KAN &LR;      10-06 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOUNTY-AWARD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ATTACKED BY BOUNTY HUNTERS WANTS TO USE CASE TO MAKE HIS
ADOPTED LAND BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Martin Tong probably will get little of the
more than $1 million a judge awarded him on Monday. But he has a
new goal: to use his experience to help improve his adopted land.
</P>
<P>
   His case provides ammunition for state and federal lawmakers and
others who want tougher regulations on bounty hunters and bonding
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Tong, 21, left Sudan for Kansas City three years ago to escape
civil war and to better himself in a new nation.
</P>
<P>
   Last year two bounty hunters looking for a traffic offender
mistakenly kicked in Tong's door, chased him to his basement and
shot him three times. Tong turned to the justice system.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Jackson County, Mo., Judge Lee E. Wells ordered the
bonding company and the bounty hunters to pay Tong more than $1
million. Tong, however, probably will get only a pittance. The
bonding company has gone out of business, and the two bounty
hunters have little money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law should make it so things like this don't happen to
other people,'' Tong said.
</P>
<P>
   Tong's attorney, Rick Gepford Jr., said he and his client sued
mainly on principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something had to be done,'' Gepford said. ``We make fun of the
caning in Singapore and the cutting off of hands in the Middle
East, but here we shoot people for traffic offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonding agents are licensed, but they hire unlicensed,
unregulated bounty hunters to arrest persons who do not show up in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation requiring bonding companies to train and license
bounty hunters failed this year and last in Missouri. Small bonding
companies said requiring them to deposit $25,000 to $100,000 with
the state would put them out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Reformers say the state needs the deposits, in part, to pay
victims such as Tong. They promise to try again next year in the
legislature, and they wave Tong's case like a flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might finally wake people up,'' said Jackson County
Prosecutor Claire McCaskill. Mistaken identity Tong testified in
the civil hearing before Wells last month and has testified twice
in the bounty hunters' criminal trials. Court records and a recent
interview tell his story:
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 2, 1997, Arrowhead Bonding sent bounty hunters Terry
Woods and Donnell Phillips to Tong's home in search of William
Hernandez, who had jumped bond on Claycomo, Mo., traffic
violations. Hernandez had moved out and was in an Omaha, Neb., jail
that night.
</P>
<P>
   An armed bounty hunter banged on Tong's door and asked for
Hernandez. Tong said Hernandez didn't live there, locked his door
and ran to call police. The two bounty hunters kicked in the door,
and Tong ran to hide under a basement stairway.
</P>
<P>
   Woods shot Tong in the foot. Tong pulled a steel bar off a
basement window and flailed at the men. Woods shot him in the wrist
and the ear. Phillips also tried to shoot Tong, but his pistol
jammed. Tong escaped out a basement window.
</P>
<P>
   Tong said the bounty hunters might have screamed ``bond
enforcement agents,'' but he said he did not know what that meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had read a book that told everything about American culture,
but I didn't read anything like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County jurors last year convicted Woods, of Grandview,
Mo., of second-degree assault and trespass and recommended six
years in prison. A judge sentenced him to six years but released
him on probation after 120 days.
</P>
<P>
   Another jury last year found Phillips, of Kansas City, guilty of
the same charges and recommended a year in prison. A judge placed
Phillips on probation.
</P>
<P>
   Arrowhead and Phillips did not contest the civil lawsuit, but
Woods acted as his own lawyer in a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he was not at fault. The bonding company should not
have sent him to catch a man already in jail, and Tong should not
have assumed that the bounty hunters were a threat, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With reckless and evil intent, Mr. Tong attacked both myself
and Mr. Phillips,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells on Monday ordered Arrowhead and Woods jointly to pay Tong
$350,000 and assessed an additional $605,000 in damages separately.
He ordered Phillips to pay $113,735. Phillips agreed to pay Tong
$75 a month. Woods has said he would appeal. He could not be
reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In another Jackson County bounty hunter case, Zebedee Collins of
Kansas City last month signed a confidential settlement agreement
with C&AMP;M Bonding. He sued after bounty hunters allegedly forced
their way into his house three years ago to look for another man.
</P>
<P>
   Incidents throughout the country illustrate problems with bounty
hunters. In Ohio, a bounty hunter last year was convicted of
abduction and burglary. He broke into a home, handcuffed a
17-year-old girl and forced her at gunpoint to help him find her
boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   These incidents have prompted calls for national and state
reforms. Reform efforts One federal bill would require background
checks on bounty hunters and provide model legislation for states
that want to license bounty hunters. Another would require bounty
hunters to follow the same civil rights laws as police do.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona this year made it illegal for bounty hunters to force
their way into houses.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Rep. Marsha Campbell, a Kansas City Democrat, said she
would again co-sponsor a bill next year to regulate bounty hunters
and bonding agents.
</P>
<P>
   More states also are requiring training for bounty hunters, a
move supported by bonding agents in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Burton, director of the National Institute of Bail
Enforcement Agents, in Tucson, Ariz., is meeting with Missouri
bonding agents this month. His group provides legal training to
bounty hunters in several states. Burton cited a key first lesson:
``You can't go into a house unless you know for sure the bad guy is
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The bonding system works, Burton said, because 14,000 people are
licensed to write bonds nationwide and about 1,800 bounty hunters
serve them _ ``the largest private arrest army in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   They get bail jumpers 87 percent of the time, he said. Kicking
in doors is rare, because only three of every 100 arrests are made
in houses, Burton said. Good bounty hunters use brains more than
guns, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who like to track human beings in what we
call the big chess game,'' Burton said. The job requires training
and good judgment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Tong, he moved to an apartment north of the Missouri
River. Even before the bounty hunters broke his door down, burglars
had stolen all he had. At his new apartment, someone has already
stolen his car, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had any luck in this country,'' Tong said.
</P>
<P>
   He tries to make his own luck. He attends school to earn a high
school diploma and works full time as a bell captain at a Kansas
City hotel. He wants to enter college soon and eventually become an
American citizen.
</P>
<P>
   His life in the United States can only get better, Tong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
