A2591 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOARD-STRAW-KAN &LR;      10-06 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOARD-STRAW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY AIMS TO BECOME LEADER IN CONVERTING WHEAT STRAW INTO
PARTICLE BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The idea sounds good.
</P>
<P>
   Take wheat straw and convert it into particle board that can be
used as a wood replacement for furniture and other products. The
environment is protected as trees get saved, and farmers gain
additional income by selling their unneeded wheat straw. In
addition, furniture makers get a product that's touted as being
stronger, more water-resistant and lighter than wood particle
board.
</P>
<P>
   That's the proposition behind Harvest Board International Inc.,
a Kansas City-based start-up company aiming to become a leader in
an emerging industry.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest Board, which was formed last year, took another step
forward Saturday when it broke ground on a $50 million
manufacturing plant in Rawlins County in northwest Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials hope the plant, west of Atwood, Kan., will be
turning wheat straw into composite board panels by the fourth
quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Harvest Board plants are on the drawing board for
northwest Kansas, bringing the total value of the investment to
$160 million. All three plants should be ready by the end of the
year 2000, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   David M. Hulshof, one of the company's founders and its chief
operating officer, said Harvest Board would be making its composite
panels at an optimum time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a declining supply of wood, especially in North
America,'' he said. ``At the same time, there's an increase in
demand for this product.''
</P>
<P>
   Particle board is used in ready-to-assemble furniture, store
fixtures, kitchen cabinets, countertops, millwork, manufactured
homes and consumer electronics equipment. One of Harvest Board's
first customers is Hallmark Cards Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Hulshof said a trade industry group estimated that consumption
last year of particle board was about 6 billion square feet. By
2005, that number is expected to exceed 8 billion square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Hulshof, who previously was with the Kansas City accounting firm
of Mayer, Hoffman, McCann LC, and others at the company have
researched the market for the particle board industry. They think
their agrifiber composite panel will fill a void created by
declining forest reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Before turning dirt on its first plant, Harvest Board created
alliances with investors, farmers and suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The company got early, jump-start financing from its own
resources and business associates. Since then, however, Harvest
Board has brought on Friedman, Billings, Ramsey &AMP; Co. Inc. as its
financial adviser. The Arlington, Va., investment banker was fourth
in dollar volume among issuers of initial public offerings last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Keeley, Friedman Billings' managing director, said
his company agreed to work with Harvest Board last year and helped
raise equity and debt capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an industry that made a lot of sense, using wheat
straw that otherwise would be burned,'' Keeley said. ``There's a
market for this type of product, and we were impressed with Harvest
Board's management team.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial assistance also came from Kirkpatrick Pettis, an
investment banking subsidiary of Mutual of Omaha. The firm helped
manage the sale of $100 million to $130 million in bonds for plant
construction.
</P>
<P>
   With Friedman Billings' assistance, Harvest Board has created
several partnerships with equipment suppliers, contractors and
others.
</P>
<P>
   One of Harvest Board's agreements is with Dow Chemical Co.,
which is providing the resin to process the fiber and convert it
into particle board. Harvest Board says the resin, a type of glue,
does not emit environmentally damaging toxins, unlike traditional
wood fiber products.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest Board also has supply agreements with farmers within a
60-mile radius of where its plant is being built. About 40,000
acres of wheat straw have been committed to supply the plant for
five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not taking the entire stalk or root that provides
nutritional value,'' Hulshof said. ``We're leaving some of the
straw for the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   How will Harvest Board cope with adverse weather conditions that
don't yield a bountiful wheat harvest?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to make sure to locate in an area that has three
times the amount of straw we need for production,'' said Kenneth A.
Roberson, Harvest Board's senior vice president. ``So in case of a
weather event, it won't be a complete setback.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulshof added that each plant would have 1 times the amount of
straw needed for production at any time.
</P>
<P>
   The first plant is expected to produce 76 million square feet of
particle board, generating $23 million in sales. The goal for the
three plants combined is 228 million square feet of product and $70
million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest Board also is in the process of finding customers for
its product and says it has commitments for more than 80 percent of
what the three plants will produce.
</P>
<P>
   One of Harvest Board's first customers will be Kansas City's
Hallmark Cards, which has agreed to buy composite panels for one of
its manufacturing plants in Texas. Hallmark uses the particle board
for fixtures at retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest Board's effect on rural Kansas could also be beneficial.
In addition to creating 60 jobs at each plant, Harvest Board's
presence means more jobs baling and delivering the straw, said
Arlene Bliss, economic development director for Rawlins County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope this will mean jobs for farmers and farmers' wives,''
she said. ``We also hope the jobs may draw some people to this
county.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss also noted that Harvest Board did not seek financial
incentives to locate in Rawlins County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of footwork to find out the interest among the
farmers here,'' she said. ``But we provided no formal incentives,
just our hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvest Board estimates that buying raw materials from farmers
could add 10 percent to their income.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Bujold is president and chief executive officer of
Harvest Board. Bujold was with Alexander Proudfoot, a management
consulting firm, before joining Harvest Board last year.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest Board's headquarters is a suite in the American Century
Towers, with six staffers. Hulshof said it was Bujold's idea to
create a company ``war room,'' where the company's progress and
goals are tracked to the smallest detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity that may come along once in a
lifetime,'' Hulshof said. ``It's a passion that drives this
company. A lot of blood, sweat and tears have been put into this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
