<HEADER>
A2594 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDICIARY-IMPEACH-KAN     10-06 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDICIARY-IMPEACH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT PROCESS OFF TO A PARTISAN START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee on Monday took the
first step toward the third presidential impeachment inquiry in
American history, voting along party lines to recommend that the
full House of Representatives approve a formal investigation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 21-16 more than 10 hours after the hearing began,
the committee adopted an impeachment resolution that allowed a more
open-ended inquiry of President Clinton. It came after several
failed attempts by the Democrats to narrow the focus on both the
timetable and the subject matter to just his affair with Monica
Lewinsky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The full House is expected to vote on the resolution by Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans now will be allowed to consider other issues
that have dogged the president, including Whitewater, the travel
office firings, the White House's gathering of FBI files on
Republicans, campaign finance and missile sales to China. Except
for the missile sales, Congress already has examined all of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to decide whether or not to impeach Mr.
Clinton,'' Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican,
said as he opened the hearing. ``We are here to ask and answer this
one simple question: Based on what we know now, do we have a duty
to look further, or to look away?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his presentation to the committee, David Schippers, the
Republican majority's chief counsel, alleged 15 offenses by
Clinton. A lifelong Democrat, Schippers spoke for an hour in
outlining charges that ranged from obstruction of justice to
witness-tampering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My staff and I have made a deliberate effort to discount the
political aspects of our examination and to ignore any partisan
tactics and strategy,'' he told the committee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Schippers dropped the abuse of power allegation in the 11-count
report to Congress by independent counsel Kenneth Starr. He added
others, including several that had to do with making false
statements and another alleging that Clinton had concealed a felony
concerning his knowledge of Lewinsky's false affidavit in the Paula
Jones sexual-harassment case. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abbe Lowell, the Democratic counsel, emphasized a point repeated
by several committee Democrats: that by beginning the inquiry
without first setting the bar for impeachable offenses was like ``a
ship's captain leaving on a difficult, uncharted voyage hoping to
find his or her compass somewhere along the way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the daylong debate, Republicans and Democrats on the
committee took note of the historical significance of the hearing,
even while they differed starkly on the need to conduct an
impeachment inquiry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They drew upon the Bible, the Constitution and the Federalist
Papers as guideposts for their deliberations. Overshadowing it all
was Watergate, the scandal that triggered the last impeachment
inquiry and led to the resignation of President Nixon in 1974. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Watergate,'' said Rep. John Conyers of Michigan,
the senior Democrat, sounding a running argument of his party. ``It
is an extramarital affair.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, meanwhile, echoed what has been the crux of the
division over the Lewinsky investigation _ that it was not about
sex, but about breaking the law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This debate is not about the fact that President Clinton had
an affair with Monica Lewinsky and then lied about it,'' said Rep.
James Sensenbrenner, a Wisconsin Republican. ``It is about Judge
Starr's finding that the president violated his oath to the tell
the truth.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they had taken pains to follow the path laid in
1974 by Peter Rodino, Hyde's predecessor as Judiciary chairman and
a Democrat who steered the Nixon impeachment investigation. His
portrait loomed over the hearing room. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even so, at least one Republican, though he voted for the formal
inquiry into Clinton's possible impeachment, said he was still
uncertain whether the president's alleged actions amounted to the
``high crimes and misdemeanors'' that the founders had envisioned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this Watergate or Peyton Place?'' said Rep. Lindsey Graham,
a South Carolina Republican with a history of bucking his party
leadership. ``I don't know. If I followed the polls, I know what I
would do. Eighty-two percent of the people in one part of my
district want him thrown out of office. I want to be a good
congressman who 30 years from now, not just 30 days from now,
people thought did the right thing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, various Democrats spoke of their
disappointment in the president but said they considered
impeachment too severe a punishment . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not proud of the personal conduct of the president that
has cheapened our national discourse'' said Rep. Robert Wexler, a
Florida Democrat. But he added: ``Impeachment is not about
adultery. The president had an affair. He lied about it. Does
anyone reasonably believe that this amounts to subversion of
government? Does anyone reasonably believe that this is what the
Founding Fathers were talking about?''
</P>
<P>
   The committee sought an even-handed tone, and the debate had
little of the razor-sharp partisan rhetoric of recent weeks. But
for all the historical drama, the proceedings were largely
anti-climactic because, with a five-vote Republican majority, the
outcome was never in doubt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the White House could claim some measure of victory, despite
Clinton's lasting blemish of becoming just the third president to
face a possible impeachment vote. Besides Nixon, who would have
faced an impeachment vote had he not resigned, Andrew Johnson
survived a vote of impeachment in the Senate in 1868 by one vote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's case, his supporters know they may lose the votes
of some Democratic members, particularly those in close re-election
races, when the resolution is brought up for a vote Friday in the
full House. But they successfully avoided any Democratic defections
in the committee.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, press secretary Joe Lockhart repeated
Monday: ``We don't believe there is anything here that rises to the
level of an impeachable offense.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The president's supporters have tried to paint Starr as an
overzealous prosecutor who set out to get Clinton and to portray
his report to the committee, and the committee's work itself, as
partisan efforts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The same line of attack was evident in the presentation by
Lowell, who spoke of Starr's ``prosecutorial excess'' by detaining
Lewinsky for 10 hours, ``despite her asking for a lawyer,'' and his
summoning of her mother, ``who was brought to tears by their
conduct.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said Schippers, by eliminating, revising and increasing the
offenses alleged of Clinton in Starr's report, engaged in a
``prosecutor's strategy which courts routinely disapprove by which
they divide what they believe to be a single offense into many
different charges. They do this to make the case look more serious
or foreboding.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Schippers offered a catalog of alleged offenses that said
Clinton and Lewinsky might have been part of conspiracy to obstruct
justice in the Paula Jones case by giving false testimony and
withholding evidence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the end, he offered what he called a brief personal
statement, one as ``a citizen of the United States who happens to
be a father and a grandfather'' in which he paraphrased lines from
a play about St. Thomas More: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The laws of this country are the great barriers that protect
the citizens from the winds of evil and tyranny. If we permit one
of those laws to fall, who will be able to stand in the winds that
follow? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen generations of Americans, our fellow Americans, many
of whom are reposing in military cemeteries throughout the world,
are looking down on you and judging what you do today.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Democrats protested the allowing of such personal comments, and
they were stricken from the record until Rep. Bob Barr, a Georgia
Republican, volunteered to have the statement appear under his
name. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hyde has said he hopes to finish the impeachment inquiry by Jan.
1. But the no-limits nature of the impeachment inquiry resolution
worried Democrats, who saw it as a ``fishing expedition'' that
could continue interminably. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, citing Rodino's concerns about time limits during
Watergate, said they were an ``invitation to delay'' and caused
``more stress and strain trying to get the job done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ask you,'' the chairman said, ``to accept on faith that
we want to move this along.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
