<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-SMOLTZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTSEASON, SMOLTZ MADE FOR EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It had always been John Smoltz's plan to pitch for the
Atlanta Braves until he was 38 or 39 years old, then take it one
year at a time regarding career decisions. Retirement? The
righthander figured that was nothing but a speck on the horizon of
his glittering career.
</P>
<P>
   But Smoltz's career reached a crossroads May 24 when a strained
ulnar collateral ligament in his right elbow landed him on the
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   It was Smoltz's second such stint this season. He spent almost
the entire spring recovering from an offseason arthroscopic
procedure performed last Dec. 13 by Joe Chandler, the team's
orthopedic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Two years removed from his Cy Young season of 1996, when he
posted a career-best record (24-8) and guided the Braves to a World
Series berth against the Yankees, Smoltz reported to Macon and was
shocked to discover that winning in the minor leagues was every bit
as challenging as in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   He began having doubts about himself. He wondered if he'd ever
make another start for the Braves. Soon thereafter, Smoltz's
self-doubt gave rise to thoughts of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   At age 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your livelihood is pitching and your arm hurts, then it is
going to create doubt,'' said Cubs manager Jim Riggleman, whose
team suffered a 7-1 loss to the rejuvenated Smoltz in Game 1 of
their National League Division Series. ``I'm sure that's where that
came from, but he overcame it and he got fixed up and he's 100
percent healthy now, I guess, because he's been outstanding the
latter part of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Smoltz doubts himself no more.
</P>
<P>
   After emerging from his rehabilitation stint with great
trepidation, Smoltz settled down, adapted to a new pitching
strategy, and reestablished himself in the second half of the
season. Forsaking a split-fingered fastball in favor of more
breaking pitches, he posted a 17-3 record _ going 13-2 with a 2.51
ERA in 18 starts after coming off the DL June 20 _ to reclaim his
stature as one of the pillars of Atlanta's vaunted rotation.
</P>
<P>
   But the postseason? Ah, that's always been Smoltz's personal
playpen.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Smoltz became the winningest pitcher in
postseason history by registering his 11th triumph. He threw seven
innings of shutout ball before surrendering an eighth-inning
leadoff homer to Chicago's Tyler Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only blemish in Smoltz's latest postseason gem: 7 2/3
innings, five hits, six strikeouts, no walks. With that, he broke a
tie with Whitey Ford and Dave Stewart for the postseason victory
record, and he can further distance himself Wednesday night against
the San Diego Padres here in the opener of the best-of-seven NL
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was so special,'' Smoltz said. ``Dr. Chandler and
the trainers, really everybody here knows the history of the way
things have gone for me and the frustrating times. I have a lot of
pride, and there's been a lot of things said where I've been
humbled a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you have humility, you understand how to handle
adversity. This has been a year where I haven't had a chance to
enjoy too much the games I've pitched, but it's just allowed me to
handle the situations when they've come about. I've learned as a
pitcher that I don't care if I get the credit, but I think I've
shown the last couple of years that my pitching ability has
outshined my stuff, because I've had to adapt to a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Including a humbling experience in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a tough time winning in the minor leagues,'' Smoltz
said, chuckling at the recollection. ``The low point was leaving
Macon and not really being sure if I was ready. We had set a
timetable, and in my mind, I wasn't having to learn how to pitch
again but I was going to have to learn to pitch different.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Bobby Cox, ``When John came off his rehab (April
15), he didn't pitch in spring training and didn't throw until the
very end. But he had better stuff than I'd seen all spring, from
our club and anybody else's. I don't know if it was as dramatic as
John makes it out to be down in Macon; I didn't see him pitch down
there. He's really throwing the ball well and he has changed his
pitching style to some degree, but basically, he's pretty close to
what he used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz was a quick study. In his first appearance after coming
off the DL June 20, he posted a 5-1 victory at Montreal, going
seven innings and allowing one unearned run on four hits while
recording eight strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went up to Montreal, it worked faster than I
anticipated,'' Smoltz said. ``I didn't throw the ball very hard or
the effort wasn't the same, but I relied on breaking pitches and
spotting the ball. The better I felt, the harder I threw, and the
cycle repeated itself. I would say in Macon there was a lot of
self-doubt. I just decided to go up there and get it done. The
luxury for me was the great pitching staff we have and Bobby having
the patience to let me go out there and basically pitch and get
myself ready for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz says his arm feels fine. Now that the Braves are in the
playoffs after winning their seventh consecutive division title,
he's intent on following a simple strategy when dealing with his
arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken the approach for about the last month and a half
that I'm just going to ignore it and I'm just going to do what I
have to do,'' he said. ``That's what I've done. When you try to set
a plan and you try to set what the next three or four (years) will
be, it doesn't go according to plan, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   It amazes him that after contemplating retirement at Macon, he
could rebound in time to become a major league force so soon.
</P>
<P>
   If there were any lingering questions about his arm, Smoltz
certainly answered them with his win over the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I can't help but say that God's had a play in it,'' he
said. ``I mean, if it was up to me, there were many times in my
mind where I didn't think I was going to make the next start, that
I didn't think I was going to pitch in the postseason three months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it's been amazing, and that's all I can really say.
I've been through (the postseason) before, but it doesn't really
matter how many times you go through it because it doesn't get any
easier. Like I said, I've always wanted to pitch until I was 38 or
39, but there was a point where I was worrying about finishing this
year. I'm just going to keep doing what I've done all season, and
hopefully, we can celebrate a championship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
