<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-IMPEACH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 07-COX &HT;    SOME TEXAS DEMOCRATS TO SUPPORT GOP IMPEACHMENT RESOLUTION
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some Texas Democrats in the House will cross party
lines this week to support a Republican measure authorizing an
impeachment inquiry into President Clinton's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   With a vote expected Thursday, some have decided to vote in
favor of the inquiry, others against, and some remain undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ralph Hall, D-Rockwall, and Rep. Jim Turner, D-Lufkin, said
Tuesday they would support the Republican resolution approved
Monday by the House Judiciary Committee on a 21-16 party-line vote.
The resolution provides for an open-ended investigation by the
committee into whether there are grounds for impeaching Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the vote is ``a once-in-a-lifetime call'' that should
be dictated by conscience and not by party affiliation. ``It's not
pleasant,'' he said, to vote against his own party on the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Hall predicted that 30 to 40 Democrats would vote for the
resolution. ``I'd like to see 50 vote for it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said the allegations made against the president are
serious matters that Congress has a Constitutional duty to examine.
``No one is above the law, including the president,'' he said in a
statement released Tuesday. ``It is in the best interests of the
nation that we move forward with fairness and diligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Texans, such as Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Waco, and Rep. Max
Sandlin, D- Marshall, said Tuesday they were undecided about their
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Both expressed concern that the GOP resolution doesn't include a
deadline for completing the inquiry and doesn't limit the scope of
the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said that he is ``hesitant to write a blank check'' to
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., to invest millions of taxpayer
dollars investigating allegations over the next two or three years.
He said he wants to weigh possible Democratic alternatives before
making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Sandlin said he and his constituents would prefer an impeachment
inquiry that is limited in time and scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people are saying if we're going to have
an investigation, it shouldn't be a long-term, expensive rehash of
what's been done,'' Sandlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-San Antonio, who is retiring at the
end of this, his 38th year in Congress, was more certain of his
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said impeachment is too serious an action ``to be
invoked on anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never intended to be addressed ... to personal,
behavioral matters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, who control the House floor, have decided to
allow only one hour of debate on the GOP resolution, and House
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving, said Tuesday that there would
not be a vote on a Democratic resolution.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Armey said that the White House is putting pressure
on Democrats, and that First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton has been
threatening Democrats to ``stand by your man or else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that the First Lady has made recommendations to
them regarding what they might lose by way of campaign assistance
and so forth,'' Armey said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Edwards said he questioned whether Armey was a
source of reliable information about Mrs. Clinton, because in the
past Armey has treated her in a ``very undignified way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said that the White House is polling everyone about the
upcoming impeachment vote, but that he had not received a call from
Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hasn't called me. I've heard of no threats,'' he said. ``I
guess they quit pressuring me a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Christi Harlan, Washington correspondent of the Austin
American-Statesman, contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
