<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-UPN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEVEN DAYS' IS WELL-CONCEIVED SCIENCE FICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Parker, former CIA operative, is in the looney bin. Not
that he's crazy, just a little unmanageable.
</P>
<P>
   But this is no time to be relaxing in the Padded Room of the
Haha Hotel. The president, vice president and speaker of the house
have been assassinated, and America needs somebody to go back in
time to undo this calamity.
</P>
<P>
   Frank is our man in the ``Seven Days. He can go back no more
than seven days because a way-back trip would require a larger
reactor and a bigger supply of some rare fuel that was discovered
at the site of the UFO crash in Roswell, N.M., in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Once he arrives in the past, Parker knows more than his bosses,
putting him on par with the rest of us. It is his job to convince
them that a calamity is about to happen, and to help them head it
off at the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Though excessively violent and emotionally disturbing,
especially at 8 o'clock, ``Seven Days'' is well-conceived,
well-executed sci-fi that may attract a mainstream audience because
of sci that's not too dense and fi that's not too tense. (It's also
a good companion to ``Star Trek: Voyager,'' which is pre-empted
tonight to accommodate the two-hour premiere.)
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan La Paglia is perfectly laconic as the smirky, quirky
Frank Parker, and the chemistry between Parker and scientist Olga
Vukavitch (Justina Vail) is a gas. Fortunate casting also netted
Don Franklin, Norman Lloyd and Nick Searcy, all of whom make
``Seven Days'' a good week's work _ and a great escape.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritionally speaking, Aaron Spelling's ``Charmed'' satisfies
the average teen male's recommended daily allowance of spaghetti
straps, saucy tees and cheesecake midriffs.
</P>
<P>
   The show is so Fox-y (think ``90210,'' think ``Melrose Place'')
that The WB must have found the key to the henhouse, which explains
the presence of Shannen Doherty and Alyssa Milano, alumnae of
Spelling's soapers on Fox. The addition of Holly Marie Combs
(``Picket Fences'') is harder to figure, although she and Doherty
are best buddies in real life.
</P>
<P>
   They play the supernaturally gifted Halliwell sisters _ Prue,
Phoebe and Piper _ in a tasty but not-too-filling hour of mind over
matters of life and death. They also may bring to The WB a slightly
older audience that the network tried to tap a few seasons back
with Spelling's steamy serial, ``Savannah.''
</P>
<P>
   The WB's youthful viewers didn't bite then, but the timing may
be more appropriate now. As Fox has demonstrated, younger viewers
tend to set the pace (think ``Buffy,'' think ``Dawson's Creek''),
and older viewers follow a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   If a more mature audience is to be charmed by the concept of
good witches, though, it will require a more concerted effort than
tonight's premiere. Of the three sisters, Doherty's Prue is the
most convincing. She is the oldest, the most practical and the most
reluctant to use her new-found power. (Prue can move things with
her mind, Phoebe can see the future, Piper can stop time.) As
free-spirited Phoebe, Milano, who replaced Lori Rom in the cast
after the original pilot had been shot, needs seasoning, and maybe
some warm clothes. Combs' Piper, the ``earthy and creative'' one,
simply seems uneasy as a witchy woman.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, practice is the best way to eliminate Spelling
errors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seven Days. Hourlong drama about a time traveler assigned to
undo catastrophic occurrences. Starring Jonathan LaPaglia, Justina
Vail and Don Franklin. Two-hour premiere Wednesday night UPN. Check
local listings.
</P>
<P>
   Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Charmed. Hourlong drama about three sisters with supernatural
powers. Starring Shannen Doherty, Alyssa Milano and Holly Marie
Combs. Premieres Wednesday night. The WB. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   John Levesque is the P-I's TV critic. Call him at 206-448-8330
or send e-mail to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
