<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2604 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPREME-SEARCHES-HNS &LR;      10-06 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREME-SEARCHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT CONSIDERS WHETHER HOUSE GUESTS HAVE CONSTITUTIONAL
PROTECTION DURING SEARCHES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday cited examples from
poker buddies to the Avon lady as it considered which house guests,
if any, deserve constitutional protection from unreasonable
searches.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, hearing an appeal from Minnesota, questioned
attorneys for the state and for two drug dealers on whether a
police officer trampled on the Constitution's Fourth Amendment by
spying without a warrant on the men as they helped a woman bag and
tie cocaine in her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Supreme Court threw out the convictions of Wayne
Thomas Carter and Melvin Johns, ruling that Eagan, Minn., Officer
Jim Thielen violated their reasonable expectation of privacy as
house guests when he peered through a gap in the closed Venetian
blinds.
</P>
<P>
   Dakota County Attorney James Backstrom, urging the justices to
reinstate the convictions, said the two men enjoyed no Fourth
Amendment protection because they were merely ``brief, transient
visitors'' to Kimberly Thompson's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State Public Defender Bradford Colbert of St. Paul,
representing Carter and Johns, countered that a person's home is a
sanctuary and that even guests are entitled to the constitutional
safeguard against unreasonable searches.
</P>
<P>
   However, justices were skeptical of both arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter mocked the distinction Backstrom drew
between brief visitors, who have no Fourth Amendment protection,
and those who stay longer. Souter used the example of people who
meet for regular poker games, those who get together once a week at
someone's house and those who play more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they play five times a week they have (protection),''
Souter said, summarizing Backstrom's argument. ``If they play once
a week, they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   But Backstrom responded that people who play cards at someone's
house would enjoy Fourth Amendment protection due to their
personal, rather than business, relationship with the home owner.
Carter and Johns, by contrast, were not social guests so much as
``business'' associates, whom the Constitution does not protect
from police searches in a home, Backstrom argued.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer, in apparent support of Backstrom's
argument, noted that home owners often use the Spanish phrase ``mi
casa es su casa'' _ my house is your house _ to make their social
guests feel at home. But seldom do owners express that sentiment to
people who are in their house solely to conduct business, the
justice added.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Breyer, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said, ``Maybe the
(Fourth Amendment) line should be business vs. social.''
</P>
<P>
   With regard to Colbert's call for broad protection for all house
guests, O'Connor said she doubted whether the Fourth Amendment
applies to people delivering pizza or selling cosmetics in someone
else's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no expectation of privacy when the Avon lady comes
in,'' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   But Colbert responded, ``Any intrusion into the home should be
accompanied by a warrant'' unless an emergency exists inside the
house requiring quick police action.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Solicitor General Jeffrey Lamken, pressing the Clinton
administration's support for Minnesota, told the justices that the
police officer's observation of the cocaine packaging through the
blinds did not constitute an unreasonable search, as the state
Supreme Court had ruled. Lamken said the officer did not ``search''
the apartment but merely observed what was occurring as he stood in
a public area.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia apparently agreed, saying Carter and
Johns might have forfeited their expectation of privacy when they
left gaps in the blinds. ``I don't think that's a reasonable
expectation of privacy'' if you fail to close the blinds, Scalia
said.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision in the case
by this summer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
