<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PROTEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KREMLIN MAKING SURE ECONOMIC PROTESTERS HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The water cannons and the riot troops will probably be
kept out of sight. And the listening devices most certainly will
be.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of protesters are expected to take to the streets
Wednesday to call for President Boris N. Yeltsin's resignation in a
nationwide protest against late wages and low living standards that
union leaders say will be the largest since the fall of Soviet
Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kremlin does not plan to fight the demonstrators. It
plans to eavesdrop on them.
</P>
<P>
   In what may be the largest bugging operation in history,
thousands of government agents and an array of cameras and special
listening devices will be positioned to pick up anything protesters
might say that could violate Russia's laws on sedition or racism.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's justice minister, Pavel Krasheninnikov, said officials
would be listening in at rallies planned all over the country to
make sure none of the speakers call for the violent overthrow of
Yeltsin or his government.
</P>
<P>
   Just a month ago, Oct. 7 looked as though it would bring
apocalypse to Russia's streets. The ruble was in free-fall, prices
were in the process of tripling, banks were closed, the country's
leaders were quarrelling, Yeltsin was absent, and social unrest
seemed certain.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov on Sept. 12
has not solved all of those problems. But Primakov's arrival in
government with the blessing of Russia's main opposition party, the
Communists, and his choice of several Communist-backed officials as
senior economic advisers, has softened the opposition's traditional
antigovernment slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Primakov appealed for calm in an address broadcast on
Russia's major television networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that many people who are going to demonstrate
tomorrow have reasons to be disatisfied,'' Primakov said. ``But I
want to call on all of you not to rock the boat we are all in when
the sea is already stormy.''
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to repay pension and wages debts ``down to the last
kopeck'' soon and free up the mass of debts that has paralyzed
factories, banks and businesses. But he added it would take a few
months before the government would be able to repay old debts.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders are predicting that 28 million Russians will stop
work Wednesday to demand $5 billion in back wages. Communist leader
Gennady Zyuganov, who estimates 40 million Russians will turn out.
Other protest leaders have called for Yeltsin, whose term ends in
two years, to step down now. But Zyuganov has emphasized that
Yeltsin should resign voluntarily or face legal impeachment, not a
bloody revolt.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has been virtually absent for most of the crisis, and in
the past days has been portrayed by his press service as being
actively involved in mediation of the crisis in Kosovo. The Russian
leader is clearly unpopular, but analysts believe few Russians are
ready to fight for his ouster, and say opposition leaders are not
likely to push too hard for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition is linked with the regime and is no less afraid
of an uprising than'' the regime is, commented Alexander Tsipko, a
political analyst at the daily Nezavsisimaya Gazeta.
</P>
<P>
   Krasheninnikov told reporters the government had asked Russia's
chief prosecutor to open a criminal investigation against two
speakers at a rally on Sunday who had called for Yeltsin's
overthrow by force.
</P>
<P>
   One of the speakers, General Albert Makashov, a Communist member
of parliament, also made derogatory remarks against Jews that the
Justice Ministry said constituted fomenting national tensions, a
criminal offense in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Krasheninnikov said he had held talks with main opposition
leaders, who had promised to maintain order over protesters and
refrain from making inflammatory remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, some 11,000 police and 4,000 Interior Ministry
troops will be on hand in Moscow alone, but officials say most of
the officers will be unarmed. The feared OMON riot police will be
held in reserve, a police spokesman said. Meanwhile, the fire
department Tuesday announced its trucks mounted with water cannons,
used against demonstrators in mass protests in 1993, will stay out
off the streets this time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
