<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2606 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-LADN     10-06 1604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THERE'S A WILL...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; The man who runs the Los Angeles Philharmonic is
scowling. Scratching his chin. Giving an Oscar-worthy portrayal of
utter confusion.
</P>
<P>
   In his hands, Willem Wijnbergen clutches an oversize,
color-coded chart that looks like the Periodic Table of Elements,
only with the words ``Haydn,'' ``Beethoven'' and ``Bartok''
substituting for ``Hydrogen,'' ``Zinc'' and ``Potassium.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a copy of the orchestra's 1998-99 season schedule, and
Wijnbergen makes no secret what he thinks of the brochure's
complicated design and the confusing message it sends to
``consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My first question was, when I saw this, I said, `Gee, I have
to go back to business school to learn how to figure this out',''
Wijnbergen says in his impeccable Dutch-accented English. ``This is
the orchestra world gone berserk. And this is how all (orchestras)
do it!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not all. Wijnbergen intends for at least one
orchestra _ his _ to pay as much attention to its medium as its
message.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as the former Procter &AMP; Gamble executive might put it,
selling classical music these days is as much a matter of
``packaging'' as ``product.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been almost exactly one year since Willem Wijnbergen
(VIL-em VINE-ber-gun), a 40-year-old Amsterdam native, was named to
the L.A. Phil's top administrative post, succeeding the legendary
Ernest Fleischmann.
</P>
<P>
   For 28 years, the colorful, controversial Fleischmann ran the
orchestra with a tough, top-down management style. Yet few
questioned his energy or exacting artistic vision.
</P>
<P>
   During his regime, the Philharmonic launched its ``Green
Umbrella'' new-music series, created the Hollywood Bowl Orchestra,
hosted world premieres and recitals by the cream of international
performers, and rose to the stature of one of the nation's top
half-dozen symphonic entities.
</P>
<P>
   So where does the L.A. Phil go from here? And what kind of boss
does this 6-foot-5-inch Dutchman with the Cheshire-cat grin,
artfully unkempt hair and business degree from Southern Methodist
University intend to be?
</P>
<P>
   Chatting last week in his minimally furnished office at the
Dorothy Chandler Pavilion, Wijnbergen acknowledged that his staff
is still adjusting to him. Though he's been on the job since March,
the new season that opens Thursday night will mark his first full
year at the orchestra's helm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that the staff has its difficulties with me because
I'm a very impatient, pushy guy,'' he says matter-of-factly. ``And
so they have to get used to that. Ernest was tough too, but
different. So I don't know which is better. You should ask them;
you would better get the answers there. But I have a different
style of managing, which seems to be rather informal, but then
again when I want results, I want results. And I think that's the
only way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Forthright and opinionated, with a dryly playful sense of humor,
Wijnbergen has a reputation as a take-charge problem-solver. In his
previous job, as managing director of Amsterdam's distinguished
Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra, he brought fiscal stability to an
institution that had run up a $3 million deficit after losing half
its government subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on his graduate studies in business and arts
administration at SMU in Dallas (he's also a concert-level pianist
and former assistant conductor with the Rotterdam Philharmonic
Orchestra), Wijnbergen set up new fund-raising and marketing
programs at the Concertgebouw. While weaning the orchestra off the
public trough, he was able to build up its endowment, increase
subscriptions and expand its bookings.
</P>
<P>
   That track record, plus Wijnbergen's creative stamina, impressed
the L.A. Phil's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``His style is very hands-on, as was his predecessor's, and very
imaginative,'' says board president Barry Sanders. ``Of course,
he's a relatively young man for this kind of role, and I'd say the
most important thing is his fresh approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Fleischmann, a native German who has lived in South Africa
and England, Wijnbergen also is an outsider with a large, expansive
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think L.A. is a place that likes stars. Ernest was one, and
I think that Willem may be one too,'' observes Peter Pastreich,
executive director of the San Francisco Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Wijnbergen says that ``I had no gameplan, quite frankly'' at the
time when the L.A. Phil approached him. Up to that point, his
career had been a series of intense, five- to seven-year intervals:
from the Music Conservatory of the City of Groningen, where he
earned degrees in piano performance and conducting; to the
Rotterdam Philharmonic; to SMU, where he was recruited by Procter &AMP;
Gamble to serve as a brand manager in its Rotterdam office; to the
Concertgebouw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just made a commitment to my wife where I said, `Let's
not change anything for a couple of years, let's just go on,' '' he
recalls. ``And I said that at a point where the real work of the
Concertgebouw Orchestra really had been done and I was ready for
some new challenges. Because I started in this business pretty
young, and I still felt that I was too young to sit there and be
the boss, which I don't care about.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience Wijnbergen has inherited is less ethnically and
economically homogenous than the one that greeted Fleischmann in
the late 1960s, though not necessarily as sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was basically only the old supporters, the establishment
audience from Hancock Park and Pasadena when I arrived, and now
it's an audience from everywhere,'' Fleischmann says. Though its
tastes in new and contemporary music are broader, new audiences
often are not as familiar with the standard classical repertoire,
he adds.
</P>
<P>
   This year's subscription renewal rate at the Dorothy Chandler is
running at about 88 percent, up from 86.4 percent last year. But
subscriptions now account for only about 60 percent of the Dorothy
Chandler's seats, down from 80 percent 10 years ago, said marketing
director Michael Buckland, who notes that other U.S. orchestras
have experienced similar dropoffs. The subscription renewal rate
for the Hollywood Bowl is about 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While he doesn't have ``any ready-made recipes,'' Wijnbergen and
his board have begun setting priorities and mapping out long-term
goals. These include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Raising the orchestra's endowment to somewhere between $150
million and $200 million. Currently, it stands at about $40
million.
</P>
<P>
   _Bringing more jazz and world music to the Hollywood Bowl. One
of Wijnbergen's first official acts was to take over management of
the Bowl from former general manager Anne Parsons, who subsequently
left the organization. Wijnbergen says his discussions with Bowl
Orchestra conductor John Mauceri about the orchestra's future are
``in the concluding phase'' and going well.
</P>
<P>
   _Moving the Philharmonic's administrative offices out of the
Dorothy Chandler in order to consolidate operations, which
currently are spread out over seven separate locations. Board
president Sanders says three sites _ two downtown and one in
Hollywood _ are being considered, and that a deal could come by
November.
</P>
<P>
   _Expanding Fleischmann's idea of having the orchestra perform
community concerts throughout the metro area, including San Pedro,
South Central, Koreatown, the heavily Latino Southgate area, the
San Fernando Valley and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   _Promoting more cultural alliances with the Phil's downtown
neighbors, including the new Staples arena, currently under
construction.
</P>
<P>
   _Continuing to develop the ``Filmharmonic'' project, which pairs
Hollywood composers and filmmakers to create original, short music
pieces accompanied by films. The second ``Filmharmonic''
installment, a collaboration between director Renny Harlin and
composer Graeme Revell scheduled to premiere this week, has been
postponed while Harlin completes a feature film. In its place will
be a screening of the 1928, 70-minute silent film classic ``The
Wind,'' in sync with the orchestra's live performance of music by
Sibelius. ``Hollywood is not a four-letter word,'' says Winjbergen.
``Hollywood for me is part of a cultural phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   _Test-marketing ``mini-series'' of three and four concerts with
catchy themes such as ``The Magic of the Violin'' and ``This
Surprising Century.'' Wijnbergen believes this will help different
audience segments hone in on the music they like best.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps Wijnbergen's most important assignment will be
finding new ways to capitalize on his dynamic and popular music
director. Salonen credits his new colleague with making ``a bold
move'' in coming to America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the transition might be easier for him than it was
for me, but I knew from my own experience that it took me a couple
years to learn the ins and outs of the system,'' Salonen says.
</P>
<P>
   In the brief time he's been here, Winjbergen has fallen in love
with L.A.'s diversity, climate, easygoing yet restless ambience and
most everything except Westside housing prices. He and his wife,
along with their four children, have opted for a sprawling 1927
home in Hancock Park.
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like, Wijnbergen says, grinning again. His kids
love the beaches and the hiking trails. His wife is coming to grips
with the new language. ``She never spoke much English, so for her
it's a challenge. And the kids don't speak English at all. But I
put them in an American school anyway. So they have to learn before
Christmas, I told them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
