<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-WAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPT REMEMBERS `OCT. 6 WAR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ Marking the 25th anniversary Tuesday of what Egypt calls
the Oct. 6 War, this country clings to the memory of conflict at a
time when the hope for Mideast peace is slipping.
</P>
<P>
   The government-controlled television's all-day coverage was a
barrage of black-and-white images of the 1973 Arab-Israeli
conflict. At a Cairo stadium, 20,000 veterans were decorated by
President Hosni Mubarak, a veteran air force commander. The
military staged a massive parade, the first of its kind in 17 years
since President Anwar Sadat was assassinated at such a display.
</P>
<P>
   At exactly 2:05 p.m., Egyptian radio broadcast the crackly
communique that a quarter century ago announced Egyptian troops had
stormed the Suez Canal. At night, fireworks burst over Cairo's
slums and its rich enclaves.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing captured Egypt's intense desire to remember this
war, or the way the war is seared into the nation's collective
consciousness, more than a chaotic scene Tuesday at the Oct. 6
Panorama.
</P>
<P>
   With the usual $1 fee at the war monument lifted for the
national holiday, a crowd swelled to more than 10,000. When
military police tried to hold the crowd back, people scaled the
10-foot high walls. Some forced open the building's huge bronze
doors. Police briefly wielded riot batons to bring the crowd under
control.
</P>
<P>
   Just before he climbed the wall with his two sons, Magdi Shukri,
47, a veteran infantryman, said, ``I want them to see the glorious
victory we had on Oct. 6. We took back our land that was taken from
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Shukri sees a lesson in this war: ``We had to show strength to
achieve peace. I think the same is true today. We have to show
(Israeli Prime Minister) Benjamin Netanyahu that there is a price
to pay for taking Arab land. He has not lived up to the agreements.
Only force will push him to.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 6, 1973, Egypt and Syria staged a surprise attack on
Israel. Egypt advanced deep into the Sinai. But by the time the
UN-arranged cease-fire took effect Oct. 22, an Israeli
counterattack had retaken most of the ground and actually pushed
deep into Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian history teaches that the war was a victory since Egypt,
after the 1978 Camp David peace accord, reclaimed land in the Sinai
captured by Israel in 1967. Israeli history, on the other hand,
teaches that the Yom Kippur War _ as Israelis call it because it
fell on the Jewish Day of Atonement _ caught its forces off guard
but that it ultimately staved off defeat. Since 1978, both sides
have maintained a ``cold peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Still for Egypt, the initial rout of Israeli troops provides a
lasting psychological victory. That was evident at the packed
panorama Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, children merrily climbed all over Egypt's Soviet-made
Mig jet fighters and M-1 tanks. Inside, the revolving, circular
theater presented the action of the 1973 war in living color to a
wide variety of families.
</P>
<P>
   Fathers held sons on shoulders to watch model war planes glide
on wires across a dark sky, and little red lights flare to simulate
Egyptian air attacks on model Israeli planes.
</P>
<P>
   A painted battle scene depicted heroic-looking Egyptian troops
charging across a water-filled model of the Suez Canal and planting
the Egyptian flag on a hillside. The Israeli soldiers cowered in
bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   Elements of the theater seem to cast the war in religious terms.
Although Israelis at times also portray the 1967 Six Day War as a
divine miracle in the narrative of Jewish history, the Egyptian
government's memorial seemed perhaps more overt in its religious
references. As a deep-voiced narator describes advacing Egyptian
troops, dramatic music reaches a crescendo and a choros shouts
``Allah Akbar,'' ``God is great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something in the air on this anniversary,'' says
Walid Kaziha, political science professor at the American
University of Cairo. ``There is a growing feeling in Egypt that the
peace process has faltered, so the memories of the past are coming
flooding back: the sense of the Israeli threat and the question of
whether or not we are prepared for that again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A generation later, it is a way for the ruling elite that
fought this war to tell a new generation what it accomplished,''
adds Kaziha. ``They can't boast a strong economy, but at least they
can say they stopped Israel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
