<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2611 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-ILLEGAL-SEARCH-     10-06 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-ILLEGAL-SEARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT HEARS ARGUMENTS ON PRIVACY ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Supreme Court considered this question
Tuesday: If you're over at a friend's house for dinner, can you
expect the same right to privacy that you would enjoy at home?
</P>
<P>
   If not, would it be legal for a police officer to look through
the dining room window to see if anyone at the party was committing
a crime?
</P>
<P>
   These issues in a Minnesota drug case may lead the justices to
define privacy rights of guests in someone else's home.
</P>
<P>
   The case also calls on the justices to decide whether a
Minnesota police officer engaged in an illegal search of a private
apartment when he looked through a gap in the blinds of a kitchen
window to see if cocaine was being bagged for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the officer argue that his actions were a search of
the premises without a warrant and, therefore, were illegal. The
state of Minnesota has contended that the officer was merely
viewing what any person walking by the apartment could have seen.
</P>
<P>
   Representing the state, James C. Backstrom, a Dakota County
prosecutor in Hasting, Minn., argued that unless temporary guests
are staying overnight, they cannot expect the same protection given
to the homeowners under the Constitution's Fourth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   To back up his position, he cited a 1990 Supreme Court ruling
that an overnight guest in a private home has the same privacy
rights as the homeowner. In that ruling, the justices did not
consider whether such protection is enjoyed by guests who only stay
for a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Backstrom's argument was met with resistance from several
justices, who suggested a number of hypothetical instances when a
person visiting someone's home might expect the same protection
against unreasonable police searches as would the owner of the
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about a person who comes over once a week to play
poker?'' Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg asked. ``Can that person
expect privacy while their play poker?''
</P>
<P>
   Backstrom answered ``no'' but said a more frequent visitor might
have a stronger argument.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter questioned what role the frequency of
visits to a house had in the debate over privacy. ``If they play
(poker) five times a week, they get standing, but if they play
once, they don't?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer asked Backstrom why privacy should be
denied to anyone who is invited into another person's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep coming back to the idea of ``mi casa es su casa _ my
house is yours,''' he said. ``If someone invited you there,
shouldn't you expect privacy?''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor suggested that a line could be drawn
between business guests and personal guests to determine who should
expect privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why the Avon lady, with all of her products out on
the table, should expect more privacy in someone's living room than
at an office or a store,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from a drug bust on the night of May 15, 1994, in
Eagan, Minn. At about 8 p.m., a police officer, James Thielen, was
tipped off by an informant that cocaine powder was being bagged in
an apartment down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Thielen went to the apartment complex to investigate the tip. He
walked up to the window and peered through a gap in the Venetian
blinds, which were down. Inside, he saw two men and a woman
measuring and bagging what looked like cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when the two men walked left the apartment and drove
away, Thielen stopped and arrested the two men, Wayne Carter and
Melvin Johns. On the floor of the car, he noticed a handgun
sticking out of a zippered bag.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects _ who did not live at the apartment _ were
later convicted of conspiracy to commit a drug crime and aiding the
commission of a drug crime. They appealed, saying the police
engaged in an illegal search.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Supreme Court last year threw out their
convictions, saying the two men could assert their Fourth Amendment
rights and that Thielen's action were an unlawful search.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Bradford Carter, representing the two men, told
the justices that Thielen's actions became illegal as soon as he
left the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an officer can see into the window from the sidewalk,
that's one thing,'' Carter said. ``But when he crouches 12 inches
from the window and peers through slits in the blind, that's
invading privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor also noted the difference between an officer looking
into a window from the sidewalk _ where anyone would be able to see
into the apartment _ and an officer walking up to the window and
staring into an opening in the blinds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A police officer can go to a residence with a closed blind ...
stoop down to peer between the cracks ... and that's perfectly
legitimate?'' she asked. ``Isn't that different in quality and
nature'' from simply walking by and seeing inside an open window,
she asked?
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyer Jeffrey A. Lamken, who supported the
state of Minnesota, argued that it is not a search when a police
officer sees something that is exposed to outside view.
</P>
<P>
   Lower courts have denied privacy protection for activities that
are easily observable by the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
