<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2625 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     10-06 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL SEDUCES THE MASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - It took a mighty effort, but for a while there, those
disinclined to pay attention to that sort of thing could almost
ignore the Bill Clinton-Monica Lewinsky mess.
</P>
<P>
   Just another tacky political soap opera, you could tell
yourself. There are more important things to worry about. I'll wait
for the movie.
</P>
<P>
   But all that changed. Somewhere along the line Ken Starr's
crusade evolved (or devolved, depending on your point of view) from
inside-the-beltway business to genuine pop-culture phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Proof? Look no further than last week, when Roseanne, in her new
guise as a daytime talk-show host, offered Lewinsky upwards of $1
million to appear on her show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll pay her big,'' Roseanne said on CNN's ``Larry King
Live'' show, a real meeting of the minds. I can't believe I'm
saying it, but this almost made me miss Tom Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (Full disclosure: I have not seen Roseanne's talk show, so I
can't say whether she's any good at her new job. But I'm confident
she's better at this than at her previous role as national-anthem
singer. For instance, I'll bet she doesn't grab her crotch on her
show.)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier last week, Oprah Winfrey took the high road, saying
negotiations to bring Lewinsky on her show fell apart over money.
Now that she has turned Monica down, she can get back to the
business of promoting sappy novels.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I don't blame Oprah. Although at first I thought of a
Monica interview as a bad investment. After all the releases of
reports and videotapes and transcripts, once you get beyond the one
obvious question _ don't you believe in dry cleaning? _ what else
is there that we don't already know?
</P>
<P>
   On further reflection, I realized the Monica interview would be
a gold mine. The romantic, afternoon-TV types would want to know if
the commander in chief closes his eyes when he kisses, and lowlifes
would want to know . . . well, most of what they would want to know
is already in the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, though, Oprah's right _ paying for
interviews is normally frowned upon unless you work for a
publication that routinely runs stories with such headlines as
``Evidence of Bigfoot found in Martian crater'' and ``Elizabeth
Taylor speaks: My torrid affair with Nostradamus _ he anticipated
my every need.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that there aren't elements of the Monica
story that I wouldn't like to see Roseanne pay for. For instance,
whatever Roseanne's offering Lewinsky, she should pay Linda Tripp
double (begin ital) not (end ital) to talk. And a similar amount
for Tripp and her pal Lucianne Goldberg to fly back to the coven.
</P>
<P>
   More pop-culture saturation: Starr's report has been published
in three different editions, so that you can select the one that
most closely caters to your prurient needs. (Well, almost _ none is
illustrated. Be thankful for small favors.)
</P>
<P>
   And it's selling like ``The Bridges of Madison County''
(speaking of tacky soap operas), which makes you wonder about all
those polls that say Americans are sick of the whole, er, affair.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to admit to buying the report, mind you. It's like
getting caught in the checkout line of a mainstream bookstore with
a copy of ``Playboy.'' ``Uh, it's not for me! I'm buying it for a
friend. But it's nice seeing you, Father Doyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet is to wedge it in between copies of ``Ulysses''
and ``The Sound and the Fury'' and hope no one notices it.
</P>
<P>
   The whole sordid mess is rife with other pop-culture
possibilities. ``Love in the Oval Office (or right next door)''
would be a good name for a soundtrack album, pulling together songs
from the CDs the two traded as gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of blue Gap dresses _ the Intern Collection _ could keep
the Home Shopping Network afloat for months.
</P>
<P>
   And I can't believe there isn't a designer line of ``message''
ties on the market already. Is the fashion world asleep at the
switch? No wonder models are always frowning.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Who knows? But the TV movie can't be far behind. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
