 BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR  
   
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, Oct. 7. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CONGRESS (Washington) - Could we be headed toward another
government shutdown at the end of the week? Republicans paid dearly
for the shutdown of 1995-96, and there are signs that they don't
have the stomach to do it again. At issue is a giant spending bill
needed to fund government operations when the current stopgap
measure expires Friday. GOP hard-liners want the measure to include
tax cuts and environmental provisions that President Clinton
believes are irresponsible. He'd veto the bill, and the government
would be forced to close. But many in the GOP seem to be leaning
toward a non-controversial bill that would send Congress home for
the elections without having to answer questions about who was to
blame for another shutdown. We'll get the views of Arizona members
as well as national leaders. By ADRIANNE FLYNN and JEFF BARKER.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EAGLE DIES (Undated) - JD _ Arizona's most prolific and
longest-lived male bald eagle _ has died, either of natural causes
or possibly because of wounds inflicted by another bird, wildlife
officials said Monday. He was 19, nearly twice the average lifespan
of desert-nesting bald eagles in the wild. JD's twin sister, known
simply as the Alamo Lake female, now reigns as Arizona's
longest-lived bald eagle in the wild. By STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ You can buy the book. Now maybe y ou
can see the Clinton-Lewinsky mess on TV, if Monica takes Rose
anne's $1 million offer. Now the scandal is everywhere. By BILL
GOODYKOONTZ. Story moved in the ``L'' category.  &QL; 
BOOKS-NEW (Undated) _ Capsule reviews of new and notable books. By
ANNE STEPHENSON. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BOOK-NAVAJO (Undated) _ ``The First Eagle,'' Tony Hillerman's
latest mystery novel, doesn't fly. Fatal fleas, eagle poaching, a
missing woman and murder are blended in the mystery story that
stretches from a place called Yells Back Butte near Black Mesa, to
Kaibeto, Cedar Ridge and Flagstaff. They're familiar sites
throughout the land where my relatives have herded sheep for
decades. I wanted to like this story. By BETTY REID. Story moved in
the ``E'' category. &QL; 
