A2644 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PFEIFFER-TV-LADN     10-06 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PFEIFFER-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PFEIFFER' OFF TO WEAK START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR; The  &LR; situation comedy ``The Secret Diary of
Desmond Pfeiffer,'' which has sparked two weeks of protest, earned
paltry national ratings with its Monday night debut.
</P>
<P>
   Some local viewers agree the show's future is dim, but more
because of its lack of humor than its controversial premise _ a
black butler working in the White House during the Civil War era.
</P>
<P>
   The sitcom drew a national rating of 1.6 (percentages of
television sets tuned in) with a share of 2 (percentage of
television sets in use tuned in), according to Nielsen Media
Research. Those numbers are on par with the remainder of United
Paramount Network's (KCOP, Channel 13) Monday prime-time lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The show attracted its largest audiences in the nation's largest
cities. Its highest rating was in New York (4.1/6), followed by Los
Angeles (3.6/5). Its rating in the top 40 markets was 2.5 with a 4
share.
</P>
<P>
   Three protests at Paramount Studios in Hollywood led by the
Brotherhood Crusade, and the Los Angeles City Council's unanimous
vote last week condemning the show raised public awareness of the
brewing controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Geri Parker of North Hills was among those who tuned in Monday
night after hearing about the protests. Her conclusion: Take the
show off the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anything racist about it,'' said Parker, who is
African-American. ``But I didn't find it funny. I didn't really
dislike anything in particular about the show, but it wasn't funny
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmie Williams of Palmdale also found the program unwatchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see it as offensive. I don't know why people are
having an uproar about it,'' said Williams, an African-American.
``I just found it disinteresting and boring.''
</P>
<P>
   The sitcom came under fire as soon as word spread that the
``Pfeiffer'' premiere originally contained a scene of two men being
hanged in Britain _ a parallel to lynchings of the time. The scene
was edited out long before the pilot ever hit the air, but
protesters, including the Rev. Jesse Jackson, say depictions like
that trivialize the painful period of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   They are incensed that such a show dealing with a subject as
painful as slavery and oppression would be permitted on television
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all it was historically incorrect,'' said Mollie Bell
of Compton, who has attended all three rallys at Paramount,
including one on Monday morning. ``Our people did not keep diaries
in those days. It was against the law for us to read or write. I
find it very offensive. They should hear our cries and feel our
pain and do the right thing and take it off the air,'' said Bell,
an African-American.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenting voice at Monday morning's demonstration was
Randolph Scott, an African-American Inglewood resident, who stood
with a sign supporting UPN in one hand and a red Doberman pinscher
_ for protection, he says _ in the other. He likes some shows on
UPN, he said, and would not criticize the entire operation.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, an actor who has appeared on a onetime UPN sitcom called
``Sparks,'' saw the original pilot, including the hanging scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with some of the situations, like the hanging,''
he said, ``but I think there is some funny stuff in the show. UPN
gives a lot of black actors work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
