<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2650 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-SOLOMON-HNS &LR;      10-06 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-SOLOMON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PAYS TRIBUTE TO RETIRING GERALD SOLOMON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With numerous references to his famous temper and
even-handed tenure as chairman of the Rules Committee, lawmakers
across the political spectrum took to the House floor Tuesday to
praise Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon, R-N.Y., who is retiring after 20
years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In convivial banter that at times resembled a roast, lawmakers
took more than 90 minutes from a busy calendar in the final
scheduled week of the 105th Congress to say goodbye to Solomon and
hail his accomplishments during 10 terms.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1978, the 68-year-old lawmaker has represented a generally
rural and conservative upstate New York district that stretches 200
miles along the state's eastern border.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon has earned a reputation for passionate, often combative
politics, the ideological foundation of which was best articulated
by President Ronald Reagan in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   He entered Congress the same year as House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., and Solomon has been an able lieutenant in the
majority ever since the Republicans took control of the House in
the 1994 election and an ardent critic of most Clinton
administration policies.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Joseph Moakley, D-Mass., the ranking Democrat on the
Rules Committee, called the retiring lawmaker ``a tireless defender
of American veterans'' who has ``served with distinction and done
his party a great service.''
</P>
<P>
   While Solomon, a conservative loyal to Gingrich, and Moakley, a
liberal, are ideological opposites, Moakley said he considered
Solomon a very good friend.
</P>
<P>
   But Solomon's one downfall, quipped Moakley, is that he can't
resist talking about his stint during the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so proud of his beloved Marine Corps that he still gets
their haircut,'' said Moakley, referring to Solomon's crew cut.
</P>
<P>
   Another Democrat, Rep. Louis Stokes of Ohio, who also is
retiring, described Solomon as ``animated, passionate and a real
showman. No matter how much you disagree with him, you have to
admire him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen Republicans and 17 Democrats are retiring from the House
or seeking other office this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., said Solomon has ``made a great
contribution to this House.''
</P>
<P>
   With Solomon seated nearby, House Majority Leader Richard Armey,
R-Texas, joked about the accolades. ``What a mark you've made,''
Armey said. ``People that hardly noticed you when you came here
have their hearts filled with joy (now) that you are leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   But most paid tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, told Solomon that ``at a time of overpowering cynicism,
you have proven by your 20 years here in Congress that politics can
be a noble profession because you brought some nobility to it. We
will miss you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though they are in the minority, numerous Democratic
lawmakers said Solomon had always been fair and allowed them a
voice on the Rules Committee, which has executed a conservative
legislative agenda since the Republicans took over control of the
House.
</P>
<P>
   But Solomon, a combative partisan, would never give too much,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry has a way of turning you down with a smile,'' said Rep.
Carrie Meek, D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Said Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio: ``Oftentimes, when we get run over
by Jerry, he does it with style.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My nickname for Jerry is `the battler,''' said Rep. Benjamin
A. Gilman, R-N.Y., the chairman of the House International
Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Thomas, R-Calif., said Solomon was a potent
political ally because ``if you are not (on the same side of an
issue) it's full combat.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon's combativeness has ignited his well-known temper on
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, he apologized for saying on the House floor
that U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan ``ought to be horsewhipped''
for siding with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein over the interests
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1996 debate on repealing a ban on certain
semi-automatic assault weapons, Solomon, who fought to repeal the
ban, became embroiled in a heated floor debate with Rep. Patrick
Kennedy, D-R.I., who was against the repeal. After their exchange,
Solomon continued the debate with Kennedy, 31, during which Solomon
was heard to say: ``Let's just step outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Several colleagues and Solomon himself joked about that incident
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Said Solomon: ``I'm going to invite all of you ... to step
outside so that I can hug the women and shake hands with the men
and thank you,'' he said on one of his final appearances from the
House floor. ``I just love you all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
