   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, Oct. 7
</P>
<P>
   and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Tina May
at 206-448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   SINGAPORE-PROSPERITY (Singapore) There has always been an
element of fear _ some would say paranoia _ in Singapore's 30-year
effort to become one of the world's most prosperous nations.
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Redmond. (story will move in the ``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-SHAKEUP (Seattle) In another top-level shakeup at Boeing,
Larry Clarkson has been replaced as head of Boeing Enterprises, the
new unit that had been counted on to produce upwards of $5 billion
a year for the compnay. Clarkston will be replaced by Tom Schick, a
deputy of new commercial boss Alan Mulally.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SEAHAWKS-FLAP (Seattle) Searching for a unique way to
celebrate big plays, Seahawks cornerback Fred Thomas invented ``the
Flap,'' a flapping-wings motion he makes with his hands, wrists
crossed. That was two years ago, when there was little to
celebrate. Now, with the team 3-2 and unbeaten in the Kingdome,
Thomas has Kingdome fans ``flapping'' back at him. Thomas hopes he
has something to celebrate Sunday, when the Super Bowl-champion
Broncos come to town.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-COLUMN-THIEL (Seattle) You don't have to ask where the
Mariner pitching went; just watch the playoffs. It took yet another
ex-Mariner -- Sterling Hitchcock -- to knock Randy Johnson and the
Astros out in the NL playoffs. The M's have given their best
pitching away, and if there is any lesson to be learned from the
playoffs, it is that pitching is the key to success. The fact that
the M's are talking about finding a No. 2 or No. 3 starter
indicates they haven't learned that lesson yet.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-COUGARS (Undated) The Washington Cougars are facing the
nation's top passer this season, but the surprise is that it's
Oregon's Akili Smith _ not UCLA's Cade McNown or Washington's Brock
Huard. Cougs preparing for Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   By Angelo Bruscas. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
