<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM BESETS CLINTON ADMINISTRATION'S KOSOVO PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon offered fighter planes for a NATO
attack to halt an offensive in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo and
said that an international force of ground troops might be
dispatched as peacekeepers. But Congress and European allies
expressed doubts Tuesday about what a strike could accomplish. The
increasing criticism, coming from Republicans and Democrats alike,
jeopardized the Clinton administration's threats of an imminent
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the administration found itself thwarted by
the slow decision-making of the United Nations and NATO as well as
the political skills of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. As
he has after several attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
province, Milosevic kept negotiations alive Tuesday, tantalizing
Westerners who want a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
   After talking by phone to British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
Clinton said ``NATO is prepared to act'' with air power. Milosevic
can avoid an attack by halting his offensive against separatists,
allowing refugees to return home, giving aid groups free access to
villages that have been razed and starting real talks with the
separatists, the president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are high,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House says time is running out because Milosevic's
forces have driven 250,000 people, mostly ethnic Albanians, to the
hills, where they face starvation and disease this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Denouncing the ``arrogance'' of Milosevic, Defense Secretary
William Cohen said the US government has pledged to provide attack
planes to NATO if there is an air strike. NATO's plans for
Milosevic involve ``inflicting enough damage to reduce his capacity
to wage war,'' Cohen told the Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He said a ground force of peacekeepers _ a smaller version of
the force that includes 7,500 American troops in Bosnia _ would be
``a possibility.'' But he added that the soldiers should Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Even one of Clinton's supporters, Carl Levin, the
highest-ranking member of the Senate Armed Services Committee,
called military action in Kosovo ``the best of a number of bad
options.'' Republican Senator Strom Thurmond, who chairs the
committee, was more critical. ``We have not considered the impact
of this decision on US and NATO (peacekeeping) forces in Bosnia''
who could be targets of retaliation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Senator John McCain, a Vietnam veteran, dressed down
the Pentagon chief, saying, ``I have to tell you, Secretary Cohen,
right now many of us are very concerned'' about the prospect of an
attack. McCain said the administration suffers a ``credibility
gap'' because of a broken promise in 1997 to withdraw America
peacekeeping forces from Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has put together plans for both a quick strike and a
prolonged strike, and a final approval from the 16 members is
expected this week. But Congressional aides who keep tabs on the
Pentagon and the State Department predicted that there would not be
an attack just yet, if ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've waited too long on Kosovo, and Milosevic has
basically been able to accomplish 90 percent of what he wanted
while NATO and the US were dawdling,'' said a foreign policy
specialist who works for a Congressional committee who did not want
to be named. ``And let's face it. we're in the middle of this other
mess (a debate about impeachment).''
</P>
<P>
   Staff members in Congress and humanitarian groups in Washington
complained that most European countries have given a tepid
reception to discussions about an attack on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's tough talk was contradicted by a flurry of
diplomatic efforts in New York, Moscow, Belgrade and Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin warned that any NATO attack
would lead to ``serious international consequences.'' Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov announced that Russia would veto any effort in
the UN to authorize air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A military strike will not help normalize the situation but
will have the opposite effect,'' Iganov said in comments that
convinced other diplomats the UN Security Council will not agree to
a strike. Russia is one of five permanent members of the council.
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Seleznyov, the speaker of the lower house of parliament,
said legislators would call for a review of Russia's relations with
NATO if the alliance used force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
