<SLUG> BC-TUTU-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUTU CHIDES US FOR FAILURE TO SETTLE RACIAL ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Archbishop Desmond Tutu of South Africa spoke
Tuesday of the miracle of South Africa's peace, the promise of
Ireland's, and of the failure of the United States to come to terms
with its own racial struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have scored a great victory over Apartheid,'' Tutu said.
``Miracles do happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu, 66, has just completed some of the most emotionally
wrenching work of his life, as chairman of South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission. The commission has heard testimony from
the victims of apartheid _ and from their victimizers.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu, retired Episcopal archbishop of South Africa, won the
Nobel Peace Prize in 1984 for his crusade against apartheid. He is
living in the United States for a year on sabbatical, and begins
teaching at Emory University in Atlanta in January.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke Tuesday 25th annual meeting of the New Hampshire
Humanities Council, in the only state in the nation to fail to
enact a holiday honoring Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's a great shame,'' he said of New Hamshire's
failure to enact the King Day legislation. ``And I would hope that
those who are able to do so would correct a very bad mistake as
soon as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu discussed his recent visit to Northern Ireland, where he
met with leaders of the Irish peace process.
</P>
<P>
   To the people of Ireland, Tutu said: ``keep on going on, and
hold on, because the prize is too precious. ...There is no doubt at
all. The Good Friday settlement is going to succeed. The people are
too determined for anything else to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu also said Tuesday that the United States must to come to
terms with its own ugly racial past, if wounds opened by slavery
and oppression are ever to heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't dealt with the aftermath of slavery and the Civil
War,'' Tutu said. ``And there are pains in the pit of the tummy of
so may people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't healed,'' Tutu said of America's racial wounds.
``They've festered. Open them up. Cleanse them. ...You're
constantly, I'm afraid, going to be shocked by racial outbursts
until you find a way of trying to come to terms with your past.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu also expressed increduilty over the investigation of
President Clinton for his sexual transgressions. He recently signed
a letter of protest against special prosecutor Kenneth Starr's
investigation, which has cost American taxpayers more than $40
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am actually quite surprised by what seems an extraordinary
obsession,'' over the Lewinsky matter, Tutu said. ``To spend over
$40 million. ...'' Tutu burst into laughter. ``Forty million?''
asked Tutu, shocked. ``For what?! People are hungry, even in this
country. I would think $40 million could have been used in so many
more creative ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your president has done what it is very difficult to do when
you are wrong. I don't know about you, but I find it very difficult
even in the intimacy and privacy of my bedroom to say to my wife
`I'm sorry.' Can you imagine having to say it in the full glare of
television lights?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you want to rub his nose in the mud? Why do you want to
wipe your boots all over him?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You (Americans) really are an incredible people,'' Tutu said.
``Generous and loving, and caring...but you are also very
strange.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
