<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-RELIEF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ, KENNEDY OFFER FUNDS TO SHIP RELIEF GOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Red Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez, Red Sox CEO John
Harrington, Congressman Joseph P. Kennedy and Catholic Charities
stepped into the breach to pay between $30,000 and $40,000 to ship
supplies that have been stranded in Massachusetts to victims of
Hurricane Georges in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a report in Tuesday's Globe about difficulties
Dominican leaders are having sending tons of donated goods to the
Dominican Republic, Martinez, who is Dominican, announced he would
give $10,000 toward shipping costs.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Harrington promised to match Martinez's gift with $10,000
from the team's Yawkey Foundation. Kennedy said from Washington
that he would donate funds through his Citizen's Energy
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Charities of Boston will collect the funds, adding a
gift of its own, according to Jack Dunn, the organization's vice
president for external affairs. The money will then go to Catholic
Relief Services, which will oversee the shipping.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Steve Cunningham of American Medical Resources
Foundation said his organization would pay to ship one or two
45-foot containers of merchandise to the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The Dominican Relief Fund, established by 35 local Dominican
community leaders, has collected enough donations to fill 15
45-foot shipping containers _ including everything from insulin and
baby formula to 500 beds donated by Holiday Inn. Most of the items
were donated by Latino communities in Massachusetts and Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
   The effort had come under criticism when organizers failed to
find a means for shipping the donated goods, which as of Tuesday
were being warehoused at a school in Lawrence, a Cablevision office
in Hyde Park and an Army base in Worcester. Some members of the
Dominican-American community questioned the committee's
professionalism for campaigning hard to collect items, without
having secured a means for transporting the merchandise ahead of
time.
</P>
<P>
   But Carlos Veras, assistant to the Dominican Consul in Boston
and one of the people who spearheaded the effort, defended his
group's actions, saying they had been working ``20 hours a day
since the hurricane hit'' to find transportation for the goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just much, much more expensive than we realized,''
Veras said.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Martinez has given money to causes in
the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things he did after signing a $75 million
contract with the Red Sox was to build a church, school, day care
center and ball diamond in his hometown of Manoguayabo.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez told the Globe he still remembers the terror he felt
living through Hurricane David when he was 7. Citizens of
Manoguayabo reportedly used the church Martinez built as a shelter
during Hurricane Georges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
