<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREME-PATENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS INVENTOR WANTS HIGH COURT TO OVERTURN RULING, RESTORE
PATENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An inventor from suburban Dallas urged a skeptical
Supreme Court on Tuesday to restore his high-tech patent, which a
lower court revoked because he missed a one-year filing deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Jerry Selinger, pressing the case of inventor Wayne
Pfaff, said the federal appeals court misread federal law when it
ruled that his client waited too long to seek a patent for his
invention after placing it on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Selinger said the one-year time limit begins only after an
invention has been finished, not when it is merely substantially
completed, as the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit
ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaff's creation, a socket to hold computer microchips during
testing, was only in preliminary stages when he agreed to sell the
product to Texas Instruments on April 8, 1981, more than a year
before applying for a patent on April 19, 1982, Selinger added.
</P>
<P>
   But attorneys for a high-tech company that sells a competing
socket design and the Clinton administration countered that the
one-year clock begins before the product is finished.
</P>
<P>
   C. Randall Bain, who represents Wells Electronics, said the
clock starts when a proposed invention is sufficiently complete
that it would qualify for a patent. Assistant Solicitor General
Jeffrey Minear argued that an inventor runs afoul of patent law
when he advertises his still unfinished product for sale and then
waits more than a year before seeking a patent.
</P>
<P>
   However, the justices were critical of all the arguments,
questioning the attorneys' contrasting definitions of ``invention''
under the patent law.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, noting that patents have been
awarded based solely on blueprints, said that the one-year limit
perhaps starts as early as when plans are drawn for an invention.
But Justice Antonin Scalia asked whether a sale can be made before
an invention is actually completed.
</P>
<P>
   Selinger responded that an invention, for patent law purposes,
refers to a new product that has progressed well beyond the
planning stages to something that has been ``reduced to practice.''
Congress did not intend for the one-year clock to start until an
invention is complete so as to allow inventors to test the market
for their ideas, the Dallas attorney added.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bain countered that the one-year clock begins when an
invention, or the idea for one, has progressed to the extent that
it is capable of being patented. Congress intended the time
constraint to encourage inventors to apply for patents at the
earliest possible time, the Phoenix lawyer argued.
</P>
<P>
   Minear defended his even broader definition of invention, saying
Congress intended to put the onus on inventors to finish their
proposed creations. When the one-year clock starts is solely ``in
the hands of the inventor,'' who puts the time in motion when he
places his prospective invention on the market, the government
lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaff so far has had mixed results in court. The U.S. District
Court for Northern Texas agreed with his claim that Wells
Electronics infringed on his patent, which was awarded Jan. 1,
1985. But the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, which
hears patent cases, reversed that decision, saying the one-year
clock was already running when Pfaff reached the sales agreement
with Texas Instruments.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is expected to render its decision by next
summer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
