<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      10-06 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: CELEBRATING HITCHCOCK; NOBEL SEASON BEGINS; MUTI
WELCOMED BACK; JAZZ AROUND THE WORLD; BANNED AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Next year will be the centennial of the birth of
Alfred Hitchcock, cinema's master of suspense, who was born on Aug.
13, 1899, and died in 1980. The Museum of Modern Art intends to
celebrate with a complete retrospective. From April to July, it
will show Hitchcock's 53 feature films and two shorts and exhibit
posters, photographs and papers relating to the life and work of
the man who made films like ``The 39 Steps,'' ``Rebecca,'' ``Rear
Window,'' ``Vertigo'' and ``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   Contenders
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Nobel Prize season opens Wednesday in Stockholm with
the announcement of the award in literature. The six prizes _ in
medicine, physics, chemistry, economics and peace _ each carrying
an award of $938,000, will be announced over nine days ending Oct.
16.
</P>
<P>
   Because last year's Nobel laureate in literature, the Italian
playwright Dario Fo, proved a surprise, speculation is cautious
this year. But the French writers Michel Tournier and Jean-Marie Le
Clezio have been contenders for a decade, along with Gunter Grass
of Germany and the Dutch writer Cees Noteboom. Also mentioned are
the British author Salman Rushdie, the Albanian writer Ismail
Kadare and the Portuguese writers Jose Saramago and Antonio Lobo
Antunes.
</P>
<P>
   Return Engagement
</P>
<P>
   Five years after he stepped down abruptly as music director of
the Philadelphia Orchestra, Riccardo Muti was greeted with a
thundering standing ovation when he returned Monday night to lead a
benefit performance of Italian and theatrical works at the Academy
of Music in Philadelphia. ``This is a very short visit, but I
promise it will not be my last,'' he said. Muti, 57, is now the
music director of La Scala opera house in Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Road Trip
</P>
<P>
   With a performance Wednesday night in Rossiya Hall in Moscow,
the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra, led by Wynton Marsalis, begins
its fall 1998 World Tour of 33 cities in Europe, the United States,
Canada and South America. Prior to many concerts, the orchestra
will offer educational programming that includes master classes,
clinics, lectures and workshops for students and others.
</P>
<P>
   Naysayers
</P>
<P>
   Having already banned productions of the 16th-century opera
``The Peony Pavilion'' at Lincoln Center Festival '98 and at the
Paris Autumn Festival, Chinese officials have now forbidden the
Shanghai Kunqu Opera Company to perform the opera at the annual
Hong Kong Arts Festival, opening in February. The 19-hour epic
deals with a young woman who meets her lover in a dream. Cultural
officials in Shanghai have deemed the production ``ideologically
unsuitable and pornographic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
