<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-UNREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME MINISTER APPEARS FOR CALM AS WORKERS PREPARE FOR NATIONWIDE
STRIKE S 
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's Prime Minister made an extraordinary appeal
for calm Tuesday night as millions of Communists and trade
unionists prepared nationwide strikes over the ravaged economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way out of the crisis for Russia is in public order and
consent, stability and discipline,'' the prime minister, Yevgeny
Primakov, said in a televised address. ``I would to like call on
everybody not to rock our common boat in today's stormy seas.''
</P>
<P>
   And in case the summons to patriotism was not enough, Primakov
piled promise upon promise in a last-minute effort to win over
Russia's disaffected and dispossessed.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two weeks in office, Primakov has yet to
complete a plan to drag Russia out of its economic distress. But
the strikes, planned for Wednesday, clearly weigh heavily on the
minds of Kremlin officials.
</P>
<P>
   With prices soaring, the ruble sagging and a mountain of wages
due, the Communists, unions and an array of splinter groups are
flexing their muscles.
</P>
<P>
   They have already placed Communists at the head of the Central
Bank and at the helm of the government's economic policy. The
strikes appear aimed at maintaining the pressure on Primakov to
steer a leftward course and on President Boris Yeltsin to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist leader, boasted Tuesday that 10
million Russians would stop work and join in the protest over
overdue wages and a faltering economy. Millions more, he insisted,
would find other ways to show their support.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists have a record of exaggerating their numbers.
Moscow authorities, however, are taking no chances: An estimated
11,000 police officers and 6,000 interior ministry troops are ready
in the capital to maintain order.
</P>
<P>
   The permits issued by the authorities for the protests specify
that the main demonstrations are to be held far from the White
House, the government headquarters, which is still a potent
emotional symbol for the left. The vast marble structure was
shelled in 1993 after Yeltsin called out tanks to quell a
rebellious Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists and their allies insist that as many as 200,000
protesters will march toward St. Basil's Cathedral in Red Square.
Protests are also scheduled in St. Petersburg, where demonstrators
plan to gather in front of the Winter Palace, which was the focus
of the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution, and in other cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's speech was something of a national debut for
Primakov, 68. His career was built largely out of the public eye,
at the foreign ministry and as chief of the intelligence service,
and the role of national conciliator is a new one. It is a part he
is clearly still struggling to master.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov has extolled Franklin D. Roosevelt and talked about the
need for a Russian New Deal. The intent of his address was to
uplift the nation, much as Roosevelt did with his ``fireside
chats.''
</P>
<P>
   But in many respects it appeared to be a heavy-handed government
production. The taped address was broadcast during prime time,
against a backdrop of Moscow evening traffic, as if to assure a
nervous nation that life in the capital was proceeding more or less
normally. The tape was heavily edited, with jarring transitions
between close-ups and longer-range shots of the somber Prime
Minister.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he appeared to say what many Russians want to hear,
mainly by cataloguing measures that have already been announced.
</P>
<P>
   The new prime minister promised to pay back wages to the army.
He promised Russians they would have sufficient fruit, vegetables
and potatoes through the winter. Rail tariffs for food are to be
slashed, and Ukraine and Belarus will be allowed to pay debts to
Russia by bartering food.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov even promised to return more than $1 billion worth of
equipment that was confiscated from tax delinquents in order to
help those enterprises make a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   Having sought to placate the left, Primakov balanced his appeal
by saying that he did not want to insult the government of his
predecessor, Sergei Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov also said privatization would go on, the tax system
would be reformed and foreign and domestic debts would be paid.
</P>
<P>
   He did not say exactly how all this would be accomplished, but
insisted that he was being unfairly criticized for failing to issue
an economic plan.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov said his government could not complete his program
until it knew if the International Monetary Fund would disburse
billions in fresh funds. Such aid seems very unlikely until
Primakov demonstrates that he is prepared to take the tough steps
to build a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I and my colleagues have been reproached for not producing a
complete, finished economic program within the government's first
few weeks,'' he said. ``There will be a program. But the financial
side of the program depends on negotiations we are conducting in
the country and outside it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
