<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2684 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-06 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEYRITZ SURE, STEADY UNDER PLAYOFF PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I probably shouldn't be spilling trade secrets, but
they try to spoon-feed us when the big games come. Tuesday
afternoon they dragged the usual interrogation suspects to the
interview room. You know, there were the skippers, Bobby Cox and
Bruce Bochy. There were Wednesday night's National League
Championship Series Game 1 starting pitchers, John Smoltz and Andy
Ashby.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, there was Jim Leyritz.
</P>
<P>
   Who isn't even in the San Diego starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz, the new Mr. October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always joked that I get paid for April and October,'' he
says. ``April, most of the guys are hurt coming out of spring
training and I get to play a little more. And I've had some success
in October.''
</P>
<P>
   You mean success as in three home runs in four games of the
Division Series against the Astros? You mean success as in the
three-run, game-tying, eighth-inning homer off Mark Wohlers in Game
4 of the '96 World Series? You mean success as in a 15th-inning,
game-winning home run in Game 2 of the '95 Division Series?
</P>
<P>
   I think, yes, that's what he has in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz is one of those sports oddities who keep the entire
enterprise from ever becoming mundane. He is a career .270 kind of
hitter, a versatile guy who has played first, second, third,
outfield, catcher, and, of course, DH. He is a fielder of no
particular distinction, but he's good enough to get by.
</P>
<P>
   No manager has ever looked at him and said, ``This man is too
good to keep out of the lineup.'' The 114 games he managed between
the Red Sox and San Diego this year exceed his previous season high
by 19. But turn the biggest spotlight you've got on this guy, and
suddenly, he's Joe Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about Jim Leyritz, but he's gotta have heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy performs under pressure the way he does,'' says
Bochy, the Padres manager, ``and comes through with the kind of
clutch hits he gets, it's obvious he's very relaxed and wants to be
the guy up there with the game on the line and he's got the perfect
makeup for it. He enjoys the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz has an interesting theory about his ability to produce
the big hit. It starts with the fact that he was an undrafted
player coming out of the University of Kentucky. No one ever gave
him anything in this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think some of the other guys understand what it's
like,'' he explains. ``I have always felt that I've had to prove
myself every single day. I've never had the luxury of being put in
the lineup for three weeks or a month and left alone. Every at-bat
I've ever had in the big leagues has been a big situation for me
because I never knew what the next day would bring. I've hit six
homers in a week and then not started the next game. That's why I
don't identify pressure, I guess. I always feel I'm under
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows indignity. He wanted to go back to his senior year at
Kentucky in order to catch, but his coach, Keith Madison, told him
he was too small to catch, that he wanted him to play third. An
angry Leyritz turned around and signed with the Yankees because
they would let him catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madison was pretty mad,'' Leyritz says. ``I signed two days
before school started and he lost a scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the last time he irritated someone in the game of
baseball. He distinguished himself in New York by his constant
moaning about playing time, and when he hit that big homer against
the Mariners three years ago, there were a few mates who rolled
their eyes and sighed, ``Anybody but him.'' He wasn't happy in
Anaheim last year. He wasn't happy in Texas last year. And when he
left Boston June 21 this year, he was classically disgruntled over
not being used more.
</P>
<P>
   But he left his mark in Boston, all right, whacking eight homers
and slugging .519 in 129 at-bats. He was a central figure in the
memorable April run with timely long-distance hits. The trouble
was, he was doing it as a DH. He wanted to catch and he let the
manager and general manager know that.
</P>
<P>
   When he was traded, he predicted that the Red Sox would miss him
in time, and so it is natural to ask him if he let his thoughts
stray toward the Hub while he was smashing those big homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I followed them,'' he says. ``I enjoyed the 25 guys I played
with.'' (He cited Mo Vaughn, Damon Buford, John Valentin, and Jason
Varitek among those he considers friends). ``It was a problem
between me and the manager and the ownership as far as what my
playing time was. But as far as anything else goes, no. The 25 guys
I played with over there, I did miss those guys, and that was
unfortunate to see them lose.''
</P>
<P>
   He's still Jim Leyritz, and managers have him slotted. The three
home runs against Houston may have earned him applause and a spot
in the interview room ahead of eight-time batting champ Tony Gwynn,
but it can't get him into Wednesday night's lineup. Nor tomorrow's.
He is scheduled to catch Sterling Hitchcock in Saturday's Game 3.
Meanwhile, he waits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Double switches, pinch hitting, you never know when he'll be
used,'' points out Bochy. ``Don't forget, he can play a lot of
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a valuable guy to have around,'' agrees Atlanta's Cox,
who can still see Leyritz changing the course of the '96 Series
when he redirected that Wohlers heater into the left-field stands.
``A righthand bat like that is pretty powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, meanwhile, thinks he should be playing. He always
thinks he should be playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying _ and everybody in else in the New York Yankee
organization would know I'd be lying _ if I said I'm happy about
it,'' he says. ``They'd know I'd be lying.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the original squeaky wheel. But come the ninth inning, Jim
Leyritz is the guy you want at the dish. Let him yap. The man can
rip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
