<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALES-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP SUES OVER COLLISIONS WITH WHALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ An environmental group is suing the owners of two whale
watch boats that rammed whales off the Massachusetts coast last
summer, charging that the collisions are part of a pattern of
illegal harassment of the big marine mammals by whale watchers.
</P>
<P>
   GreenWorld, a group that has repeatedly filed lawsuits to oppose
whale watching, alleges that Boston Harbor Cruises violated the
Endangered Species Act when its boat struck and seriously injured a
humpback whale last August. The group also says a boat owned by
Hyannis Whale Watcher Cruises violated the law in September when
its boat killed a minke whale.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marine Fisheries Service is still investigating
both incidents, but GreenWorld Leader Max Strahan said the
accidents were inevitable with the growing popularity _ and light
regulation of _ the whale watching industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have whale boats that intentionally go after whales
on a daily basis, you are asking to have whales struck and
killed,'' said Strahan, a combative activist who calls himself
``The Prince of Whales.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit charges, in essence, that all whale watching boats
violate the Endangered Species Act, even when no whales are
directly injured, because the law prohibits both harassment and
pursuit of endangered species such as the humpback and Northern
right whales.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Boston Harbor Cruises said Strahan's lawsuit is
groundless, noting that some biologists believe whale watching may
even aid whales by building public support for their protection.
</P>
<P>
   But they also stressed that the company has already adopted the
strictest safety standards in the business, including a slowdown
zone that begins within three miles of Stellwagen Bank, a popular
whalewatching area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are operating with more caution than any other whale watch
out there,'' said Rick Nolan, managing partner of Boston Harbor
Cruises, adding that the humpback whale his boat struck apparently
survived.
</P>
<P>
   Hyannis Whale Watcher Cruises could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Although Greenworld is known for taking extreme positions, the
lawsuit reflects growing concern over the safety of whales in the
wake of the two collisions. Animal welfare advocates are
particularly concerned about the Boston Harbor Cruises boat that
struck an endangered humpback whale. It is part of a new generation
of boats that go much faster than conventional whale watches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be more of a potential for vessel
collisions'' than federal regulators had realized, said Doug Beach,
protected species coordinator for the National Marine Fisheries
Service in Gloucester. He said his agency is considering whether to
toughen its voluntary whale watch guidelines governing boat speeds
and distance from whales.
</P>
<P>
   And the co-chairman of a panel looking at how to prevent
collisions between whales and ships, said the National Marine
Fisheries Service needs to consider binding regulations on the
industry, valued at up to $60 million a year and growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any vessel out there poses a hazard to whales ... These
vessels in particular may pose an additional hazard because they
are whalewatching,'' said Bruce Russell, who heads a review of ship
strikes for the New England Implementation Team, an independent
panel carrying out federal plans to help endangered whale species
recover.
</P>
<P>
   However, National Marine Fisheries Service spokeswoman Teri
Frady said her agency's investigation of the two collisions had
revealed ``nothing unusual'' in the way the boats were operated
when the collisions occurred. Although the collision with the
endangered humpback is a technical violation of federal law, the
agency could choose not to prosecute, agency officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.S.-NYT &LR;      10-06 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO AID IRAQI OPPOSITION MOVING THROUGH CONGRESS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bill that would allow the Clinton administration
to spend nearly $100 million to aid Iraqi opposition groups seeking
the ouster of President Saddam Hussein is moving rapidly through
Congress, with final approval virtually certain.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the bill on Monday, by a vote of 360 to 38,
and passage of the so-called Iraq Liberation Act by the Senate is
expected shortly.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is seeking some changes in the bill, including a
clearer definition of which groups would be permitted to receive
the aid and the scope of the assistance that could be given to
them. But administration officials say they are likely to support
whatever eventually emerges from Capitol Hill, especially since it
is not binding on the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Even at a time of domestic political turmoil, the White House
and Congress agree on the need for the United States to do what it
can to bring about the ouster of Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would permit _ but not require _ the president
to spend up to $97 million in arms and other assistance to rebel
groups seeking to replace Saddam with a democratic government.
</P>
<P>
   It would also provide $2 million to Radio Free Iraq, a broadcast
service that was set up under earlier legislation, and it calls for
the administration to press for a United Nations international
criminal tribunal to prosecute Saddam and other Iraqi leaders found
guilty of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill will give our government additional tools with which
to confront the threat to international peace and security posed by
Saddam Hussein,'' said Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., who is
chairman of the House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that while they support the intent
of the bill, they are concerned about the mechanism for providing
money and arms to the Iraqi opposition, which includes dozens of
groups, many of them feuding. They said it might also weaken
support for international sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should underestimate the difficulty of unifying the
Iraqi opposition,'' said Rep. Lee Hamilton of Indiana, the ranking
Democrat on the International Relations Committee. But he noted
that because the bill is nonbinding, it ``states the sense of the
U.S. Congress; it it does not change U.S. policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
