</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-DEBARTOLO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBARTOLO PLEADS GUILTY TO ROLE IN ALLEGED EXTORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eddie DeBartolo has made his deal with the government, but not
with the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, former owner of the San Francisco 49ers, pleaded
guilty Tuesday in Baton Rouge to failing to report an alleged
extortion. DeBartolo is expected to be a key witness in the
government's case against former Louisiana Governor Edwin Edwards
and his son, Stephen Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo was fined $1 million, placed on probation, and agreed
to cooperate with the government.
</P>
<P>
   But NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue said that for at least the
remainder of the 1998 season, all 49ers business will be conducted
by Denise DeBartolo York, Eddie's sister, and Larry Thrailkill, her
representative, who is currently running the team. Tagliabue also
said there is no understanding between him and Eddie DeBartolo
regarding his future status with the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until our office is able to complete a thorough review of
today's agreements and related matters,'' said Tagliabue, ``I have
directed Mr. DeBartolo to continue his current inactive status with
respect to the affairs of the 49ers and the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   When it first came to light late last year that DeBartolo was
involved in the case, which centers around the granting of a
riverboat casino license in Louisiana, Tagliabue asked him to step
aside until it was resolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2694 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LETTERMAN-STALKER-SUI     10-06 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETTERMAN-STALKER-SUICIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celebrity stalker Ray kills herself
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving on (a) General News and (e) Entertainment
categories.)
 &HT;    By Ted Taylor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOTCHKISS, Colo. _ Margaret Mary Ray, who for years claimed to
be Mrs. David Letterman and repeatedly broke into the late-night
star's Connecticut home, killed herself near Hotchkiss Monday
afternoon by kneeling in front of an oncoming train.
</P>
<P>
   Delta County, Colo. Sheriff William Blair said it appeared Ray
walked onto an isolated stretch of the railroad near an
intersection with Highway 133 at about 1 p.m. Monday, knelt down
and leaned over the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said Ray left a note near the scene of the accident asking
police to contact a friend in town so that person could notify her
parents in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a short note saying, `Please contact this
person,''' Blair said. He would not release the name of the friend.
</P>
<P>
   The coal train heading northwest toward Grand Junction, about 60
miles away, was already going slow through the intersection and it
had applied the emergency braking system slowing down even more,
but engineers had no time to stop the 105-car train, Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The engineer and conductor saw her, but there was nothing they
could do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman'' officials told Letterman of
the news Tuesday after a call from The Daily Sentinel to the show's
New York City headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Letterman released a one-sentence statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad ending to a confused life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, 46, who was arrested seven times for trespassing at
Letterman's New Canaan, Conn., home, did not have a home in the
Hotchkiss area, Blair said, but moved around from house to house
living with friends and acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   She did have a post office box in Crawford, Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman may have been Ray's most celebrated stalking victim
but he wasn't her only one.
</P>
<P>
   The Danbury, Conn., native was released from a Kissimmee, Fla.,
jail in August, where she spent time in jail for stalking former
astronaut Story Musgrave. She spent 10 months in prison and 14
months in mental institutions for the Letterman stalking
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, she was ruled incompetent to stand trial in the
Musgrave case by an Osceola County, Fla. judge.
</P>
<P>
   While incarcerated, she was to undergo psychiatric evaluation,
the Associated Press reported in a story last September.
</P>
<P>
   The Osceola County judge who sentenced her, the AP reported
then, wanted to send Ray to a mental hospital for five years. But
because the stalking charge was a misdemeanor, he could not do so.
</P>
<P>
   Her obsession with the star of CBS's ``Late Show with David
Letterman'' first made news in 1988 when she stole, then was found
driving, Letterman's Porsche through New York City. When she
couldn't come up with the $3 toll at the Lincoln Tunnel, she told
the attendant she was Letterman's wife, according to a ``Late
Show'' news Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said he had met Ray on numerous occasions and thought she
was ``fairly laid back and quiet, but you could tell she had some
severe problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While she was in our area, I thought she did fairly well,'' he
said. ``It was when she went back to Connecticut _ that's what got
her in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair also said from what he knew of Ray, the way she killed
herself didn't necessarily surprise him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a horrible thing to say, but this is kind of
Margaret Ray,'' he said. ``She wouldn't just go off and take pills
or something. This is kind of the way she would want to go out.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Paonia Police Chief Scott Leon called Monday's scene
and the entire situation ``emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You had the two people on the train who saw it and couldn't do
anything, Margaret knew in a few seconds the train was going to run
her over and you have all the officers who had to clean it up,''
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   He hoped that Letterman, who has been known to joke about Ray
during his late-night talk show, would treat this incident with
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Letterman will hear about it and probably breathe a sigh
of relief,'' Blair said. ``And I hope he understands she was a
human being with feelings too. Hopefully he won't make light of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Taylor writes for The Daily Sentinel, Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
