<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-WIRED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS BUYING WIRED DIGITAL INC. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lycos Inc. will pay $83 million in stock to acquire Wired
Digital Inc., one of the best-known brands in high technology.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, set to close by year's end, is the latest move in
Lycos' campaign to establish itself &UR;  &LR; as one of the Internet's most
powerful companies.
</P>
<P>
   Wired Digital employs 150 people and is based in San Francisco.
It was once owned by the founders of Wired, perhaps the most
influential print magazine covering computers and high technology.
Although it became the bible of young, affluent computer users,
Wired magazine was in constant financial turmoil. The print
publication was purchased earlier this year by Conde Nast
Publications Inc., publishers of Vanity Fair and GQ magazines. But
Conde Nast didn't want Wired's on-line properties, and they were
left behind as an independent, privately held firm.  &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By acquiring Wired Digital, Lycos will add a number of popular
sites _ including Wired News, the HotBot search engine and the
satirical Web magazine Suck _ to its sizable stable of Web
businesses. Lycos already runs a major Internet search service of
its own, and the Tripod and Angelfire Web page hosting services,
and the WhoWhere Internet directory &UR;  &LR; of addresses and phone
numbers. The company's goal is to establish itself as an Internet
``portal'' _ a major gateway to the Internet. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lycos president Bob Davis said Tuesday that with Wired Digital's
audience, the Lycos companies are now closing in on the Yahoo
search service, one of the world's most popular Internet portals.
``We're just single-digit percentage points behind the leader, and
gaining rapidly on them,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis estimated that after the Wired transaction is complete,
Lycos properties will reach about 41 percent of all Internet users
at least once a month. According to the research firm Media Metrix,
Yahoo reached 40.4 percent of home Internet users in August 1998,
and 46 percent of business Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   But Chris Charron, an analyst with Forrester Research Inc. in
Cambridge, Mass. thinks that Lycos still has a long way to go
before it can truly challenge Yahoo. Charron praised the Wired
Digital acquisition, but added, ``It takes more than a collection
of sites to be a portal.''
</P>
<P>
   Charron argues that companies like Yahoo have a unified brand
strategy. All of Yahoo's various on-line features are promoted
under the Yahoo brand, thus establishing the company's name in the
public mind. But Lycos runs its various Internet businesses as if
they were separate entities, thus doing little to enhance the value
of the Lycos brand.
</P>
<P>
   While Charron dislikes this independent approach, it suits Wired
Digital president Beth Vanderslice. She said that Davis' promise of
a hands-off approach was a key reason her firm agreed to the
acquisition. ``Certainly we had a variety of strategic
alternatives,'' Charron said. ``Lycos made the most sense because
we were confident we would be able to preserve our brand and our
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Wired magazine and its Web site were founded by Louis Rossetto
and Jane Metcalfe, who aimed to create a publishing and on-line
empire to cover the Internet. Rossetto will not be involved in the
operation of the Wired Web sites under Lycos, the Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Stock in Lycos, based in Waltham, Mass., closed down 1 13/16 at
30 1/8 on the Nasdaq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
