<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-NASA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN ARRIVES AT KENNEDY SPACE CENTER FOR FINAL PREPARATIONS BEFORE
LIFTOFF 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., _ The air was as thick with nostalgia as
with humidity and the sweet scent of palmetto Tuesday as John
Glenn, the 77-year-old Mercury astronaut turned U.S. senator,
jetted into the balmy realm of NASA's Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   Late this month, Glenn, who in 1962 became the first American to
orbit the Earth, will be among an international crew of seven
astronauts as they blast off aboard the shuttle Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's nine-day science mission will serve as a belated
encore for Glenn. His solo, five-hour flight on Feb. 20, 1962,
aboard the Friendship 7 Mercury capsule gave the United States a
much-needed foothold in space when the whole notion of rocket
travel was a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   With eight months of mission training drawing to a close,
Discovery commander Curt Brown and his crew will spend the rest of
this week at Kennedy preparing for their Oct. 29 liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   They will train to make the kind of hasty escape from their
towering 20 story, coastal launching pad that would be required if
an explosion, fire or toxic chemical spill occurred while they
awaited lift off. They will also don their bulky pressure suits
early Friday and board Discovery flight deck as if it was launching
to rehearse the busy final hours of their countdown with the launch
control team.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise has been repeated here by 91 previous shuttle crews
over the past 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's presence, however, makes this one novel again.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese and Spanish journalists mingled with dozens of news
photographers and reporters from the Cable News Network and other
major U.S. news organizations to capture Glenn's arrival.
Typically, only a handful of reporters would traipse to Kennedy's
runway tarmac to record such an event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become more than a photo opportunity,'' said Bruce
Buckingham, one of the NASA public affairs staff tasked with making
the arrangements. ``It's become a news event.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking trim, tan and relaxed, Glenn and his colleagues climbed
from five sleek NASA T-38 training jets dispatched from Houston's
Ellington Field. Their departure from Houston's Johnson Space
Center, where they have trained for their flight, was delayed 4 {
hours by severe weather in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very happy to be down here in Florida,'' Brown said.
``The practice countdown always marks a big milestone in our
training.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was asked how he felt and replied, ``great, great,'' and
gave a thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's lift off promises to rival any NASA spaceflight for
public attention, certainly Glenn's Mercury flight.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency has received 2,500 requests for news media
credentials, more than four times the number who attended Glenn's
Mercury mission.
</P>
<P>
   If all attend later this month, the total will surpass those who
assembled to cover the Sept. 29, 1988, launching of Discovery on
the first U.S. human spaceflight in the wake of the 1986 Challenger
accident.
</P>
<P>
   It would also approach the number who attended the launching of
the Apollo 11 moon landing mission in July 1969 and the first space
shuttle launching in April 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Experts here estimate that Glenn's lift off will draw 250,000 to
300,000 tourists to the Cape Canaveral, Fla., area, twice the
normal crowd who line the beaches and highways of Central Florida
for a shuttle launch.
</P>
<P>
   The closest hotel rooms and condominiums have been booked since
July.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of tourists who contribute a half billion dollars to
the local economy are expected to spend $10 million on Oct. 29
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This interests more than just the elderly,'' said Rob Varley,
executive director of the Florida Space Coast office of tourism in
Cape Canaveral. ``The nostalgia thing has a lot to do with it. But
I also think it's the idea that someone close to 80 years old can
go into space. This fascinates people who think that by the year
2010 or 2020 we might actually have space tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's mission is multifaceted. But the opportunity to
participate in experiments that might help researchers compare the
physical effects of spaceflight to the bodily changes that
accompany aging prompted Glenn to mount a campaign to fly again.
</P>
<P>
   Those experiments will examine changes in the bones and muscles
of the shuttle astronauts as well as their sleeping patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's primary payload is a reusable satellite called
Spartan that will be deployed and retrieved by the shuttle
astronauts. Equipped with telescopes and cameras, Spartan will
collect images of the sun's outer atmosphere during two days of
free flight. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
