<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WARNS FINANCIAL LEADERS `WE DON'T HAVE A MOMENT TO WASTE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
and CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton called on financial leaders from
around the globe Tuesday to find new ways to tame the cycles of
boom and bust that are shaking economies from Asia to Latin
America, warning: ``We don't have a moment to waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, addressing a group of finance ministers and central
bankers attending annual meetings of the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank, urged world leaders to take ``urgent
steps'' to restore confidence in the world economy and to avoid
such painful economic and currency crises in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The global economy simply cannot live with the kinds of vast
and systemic disruptions that have occurred over the past year,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sparked by the collapse of the real estate market in the Thai
capital of Bangkok 15 months ago, the world financial and currency
crisis first ravaged the economies of East Asia, then attacked
Russia and is now hitting Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``When nations half a world apart face the same crisis at the
same time, it is time for decisive action,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But the leader of the world's largest economy also cautioned
against grasping at solutions merely to do something.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not embrace false cures that will backfire and lead in
the end to less liquidity and diminished confidence when we need
more of both,'' Clinton said. But he added: ``We must _ we must _
keep working until we find the right answers.''
</P>
<P>
   While short on specifics, Clinton's speech was the latest in a
series of public statements designed to assure nervous investors
that the United States is actively engaged in trying to stem the
economic contagion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crisis poses a challenge not to any one nation but to
every nation,'' Clinton said. ``None of us _ none of us _ will be
unaffected if we fail to act.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's address followed a more substantive speech last Friday
in which he called for the creation of new, emergency lines of
credit for countries caught up in the investor panic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged the most important thing U.S. officials can
do is ``keep our economy growing and open to other's products and
services.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials are mulling the possibility of holding a
summit of leaders from the Group of Seven industrialized nations to
discuss the economic crisis. The prospect of such a meeting was
advanced by British Prime Minister Tony Blair, a senior
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had said he would agree to a summit if the session could
be ``useful.'' Before such a meeting was called, there would almost
certainly have to be an agreement on Clinton's proposal or some
other high-profile plan.
</P>
<P>
   The danger in such a meeting is that it would raise
expectations, including in the market, and if a meeting did not
result in a definitive program there could be bad reaction. ``I'm
sure this will be batted back and forth,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not raise the possibility of a G-7 summit in his
speech Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, reiterate his call for Congress to provide
nearly $18 billion in new funding for the IMF, the Washington-based
financial rescue fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already approved the higher funding request, but
conservative opponents in the House _ led by Majority Leader Dick
Armey, R-Irving, and House Whip Tom DeLay, R-Sugar Land _ approved
only $3.4 billion in funding.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators are now trying to hash out a deal.
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Tuesday ``there are some
indications now that that position may be softening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between now and Friday,'' Lockhart added, ``it's our hope that
we get to the point where they can send us a bill that has the full
funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, said he is hopeful an agreement can be
reached to provide the full funding.
</P>
<P>
   House lawmakers have agreed to disentangle IMF funding from an
even more contentious issue, the use of U.S. foreign aid money by
international organizations that perform abortions or promote
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Embroiled in this domestic dispute over IMF funding, the United
States _ and Clinton in particular _ did not assume a strong
leadership role in the fight to stop the financial contagion until
the last several weeks, when the crisis threatened to wreck the
economies of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, however, the economies of East Asia had been
struggling with recessions and even depressions for more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Clinton will travel to Malaysia for the annual
meeting of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum. Malaysia's
economy has been hard hit by the crisis, but its government has
exacerbated investors' concerns by arresting _ and allegedly
beating _ that country's leading proponent of economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   After Malaysia, Clinton will go on to visit Japan and South
Korea, two other economies hurt by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the contagion, trade between the United States and
the affected economies of East Asia has dropped 11 percent over the
last year, the U.S. Treasury Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, events in Asia, Russia and Latin America are having a
direct impact on the prosperity of America's farmers, workers and
businesses,'' Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said. ``The United
States has a very real interest in stemming the tide of global
economic turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas ranks fourth in the nation in terms of exports to Asia,
with that region accounting for 20 percent of the state's
merchandise exports last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury report did not specify whether the Lone Star
State's overall exports to the region have actually declined. But
the study did note that exports of chemicals _ one of the prime
drivers of the Houston economy _ dropped 40 percent in the first
quarter of 1998, compared with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Texas exports to South Korea, one of the state's leading Asian
trading partners, were off 31 percent in the first quarter, while
sales to Indonesia fell 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   California, the nation's leading exporter to Asia, experienced
an 11 percent drop in exports to the region in the first quarter,
with sales to Japan off 12 percent and exports to South Korea down
43 percent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
