<SLUG> BC-TXEXXON-KING-RANCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING RANCH SUES TO END EXXON'S EXCLUSIVE RIGHTS TO DRILL ON LAND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A longstanding relationship that has brought much wealth to the
famed 1,300-square-mile King Ranch in South Texas and Exxon is on
the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   King Ranch Minerals Inc., a King Ranch subsidiary that controls
mineral rights to some of the property, filed a state district
court lawsuit here Monday seeking to end Exxon's exclusive rights
to drill on the land.
</P>
<P>
   The suit accuses Exxon of violating state law and contractual
obligations by mingling natural gas and oil production from varying
depths in Kleberg and Willacy.
</P>
<P>
   Different people own the mineral rights at different depths, the
lawsuit said, and Exxon must separate this production for them to
receive their proper royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon spokesman Dave Gardner said it does not comment on pending
suits and hopes it can work out its differences with King Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon's corporate predecessor, Humble Oil &AMP; Refining Co., signed
a contract in 1933 giving it exclusive rights to drill for oil and
natural gas on the ranch's nearly one million acres. The area
included parts of Kleberg, Jim Wells, Kenedy, Nueces, Brooks,
Hidalgo, Willacy, Starr, Jim Hogg, Goliad and Bee counties in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Worden, vice president and general counsel for King Ranch,
said King Ranch Minerals owns about 23 percent of the mineral
rights on the ranch, started in 1853 and still the nation's largest
cow and calf operation.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the mineral rights is owned by individuals,
Worden said, but any change in the contract between King Ranch
Minerals and Exxon can change Exxon's exclusive rights to drill on
the rest of the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   King Ranch Minerals pays royalties to its 20 owners, and
royalties are paid to various people depending on the location and
depth of drilling, Worden said. He declined to name any owner.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon is primarily producing natural gas in areas owned by King
Ranch Minerals, Worden said.
</P>
<P>
   He said King Ranch Minerals and Exxon have tried for more than a
year to settle their disagreement, and the suit was filed because
of an approaching statute of limitations deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Oil and natural gas produced at King Ranch have brought a
``significant amount of money'' to the ranch and Exxon, Worden
said.
</P>
<P>
   King Ranch and Exxon co-developed the Kingwood subdivision
recently annexed by Houston, he said, but both have sold their
interests in it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
