<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER DOGS THE NATIONAL PASTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He was one of us, a Massachusetts kid who made it all
the way to the big leagues. He once held the Boston Garden tourney
record for concutive free throws by a high school basketball
player, but baseball was his game and Mark Belanger became the
finest fielding shortstop of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger, a Pittsfield native, died of lung cancer Tuesday at
the age of 54.
</P>
<P>
   If 1998 goes down as the Year Baseball Came Back and the Year of
the Home Run, then it also should be remembered as the year cancer
visited the National Pastime with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Charisse Strawberry, wife of Darryl Strawberry, threw out the
first ball before Tuesday night's ALCS opener between the Yankees
and Indians (``Darryl, our hearts are with you'' read the big board
in center). Four days ago, Darryl Strawberry had surgery to remove
a cancerous tumor in his colon. Strawberry's childhood friend, Eric
Davis, battled colon cancer last year and came back in 1998 with a
borderline MVP season.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week baseball has been hit with the death of
45-year-old former Royals reliever Dan Quisenberry (brain tumor),
the Strawberry diagnosis, Monday's news that Cal Ripken Sr. has
lung cancer, and Tuesday's sad news on Belanger.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Weaver was home in Florida Tuesday night, having dinner
with his wife when he took a call and got the news about Belanger
and Rip Sr. No one had to tell Earl that Belanger and Cal Sr. were
two of the worst chain smokers in baseball. Earl, who had a heart
attack last month, just quit the butts. Weaver used to joke about
exchanging 30,000 Raleigh coupons for a brass coffin. Nobody's
laughing now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry I'm not smoking now, but my wife is happy about
it,'' said Earl. ``Of course, with Mark it was different. He was
only 54. He could be my son. That's too young.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Singleton, Belanger's Baltimore teammate for several
seasons, who is working the ALCS as a commentator for Major League
Baseball International, said, ``Mark smoked too much. All the time.
Even in between innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger's nickname was ``Blade.'' He came to the majors in 1965
and eventually replaced Hall of Famer, Luis Aparicio, as the
Orioles everyday shortstop. He couldn't hit much, but alongise
Brooks Robinson he anchored the finest infield left side in
baseball history and appeared in four World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember this,'' said Weaver. ``There's be two men on base
and one out and somebody would hit a ball into the hole. We knew
the ball wasn't going through. Either Brooks or Mark would get it.
Doubleplay. So we're back in the dugout getting ready to hit and
another club would have one run in, and still be on the field with
only one out. That was nice for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver and Belanger were never close. The Blade was the son of
Pittsfield union family and he never forgot lessons his parents
taught him about the General Electric company. Belanger's union
activity didn't win him many friends in the front office, but after
he retired he enjoyed a second career as lieutenant to Players
Association czar Donald Fehr.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger's union fanaticism almost overshadowed his extraordinay
baseball skills. Yankee shortstoop Derek Jeter, the sensational
Yankee shortstop who is re-inventing the position along with Alex
Rodgiguez and Nomar Garciaparra, sat in the dugout before Tuesday
night's game and said he'd never seen Belanger play. Jeter knew
Belanger only as one of his union reps.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeter has more in common with the Blade than he knows.
Jeters uses a tiny fielder'mitt _ just as Belanger did. The Blade
would get mad if anyone put his hand inside his glove. He believed
it altered the mold made by his own hand. The little mitt won him
eight Gold Globes.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger was a lifetime .228 hitter, which keeps him out of the
Hall of Fame. Venerable Globe scribe, Clif Keane, described him on
these pages as a ``Coke and hot dog hitter.'' Belanger asked what
this meant and Clif told him, ``Because when you hit, fans are
comfortable going out for a Coke and a hot dog.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blade was an expert card-player, taking fistfulls of cash
from Oriole rookies in a floating low-stakes game called ``pluck.''
He was proud of his Western Massachusetts connection and once
dedicated a rare Fenway homer to Rep. Silvio Conte. Belanger owned
Nolan Ryan and Weaver always had him bat second against the
strikeout king.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good friend and a very good teammate,'' rememebered
Singleton. ``And he was as good a shortstop as I ever saw. Today's
shortstops, like Jeter, are more offensive. But I never saw Mark
make a bad throw to first. And his hands were so quick, it looked
like he never got a bad hop.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blade passed away Tuesday, much too young, another baseball
cancer victim of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
