A2790 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      10-06 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE MANEUVERS TO DEFLECT IMPEACHMENT MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House and Democratic leaders struggled
Tuesday to rally last-ditch support for President Clinton, an
effort aggravated by election-year fears among many House Democrats
that they will be attacked as apologists for the embattled
president.
</P>
<P>
   As the House prepares to vote Thursday on opening a full-scale
impeachment inquiry into Clinton's sex scandal, limiting Democratic
support for the Republican-sponsored proposal is crucial to
Clinton's survival plan of portraying the historic proceedings as
the product of a partisan vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   The intense effort to prevent widescale Democratic defections
played out behind the scenes as party leaders tried to craft an
alternative to the Republican impeachment plan that would satisfy
as many of the 206 House Democrats as possible.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican majority virtually united, the White House
Tuesday expressed hopelessness in trying to block the first
presidential impeachment inquiry since the Watergate hearings in
1974. ``There is a certain sense that the die is cast,'' said White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials tried to contain the political damage
by accusing GOP leaders of creating a national crisis for partisan
gain. ``Rather than being designed to be fair and somber and
befitting of the constitutional importance it takes,'' Lockhart
said, the GOP impeachment effort ``has been driven more by politics
_ maybe not politics, but partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   The House majority leader, Representative Dick Armey of Texas,
disputed the White House assertion and said he expected Republican
members to back the impeachment measure without pressure from GOP
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't create this problem,'' Armey said. ``We are appalled
by it. We are saddened by it ... . None of us want it. We are going
to move on it professionally and responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey added: ``The fact of the matter is, it is about
obstruction of justice. It is about lying to the American people.
It is about using all the instruments, and many of the people in
the White House ... to go out and tell a story that the president
himself knew to be untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some Democrats, who last week predicted more than 50
Democratic lawmakers would support a full impeachment probe,
expressed cautious confidence Tuesday that the number will decrease
by tomorrow. Their goal is to limit the number of defectors to 25
or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum is swinging so that it's coming down by the
hour,'' said Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts
Democrat who serves on the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan and other lawmakers said an unspecified number of uneasy
Democrats felt less inclined to break with party leaders after
watching the Republican-controlled Judiciary Committee pass the GOP
impeachment measure and defeat two Democratic alternatives on
Monday. All the votes were along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, Democrats in tight races who watched the debate on
the Judiciary Committee came away feeling better about the
Democratic alternative,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the effort to boost support for Clinton is likely to
turn on the Democratic alternative, which would be voted on after
the Republican measure passes Thursday. The alternative, which is
expected to be defeated, would instruct the House to send the
impeachment plan back to the Judiciary Committee with instructions
to change it.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Republican proposal, the Democratic plan is expected
to call for imposing a deadline on the inquiry and limiting its
scope to events stemming from Clinton's affair with former White
House intern Monica S. Lewinsky. Two variations of the plan were
rejected by the Judiciary Committee on Monday along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders, with one eye on helping and the other on
trying to recapture the House in next month's elections, were
meeting privately last night to try to develop their final
alternative plan. They also hoped to recruit some Republicans,
although that prospect was highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan sets no deadline and leaves open the
possibility that the inquiry could be expanded to such issues as
the Whitewater real estate venture, the White House travel office
firings, and campaign fund-raising abuses in the 1996 elections. If
the House passes the GOP proposal, the Judiciary Committee would
launch an investigation and open hearings after the Nov. 3
elections. Chairman Henry Hyde of Illinois has said he hopes the
inquiry would be completed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we always need to look at ways to generate Democratic
support for the inquiry,'' said Representative W. Asa Hutchinson,
an Arkansas Republican on the Judiciary Committee. ``But we voted
out a fair resolution that followed the Watergate model with broad
support and we need to stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the White House and Democratic leaders, the major challenge
is convincing some moderate Democrats they will not pay a hefty
political price for appearing to condone Clinton's misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat and senior
member of the Judiciary Committee, said some Democrats facing
election opponents fear attack ads accusing them of protecting
Clinton from a legitimate inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said many Democrats believe the impeachment process could
eventually backfire on the Republicans. ``They are riding a
tiger,'' he said, ``and after the election they have to figure out
how to get off.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans acknowledged the potential for trouble, even as
they prepared to vote to launch the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is dangerous political ground that both Democrats and
Republicans must tread,'' said Representative Charles F. Bass, a
New Hampshire Republican who is the GOP whip for New England.
``There is a general perception on the part of the electorate that
this is going on too long,'' he said, referring to an extended
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Bass and other House Republicans said GOP leaders have applied
no pressure for them to back the inquiry. But members of both
parties said there is more than enough pressure as the House vote
occurs less than a month before their elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Controversy is the enemy of the incumbent,'' said
Representative Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican.
``Everyone is uneasy about this. In the end, I only make enemies on
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Judiciary Committee's chief Republican
investigator, David P. Schippers, called a news conference to
defend his report on Monday that laid out 15 counts of possibly
impeachable offenses against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans have privately criticized Schippers for being
too soft on Clinton, and many Democrats have accused him of
inappropriately ``piling on'' the president by raising four
allegations that were not in independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played it straight down the middle,'' Schippers said. ``We
could have been a lot harsher if we wanted to be, if we wanted to
take the role of a prosecutor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
