<HEADLINE>
STOCKS MIXED IN ACTIVE TRADING; NASDAQ DOWN, DOW UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks were mixed Tuesday in a volatile session as
the technology-heavy Nasdaq declined for a second consecutive day.
Traders and analysts said investors remain nervous about a number
of outstanding issues threatening the global and domestic economy,
and are using brief rallies as an opportunity to sell shares.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks looked like they might be poised for a strong rally,
because many of the elements that previously might have triggered
waves of buying were evident early in the session: a strong
performance on foreign equity markets and better-than-expected
third-quarter earnings reports from Aluminum Company of America and
Motorola, two big, globally-oriented companies.
</P>
<P>
   Those factors did in fact propel prices higher in the early
hours; at one point the Dow Jones industrial average was up 154
points and the Nasdaq composite index was up 40 points.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dow managed to generate a small gain, broader indexes
registered declines, especially the Nasdaq. The Dow rose 16.74
points, or 0.22 percent, to 7,742.98. But the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell 3.97 points, or 0.4 percent, to 984.59. The
Nasdaq composite index declined 25.80, or 1.68 percent, to
1,510.89. The Russell 2000 index of smaller stocks dropped 4.25
points, or 1.26 percent, to 332.55, its ninth consecutive loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is nervous,'' said Alan Ackerman, an executive vice
president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at continuing fear of a world recession, and an
erosion of confidence that it can be staved off. Growth is slowing
in world markets, and needs to be stimulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares bore the brunt of the concern about a global
economic downturn and weakening earnings, as high-profile,
market-moving names like Cisco Systems, Microsoft and Intel were
battered again. ``The technology stocks are discounting the
possibility of a global recessionary environment in 1999,'' said
Michael Molnar, a managing director in sales and trading at Salomon
Smith Barney. ``The mind-set that people have is to sell any
strength in technology, and the most vulnerable stocks are the ones
with maximum global exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco fell 2[, to 46 3/16; Microsoft dropped 3 9/16, to 97|, and
Intel lost 15/16, to 79|.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, which released third-quarter earnings that were better
than expected after the market closed Monday, was an exception,
rising 3\, to 41 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa, the world's biggest aluminum producer, was the catalyst
behind the rise in the Dow Jones industrial average. Its shares
jumped 4 5/16, to 72{, after its earnings exceeded analysts'
expectations. The company said that cost-cutting had helped to
offset lower metals prices.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores reported better-than-expected sales gains for
September and said that it intends to open, remodel or relocate as
many as 426 stores next year. Shares of Wal-Mart gained 2\, to 59{.
</P>
<P>
   Some other big retailers also rallied. Dayton Hudson rose 1
7/16, to 35 13/16, and Sears, Roebuck gained 1 3/16, to 43}.
</P>
<P>
   Financial services stocks, however, continued to be beat up.
J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. fell ~, to 79. Citicorp lost 1, to 85 and Merrill
Lynch lost 1, to 41 15/16. ``The financial sector is usually a
market leader at both tops and bottoms,'' said Gail Dudack, chief
investment strategist at UBS Securities. ``I haven't seen them turn
yet, and that makes me nervous. I will need to see the whole
financial sector sort of stabilize before I change my view that we
are out of a bear market.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
