<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES SAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices ended lower Tuesday for the first time in
six trading sessions, reflecting some gains in battered overseas
stock markets that diminished demand for Treasury securities as a
safe haven investment. The 30-year bond fell 8/32, to a price of
112 7/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction
from the price, rose to 4.73 percent from its 12-year low of 4.72
percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After the enormous gains over the last few weeks in the bond
market as investors sought a safe-haven from tumbling stocks,
analysts said it was understandable to see a pullback.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pugliese, senior vice president and director of fixed
income at the J.W. Genesis Financial Corp. in Boca Raton, Fla.,
said bond prices have risen so quickly and yields fallen so much
that the market is now vulnerable to sudden sell-offs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors realize that we are at very lofty prices levels,''
he said. ``With the government long bond yielding in the
neighborhood of 4.70 percent, the market is susceptible to any kind
of negative news.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
