<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES FACE A BRAVES TEAM AT THE TOP OF THEIR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Same old Atlanta Braves. They don't get older and
weaker. They just get better.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the National League Championship Series with the
San Diego Padres, you heard this a lot. Facing 17-game winner John
Smoltz in his home park is asking a lot of the NL West champions.
Knowing that 20-game winner Tom Glavine will follow Smoltz is just
plain cruel. And don't even mention Greg Maddux and Denny Neagle,
who will pitch in San Diego over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are in the NLCS for the seventh straight time since
1991 (there were no playoffs in 1994 because of the player's
strike). They are healthy and have depth and experience on the
pitching staff. There has been as much praise for rookie reliever
Kerry Ligtenberg as for veteran Dennis Martinez. The offense is
clicking. You don't win 106 games with a club that has a glaring
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   After losing last year to the eventual champion Florida Marlins,
the Braves are eager to get back to the World Series, especially
after the embarrassment of being beaten by a wild card team and one
that had been in the league only since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But San Diego is a mirror of the Braves in many areas. With
pitcher Kevin Brown leading the way, they are a legitimate threat
to reach the World Series for the first time since 1984. If the
Braves aren't worried, they should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, Florida was a conglomeration of high-priced talent
gathered from all the clubs in baseball,'' said Braves general
manager John Schuerholz. ``They did a good job in deciding how they
would put the club together. And they beat us.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we're rock solid. The key is our pitching. It's
always there. In addition to the starters, young guys came through
for us in the bullpen and did a good job. We had more balance. The
new guys, Andres Galarraga and Walt Weiss, contributed mightly.
Weiss solidified the infield early and made the All-Star team.
Andruw Jones emerged as the finest center fielder in baseball. And
our defense led the National League for the first time in 20
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres and Braves have not met since mid-August, when
Atlanta won three of four to take the season series, 5-4. With a
huge lead in the NL East, the Braves then went into cruise control.
San Diego, meanwhile, had to fight off a September bid by San
Francisco before winning the division by nine games. The Padres
lost eight of their final 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   But in the division series, the Padres played mistake-free
baseball and beat Randy Johnson twice, ousting the Central champion
Astros in four games. Brown logged two victories, the second on
three days' rest. He is scheduled to work Game 2 of the NLCS, after
Andy Ashby (17-9, 3.34) opens the series Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the main thing is to stay away from a big inning,''
said Ashby. ``I looked back to my game against Houston, where a
double and a walk helped create two runs. I'm saying to myself, `Go
out and get ahead and try to minimize your mistakes.' With our
offense, if you give them a chance, they can bust out anytime. The
time I get into trouble is when I try to be too fine instead of
aggressive and letting the ball move the way it was earlier in the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have manager Bobby Cox singing their praises, and
that is rare. He likes the fact that his lineup is balanced and he
has his best bullpen in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some great additions,'' said Cox. ``We were able to
get Andres Galarraga to play first. Nothing against Fred McGriff,
who got us to many playoffs, but it changed our lineup because he
is righthanded and he's had a super year here. Walt Weiss had a
great first half until he got hurt. I think one of the factors
overlooked is Ozzie Guillen being able to pick up for Walt when he
couldn't play. Walt is better now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg may not be well known, but he had 30 saves and filled
the void left by the demise of Mark Wohlers, who is not even on the
playoff roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they've all heard of Trevor Hoffman and the job he's
done for San Diego,'' said Cox. ``But these guys can get the job
done. Ligtenberg was playing in an outlaw league in Minnesota. John
Rocker never did shoot the lights out in our organization, but he
went to the fall league in 1997, went through the draft, and now he
is a dominating lefthanded pitcher. Don't forget Dennis Martinez.
He's 43 years old and can still come in and get ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bullpen that is very functional, very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz takes nothing for granted against the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of veteran experience,'' said Smoltz. ``People
talk about pressure, but it is only being in a situation you have
not seen before. A lot of us have been in these situations before,
which is why people think we have the edge. We still have to go out
and execute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
