<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-385&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS FRET AS BRAZIL SOFT-PEDALS NEED FOR AUSTERITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ In gatherings with financial officials
and international investors in Washington, Brazilian officials have
been pledging drastic, if unspecified, measures to cut spending by
$25 billion over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Brazil, the message has been far softer. And
investors are beginning to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Here, officials shun the word ``package'' _ with its whiff of
sacrifices that would drastically worsen people's lives _ to
describe the set of government spending cuts that will be needed to
put Brazil's fiscal house in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me there will be no shocks or surprises,'' President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso told voters last week in his final
televised address before appearing to squeak through to re-election
Sunday. ``With me, there'll be no package.''
</P>
<P>
   The message was repeated by presidential spokesman Sergio Amaral
on Monday night. ``I reiterate that there will be no economic
package, for the simple reason that there are no measures that
taken together would amount to a package, and because the president
does not consider that the way to conduct economic policy,'' Amaral
said.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman cited a speech the president made two weeks ago,
outlining fiscal belt-tightening measures, a crackdown on tax
evasion and possible tax increases. That, he said, made ``very
clear what the government will do.'' And government officials said
Tuesday that broad measures would be made over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wall Street and at the International Monetary Fund
meeting in Washington on Tuesday, where the consensus spread that
Brazil's economy was too important to be allowed to collapse,
expectations ran the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny that people there don't want to use the term
`package,' '' James Barrineau, a Latin American equity strategist
at Salomon Smith Barney, said. ``That's exactly the word they're
wanting to hear in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, everybody has the sense that it has to be a big and
credible package, without a lot of wiggle room for the states to
siphon off money from the federal government,'' Barrineau said.
``People are waiting to see what is Brazil's goal for 1999, how
will it get there, how can it assure us that it's not going to
backslide, and how does that help the sustainability of the
economic plan.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said that the poor performance of the Brazilian market, which
fell 4.47 percent Monday, reflected the ``less than rousing
mandate'' won by Cardoso and the unexpectedly strong showing of the
leftist Workers Party in senatorial and gubernatorial races.
</P>
<P>
   With 70 percent of the returns counted by Tuesday afternoon,
Cardoso had won 52.5 percent of the vote, while his rival, Luiz
Inacio Lula da Silva of the Workers Party, had 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, markets rose 3.48 percent on the decision by Spain's
central bank to cut interest rates by half a percentage point,
which investors took as a sign that Europe would begin taking steps
to alleviate the crisis threatening Brazil, the world's
ninth-largest economy. By late afternoon, market sources said, $120
million in foreign reserves had left Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is the linchpin of the world financial system right
now, and the effort to put together credibility for the Brazilian
bailout is central to the world financial system now,'' said one
Latin American investment strategist, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``No matter what happens, Brazil cannot go down.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference between domestic and international messages is
not new. Buffeted by the Asian crisis last November, the Brazilian
government announced some 51 spending cuts and new fees to raise
$15 billion. It went ahead with the measures that raised cash but
quietly dropped more politically sensitive efforts to cut spending
including, for example, laying off tens of thousands of civil
servants.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandre Barros, publisher of a newsletter based in Brasilia,
Early Warning, said investors were willing to give Brazil some time
to work out its plan of action, but not much. Brasilia is rife with
rumors of a U.S.-led line of credit being extended to Brazil,
perhaps as a backup to an IMF package.
</P>
<P>
   But Barros said that investor patience could turn to panic in
less than two weeks. ``People expect the fund and Brazil to at
least come to terms about what they're going to do, and they're
frustrated that nothing solid has come out of the meetings so
far,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
