<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-BIAS-EMAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIST E-MAIL IS SENT TO 13 AT BOSTON COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It took minutes for a racist e-mail message to land in
the mailboxes of 13 minority students at Boston College last
Thursday. It took a few hours more before the whole campus knew
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by phone calls and fliers that asked ``Will U stand for
this?'' more than 1,000 students overflowed an auditorium that
night to condemn the act and scrutinize the e-mail, sent to leaders
of minority organizations on campus. Of the college's nearly 9,000
undergraduates, about 1,600 are members of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were screaming, yelling, crying,'' said Annelice
Morales, who received the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The message said ``BC is for white men'' and included slurs
against people who were Asian, black, Hispanic and gay. ``You all
need to go back where you came from,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The university police are investigating whether someone may have
used another Boston College student's e-mail account to send the
message. The sender, if a student, could face expulsion or
suspension, Reid Oslin, a Boston College spokesman, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Student leaders were encouraged by the strong turnout for the
meeting, which included many white students. But the meeting also
revealed what Ms. Morales called a hidden tension on campus. Six
racist, sexist or anti-gay graffiti have been reported in the
dormitories since the beginning of classes this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Boston College as a whole was aware of how often
these things happen,'' said Ms. Morales, a sophomore. ``I know in
two or three months it's going to be forgotten and things will be
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston College is the latest of several colleges and
universities to see hateful e-mail sent on their systems in recent
months, including the University of Nebraska at Lincoln and the
University of North Carolina. At the University of Maine at Orono,
a student was ordered to do community service and had his computer
account suspended after he posted a threatening message last year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Congress passed a bill that would require colleges
and universities to expand their reporting of hate crimes to
include biases based on sex or disability. Sen. Robert Torricelli,
D-N.J., who sponsored the original bill, also wanted to require the
reporting of harassment and vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately those were stripped out of the bill during
conference,'' said Joy Howell, a spokeswoman for Torricelli. ``We
still think it's a problem that needs to be addressed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
