u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      10-06 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, DEMOCRATS SCRAMBLE TO LIMIT DEFECTIONS DURING IMPEACHMENT
INQUIRY VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
and JOHN DRAKE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House stepped up criticism Tuesday of the
Republican drive to begin an impeachment inquiry against President
Clinton as Democrats scrambled to limit defections when the issue
comes to a vote Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders who control the House said Tuesday that
debate would be limited to one hour on a GOP resolution to begin
only the third presidential impeachment investigation in the
nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Republicans turned down a Democratic
request to offer an alternative resolution that would set a
deadline for finishing the inquiry and limit it to the president's
effort to cover-up his affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have the right resolution,'' said House Republican
leader Dick Armey of Irving. ``I think it is just time to move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution calling for an open-ended impeachment
investigation cleared the Republican-controlled House Judiciary
Committee late Monday with all 21 GOP members supporting the
proposal and all 16 Democrats in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   By identical party-line votes, the committee rejected two
Democratic proposals _ each calling for an investigation but with
limits on the scope and duration.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart accused the
Republican leadership Tuesday of using the impeachment issue ``to
embarrass the president'' and to win votes in the Nov. 3
congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does appear after watching this for the last month that the
(GOP) leadership is pursuing a strategy for electoral advantage,''
Lockhart said. ``There is a certain sense that the die is cast on
this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision by House Republican leaders to limit debate and not
allow a Democratic alternative to be discussed drew criticism, even
from some conservative Democrats who plan to vote for an unlimited
investigation that could lead to Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hour of debate seems a little peculiar to me on something
as important as the possible impeachment of the president of the
United States,'' said Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Stamford. ``There
are a lot of viewpoints that need to be heard on this, and I'm not
sure it can be done in one hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marty Meehan, D-Mass., complained that Armey ``wants to
make it appear there is no alternative'' to the GOP resolution and
predicted no Republicans would vote against an impeachment inquiry.
``They see the House as a grand jury and they're ready to indict
and send it over to the Senate for a trial,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Houston, said an effort will be made to
limit the Judiciary Committee's ability to expand its impeachment
investigation beyond the Lewinsky affair. ``This is what we should
be addressing and not every gripe the Republican leadership may
have had with the Clinton administration in the last six years,''
Bentsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
House membership is not near unity on the issue of an impeachment
investigation. Liberals from safe seats generally oppose any type
of inquiry, moderates see the need for a limited inquiry and
conservatives _ such as Stenholm, Jim Turner of Crockett and Ralph
Hall of Rockwall _ and others facing tough re-election battles are
ready to side with the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and White House allies were
calling Democrats Tuesday trying to bolster support for the
president. But Democratic House members said they were being told
by Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri there would be no
arm-twisting.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats are hoping to keep defections to a minimum to
keep Republicans from putting a bipartisan spin on their open-ended
investigation, preliminary vote counts Tuesday indicated an uphill
battle. Republicans counted a minimum of 21 of the 206 House
Democrats ready to vote for the Republican resolution. Democratic
tallies put the number of defectors at ``around 50, down from about
120,'' one source said.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, the liberal advocacy group the People
for the American Way unveiled a television advertisement aimed at
pressuring Congress to put the sex scandal aside and ``move on'' to
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Showing photos of Republican House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
television evangelist Pat Robertson and independent counsel Kenneth
Starr, the 30-second advertisement says: ``Some in Washington are
listening to the religious right _ not the people. It's time to get
back to what really counts: first-rate schools, Medicare and Social
Security.''
</P>
<P>
   The group said the $1 million advertising campaign, which began
airing Tuesday on CNN and in eight U.S. urban markets, but not in
Texas, was designed ``to give voice to the millions of Americans
who have told pollsters that they are sick of the scandals and want
to see Washington dealing with real issues.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the National Republican Congressional
Committee announced its own advertising campaign, which defends the
GOP-controlled House and Senate, and took a swipe at the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though the public may not have read about it in newspapers, or
heard about it on the TV news, the Republican majority has been
working overtime on behalf of America's working families,'' said
Rep. John Linder, the NRCC chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are reaching out to find solutions to the problems
families face, like a $500-per-child tax credit ... even a budget
surplus that's helping save Social Security,'' says one of the ads
that began airing in 30 states, including some areas of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers for Paula Jones, whose sexual harassment suit
against Clinton provided the setting for the president's initial
cover-up efforts, were considering his latest settlement offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has rejected the offer,'' said John Whitehead of the
conservative Rutherford Institute, who serves as one of Jones'
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead dismissed a media report that Jones had rejected a
$700,000 offer from White House attorneys and said negotiations
were continuing. Jones offered to drop her appeals several weeks
ago for $1 million. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
