<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-VICTORIOUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER BEATING PACKERS, VIKINGS TALK SUPER BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ While the Green Bay Packers spent Tuesday
morning recovering from the hangover of one of the worst losses in
the history of their franchise, the Minnesota Vikings were looking
ahead. They are not content with beating the Packers. They will not
be happy with winning the National Football Conference Central
crown.
</P>
<P>
   They want it all, and some on the team are not shy about
mentioning the ``S'' word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, this is a Super Bowl team,'' said the team's new owner,
Red McCombs, in a quiet moment away from hugging Vikings players
and coaches after Monday night's 37-24 victory over Green Bay.
``Right now, you'd have to say there is not a better team in the
NFC. We played a great team, and it was total domination. We took
complete control of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota hammered the top-ranked defense in football for 442
yards passing, the most ever given up by the Packers. Quarterback
Randall Cunningham, who several years ago was out of football and
working in a quarry cutting granite, torched one of the best
secondaries in football with four touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   All those bombs were not just an impromptu game of catch between
Cunningham and the rookie wide receiver Randy Moss, who had 5
catches for 190 yards and 2 touchdowns. They were a crucial part of
Minnesota's game plan.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive coordinator, Brian Billick, is one of the best in
the business. And he told Cunningham, who has 10 touchdowns and no
interceptions, that if he ever noticed the Packers using single
coverage on Moss, to throw the ball deep and let Moss leap for it.
Incredibly, Green Bay used man-to-man coverage a lot on the
6-foot-4-inch Moss. When the Packers did, Cunningham spotted it
immediately and threw the ball up for grabs. Moss would come down
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Billick believes that if you throw 10 deep balls to Moss, he
will catch 9 if he is working against single coverage and catch 7
if he is double-teamed. To Billick, Moss is Michael Jordan and
Cunningham is a point guard who lobs an alley-oop for the dunk.
Most of the time, Jordan will make that shot.
</P>
<P>
   Moss had a lot of big catches against Green Bay: 52 yards, 41
yards, 46 yards and 44 yards. A 75-yard catch for a touchdown was
negated by a holding penalty and another long pass to Moss was
dropped. That was his only mistake of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Were the Vikings surprised that Moss, perhaps the best athlete
on the field, got so much single coverage? ``Not really,'' Cris
Carter said. ``We have three Pro Bowl receivers, which means to
really stop us you need three good cornerbacks. Most teams barely
have two. So I guess they figured that Randy was the weak link. I
guess they were wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Vikings coach Dennis Green had another explanation. ``The
Packers use a lot of man-to-man, and teams can't change their style
in a matter of days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What is also interesting about the Vikings is their brash
attitude as players who have had a chip on their shoulder all
season. In the locker room after the game, they chastised members
of the Minnesota news media for picking the Packers to win.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for a player to say ``I told you so'' after a
big victory when some members of the news media picked them to
lose. But the Vikings gloated a little extra. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay is not ready to concede the division title _ or a
return trip to the Super Bowl _ just yet. The Packers are already
looking to the rematch at Minnesota on Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vikings won this one fair and square,'' Green Bay coach
Mike Holmgren said. ``But, like I said, we have another crack at
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
