<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSOVIC RESISTS HOLBROOKE'S EFFORTS TO EXTRACT CONCESSIONS  (JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The American envoy Richard Holbrooke has
so far failed to extract concessions on a pullback of troops or
return of refugees in Kosovo during talks with President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia, diplomats said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic appeared to be resisting in the face of demands from
Washington that he comply with a U.N. Security Council resolution,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav leader maintained, the diplomats said, that the
Yugoslav Army and Serbian police forces are back at their bases in
Kosovo, the southernmost province of Serbia, where a conflict
between ethnic Albanian separatists and Milosevic's forces has been
under way for six months.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time there were signs that the nature of Holbrooke's
mission had changed from giving Milosovic a stern message that he
must comply with the resolution to starting a round of negotiations
of the kind that helped bring an end to the ethnic conflict in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night American officials said it was possible that
Holbrooke might stay in Belgrade Wednesday, lengthening his visit
beyond the original timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said Monday that he had not set a precise deadline for
Milosevic's compliance.
</P>
<P>
   The measures in the Security Council resolution, which
Washington says Milosevic has failed to meet, center on a pullback
of Serbian forces, encouragement to 250,000 refugees to return to
their homes and the start of serious political talks on the future
status of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic appeared to be playing for time and calculating that
the longer the sessions with Holbrooke go on, the more difficult it
will be for NATO to intervene, Western diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many possibilities of delay _ Milosevic can say
I'm pulling back, I'm discussing _ and that makes it more difficult
for NATO,'' a Western diplomat said. ``My guess is that Milosevic
will buy time.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also using a threatened NATO attack to consolidate
support among Serbs. The state-controlled Serbian television said
Tuesday night that in contrast to the ``aggression'' from the West,
Milosevic was in favor of a political solution.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating Washington's hard line with Milosevic is
the valuable support he won from Russia, a traditional ally of
Serbia, which makes up the dominant portion of Yugoslavia. Moscow
announced Tuesday that it would veto any Security Council
resolution approving air strikes against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Western diplomats said Tuesday, Holbrooke's diplomatic
task is becoming less to do with what is going on in Kosovo than
the credibility of NATO's military threats and its willingness to
carry them out after strong pronouncements. Washington also has to
assess if it wants to go ahead and punish Milosevic with air
strikes in the face of Russian opposition, the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke returned to Belgrade Tuesday night after a quick visit
to Pristina, the capital of Kosovo. There he met with ethnic
Albanian political leaders and members of the Kosovo Diplomatic
Observer Mission, who include American, European Union and Russian
military experts.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said he had heard nothing good from the experts, even
though the mission's daily written reports over the last five days
have given details of Serbian withdrawals and a sharp reduction in
attacks on ethnic Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Yugoslav military is far less visible in Kosovo
than it was a week ago, NATO military officers say it is in a
position to unleash tanks and artillery at short notice. In his
talks with Milosevic, Holbrooke is trying to get him to pull more
troops out of Kosovo and to have those troops that remain in Kosovo
more closely monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Also under discussion is a political plan for Kosovo, drafted by
the State Department with input from the Serbs and the ethnic
Albanians, that calls for broad autonomy for the province.
Milosevic scrapped that autonomy in 1989 and has since kept the
ethnic Albanian population, which outnumbers Serbs nine to one,
under the authoritarian rule of the Serb police. Ethnic Albanian
guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army are fighting to make
Kosovo independent.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. high commissioner for refugees said Tuesday that an
estimated 50,000 of more than 250,000 ethnic Albanian refugees had
returned home in the week since the fighting quieted.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the agency in Pristina, Fernando del Mundo,
stressed that there were still tens of thousands of ethnic Albanian
refugees camped outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   These people whose homes had been burned by Serb forces during
the tank and artillery offensive ordered by Milosevic to quell
separatist guerrillas were still too scared to return their
villages because of the Serb police, Del Mundo said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIRCLE-HAMLET-THEATER     10-06 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRCLE-HAMLET-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CIRCLE HAMLET': TO BE, OR WHATEVER, IN A SHAKESPEAREAN
FRACAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By D.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The aim of the new theater company Public Domain in
its first production, ``The Circle Hamlet,'' is to sharply focus
the attention of the actors, and thus of the audience, on the words
of the play, a slightly trimmed version of Shakespeare's
``Hamlet,'' with occasional variations of familiar lines and
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   One device it uses is seating the audience in a single row
around and only a few inches from a large rectangular stage raised
only inches above the floor. Taking viewers that close to the
action _ in effect putting them onstage _ certainly concentrates
attention. But does it focus the mind on the play?
</P>
<P>
   It is notorious that the people at greatest risk of losing sight
of the whole play during a performance are members of the cast.
There are times during this performance when for the audience the
play simply disappears among the details.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it is lost in manipulations of the text by Derek Lucci,
one of the two directors, who also takes the title role. Most
annoying is his assignment of the last lines to Hamlet's friend
Horatio rather than to Fortinbras, the claimant to the Danish
throne. This effectively obliterates the political framework of the
play.
</P>
<P>
   In this conception, ``Hamlet'' is very much a man's story. M.J.
Karmi's Gertrude has sufficient strength of personality to be a
force in the action, but in all the frantic tussle called for by
the directors she is all but shoved into the wings. Jenni Blong
does not project the emotional power needed to make Ophelia a
tragic figure, and none of the characters around her demonstrate
much affection for her: not her father, not her brother and
certainly not Hamlet; when he says after her death, ``I loved
her,'' no one watching will be naive enough to believe him.
</P>
<P>
   Lucci's Hamlet is a whirlwind. There is not a moment's
introspection in him. In his mouth ``To be, or not to be'' could be
a joke in a ``Seinfeld'' episode. As he dashes around the stage
threatening the king, terrifying his mother, taunting courtiers and
bullying Polonius, he seems to spin other characters around him in
a funnel cloud. On the other hand, Louis Vuolo as the ghost is a
real player _ at last. Although some characters cannot see him, he
is not the shadow on the parapet of most productions; he is often
the engine of the relentless movement of the play and a threatening
presence to the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Next to this Hamlet, King Claudius (Joe Muzikar) looks quite
dignified. You don't like what he has done, but you doubt it is
reason enough for regicide. Muzikar has picked up some of the
brooding indecision Lucci shed from Hamlet, so his king is a bit
puzzling, but very interesting. And Christopher George as Laertes
is a worthy foe for Lucci's Hamlet; he is out to get him from the
beginning, and when the two are dying he seems deeply satisfied to
know he is not going alone.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that while this company emphasizes the text,
10 of the 11 actors betray no mastery of the cadence or meters of
Shakespeare's verse. That failure is pointed up by the 11th person,
who is both Polonius and the gravedigger, David Saire. He creates
two warm, delightful characters. Saire, who was trained in British
theater and had a London stage career, possesses a repertory of
long-proven theatrical gestures and poses that grab audiences _
something the others in this cast lack _ but much of his
distinctive presence is shaped by his knowledge of how to speak
Shakespeare's lines. It makes a lot of difference.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE CIRCLE HAMLET'
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the play by William Shakespeare; directed by Derek
Lucci and John Edwards. Production stage manager and properties,
Michael Madigan; production manager, Quinn K. Pawlan. Presented by
Public Domain, Jennifer Gilkie, managing director; Derek Lucci,
artistic director. At IS 70, 333 W. 17th St., Chelsea, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Derek Lucci (Hamlet), Tom Huston (Horatio), Joe Muzikar
(Claudius), Christopher George (Laertes), David Saire
(Polonius/gravedigger), M.J. Karmi (Gertrude), Jenni Blong
(Ophelia) and Louis Vuolo (Ghost).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
