<HEADLINE>
LIBERAL AND GOP GROUPS LAUNCH ADS FOCUSING ON ISSUES, NOT SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican Party organizations and a liberal
advocacy group Tuesday unveiled television advertising campaigns
that seek to energize voters by emphasizing issues and not the
White House scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The National Republican Congressional Committee and the
Republican National Committee began broadcasting a 30-second
advertisement in about 40 congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   The spot is intended to counter assertions by Democrats that
Republicans in Congress have not accomplished much. In the
commercial, the narrator says over shots of a family at breakfast
that ``Republicans are reaching out to find solutions to the
problems families face.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the new advertisement, the committee Tuesday
began broadcasting 15 commercials specific to House districts.
Those advertisements either raise questions about Democratic
opponents or discuss issues like family values.
</P>
<P>
   Another nationwide campaign was opened Tuesday by People for the
American Way, a liberal group. Its advertisement features Carole
Shields, the group's president.
</P>
<P>
   As her 4-year-old grandson, Donny, sits in her lap, Ms. Shields
says: ``Let's move on. That's what the American people are saying
loud and clear. But some in Washington are listening to the
religious right, not the people.'' Small photographs appear on the
screen of House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Christian Coalition founder
Pat Robertson and Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   While both groups' 30-second commercials are intended to
embolden voters on opposite parts of the political spectrum, they
are similar in reflecting a sense in both parties that President
Clinton's troubles may not be enough in themselves to motivate
people to vote.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Republican Congressional Committee, officials
said their polling had shown that voters had grown weary of hearing
about the White House scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to turn on your TV these days without seeing
something about the president,'' said Todd Harris, a spokesman for
the congressional committee. ``We didn't need to use our national
advertising campaign to pile on top of that.''
</P>
<P>
   While voters may not want to hear more about the scandal, Harris
said, ``it doesn't mean they want it swept under the rug.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder, R-Ga., chairman of the Republican
congressional committee, acknowledged the risk of a backlash
against Republicans. ``If we came out as a national campaign, and
just came out against the president,'' Linder said, ``I think it
would be viewed as overreaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials said the budget for the campaign begun
Tuesday was about $7 million and was part of what Republicans said
was an overall $25 million advertising drive to help House
candidates. A month ago, Linder said the goal for the campaign was
$37 million. Tuesday, party officials insisted that they did not
need to spend as much as initially planned but did not explain why.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Sallick, a spokesman for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, said, ``The NRCC is perpetually inflating their
electoral prospects _ and now they have to admit they've been
inflating their issue-ad budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Republican committee's overall advertising budget
dwarfs the amount Sallick's committee is expected to spend on
advertising this year, which is roughly $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Taking issue with the message in the Republican commercials,
Sallick asserted, ``This has been a do-nothing Congress that had
failed to act on health reform and failed to improve public
education and failed to shore up Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   When People for the American Way disclosed its advertising plans
last week, it drew attacks from Democratic officials who feared
that the committee was competing within the party for tight
advertising money. But the group went ahead with its advertising
plans, although officials there indicated that it might not have
been as ambitious as initially planned. The budget for the first
week is nearly $1 million, according to the group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
