<HEADER>
A2823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UTVOLS-COX     10-06 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UTVOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols' starting lineup sprinkled with players from Georgia
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE _ Cosey Coleman remembers his first meeting with
Rodney Garner, the man who would convince him to sign with
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, a Parade All-American from Atlanta's Southwest DeKalb
High, told every recruiter who walked in his door (and there were a
lot of them) that he wanted to play defensive tackle in college.
</P>
<P>
   Garner did something recruiters rarely do: He told the prospect
he was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Garner looked Coleman in the eye and told the 6-foot-5,
315-pounder that his professional football future was as an
offensive linemen. ``A good defensive tackle in the NFL makes
$200,000 per year,'' Garner told him. ``A good offensive left
tackle makes $2 million a year. Which would you rather be?''
</P>
<P>
   Although Garner underestimated the earning power of starting
defensive tackles (their average salary in the NFL is about $1
million a year), Coleman saw the light. And after a strong
flirtation with North Carolina, Coleman decided he would rather be
at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with mixed emotions that Coleman, now an All-SEC
candidate on the Volunteer offensive line, returns to his native
state Saturday when Tennessee meets Georgia at Sanford Stadium.
There will be lots of family and friends to greet him and wish him
well. That will be fun, Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Garner, the man who originally led him to Tennessee, will be
on the other side of the field. Last January, he left Tennessee to
become Georgia's defensive line coach and recruiting coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be different, seeing Coach Garner over there,''
Coleman said. ``But I've got a job to do. There was a reason he
recruited me to come to Tennessee. I want to remind him that he
made a good decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other Tennessee starters, both sophomores, were also
recruited out of Georgia by Garner to play for the Vols in 1997.
Running back Jamal Lewis of Douglass High in Atlanta was a freshman
All-American last season after rushing for 1,364 yards. Defensive
back Deon Grant of Augusta's Josey High moved into the starting
lineup this season.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is out for the season with a knee injury. But Grant, 6-3,
190, is considered one of the rising young stars in the SEC. He is
second on the team in tackles with 29 and made one of the most
athletic plays of the year on Sept. 19 with a one-handed
interception in the 20-17 overtime win over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Like Coleman, Grant said he is looking forward to coming home on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of friends who are coming to the game and there
are a lot of guys I know on the Georgia team,'' Grant said. ``Any
time you leave some place and then go back, you want to show people
that you can do the job. I'm really excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The three sophomores are among six Georgians listed on
Tennessee's starting 22 players. Senior Mercedes Hamilton of Burke
County, Ga. will start at one of the guards, and Griffin, Ga.'s
Fred White and Steve Johnson of Powder Springs, Ga. join Grant in
the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   All of the players said this week that they have had this date
circled on their calendar for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem is I can't get enough tickets,'' said White, who
has over 30 requests from friends and family members. ``It's going
to be like a big family reunion out there on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Georgians make up almost one-third of Tennessee's
starting lineup is a sore point with many Bulldog fans. They
believe that the key to Georgia's future success is being able to
keep this kind of blue-chip talent from leaving home. It is just
one reason head coach Jim Donnan hired Garner away from Tennessee
and made him recruiting coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   That Georgians play significant roles on the Tennessee football
team is nothing new. Georgia has long been a fertile recruiting
ground for the Vols, who have been able to sign All-Americans like
Chip Kell, Willie Gault, Dale Carter, Antoine Davis and Chuck Smith
out of the Peach State.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, games like Saturday's between Georgia and
Tennessee, have an impact on impressionable recruits. That's just
another reason the stakes are so high. Georgia plans to invite
approximately 100 recruits to Saturday's game and for a player
looking at both Tennessee and Georgia, the winner has a slight
edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games like this can always have some kind of impact on
recruiting,'' said Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer. ``We recruit all
of the contiguous states and when you play those teams it is a
factor. You don't worry about it, but it is part of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
