</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATECH-SECONDARY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech secondary excited about challenge of lightening bolt Holt
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just when Georgia Tech was enjoying a nice little run
of playing solid pass defense, here comes Torry Holt.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. State's senior receiver is playing like he's one of the
best in the country. He's second in the nation averaging 148.5
yards receiving yards per game and ninth averaging 7.3 receptions
per game.
</P>
<P>
   Against Ohio University in the season opener, Holt had a 62-yard
touchdown catch and followed the next week with a 63-yard TD catch
and a 68-yard punt return TD in the upset win over Florida State.
Against Baylor, he had an 80-yard touchdown catch and finally
against Syracuse, the Orangemen ``stopped'' him - holding him to
161 yards receiving and no touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Tech secondary seems excited about the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking about that (Monday),'' cornerback Jamara Clark
said. ``This is the game you wait for, against one of the best
receivers in the nation. This is the chance you've got to show how
good you are and what Georgia Tech is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to play a Torry Holt every week. It would make me a
better player. It would make us a better defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech players and coaches are not divulging any plans they have
for stopping No. 81. And they may not have any.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been covering receivers pretty good, so why change?''
free safety Travares Tillman said.
</P>
<P>
   Using a mix of man and zone coverages, Tech has limited its
opponents to 170 yards passing per game. That's after giving up an
average of 296.3 per game last year.
</P>
<P>
   Coach George O'Leary has said no one in the country can cover
Holt man-for-man, so don't expect to see Tech defensive backs left
alone much to deal with Holt. But the Yellow Jackets also know that
too much emphasis on Holt and receivers Chris Coleman or Eric Leak
can beat you too.
</P>
<P>
   Clark (5-8, 170) and Jason Bostic (5-9, 181) are both giving up
size to Holt (6-2, 188), but they will rely on their improved
technique under defensive coordinator Randy Edsall's tutelage,
decent speed and help from their safeties to stay with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to know where (Holt) is in the sets and make sure
your players understand what's going on,'' O'Leary said. ``He's
going to get his plays, just like any good receiver. You just can't
give up and lot of big chunk plays. That's what he's gotten in
every game I've seen on tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing where to find Holt in a set should be easy enough to
pick up. As for what kind of routes Tech is expecting from Holt?
Deep ones. With his 29 catches for 594 yards and four touchdowns,
Holt is averaging 20.5 yards per catch.
</P>
<P>
   He has got all the tools, with speed, size, great hands and
smarts. But his biggest advantage is his speed. Don't give him a
big enough cushion and he'll blow by defenders. Give him too big a
cushion he'll cut a crossing route in front of the secondary and
beat everybody for a big gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``His first few steps are really fast, so it's hard to press
him,'' Tillman said. ``He's a Peter Warrick type receiver.
Explosive, that's a word for him, explosive.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
