<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Watson battles distractions
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tom Watson, 49, has been on a mental roller coaster in
1998. At his high point, Watson won the Colonial Invitational May
24, renewing thoughts of pushing back a move to the Senior Tour
when he turns 50 next September. Contrast that with a missed cut at
the PGA in August _ his fifth straight in a major. Not what you
would expect, even at 49, from a player with five British Open
wins, two Masters and a U.S. Open. Last week before missing the cut
at Callaway Gardens, Ga., Watson admitted that going through a
divorce this year from his wife of 23 years, Linda, has been ``a
huge distraction.'' Watson also has quit drinking for unexplained
reasons. ``Life's full of ups and downs,'' he said. ``You just have
to hope it goes back up again.'' Cementing his position in the Tour
Championship would help, but Watson is 27th on the money list and
might need one more decent check to be safe. He ``very much'' wants
to make the 1999 Ryder Cup team that plays Europe at The Country
Club in Brookline, Mass., next September. Watson discovered
recently that he's been aiming too far left on his putting ``for
probably much of my career'' _ as much as three inches off line on
a putt of eight feet.
</P>
<P>
   Duval: 'Union' misleading players
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say enthusiasm for the proposed ``Tournament
Players Association'' organized by Larry Rinker, Mark Brooks and
Danny Edwards is muted. They so far appear to be a bunch of
``have-nots'' trying to capitalize on the ``haves.'' At this stage,
it doesn't appear the TPA will be getting a $1,000 dues check from
leading money winner David Duval, who feels the group is misleading
the public and the players. ``I think it's misleading to say they
don't want an adversary role when they hire a counsel (Leonard
Decof, who successfully represented Ping in its ``square grooves''
suit against the PGA) who has had an adversarial role in the
past.'' For what it's worth, Duval, a member of the 16-man Player
Advisory Council, which acts as a representative arm beyond the
four players on the PGA Tour Policy Board, said, ``None of those
three players has come to me on the PAC this year with a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   Had Buick Challenge winner Steve Elkington gone into a playoff
with Bill Glasson Sunday, considering their laundry list of medical
problems, they would have needed an ambulance to follow them.
Elkington even played with a new injury, having cut the palm of his
left hand while gardening the previous week. . . . Albany's Ed
Everett finished ninth in his defense at the Senior Club
Professional Championship at Ibis Golf and Country Club in West
Palm Beach, Fla., five shots behind winner Wes Smith of Cooper
City, Fla. . . . The LPGA has added a tournament in Austin, Texas,
The Phillips Invitational Honoring Harvey Penick, starting next May
20-23.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
