<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PLAYERS-ON-BUBBLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall brings nervousness to many fringe golfers
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Apologies officially are extended to all those who
play golf solely for the love of the game. At this time of the year
in professional golf, it is about cold, hard cash and nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the bubble'' is the operative phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Players are on the bubble _ particularly the ``top 125 bubble''
_ when they don't know if next year they will be playing golf on
the PGA Tour or on their home computer. Those finishing among the
top 125 moneywinners in three weeks gain fully exempt status for
1999 events. Those without even limited status might head for the
dreaded PGA Tour Qualifying School, which is sponsored by Mylanta,
Goody's Headache Powders and the National Shock Therapy Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Even recent PGA Tour event winners such as D.A. Weibring, the
1996 Greater Hartford Open winner, are in the sweaty palms portion
of the season. At 158th with $143,504 earned, Weibring needs a good
week of, say, $60,000 just to reach the bubble area of the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm up against the wall,'' Weibring was saying at Callaway
Gardens Sunday after a final-round 74 allowed only a tie for 27th
and $11,100. ``It probably hurts my pride more than anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one spot higher, at 157th, is Columbus, Ga. native Hugh
Royer, who also needs a fast finish to avoid Q-School. Fairly
prominent names are teetering on the edge such as David Ogrin
(129th), Clarence Rose (134th), Chris Smith (137th) and former
Masters champion Sandy Lyle (140th). Veteran Blaine McAllister, who
needed Q-School last year to get exempt, is 121st, but must earn
enough now to stay there.
</P>
<P>
   Though more of a bonus bubble and without the financial
ramifications, there's also one for the top 30, which allows entry
into the Tour Championship in four weeks at Atlanta's East Lake
Golf Club. Just making the top 30 earns a minimum check of $64,000
at East Lake. The winner pockets $720,000; the runner-up $432,000.
Third at the $4 million tournament gets $276,000 _ a bigger check
than many that accompany trophies during the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to talk about it,'' Andrew Magee, No. 29,
said at the Buick Challenge _ and that was before he missed the cut
and dropped two spots. ``No, I don't feel safe at all.''
</P>
<P>
   East Lake members Stewart Cink (32nd) and Billy Andrade (42nd)
have different tasks. Cink needs one relatively high finish, but
Andrade probably needs two in the top three.
</P>
<P>
   The Senior PGA Tour's exempt list is the toughest to crack in
all of golf. Unlike the PGA Tour, where a win brings two years of
eligibility, the Senior Tour allows only a one-year pass. A finish
among the top 31 moneywinners is needed to gain full playing
privileges for 1999. The LPGA'S exempt list already is finalized,
with players securing full status through a finish in the top 90.
The Nike Tour's top 15 moneywinners earn PGA Tour cards for 1999,
so that puts Savannah's Gene Sauers on the spot. He's 18th and just
over $6,000 from the cutoff point. Casey Martin is 26th, about
$22,000 out, and in need of a win.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
