<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEMANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Petit Le Mans notebook
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Unlike most major races in the Atlanta area,
Saturday's Petit Le Mans field will feature four types of cars
rather than one.
</P>
<P>
   They are: World Sports Car; Le Mans Prototype; Grand Touring 1
(GT1) and Grand Touring 2 (GT2).
</P>
<P>
   World Sports Cars are open-cockpit, closed-wheel prototypes with
engines from Oldsmobile, Ferrari, Ford, Chevrolet, Mazda and BMW,
with a top speed of 180 mph. Le Mans Prototypes are two-seaters
with open cockpits. No minimum production is required.
</P>
<P>
   GT1s are production-based, tube-frame cars with engines over 3
liters. Models include Panoz Ford, Porsche, Olds Aurora, Dodge
Viper, Mustang and Camaro with a top Speed of 175 mph.
</P>
<P>
   GT2s are stock-based unibody cars with turbo-charged or normally
aspirated engines based on an equivalency formula. GT2 engines are
up to 4 liters and non-turbo models are up to 8 liters. Porsche 911
GT2s and Dodge Viper GT2s are included in this class. Top speed is
170 mph.
</P>
<P>
   All will be at Lenox Square in Atlanta today, from 9 a.m. to
4:30 p.m., undergoing ``scrutineering,'' or inspection. In the
tradition of the 24 Hours of Le Mans, scrutineering is done in
public rather than a garage area in order for fans to see the cars
and meet the drivers. The winning car from this year's 24 Hours of
Le Mans, the No. 26 Porsche 911 works car to be driven by Yannick
Dalmas, Le Mans winner Allan McNish and Uwe Alzen, is scheduled for
inspection at 1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   today.
</P>
<P>
   Local connections
</P>
<P>
   In an event named after a race in France, metro Atlantans might
draw a blank about which car to cheer for in Saturday's
1,000-mile/10-hour Petit Le Mans, but there are some cars with
Atlanta connections in the field. First, there are the entries by
Team Panoz _ No. 4 GT1 driver by David Brabham, Scott Pruett and
Andy Wallace; No. 5 GT1 driven by Eric Bernard, Johnny O'Connell
and Jamie Davies; and the No. 07 Panoz hybrid GT1 driven by John
Nielsen, Doc Bundy of Gainesville, Ga. and Christophe Tinseau. In
the World Sports Car field, the No. 7 Ferrari is co-sponsored by
Atlanta-based Lease Plan; the No. 63 Mazda Kudzu was built and will
be driven by Atlantan Jim Downing; the No. 39 Carolina Turkey
Ford/R&AMP;S Mk III will be driven by David Murry of Atlanta; the No.
88 Ferrari 333 SP will be driven by Anthony Lazzaro of Atlanta; and
the No. 8 GT2-SC Porsche 968 Turbo RS will be driven Atlantans Jeff
Purner and Joe Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket update
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 advance tickets have been sold, but no one at Road
Atlanta is worried, said spokesperson Claudette Ashman. ``It's rare
that we get more than 3 percent advance sales,'' she said. Another
sign that something is happening in the area is that all lodging
close to the track _ from Commerce, Ga. southward _ is sold out on
Oct. 10. Some could be because of another event, the
Georgia-Tennessee game. To order tickets or for race information,
call 1-800-849-7223. . . . BellSouth Mobility will distribute
coupons for free paddock passes, a $20 value, at its Atlanta-area
stores. The coupons can be redeemed for a paddock pass at the Road
Atlanta gate with the purchase of a four-day or Saturday-Sunday
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
