<HEADER>
A2828 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORWICH-COX     10-06 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWICH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman finds herself in hot water with town
 &HT;    By Colin Campbell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORWICH, England _ A few weeks ago, a divorced mother of three
named June Wilson _ born in the proud old city of Norwich _ wrote a
letter to a local newspaper complaining that her city and the whole
rural county of Norfolk were ``very boring.''
</P>
<P>
   A TV personality had been making Norfolk jokes again, and the
locals had been rising to their shire's defense. Now up popped
Wilson, a local herself who lives on Magpie Road, agreeing with the
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norwich is very boring,'' she wrote to the tabloid Evening
News, ``and the great majority of Norfolk people are also very
boring.'' She added that they were backward, rude and apathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Like vast stretches of America, Norfolk has been the target of
such pokes for years. In the 18th century Horace Walpole called the
people of Norfolk ``roast beef in human form.'' Londoners sometimes
call the locals ``carrot crunchers'' and other names suggestive of
turnpike stupidity. And a Len Deighton novel once characterized
East Anglia (an old historic zone bigger than Norfolk but centered
here) as ``the lost continent of Great Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   But reaction to Wilson's letter was loud and swift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had endless phone calls, though many are from people who
support me,'' said Wilson, 49. ``And I've had these short,
anonymous letters telling me to go back from whence I came. But of
course I'm from here!''
</P>
<P>
   One piece of hate mail seemed threatening enough that Wilson
called the police. They in turn announced firmly that she had a
right to her opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Then Wilson began showing up on TV. And by early last week a few
national British papers were making the story sound as though the
Salman Rushdie tragedy were being replayed as grim rural farce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, no, no,'' Wilson said when asked about the threats.
``The (London) Telegraph went rather over the top with the story. I
didn't make a formal complaint, and I didn't end up with
bodyguards. I merely informed the police. The whole thing just got
blown out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   But she's sticking to her guns on the subject of Norfolk. She
lived in Germany five years, in South Carolina for six months (her
ex-husband was in the military there) and in California six months.
</P>
<P>
   Rural Norfolk is one of England's fastest-growing counties, but
it was hard for Wilson to come home after years away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The English are very reserved, and Norfolk people are even
worse,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What's so extra-boring about Norfolk or the city of Norwich, a
little more than 100 miles north of London?
</P>
<P>
   ``People move here from London, which is a ratrace, and they
think the pace here is perfect. But it's like a tortoise. It has
two speeds, slow and stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Norfolk's recreational distinctions probably do leave
some people cold while enthralling others: North Sea beaches, a
huge lavender farm, a narrow-gauge railway, birdwatching and a
ranch for retired horses. The web of streets that twist away from
the great Norman castle in the heart of Norwich (which rhymes with
porridge) appears to be very quiet at night, though, in the wee
hours, rowdy youths sometimes howl as they leave the pop music
clubs. And the once-beautiful village of Wroxham, on the River
Bure, has learned to attract tourists by selling plastic fast food.
</P>
<P>
   But Norfolk is home to beautiful villages, old pubs, countless
medieval churches built of fist-sized pieces of flint and rolling
green farmland.
</P>
<P>
   In typical British style, history suffuses the place: In the
first century A.D., for example, a Celtic warrior-queen named
Boudicca swept out of Norfolk with her army, torched London, killed
tens of thousands of Romans _ and lost. Lord Nelson (the naval
hero), Thomas Browne (the essayist), Dame Julian of Norwich (the
medieval mystic), the artists John Crome, John Sell Cotman and
others of the Norwich School, Robert Walpole (Britain's first prime
minister), Abraham Lincoln's ancestors . . . the list of Norfolk's
famous folk is long.
</P>
<P>
   And a large number of non-boring women also are associated with
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Not just the warrior-queen or medieval mystics, not just Anne
Boleyn and Katharine Howard (two of Henry VIII's wives), but also
Anna Sewall (who wrote ``Black Beauty''), Fanny Burney (a novelist
friend of Samuel Johnson), Edith Cavell (a World War I nurse in
Belgium executed by the Germans for helping British soldiers escape
imprisonment) and other social reformers, artists and free spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe June Wilson is another. In any case, the bitterness of her
fight got a bit sweeter late last week when her most threatening
correspondent wrote a second anonymous letter to apologize. She'd
been joking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have certainly learnt my lesson,'' the deflated fatwa-writer
of Norwich wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And the police say they hope the matter will now be closed.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Campbell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
