<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CHIPPER-Q-AND-A-C     10-06 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHIPPER-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10 questions with Chipper Jones
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chipper Jones, who had the game-winning hit against
the Cubs in Game 2 of the division series, is playing in his fourth
postseason. The third-baseman, who is batting .385 in the NLCS,
wants redemption after a mistake at third and a base-running
blunder against the Marlins last year. In the regular season, Jones
had a career year with highs in home runs (34), games (160), hits
(188), runs (123) and average (.313).
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you have to do to win the World Series?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think our pitchers are going to have to throw eight
shutouts (laughs). That will pretty much assure us of winning a
World Series. Certainly that's a tough task, but our pitching's
capable of shutting anybody out on any given night. And hopefully
our offense will squeeze out just enough runs to win.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Going into the season, with so many different players, what
was your outlook?
</P>
<P>
   A: I thought if we kept everybody healthy, we'd be back in the
World Series. Obviously, the acquisitions of (Andres) Galarraga and
(Walt) Weiss are huge. You throw Galarraga into the middle of our
lineup with all our lefties, and all of sudden we 've got a pretty
versatile lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the high point of the season for you?
</P>
<P>
   A: The game-winning hit against Chicago in Game 2 (of the
division series). Not often do you get a chance to come up in a
situation like that and do some damage, and then come through.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the low point?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably three weeks before the season was over, and we lost
eight out of 10 and were really kind of dead in the water. We
weren't playing very well at all, but we've turned that around. You
always have doubts; you wonder if the guys are on the same page you
are, but luckily the higher-ups got together, we had a team meeting
and got everybody on the same page, and we've been playing great
since.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is this team different from last year's?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think we're a little closer as a team. The guys all pull
for each other. We're not family, but when we're in the clubhouse
and the dugout, we are family and the guys act like it. They show a
lot of love toward each other. They're the first ones to pat each
other on the back, and when somebody needs talking to, somebody
will talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How fired up are the Braves?
</P>
<P>
   A: We got pretty excited in the Chicago series. I thought we
matched their emotion pitch-for-pitch. When good things happened,
we got as excited as anybody. We're going to have to do that again.
This business-type attitude has not gotten the job done the last
couple of years, so we're going to have to pump it up a little. I
fully expect every time we do something great for guys to get up
off the bench. I think this team needs to thrive upon those
situations, to let off a little steam and once we do it, relax.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it more exciting in the postseason compared to last
season?
</P>
<P>
   A: I can't say that. It's a situation where you go into every
postseason like it's your last, and that's the only way you can
play your best. If you go into a postseason nonchalant, relaxed,
you're going to get beat.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is this the kind of stuff you dreamed about as a kid, playing
in October?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think you start playing this game unless you have
some dreams of playing in October at baseball's highest level. It's
quite an honor to don one of these major league uniforms. The
competitor in all of us wants to be in these clutch situations in
October, vying for a world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you see Game 1 against the Padres, with Andy Ashby
pitching instead of Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ashby's been just as tough on us as Kevin has. Since I've
been in the big leagues, I don't ever remember this team beating
Ashby. He's been as quality a pitcher as Kevin Brown. We've just
got to be patient, go out and put the ball in play. Ashby is a lot
like Brown. The ball moves all over the place; he throws hard; he's
a tremendous competitor. He's as much a thorn in our side as
Brown's been.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have one eye on the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think any time you get a chance to watch the other team on
TV and do a little scouting yourself, you take advantage of it. Not
so much the Yankees as the Yankees and the Indians. This is a funny
game. You never know which one you're going to play.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
