<HEADER>
A2833 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-KEY-COX     10-06 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-KEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Five keys to a Padres pennant
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Get into the Braves bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   This might be easier said than done, as John Smoltz, Tom Glavine
and Greg Maddux rank as the best 1, 2, 3 combination in the game.
Best hope might be that the Braves are put in position to pinch-hit
late in the game. Kerry Ligtenberg saved 30 games after Mark
Wohlers unraveled, but he and setup guys Rudy Seanez and John
Rocker are green and untested under the glare of post-season.
</P>
<P>
   2. Ride the right arm of Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the Padres would love to get Brown three starts, but
that's not likely to happen with him being held back to Game 2 .
Brown is the equal of Smoltz, a dominant right-hander who thrives
in the post-season _ twice beating the Braves in the '97 NLCS. The
rest of the staff feeds off his no-nonsense demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   3. Turn up the offensive production.
</P>
<P>
   Against Houston pitching, journeyman Jim Leyritz was another Mr.
October in the NL Division Series, but his was the only bat that
consistently made any noise. The Padres struggled to score runs
late in the season and hit just .216 against the Astros. They
collectively hit an even worse .209 in the regular-season against
Atlanta pitching. So it's pivotal that the big bats of Tony Gwynn,
Ken Caminiti and Greg Vaughn come alive.
</P>
<P>
   4. Make the Braves play little ball.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego did just enough offensively in the Houston series,
while holding the league's top run producing team to a single run
in three games. The potent Killer B's (Craig Biggio, Derek Bell and
Jeff Bagwell) were transformed into fleas, hitting .146 with a solo
home run. The Atlanta sluggers need to be kept in the park to avoid
any big innings. The Padres will have to scrap for runs in hopes of
winning low-scoring ballgames.
</P>
<P>
   5. Be in position to turn it over to Trevor Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman nailed down 53 of 54 save opportunities during the
season, and that dominance makes him among the favorites for the Cy
Young award. Stat to remember: Padres were 85-0 when leading after
the eighth inning this season, 174-0 since July 24, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
