<HEADER>
A2834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-Q-AND-A-CO     10-06 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10 questions with Tony Gwynn
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tony Gwynn, the Padres' elder statesman, is one of the
greatest hitters of his generation _ .340 lifetime and winner of
eight batting titles. Gwynn discussed the NLCS playoffs after the
division series victory over Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the NL Division Series against the Houston Astros?
</P>
<P>
   A: In that series, nobody gave us a chance. People wrote us off
because we weren't doing anything offensively. And here we are. We
like the fact that nobody thinks we're (good). And I think when
you're the underdog, you have a chance to relax.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can the underdog prevail against the Atlanta Braves?
</P>
<P>
   A: In this series, we've got to be a lot better offensively.
Against their pitching staff, it's going to be tough. I just feel
we're going to find a way to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does advancing to the NLCS mean to the San Diego
franchise?
</P>
<P>
   A: When we went to spring training, I thought we had a chance.
Now, we've gotten out of the first round in the postseason, and I'm
thrilled for this organization, for this city. The organization has
gone out and gotten quality guys. Going into the championship
series is huge.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your perspective on the Atlanta Braves pitching staff?
</P>
<P>
   A: They're the best in the business. (John) Smoltz is throwing
the ball extremely well. They all are. Going into the series, we
just have to find a way to get some runs on the board. I'm feeling
the heat already. But on the other side, our pitching isn't bad,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you get ready for Smoltz &AMP; Co.?
</P>
<P>
   A: With me, it'll be a lot easier. I didn't have that many
at-bats against Randy (Johnson), because he was over in the
American League. Against Atlanta, I've faced that staff so many
times. I've got a lot of video and notes that I can go back and
review. I've never faced them in the postseason, so it might be
different. But I said all year that the road (to the World Series)
goes through Atlanta. I know they're the team of the '90s. I know
they've been to the World Series. They have plenty of postseason
experience, but we can't worry about it now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As good as they pitch during the season, do you think the
Braves take it up a notch in the postseason?
</P>
<P>
   A: They definitely pitch even better. They know how to focus, to
concentrate. You know in the postseason that there are not going to
be many balls middle of the plate. So you're going to have to hit
the pitcher's pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What influence did Kevin Brown's ability and mental toughness
have on the Padres pitching staff?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kevin Brown is very intense on game day. The other guys on
the ballclub benefitted from seeing him do his thing. He and
(pitching coach) Dave Stewart have been a big influence on our
staff. I mean, our staff has been great all year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the American TV audience ready for the Padres?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't care if the people know about us. We're in prime time
now. There are only four teams left. I know people know about Kevin
Brown. They probably think of the rest of us as just West Coast
guys.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You had an un-Gwynn-like series against the Astros (.200,
3-for-15). What's that all about?
</P>
<P>
   A: My timing is off right now. I'm just not seeing the ball
good. I'm out in front of balls. My discipline is just gone. So I
have a lot of work to do, because I want to be better.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've had problems with an Achilles' and a thumb injury.
What's your physical status?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm good. We've had a couple days off, so I should be good
come Wednesday. What I like is there's no Astroturf.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
