   '98 Postseason .100 1 0 1 0
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT FIELD: Tony Gwynn
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're pulling for the Braves, you want to catch Gwynn
work his magic at the plate. The best pure hitter since Ted
Williams, he owns eight batting titles second only to Ty Cobb's
dozen and a .339 lifetime average. He's hobbled by a tender
Achilles', but he loves the limelight and he's handled Braves
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   vs Atlanta .286 6 1 4 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .321 148 16 69 0
</P>
<P>
   '98 Postseason .200 3 0 2 0
</P>
<P>
   CATCHER: Carlos Hernandez
</P>
<P>
   A nice player, but the Braves own a huge advantage in Javy
Lopez. He's coming off his most productive season, with nine homers
and 52 RBIs. He deserves credit for handling the Padres pitching
staff. Jim Leyritz will likely be behind the plate when Sterling
Hitchcock starts.
</P>
