<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks get message to fans: 'we don't want this'
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They didn't walk a picket line. That was never their
intention.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't pound on the front door and scream, ``Let me in!''
The gymnasium at Life University is always open.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of Hawks players and free agents were able to
present their points of view Tuesday as they vented over the NBA's
lockout, now in its 98th day.
</P>
<P>
   On the day training camps were to have opened, union officer
Tyrone Corbin said, ``We want the fans to know we're ready to play
and we don't want this.''
</P>
<P>
   A free agent who hopes to be back with the Hawks, Corbin will
accompany fellow vice president Dikembe Mutombo of the Hawks to New
York for a scheduled negotiating session Thursday. The league
recently made a detailed new proposal to the players association
and Mutombo predicted its restrictive language would not hasten a
settlement one bit.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo said that the prospect of a hard salary cap remains
onerous to the players, even if the cap is set at a high figure.
``You could make it $40 million (it's now $26.7 million) and It
still comes down to forcing too many players on a team to slice up
a small piece of the pie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He complained that the league is not putting enough of its
income into the pot for distribution to salaries and he said the
league under-estimates its potential for income from foreign
markets. ``The whole world is hungry for NBA games.''
</P>
<P>
   The league, on the other hand, says the players are not
realistic about costs, over-estimate income potential and insists
upon instituting controls on the cost of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our proposals would result in an average player salary of more
than $3.1 million and a minimum salary for 10-year veterans of
$750,000,'' NBA Deputy Commissioner Russ Granik points out.
``Unfortunately, the union leadership has been unwilling to give
any serious consideration to what we have offered.''
</P>
<P>
   While the NBA may have gained some public sympathy, Mutombo said
players were offended by new restrictive rules of conduct and
increased fines for missed practices or exhibition games or
unacceptable forms of behavior.
</P>
<P>
   While the players agreed on a more inclusive drug policy,
Mutombo said, ``By injecting this now they are treating us like
gang members. There are a few young guys who have problems, but
you're talking about more than 420 guys and most of us live a very
quiet lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand Tuesday were Hawks veteran Steve Smith, free agents
Alan Henderson, Pig Miller and Ivano Newbill and rookie Shammond
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Players from New York, Washington, Milwaukee, Indiana, Portland,
Houston, Denver, Miami, Philadelphia and Charlotte were also at
practice sites Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
