<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons say their offensive line starting to gel
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Monday was a lot different this week for Atlanta
Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler _ he could walk and talk without
grimacing.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler was sacked just once in Sunday's 51-23 wipeout of
Carolina, a stark contrast to being sacked seven times the previous
week in a 31-20 loss to the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's offensive line was that much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result of a game really shows how everybody plays,'' said
Chandler, who last week was limping with a sprained ankle and
favoring a wrist/forearm injury. ``When we win by the score we did,
it generally means everybody played good.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (3-1) allowed just two sacks Sunday, including a late
drop of reserve Steve DeBerg, a dramatic improvement over last
month's game at Carolina, when Chandler was sacked six times.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday against the Giants (2-3), the Falcons will face a
4-3 alignment rather than Carolina's 3-4, but New York still brings
a lot of pressure. The Giants are tied for second in the NFL with
19 sacks, and end Michael Strahan has six.
</P>
<P>
   To prove Sunday wasn't an aberration, left tackle Bob Whitfield,
left guard Calvin Collins, center Robbie Tobeck, right guard Gene
Williams and right tackle Ephraim Salaam will have to show
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson, who has the first back-to-back
100-yard games of his career after rushing for 117 Sunday, says the
line is playing better because the players are closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're working harder as a unit,'' Anderson said. ``The
little things they do together, like going to lunch, doing stuff as
a unit on the road . . . all that factors into how well they play
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield said that when the line gets it done, the running game
gets going, and a defensive line can't pin back its ears and rush
the passer.
</P>
<P>
   Salaam, the only rookie in the unit, agrees with that, and with
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great game plan. We ran a lot, and ran hard and
well,'' he said. ``You fight harder with your family. There's a
sense of pride. The more we work together, the better we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Salaam has drawn the most attention on a unit that allowed 16
sacks in the first three games. Sunday, he worked against outside
linebacker Kevin Greene, who had both sacks, both coming, however,
when receivers were covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still got a long way to go,'' he said. ``But we were more
aware, reading keys and communicating better. When they would bring
the strong safety down, or move the (middle linebacker) over
(tipping potential blitzes), we noticed things like that, and we
were making calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly: The Falcons are finalizing arrangements with Furman
University in Greenville, S.C., to have training camp there next
summer, with options to hold camp there in 2000 and 2001. Furman
was the site of Falcon training camps from 1971-77. . . . Former
Falcon DT Nathan Davis, a second-round pick in 1997 who quit the
team on the second day of camp, signed a one-year deal with Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
