<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVERSITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School president has vision of 'world house' environmentBy Ernie
Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For Walter Massey, a veteran of the California
affirmative action wars, convincing people that there is diversity
on the campus of Morehouse College shouldn't be that hard a task.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been emphasizing diversity here,'' said Massey, the
president of Morehouse. ``But what does diversity mean to a
historically and predominantly black college that is all male?''
</P>
<P>
   Standing beneath a photo of Martin Luther King Jr. in the
visitors' center of the slain leader's national historic site,
Massey explained Morehouse's mission toward diversity by stressing
his school's most famous graduate's desire for a ``world house,''
in which different cultures could come together.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have stressed is diversity isn't just black and
white,'' said Massey, who was the provost of the University of
California System when affirmative action was being challenged in
the mid- 1990s and eventually overturned in 1996, after he had
left. ``We have to live with people of all cultures _ racial,
ethnic and gender related.''
</P>
<P>
   Massey was on hand Tuesday, along with Emory University
President Bill Chace, to discuss the results of the Campus
Diversity Initiative, commissioned by the Ford Foundation to gauge
the attitudes of people regarding diversity and diversity education
in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 registered voters, including 200 Georgians,
participated.
</P>
<P>
   The survey concluded that 70 percent of Georgians think it is
very important that colleges prepare graduates to get along in a
diverse society. Another 54 percent said every college student
should have to study different cultures in order to graduate, and
by a margin of four to one, those who have an opinion say that
diversity programs in colleges and universities raise, rather than
lower, standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe all of education is formed by having students
face-to-face with the unfamiliar,'' Chace said. ``This is the
nature of education. People don't come here to relearn that which
they already know. People come here to deepen what they already
know or to be thrust into circumstances with which they have no
familiarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Chace said students at Emory get that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Journal of Blacks in Higher Education'' recently ranked
Emory first in the country among high-ranking liberal arts colleges
for black enrollment, reporting that 10.2 percent of Emory's
students are black, up from 3 percent in 1980. As late as 1967, no
black had ever graduated from Emory.
</P>
<P>
   Chace credits that to a concerted effort by Emory to attract
more blacks and minorities. About 30 percent of Emory's students
are minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had it not been for affirmative action programs and our focus
on having an African-American community, we wouldn't have (an
African-American community), '' Chace said. ``Only that kind of
constant application and focus can explain our meteoric rise.''
</P>
<P>
   While, Emory is more diverse on the surface than Morehouse,
which is about 98 percent black, Massey said his students hail from
each of the 50 states, and several foreign countries. Earlier this
semester, the BBC was on campus filming a documentary on British
students at Morehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are part of a diverse community here,'' Massey said. ``And
in order for diversity to really work, diversity must occur within
the racial, ethnic and gender boundaries. It begins with diversity
among yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Both presidents agreed that the results of the survey didn't
signify an end of anything or a specific turning point, therefore,
neither would adopt a ``where do we go from here,'' approach,
instead opting to continue in the direction they are going.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no substitute for constant applications and focused
efforts,'' Chace said. ``If we say we are finished, we are done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Suggs writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
