<SLUG> BC-GAS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PSC gives OK to gas companies
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Public Service Commission gave the go-ahead
Tuesday to 19 companies to start selling natural gas in Georgia at
decontrolled prices, and one marketer immediately offered onetime
$50 discounts to every customer it signs up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a historic moment in Georgia and for the gas
industry,'' Chairman Robert Baker said as the PSC approved all of
the certification applications.
</P>
<P>
   But commissioners put the marketers on notice that there will be
zero-tolerance for ``slamming'' _ changing a customer's service to
another provider without permission _ or other deceptive practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joan of Arc might think she had it good compared to the first
company found guilty by this commission,'' Commissioner Stan Wise
said.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties will include fines of $15,000 for each incident of
slamming and $10,000 for each day it continues. Companies who
engage in such practices, which have marred telecommunications
deregulation, could also have their operating certificates revoked.
</P>
<P>
   The marketers can immediately begin quoting prices and making
deals to supply gas starting Nov. 1. Consumers must sign up with a
marketer by Oct. 25 to receive gas on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Gas Light Co., which is getting out of the gas sales
business, will continue supplying customers while deregulation is
fully phased in. But consumers who do not choose a marketer other
than AGL eventually will be assigned to one by the PSC.
</P>
<P>
   The competitors are in various stages of developing their
marketing plans and rates to lure 1.4 million residential and
business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Some are still assessing whether to even make major efforts.
Most TV and radio ad campaigns are not expected to start until next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Within 15 days, Atlanta Gas Light is scheduled to distribute
computer discs to marketers that include customers' names,
addresses and gas usage histories. Some companies said they will
not be able to quote specific prices until they receive such
information from the gas company or consumers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But Warren A. Darby, senior vice president in charge of Georgia
operations for SCANA Energy, said his company would immediately
offer $50 discounts on the first month's bill of residential
customers who sign up with the South Carolina-based company.
</P>
<P>
   Darby also promised an additional 5 percent reduction on what
residential customers currently pay Atlanta Gas Light. The PSC says
bills now average $520 a year. SCANA's reduction on that average
would be about $26 for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gunther, president of Georgia Natural Gas Services Inc.,
a subsidiary of AGL Resources Inc., which is Atlanta Gas Light's
parent, said his company is prepared today to offer a market price
close to what consumers are currently paying. Other pricing
options, such as a fixed rate over a 12-month period, will also be
available. The company will launch a statewide TV and radio ad
campaign next week, Gunther said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Raymond, president of Houston-based Shell Energy Services,
said the Shell Oil Co. subsidiary will also launch its ad campaign
next week and be ready to quote prices at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Kathi Dish, a spokeswoman for Columbia Energy Services, said the
Ohio-based firm plans a mass mailing to 1 million consumers. The
company, however, has not yet set prices.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Latham, president of Optimum Energy Sources, said her
Roswell-based company, which will operate as Peachtree Natural Gas,
is prepared today to sign up customers who call electric membership
corporations with which it has formed marketing alliances. Optimum
has agreements with the Coweta-Fayette, Walton, Jackson and Sawnee
EMCs.
</P>
<P>
   Peachtree will offer a flat monthly rate that includes a
guarantee against weather-driven price fluctuations, Lahtam said.
But she added it would be difficult to quote prices until the
company receives gas usage information.
</P>
<P>
   The PSC scheduled a meeting Friday to discuss a number of
unresolved deregulation issues. That could include possible
measures to protect personal privacy and proprietary information
for businesses when the gas company turns over customer information
to marketers.
</P>
<P>
   The commission may also revisit a 2 percent rate increase
awarded Atlanta Gas Light Co. earlier this year for transportation
of gas and rule on a proposed $12.3 million two-year public
education campaign by AGL on deregulation that ratepayers would be
billed for.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
