<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Re/Max offices join to form mega-brokerage
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fourteen Atlanta area Re/Max franchises have merged to
form a new company, Re/Max Greater Atlanta, now one of the largest
real estate brokerages in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Once three new offices open, the new brokerage will employ up to
1,100 agents.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lee Finch, who will be chairman of the new company,
the new offices will be in the Vinings, North Point Mall and Duluth
areas of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Finch, also the current president of the Atlanta Board of
Realtors, and real estate veteran Tim Lennon owned Re/Max North
Atlanta, with eight locations and $1.3 billion in closed sales
through August. They expect combined closed sales for all of 1998
to be more than $3 billion, Finch said. Closed sales represent
consummated transactions, Finch said, and is usually a lower figure
than gross sales, which may include transactions that were not
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The other brokers involved in the deal will be partners as
brokers/owners in the new company. They are: Mary Ann Frolik, who
owned Re/Max Achievers and Re/Max Intown, and Denny Jones and Ben
Christopher, who co-owned Re/Max Northwest in Cobb County and
environs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the size of this transaction, Re/Max franchises have
considerable visibility in the metro area. There are still about 50
others ringing Atlanta, from Griffin to Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   Finch acknowledged that the Re/Max Greater Atlanta combination
is part of a general trend toward consolidation in the industry,
adding that it gives the new company far greater reach and market
share. But, he added, in this case there are special elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the name recognition. But we also have productivity
per office and productivity per agent that will be at least twice
what any of our competitors have.''
</P>
<P>
   Such productivity, he explained, is measured by transactions per
agent tracked from third-party sources such as the multiple listing
services.
</P>
<P>
   Although Finch did not rule out the possibility of forays into
subdivision development, he said the new company's immediate goal
is to acquaint every agent with its computer lab and
real-estate-specific learning modules.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
