<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELFTAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Foundation's dealings with Republican party may violate status
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _The Atlanta-based Southeastern Legal Foundation may
have violated its tax-exempt status with a fund-raising appeal that
was too closely allied with the Republican party, according to two
tax experts.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old public interest law firm has recently raised its
profile by successfully challenging in federal court the Clinton
administration's plans to use statistical sampling to get a more
accurate count of minorities in the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   But a letter from Amos McMullian, a foundation board member and
chief executive of a south Georgia baking company, soliciting money
for the suit may have crossed the line that keeps charities out of
political activities.
</P>
<P>
   McMullian, chairman of the board and CEO of Flowers Industries
of Thomasville, Ga., asked business executives in a Feb. 18 letter
to give between $5,000 and $50,000 to Southeastern Legal for its
lawsuit. Contributions are ``completely tax deductible,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The part of his letter that has raised concerns is his reference
to an analysis of the partisan impact of census sampling provided
by the Republican National Committee (RNC).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton Census plan could provide Democrats the crucial
edge needed to take over Congress and also prevail in close
contests to control several state legislative chambers,'' McMullian
wrote, enclosing a copy of a memo written by RNC chairman Jim
Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   In his memo, Nicholson said census sampling was ``an issue of
unusual importance to the future of the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   When shown the letter, Greg Colvin, a San Francisco tax
attorney, said, ``The letter, with the memo, is designed to
motivate a giver on partisan ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Colvin, chairman of an American Bar Association committee on
political activities by tax-exempt organizations, said the
fund-raising appeal may not have raised objections if it had not
included the RNC memo and references.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Hill, a University of Miami law professor, agreed. ``The
central bad fact is that Nicholson's memo is part of the
solicitation,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   The tax status enjoyed by the Southeastern Legal Foundation
allows donors to claim tax deductions for their contributions and
exempts it from most federal taxes. In return, the organization
agrees not to take part in partisan political activities.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who has written about the political activities of
charitable organizations, said she sees similarities to the case of
the American Campaign Academy, a Virginia trade school formed in
1986 to train top managers for political campaigns. Joe Gaylord,
Speaker Newt Gingrich's top political adviser, helped organize the
school.
</P>
<P>
   The academy closed its doors in 1989 after the U.S. Tax Court
upheld an IRS ruling that the academy did not qualify for
tax-exempt financing because it primarily benefited the Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The letter in this matter is important because it suggests
that the benefit to the Republican party was more than incidental
to the lawsuit,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Glavin, the foundation's president, denied that there were
partisan motivations behind the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a Republican in the White House was trying to do the same
thing, the Southeastern Legal Foundation would still be filing a
lawsuit,'' Glavin said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said McMullian wrote the letter on his company's
letterhead, not the foundation's. But McMullian wrote that he was
acting at the foundation's behest, and Marta Turner, a spokeswoman
for Flowers Industries, referred all questions about the letter to
Glavin.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation raised $20,000 from McMullian's appeal, Glavin
said.
</P>
<P>
   IRS spokesman Frank Keith said he could not discuss whether the
agency is looking at Southeastern Legal's tax-exempt status. Glavin
said his organization is not under investigation. ``We haven't done
anything wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McMullian is a longtime political supporter of Gingrich. His
company has contributed regularly to GOPAC, the Republican
political organization Gingrich once ran and remains close to.
Flowers has contributed $25,000 this year, GOPAC records show.
</P>
<P>
   McMullian also noted in his appeal that a separate letter from
Gingrich on behalf of the foundation prompted him to donate money.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have contended that opponents of the administration's
census plan are driven mainly by their concern that sampling, a
scientific method of adjusting the population without actually
counting every person, would add millions of people to the
populations of traditionally Democratic areas. ``From the
beginning, the opponents of a scientific census have had only a
political agenda,'' Rep. Carolyn Maloney (D-N.Y.) said at a recent
congressional hearing on the census. Maloney first called attention
to McMullian's letter.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, two federal courts have unanimously agreed with
opponents of sampling that it is illegal. A month before
Southeastern Legal won its lawsuit, a federal court in Washington,
D.C., ruled in favor of Gingrich in a suit he filed as part of a
compromise with the White House to seek a speedy legal resolution
to the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is scheduled to hear arguments on the sampling
issue on Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
