<SLUG> BC-STARR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tough-district Democrats feel dual pressure
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Preparing for tomorrow's historic vote on opening
an impeachment inquiry against President Clinton, Democratic
leaders on Capitol Hill scrambled to keep members in line.
</P>
<P>
   With congressional elections just a few weeks away, the House
vote could be a test for many Democrats facing tough re-election
bids.
</P>
<P>
   If they vote for a GOP resolution calling for a Watergate-style
inquiry, they could face the wrath of their party. If they vote
lockstep with their party leaders and oppose the inquiry, they
could face the wrath of voters in their district.
</P>
<P>
   And Republicans aren't making it any easier for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Dick Armey (R-Texas) said that he had no
intention of giving Democrats a chance to vote on their own
resolution, which would offer cover for Democrats in tight
re-election bids since they could vote for an investigation
sanctioned by their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who control the House floor, have decided to permit
debate _ one hour's worth _ only on a GOP resolution author- izing
the Judiciary Committee to launch an open-ended impeachment inquiry
reminiscent of the 1974 Watergate inquiry into former President
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have the right resolution,'' Armey told reporters.
``I think it is just time to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides and Democratic leaders reached out to about
35-55 Democrats who they fear might support the Republican
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee did not mince words
in attacking the Republican way of doing things.
</P>
<P>
   ``To not allow an alternative to be debated would be the
grossest form of partisanship,'' said Barney Frank (D-Mass.), a
member of the House Judiciary Committee, which will oversee the
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Republican majority in the House, it is all but a
foregone conclusion that an impeachment inquiry will be approved
tomorrow, for only the third time in the history of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The next step will be for a Judiciary subcommittee to hold a
hearing on October 22 to determine what constitutes an im-
peachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   But even that is controversial.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after Republicans Charles Canady of Florida and Asa
Hutchinson of Arkansas held a press conference to announce the
parameters of that hearing, the chief democrat on the subcommittee
sent out a media advisory suggesting that he had not been
consulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped that we would be able to bring a level of
bipartisan- ship to the subcommittee hearings that had been absent
from the full committee considerations of the impeachment issue,''
said Rep. Robert Scott (D-Va.) in a letter to Canady. ``If we can't
even show fairness to each other in the simple activity of setting
a date for a hearing, I am concerned that we will be hampered in
our efforts to show fairness throughout the proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
