<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOPADS-COX     10-06 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP softens ads to avoid backlash
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fearing public revulsion at political attack ads,
the Republican House leadership unveiled a $7 million round of
national advertising Tuesday filled with smiling faces and talk of
tax cuts and budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The new advertising is designed to highlight congressional
accomplishments in contrast to the Clinton sex scandal, just as
House Republicans are on the verge of beginning an impeachment
inquiry against the president, said Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.),
chairman of the National Republican Congressional Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He also indicated that Republicans have had problems drawing
attention to anything other than the president's affair with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the GOP pursues an open-ended inquiry with no time limit
in the Clinton investigation, Linder said polls and focus groups
have convinced him the public is ``sick of this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   When focus groups had a look at more negative ads, Linder said,
``We got our head handed to us. It was stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue advertising is running this week in 42 congressional
districts, including southwest Georgia's 2nd District, where
Democratic Rep. Sanford Bishop faces Republican challenger Joseph
McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   It features three ``Republican solutions'': giving families a
$500-a-child tax credit, using the budget surplus to ensure the
solvency of the Social Security system and allowing employees to
retain their health insurance when they switch jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Linder also announced the debut of new advertising in 15 other
districts that is specific to those races.
</P>
<P>
   The cost equals the entire issues ad budget of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee. The Republicans are in the midst
of a $37 million fund-raising campaign, of which they already have
banked $22 million, Linder said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those contests, including the Georgia race, are
``longshots,'' Linder conceded. But he said the party would spend
money in any district where the Republican candidate had any
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost (D-Tex.), Linder's Democratic counterpart,
said the new Republican commercial is evidence that the GOP has
more money than it knows what to do with and has nothing to say.
</P>
<P>
   Because it technically does not endorse or oppose a candidate,
the advertising is not subject to federal election law spending
limits. But like virtually all so-called issue ads, it leaves
little doubt which candidate it prefers.
</P>
<P>
   In southwest Georgia, for example, the ad ends with the
McCormick campaign phone number and a suggestion to call the
candidate and ``tell him solving family problems is important.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bishop also can plausibly lay claim to each of those issues,
said his press secretary, Selby McCash. ``In a sense, they're
endorsing his record on those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Linder said the ad was well received when it was tested, and he
suggested that tougher ads would have energized Republican voters,
but at a cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have moved our base big time if we were out there
attacking Clinton, but we'd lose everyone else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
