<SLUG> BC-STAMPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Philanthropy stamp unveiled today in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The cause of philanthropy is getting a boost today
when it gets its own 32-cent stamp from the U.S. Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   The commemorative stamp will be unveiled this afternoon at a
ceremony at the Marriott Marquis in Atlanta, kicking off the annual
conference of the National Committee on Planned Giving.
</P>
<P>
   Being issued in an initial release of 50 million, the stamp
pictures a bee pollinating a flower, with the words ``Giving &AMP;
Sharing: An American Tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is happier about the release than Milton Murray, a
professional fund-raiser who's been fighting for the philanthropy
stamp since 1969 and will be recognized for those efforts today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been collecting stamps since I was 8, and working
professionally to help people and organizations share with those in
need, so I thought why not have a stamp that addresses giving and
sharing and compassion?'' says the 76-year-old resident of
Beltville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an easy process. Murray talked to fellow fund-raisers
and nonprofit foundations. He wrote letters and lobbied the Postal
Service, Congress and White House.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Murray knew he was fighting an uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consider that the post office receives 50,000 letters a year
urging subjects for stamps, that at any given moment they are
considering 2,000 subjects, and that they only issue 35-40 new
stamps a year,'' says Murray. ``And then, it's difficult to sell a
subject people don't see as exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray says that until last week he's been more relieved than
elated about the stamp's debut. ``But I got goose bumps when I
walked into my local post office Friday and a lady behind the
counter yelled out, `We've got your stamp in.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
