<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notebook: Brown slated for Thursday start
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Brownout, if it comes at all, won't happen until
Thursday, at the earliest. Kevin Brown won't start for San Diego
until Game 2 of the NL Championship Series. Not that that'll make
tonight's opener easier for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since I've been in the big leagues,'' Chipper Jones said, ''I
don't ever remember this team beating Ashby.'' That would be Andy
Ashby, the Padres' 17-game winner who faces John Smoltz in Game 1
tonight at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   After becoming the NL's first 16-game winner on Aug. 12, Ashby
finished the season in a 1-3, 7.75 ERA slump over his last seven
starts. In Game 2 of the Division Series, he lasted just four
innings against Houston, giving up six hits and three earned runs.
But it's the pre-Sept. Ashby Jones recalls, and likens to Brown.
And not just because that, at 6-foot-5, Ashby's a tall
right-hander, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been as quality a pitcher as Kevin Brown,'' Jones said of
Ashby, who beat the Braves twice this season. He went eight innings
in a 3-2 win here May 8, scattering nine hits. On Aug. 12 in San
Diego, Ashby struck out eight in seven innings of a 5-1 win.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ashby's scheduled to start Games 1 and 5. While a win in
the opener would be beneficial, Jones knows this NLCS mustn't
duplicate last year's, when Brown pitched for Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have to do what we didn't do last October, and
beat Kevin Brown at least once,'' Jones said. ''It's going to be
tough to beat San Diego if we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Personnel
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox will go with the same lineup tonight that he used in
Games 1 and 2 of the Division Series against Chicago. Michael
Tucker will be in right field, batting eighth, just behind Andruw
Jones at No. 7. Until the LDS, Cox had used the lineup (including
Keith Lockhart at 2B, batting second, and Ryan Klesko in left,
hitting fifth), just once all season _ Sept. 25, in a 6-5 win over
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   As for his post-season roster, Cox said during Tuesday's
workout, ''I don't think we're going to tinker with the roster
right now. We'll wait until after the workout, see how everybody
is. But I don't think we're going to take anybody off and add
anybody that's traveling. But the same guys will travel, if we're
fortunate enough to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, getcha tickets
</P>
<P>
   According to Braves officials, there are once again ''several
thousand'' tickets available for Games 1 and 2 of the LCS. Most are
$45 seats in the upper level and outfield pavilion, but some $60
seats in the lower level remain. Tickets are available at Turner
Field ticket windows, from 8:30-5:00. Cashier's check, money order
or cash only. Also, tickets can be purchased by phone through
Ticketmaster (800-326-4000) via credit cards only. Remember the $3
per ticket ''convenience charge'' with Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
