<HEADER>
A2861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES07-COX     10-06 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bullpens a study in contrasts
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The styles can be no more divergent than they are in
the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Qualcomm Stadium shakes between the mournful chimes
of AC/DC's ``Hell's Bells'' blasting from the sound system as
Trevor Hoffman storms his way to the mound. In Atlanta, Kerry
Ligtenberg is like the little kid next door practicing a violin.
Someday, he may learn to play the thing, unless someone breaks it
over his head first.
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions matter. When the NLCS commences tonight at Turner
Field, perhaps the most critical component over the next few days
will be the relief work. Behind Hoffman, Padres general manager
Kevin Towers assembled five new relievers _ Dan Miceli and Randy
Myers foremost _ who helped the club post a 3.46 ERA, the
fourth-lowest in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figure we've shortened the game to seven innings,'' said
Towers.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have blended three rookies with a Nicaraguan
grandfather, a journeyman laboring with his seventh organization
and the major leagues' most precise sideburns. What has developed
is a bullpen that allows a lower batting average than the Padres'
(.230 to .232). Posting a 4.06 ERA at the All-Star break, Atlanta
relievers had a 3.54 second half and the five out there now
(discounting converted starter Kevin Millwood) stand at 3.00 since
the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a bunch of guys nobody really ever heard about,'' said
Ligtenberg, ``so it's probably easy to say we're a vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we've proven in the last two or three months that
we can do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Ligtenberg do Hoffman's job? After the All-Star break,
Hoffman converted 29 of 30 save opportunities with a 1.03 ERA. At
the same time, Ligtenberg, closing for a team that led the majors
in complete games, converted 21 of 23 with a 1.13 ERA. That violin
does not screech.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't know them,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox
said. ``They've all heard of Trevor Hoffman and Mark Wohlers but
these guys can get the job done. And they got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The style has varied far more than the substance. Towers warned
his bullpen in the middle of last season that performance had to
improve. It did not and within a year, Sean Bergman, Doug Bochtler,
Tim Worrell and Pete Smith were all gone. Miceli, Donne Wall and
Brian Boehringer were all dealt for, and Myers was plucked from the
waiver wire Aug. 6 (just before the Braves had a shot at him).
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of good arms,'' Miceli said of spring training.
``They had an established closer, and you build around Trevor,
learn off him and take his lead. Our guys learned off each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the five have posted 20-save seasons, giving the Padres
a closer mentality long before the ninth. They struck out 389 in
421 innings, and in addition to Hoffman's NL-record 53 saves, they
won a major-league high 31 games. Dating back to July 24, 1996, the
Padres are 174-0 when leading in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we've got is guys who throw strikes,'' said Towers,
``guys who have more than one pitch, sliders or forkballs, guys who
have more than one above average pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were not quite so picky when the team convened in
February. From the bullpen that broke camp, only Ligtenberg and
43-year-old marvel Dennis Martinez remain. Adding hard-throwing
rookies John Rocker and Odalis Perez (major league experience: 10
games) to Rudy Seanez, who hadn't appeared in the majors since
1995, Cox had a group of fastballers.
</P>
<P>
   The missing ingredient came in through the clubhouse window.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't like the portrayal or the way people were talking
about our bullpen,'' said Martinez, whose two saves this year gave
him a total of three in the last 12 years. ``I didn't enjoy it and
I know the others didn't. Everyone was hollering to the roof and we
thought we didn't deserve that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think we should be treated that way as pitchers and
when we took it that way, I think it became more of a positive
mode. We tried to prove everyone wrong, try to make things happen
and to prove we could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   They will get no better chance this month. Since the night Jim
Leyritz took Mark Wohlers deep in Game 4 of the 1996 World Series,
Atlanta relievers have not allowed an earned run, a span of 18
innings that has done nothing to remedy the franchise's bullpen
stigma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody notices until they give up a run,'' said John Smoltz.
``They didn't give up a run to the Florida Marlins, didn't give up
a run to the Cubs. But all we got is a maligned bullpen, untested.
It's a shame. Maybe they can't win.''
</P>
<P>
   They can now. Those are the bells of October and they ring for .
. . whom?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
