<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Joyner says it's good to be back in October
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wally Joyner hasn't played in a league championship
series since 1986, when his California Angels lost to Boston. And
the Redan High graduate has never returned to his old stomping
grounds in a baseball uniform after September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wondered what it was like in October here,''
Joyner said Tuesday, before the Padres' workout at Turner Field.
``It's fun to be back. It's fun still to be playing. We thought in
spring training that this team was good enough to go somewhere in
October. We had a very good series against the Astros, played very
well, our pitchers were incredible and they won the (division)
series.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner, whose immediate family no longer lives in the area, will
start at first base. His earlier shoulder problems are no longer a
concern, and the left-hander's bat is needed against Braves
right-handed pitcher John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go out and do the job,'' said Joyner, who is ranked
second in baseball with a .412 average with runners in scoring
position. ``It's not going to be handed to us. The thing about
Atlanta is they have a game plan. If it's not working, instead of
panicking the first couple or three innings, they're going to stay
with it. What they know is eventually it's going to come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Not on the mound
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown said he was ready and willing to throw, but the
Padres opted to go with Andy Ashby for Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Kevin was more rested, because he is our ace, he would have
been the guy,'' said pitching coach Dave Stewart. ``He said,
`Whatever you need me to do, I'll do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   However, this would have been Brown's third consecutive start on
the fourth day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time he did it, he was outstanding,'' Stewart said.
``His second time out, I thought he threw the ball with great
velocity and had good stuff, but I thought his command was a little
bit off _ he walked five people. Even though he feels he is capable
of doing it, at some point we have to take responsibility as his
coach and his manager to look out for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is less accommodating with the media. He gave curt answers
about his Georgia Tech career in the clubhouse, then as he ran onto
the field he told a reporter, ``I've been turning everybody down,
it's a clean sweep.''
</P>
<P>
   On the mound
</P>
<P>
   Ashby was thrilled when Padres manager Bruce Bochy told him in
Houston that he would open the NLCS against the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing for me is just control my emotions and
excitement to a point where I can go out and do my job and be
effective,'' Ashby said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Braves are similar to the Houston lineup in that
``they've got speed at the top and a lot of power. But I think the
main thing is just stay away from the big inning. . . . Bochy said
right-hander Joey Hamilton, who lives in Atlanta, is a possible
Game 4 starter, depending on whether he is used in the bullpen in
the first three games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
