<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2887 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BETTY-CARTER-APPRAISA     10-06 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTY-CARTER-APPRAISAL-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECALLING BETTY CARTER, MENTOR TO A GENERATION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Jazz singer, composer, arranger nonpareil _ Betty
Carter, who died on Sept. 26 at the age of 69, was all these
things. But along with her own music, she leaves another
significant legacy with the musicians she nurtured, the careers she
helped shape. Over the last two decades, her band was an incubator
for jazz talent, and many young musicians who honed their skills
with Ms. Carter are now making their mark as leaders. With the
death of the drummer Art Blakey in 1990, Ms. Carter became the dean
of what insiders considered jazz's finest university. Here, eight
almuni recall the lessons they learned from a beloved teacher and
inspiring taskmaster. (Their ages and time spent with Ms. Carter
are noted below their names.)(end italics) Fletcher Roberts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRUCE FLOWERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pianist, 28. 1996-98 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Betty had a way that she liked to tell us how to play ballads.
We'd get finished playing something really fast and furious and
then we'd be trying to play a love song. And one night we were
playing, I think it was ``You Go to My Head.'' And right in the
middle of taking a solo, she comes over to the piano and she
whispers to me, ``Make love.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the first time I ever heard her say that, so I cracked
up. But it really made me aware that this wasn't about a show of
technique or anything complicated. It was just about the emotion.
And then right after that she said, ``for the ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is just to bring home the point that music is also for
females. She would always talk about that. And how if you really
want to reach everybody, you've got to think about women and
include them. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JACKY TERRASSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pianist, 32. 1993-94 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We used to do this tune, ``Lover Man,'' a duo, just me and her.
There was no particular arrangement, but every time we would try to
take it to another direction, and that was what we were looking
for, the mystery. I remember one time I was kind of playing some of
the obvious changes, and she was like ``uh, uh, uh, uh.''
</P>
<P>
   She wanted to make sure that we stayed in the area where we
weren't very sure where we were going to go and where it really
kept spontaneity going. She didn't want me to play the obvious
chord or the obvious change. She would just turn back and go ``uh,
uh, uh,'' you know, like play that funny stuff.
</P>
<P>
   That's kind of what I like doing anyway, so I was really
grateful to be able to share that with a singer, because a lot of
singers don't really like that. But Betty Carter was not only a
singer, she was more like part of the band, especially since she
improvised so well.
</P>
<P>
   I've worked with a lot of singers and I would say she's probably
the most honest of all the singers I've worked with because in her
area she had it all. So she had nothing to prove, you know. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BENNY GREEN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pianist, 35. 1983-87 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Betty had a reputation among musicians for having a bit of a
temper, but she could also show compassion. It was the summer of
'83. I'd been in her band for less than a year and I inadvertently
left her entire book of piano music in the back seat of a taxi in
the Village. And I didn't get a receipt from the driver.
</P>
<P>
   There was no name on the folder, no telephone number. There was
absolutely no way to recover this folio. And I called Betty that
evening, as soon as I got home. And Betty answered the phone, and I
said, ``Betty I have some bad news.'' And she said, ``What's wrong,
are you all right?'' I said: ``I'm fine, but I've lost your book of
piano music. It's gone. I left it in a taxi.'' Betty said: ``Oh,
O.K., as long as you're all right. We'll be able to put the music
back together.''
</P>
<P>
   I was just shocked, speechless. I think most people would have
panicked under the circumstance, and it was remarkable what a cool
head she kept. I think she cared about me and she treated me as
family. I think the side of her that I saw at that moment was there
for so many of her musicians. It's very easy to look at the surface
and see only a volatile personality. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XAVIER DAVIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pianist, 27. 1994-96 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'd been in the band about a week or so. We opened up for her
every night, whether it was the trio or quartet, if there was a
horn player. I decided this night we were just going to do a
standard called ``Remember.'' And so we didn't really have an
arrangement or anything, we were going to play the tune and just
try to swing and have fun.
</P>
<P>
   So we played it and we got through the whole show and everything
had actually been cool. I had heard that she could be hard to work
with, but I hadn't experienced any of that. She was always really
encouraging and everything.
</P>
<P>
   But that night, we were at this place called Catalina's Bar and
Grill in Los Angeles, and it's relatively small. The backstage was
separated from the dining area by just a little door. After the
performance, she came backstage and just went off on us. I don't
know if I can really say what she said in a family newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   She said you can't just go out there and play a tune without
putting some thought into it. The audience doesn't just want to
hear a jam session. She said if you ever open up like that again
... I was like, Wow. I'm about to get fired. And I've only been in
the band about a week. Betty wanted us to respect the audience.
</P>
<P>
   As jazz musicians there's a large repertory of tunes that we can
just play. And everyone knows the tunes and you don't necessarily
have to rehearse to play these tunes. So when we played this tune,
we played it well and we enjoyed it and we were swinging and
everything. But we (italics)were(end italics) treating it like a
jam session.
</P>
<P>
   Betty was telling us to think about the fact that the audience
had paid money to see us, and even if we've done something a
hundred times, the audience is usually hearing it for the first
time. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   JAVON JACKSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saxophonist, 33. 1994 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was making my first album, ``When the Time Is Right,'' which
Betty was the producer of, and there was a particular composition
we were doing, a standard, ``If Ever I Would Leave You.'' And we
did it pretty straightforward, and after we finished everybody in
the recording area kind of thought we had a pretty good take, and
Betty comes in, as only she could, and said it was ``boring.''
</P>
<P>
   And so we all kind of looked around, and she said, ``You know,
you guys have got to put more of you into it, make it a little bit
more distinctive in terms of your own delivery of it as a group.'
She suggested that maybe I do an intro and then go into the melody.
We did it again, and it was definitely a different version. I think
some of us probably still preferred the other version, but I began
to understand how unique musicians like Betty go at things.
</P>
<P>
   They try to find what is not there or the subtleties, really
trying to pull that out. And that was something that I learned from
that recording session. Betty was very, very unique, and she wanted
things to be as personal as possible. I think that experience has
helped me as a musician to try to be a little different. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WINARD HARPER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drummer, 36. 1984-88 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We really hit it off. I think it was because our work ethics
were kind of similar. We used to spend a lot of time together when
we were on the road, off the bandstand. She and I would sometimes
go to the movies together. Or shopping or just checking something
out.
</P>
<P>
   I remember one time in particular in New Mexico when I had
recently joined the band, Benny Green, Terry Shaw and myself and
her, we all went shopping. She took us to this hat shop in New
Mexico and everybody bought these black hats with wide brims.
Spending time together off the bandstand was important for me
because I wanted to understand her, her thinking, her approach to
music.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, for me, having some sort of camaraderie is a big part of
my playing because I like playing with people that I know, that I
have a lot of respect for. It's like you're all there trying to
create and make something that's of one mind and if you happen to
all be on the same wavelength or have some things in common, it
makes it much easier. And sometimes more magical. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CYRUS CHESTNUT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pianist, 35. 1991-93 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Betty always encouraged me to write a lot of music, try to come
up with something new, something different. Never just do something
just to get by or use tricks or gimmicks. One of her basic rules
was she didn't want to hear standards because she had already heard
them all.
</P>
<P>
   So one night I didn't think. I played the opening for ``If I
Were a Bell'' _ `ding-dong-ding-dong, ding-dong-ding-dong.'
(Laughs.) What did I do that for? Boy. Afterward she pulled me
aside and she gave me a lecture. She said: ``Why keep playing
something that's already been played? Why don't you think? You need
to think. I want people around me that think. Keep moving
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   So on and so on for half an hour. No one had ever jumped on me
with such great intensity before. So I mean it was like, you know,
Wow. But I always look at it like this: She knows what she wants
and she'll get it, I mean, you know, either pleasantly or
unpleasantly.
</P>
<P>
   She was in charge. No matter what we did, Betty was still in
charge. We may have opened up the set or whatever happened, but
when she came on, it was Betty time. And when she wanted something
different, boom, we were supposed to give it to her right then and
there. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARC CARY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pianist, 31. 1990-93 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We'd just played in Slovenia, which was part of Yugoslavia. And
we were on our way to Verona, Italy. We were on a tour doing
one-nighters, like six weeks of one-nighters. We had crossed the
border to Italy. I can't remember the town.
</P>
<P>
   The train was there so we got on, got our seats and realized
there was a train strike. So hours went by, man. It must have been
like 10 hours. The band started getting flaky, you know. Many
people started coming to the station. Must have been over a
thousand people at this point, trying to get a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody wanted a seat on this particular train. So Betty told
us, ``Look, you all have your money. If you all want to get a hotel
room, go get yourself a hotel room. I'm waiting on the train.'' We
were young and inexperienced. So we said ``O.K.,'' and went and we
found a hotel. There was one room. So we came back to the train and
told Betty: ``Look, we found a hotel room. You can have the bed,
and we'll take the floor.'' And Betty was like, ``No, I'm staying
on the train.''
</P>
<P>
   So of course we decided not to take the room. A couple hours
later the strike was over and the train left. We basically had to
stand up for maybe five hours on the train. We get to Verona just
in time to go to the venue and do the gig. The whole time no one
has had any sleep or anything. We get to the place, do the sound
check and change our clothes and do this concert. The band was just
whipped. We wanted to sleep. But Betty was a serious trouper.
</P>
<P>
   She could've easily canceled or postponed but she decided to do
this concert without any rest or anything. You know, she was very
professional. I carry that attitude to my own band. Musicians have
to cope with all kinds of circumstances. It's not all glamour, you
know. But Betty had a way of turning on the charm and really
blocking everything else out and dealing with the music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
