<HEADLINE>
LITTON, AMERICAN CLASSIC VOYAGES CRUISING FOR SHIP DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- In a deal that could re-energize the moribund
commercial shipbuilding industry in the United States, a unit of
Litton Industries Inc. and American Classic Voyages are in
negotiations to construct the first U.S.-built cruise vessels since
the late 1950s, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Litton's Ingalls Shipbuilding Division in Pascagoula, Miss.,
which built the last two domestic cruise ships 40 years ago, and
American Classic have signed a letter of intent to develop a design
and construction contract for the cruise line's Project America
program. The cruise-ship operator is controlled by billionaire
investor Sam Zell.
</P>
<P>
   A formal contract for two ships and an option for a third, each
worth $400 million, could be signed in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Litton beat out two other companies, National Steel and
Shipbuilding Co. in San Diego and Avondale Industries of New
Orleans, in a 10-month competition.
</P>
<P>
   The vessels will be the largest able to transit the Panama Canal
and will be designed to carry up to 2,000 passengers for the Hawaii
cruise market. Federal law requires the ships to be built in the
United States because they will be traveling between domestic
ports.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls is primarily known for building sophisticated warships
for the U.S. Navy, but the company doesn't think it will have any
trouble switching to a commercial application. Some of its vessels,
like multipurpose assault ships, have hotel space for 320 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a different customer, but it's not that far
outside our product line,'' said Ingalls spokesman James McIngvale.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls has been pursuing the cruise-ship market since 1995,
when the company initiated the Maritech project, which developed a
concept design and construction strategy for a 2,000-plus-passenger
vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very excited to work with Ingalls Shipbuilding in a
partnership which will revitalize America's commercial shipbuilding
industry,'' said Philip Calian, American Classic's president and
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people taking cruises has grown an average of 7.6
percent per year since 1980, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts were surprised by the announcement, since all of
the cruise-ship construction in recent years has occurred at
foreign ports, in part because those governments subsidize the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of cruise ships being built around the
world,'' said Paul Nesbit, an analyst at JSA Research Inc. in
Newport, R.I. ``They are much cheaper to build elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
