<HEADLINE>
GUITAR CENTER STOCK GETS ROCKED BY RETAIL SECTOR'S SOUR NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Stock of music-instrument specialist Guitar
Center Inc. hit its lowest point in more than a year as part of
Wall Street's continued disenchantment with the retail sector.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban Agoura Hills-based retailer's shares lost 14
percent Tuesday, dropping $2.375 to $14.25. That represents a 56
percent decline since Guitar Center hit its all-time high of $32.75
on July 17 and its worst performance since May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Investors began hammering Guitar Center's shares after it
announced in late July that same-store sales in the third and
fourth quarters would not match the ``very strong'' growth of 15.7
percent posted in the first two quarters. Six analysts have issued
``buy'' ratings on the stock since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like many other retail stocks, Guitar Center has come under
intense pressure since mid-July because of the perception that the
retail group is not the place to be,'' said analyst Alan Rifkin of
Piper Jaffray. Retail issues have been falling since the market
peaked July 17 on fears that the U.S. economy will follow Asia and
other emerging markets into recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guitar Center is as strong as it's ever been,'' said Rifkin,
who has a ``strong buy'' rating on the stock with a 12-month target
price of $24. ``The weakness in the stock does not reflect any
change in fundamentals. They are gaining market share in an
industry that's growing four times faster than the gross domestic
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Guitar Center, which operates 44 stores, earned $4.9 million on
sales of $91.3 million in the second quarter. It became the first
music-instrument retailer to go public, with a $115 million
offering at $15 a share in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
