A2895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYU-ONLINE-ART-NYT &LR;      10-06 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYU-ONLINE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYU TAKES MAJOR STEP IN INTERNET EDUCATION MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Moving to become a major player in the emerging
Internet education market, New York University, one of the nation's
largest educational institutions, plans to create a for-profit
subsidiary that will develop and sell specialized online courses to
other colleges, corporate training centers, as well as students who
simply prefer to attend class at home.
</P>
<P>
   The move is a direct response to what many educators see as the
biggest challenge to higher education: the rise of profit-making
companies like the University of Phoenix that threaten to siphon
off some of academia's most profitable courses _ continuing
education for adult learners _ and leave universities only in the
expensive business of undergraduate education.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these players are coming along, and we felt we needed
to get more assertive,'' said Gerald Heeger, Dean of NYU's School
of Continuing and Professional Studies, who will run the new
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   New York University already operates one of the largest
continuing education schools in the country. But unlike UCLA or
Penn State, which are developing a wide range of courses online,
NYU will start by offering a narrower range of courses that it
thinks will have broad demand _ including management, information
technology and computer languages, real estate and credit analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``On-line courses can be developed very cheaply, but what people
are discovering is that the success rates are not very high,''
Heeger said. ``The issue here is not to have thousands of courses,
but to have highly focused courses that meet large needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Universities have long reached beyond their own walls to offer
education to those off campus, through correspondence courses and
satellite campuses. But with the rise of the Internet, distance
education has suddenly become a new imperative, and universities
are scrambling to get a toehold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a broad recognition that the Internet really does
change the ball game,'' said Frank Mayadas, a former IBM executive
now at the Alfred P. Sloan Foundation, who has given grants to NYU
and other universities to help them develop their Internet
programs.
</P>
<P>
   He said that only a handful of colleges and universities _
including Penn State, the State University of New York, the
University of Illinois and the University of California at Berkeley
_ have entered the field in a sizable way. Most have fewer than
5,000 students on line.
</P>
<P>
   Like many universities, NYU has moved to put some of its courses
online, both for its 45,000 full-time students, and the 60,000
students who take its continuing education courses. And it will
continue to expand those offerings apart from the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
