<HEADER>
A2897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMF-BAILOUT-BOS &LR;      10-06 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-BAILOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURDLES REMAIN ON DEAL TO AWARD AGENCY $18B 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress inched closer Tuesday to an agreement to
replenish the strained reserves of the International Monetary Fund,
but significant hurdles remained.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton wants Congress to send nearly $18 billion to
the agency, which has committed $117 billion in loans to South
Korea, Thailand, and Indonesia amid the current economic crisis,
and is being asked to commit billions more to Brazil and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate generally supports Clinton's plan, but House
Republicans want to see major reforms at the IMF before committing
more money.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, several GOP lawmakers said they believed a deal was at
hand. ``We're about 80 percent there,'' the chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, Robert Livingston, told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Deb Fiddelke, spokeswoman to Senator Chuck Hagel, Republican of
Nebraska, said, ``We're definitely getting close, but to my
knowledge there is not a deal yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Davis, spokeswoman to one of the leading IMF critics in
Congress, House Republican leader Richard Armey, said new rhetoric
from Clinton in recent days had raised hopes of a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we heard from him from December until last week was,
`Give us the money with no strings attached.' Now, he's saying
there are certain things he expects from the IMF for it to work
better. There's definitely room for negotiations now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis said Armey remained adamant that Congress not release
money to the IMF until reforms were in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good enough to have the White House say, `Give us the
check, and we'll see if we can make the case''' for reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF is a 182-nation body charged with making sure the
world's currency exchange system works smoothly. It sometimes makes
loans to nations to help ease short-term currency problems, and in
the current crisis it has made large emergency loans to several
nations, most of them in Asia, to help as their stock markets and
currencies have fallen in value.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has significant powers to order reforms at the
IMF because it contributes the most money and holds the largest
share of votes.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $18 billion Clinton is requesting, House and Senate
leaders have agreed to set aside $3.5 billion for a new emergency
fund. House critics are balking at an additional $14.5 billion,
which represents the US share of an increase in contributions by
all members to shore up existing loan programs.
</P>
<P>
   A top aide to a senior Republican lawmaker said significant
roadblocks to a compromise remained.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Representative Jim Saxton, the New Jersey
Republican who leads the Joint Economic Committee, has proposed
legislation that would require the IMF to disclose more of its
practices and documents. Saxton wants minutes of IMF executive
board meetings to be made public, along with IMF staff analyses of
the effects its loan programs have on nations that borrow money. In
particular, IMF critics want to see a report that allegedly says
the IMF's own policies in Indonesia helped cause a bank run.
</P>
<P>
   But language that Senate Republicans proposed to their House
colleagues Tuesday would not require the IMF to disclose these
documents, the GOP aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Saxton's bill calls for the IMF to stop lending money
at subsidized rates. Some lawmakers believe that below-market loans
encourage investors and governments to take on undue risk in their
businss affairs in the belief that the IMF will provide a low-cost
bailout if their projects run into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate Republican language would not significantly
change IMF lending practices, the aide said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
