<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2898 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-ART-1     10-06 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE DEMOCRATS UNDER PRESSURE TO VOTE AGAINST BROAD IMPEACHMENT
INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add 9 grafs at end of story and for minor re-editing
throughout) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the House prepares to vote Thursday on beginning
an impeachment inquiry, Democratic leaders labored on Tuesday to
keep as many beleaguered Democrats as possible from voting for the
Republican proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders and Judiciary Committee members met throughout the day
to weigh the Democratic alternative they plan to offer this week,
and to consider bringing it closer to the Republican version in
hopes of appealing to a large bloc of nervous and angry moderates.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of a chaotic day, it appeared that they were
leaning against that approach and preferred staying with a proposal
Democrats offered on Monday in the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever approach they choose, the White House was still bracing
for desertions by anywhere from two dozen to several dozen
Democrats. The greater the level of defection, the harder it will
be to scoff at the vote as a partisan vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders, more concerned about their colleagues' electoral
success than their president, were seeking a way to enable the rank
and file to say they voted for a reasonable proposal for conducting
an inquiry into the president's behavior, but opposed a Republican
witch hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan, adopted on Monday by the Judiciary
Committee along party lines, has no time limit on the inquiry and
does not limit its focus to the possible charges recommended by
Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, who dealt only
with President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky and his
efforts to conceal it. Committee Democrats sought to give the
inquiry a Thanksgiving deadline and bar the consideration of
additional issues.
</P>
<P>
   The possible revisions being floated early on Tuesday included
extending the Thanksgiving deadline until the end of December, and
specifically allowing for the consideration of any new information
from the Office of Independent Counsel, Democratic officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For some Democrats, the idea of softening the alternative could
sweeten the pot. ``I'm trying to avoid polarizing this thing as a
political decision,'' said Rep. David Minge of Minnesota. ``I'm
searching for ways to accomplish that.''
</P>
<P>
   But for others the decision to vote for the Republican proposal
is all but a foregone conclusion. ``I'm going to vote for an
inquiry in order to move the process forward,'' said Rep. Chris
John, D-La. ``My district has consistently wanted to move this
along, and this is a way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John M. Spratt Jr., D-S.C., who is in a tight race for
re-election, said he favored an inquiry, but only one with a
deadline and a limited scope. ``If the Democratic alternative
fails, I've got a tough choice,'' Spratt said. ``I haven't ruled
out the Republican motion.''
</P>
<P>
   All day, Democrats on the Judiciary Committee and Democratic
whips tried to appeal to moderates by cautioning them that a vote
for the Republican proposal would doom the House to a long,
wide-ranging impeachment inquiry. But by evening, they seemed
discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton,
Vice President Al Gore and lobbyist friends of his like Thomas
Downey placed a new round of phone calls to House Democrats,
including some committee chairmen, to lobby and to gauge the mood.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said they could lose as many as 80
Democrats or as few as two dozen on the vote on the Republican
proposal. For their part, Republicans have said that as many as 100
Democrats could vote with them. But some on each side are playing
the expectations game, hoping to argue once the votes are cast that
they did better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote is coming awfully close to an election and a lot of
people are factoring that in,'' a White House official said.
``There will be a significant amount of people who will vote, not
based on how they feel, but on how they expect it to impact in
November.''
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating matters for the White House and its allies,
Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the majority leader, said on Tuesday that
Democrats would not be allowed to offer their proposal as a
clear-cut substitute to the open-ended Republican proposal.
Instead, Democrats will have to bring up their proposal under a
parliamentary maneuver in which debate is limited to one hour.
</P>
<P>
   And Armey again raised the possibility that the inquiry's scope,
under the direction of the Judiciary Committee chairman, Henry Hyde
of Illinois, could broaden to include accusations and evidence from
other investigations.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Committee on Government Reform and Oversight,
whose chairman is Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., is expected to vote to
release its interim report on 1996 Democratic campaign finance
abuses. A Republican aide with the committee said that there were
no impeachable offenses in the findings, but that at least one
chapter of the report contained information ``salient'' to the
Judiciary Committee's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The information deals mostly with ``White House stonewalling and
the abuse of executive privilege,'' the aide said. An estimated 80
witnesses took the Fifth Amendment or fled the country in order not
to testify before the panel, the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said on Tuesday: ``Let me remind you again, one of the
patterns that we see, that I certainly see is stonewall,
evasiveness, obstruction. So I mean these things will be pursued by
the committee.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Democratic leaders listened as member after member
expressed a sense of nervousness about the November elections and
anger toward Clinton, Democratic officials said. But by the end of
the day, the leaders had not decided on a course of action to bring
members together, torn in part between angering their traditional
liberal base and upsetting moderates who face tough re-election
bids. They will caucus Wednesday morning to discuss the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Some liberals complained that the president was worrying too
much about himself and not enough about the elections. And a few
said they were tempted to vote against any resolution that opened
the door to an impeachment investigation. That includes a
Democratic alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voting against Hyde is easy,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel of New
York, who opposes any impeachment inquiry. ``The Democratic
alternative, that's the problem. There's no alternative for those
of us who say the evidence does not rise to the level of an
inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Many New Democrats, who traditionally align themselves with
Clinton on policy matters, said they were not pleased about the
pressure they were getting from the White House. And moderates in
swing districts, who must answer to a large number of Republican
constituents, continued to express outrage about the president's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motion for an inquiry is a very proper motion,'' said Rep.
Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, stating his intention to vote for the
Republican resolution. ``I want the process to move as quickly and
expeditiously as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   While Democratic leaders stressed that ultimately members must
vote their conscience, Judiciary Committee members lobbied their
fence-sitting colleagues in the hopes of bringing them around.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an open-ended resolution, the only thing needed to keep
it going would be for someone to mail in new allegations,'' said
Rep. Robert Scott, a Virginia Democrat on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, several senior Democrats voiced skepticism that
Republicans would hold fair impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fairly convinced that House, as presently led, couldn't
conduct a fair trial on a parking ticket,'' said Rep. David Obey of
Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
