<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JONES-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES DEAL MAY BE DOWN TO A FINAL HAGGLE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Negotiations to settle the Paula Jones sexual
misconduct lawsuit against President Clinton as described by both
sides this week are increasingly coming to resemble the haggling in
a new car showroom.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones and the White House have powerful reasons to reach a
settlement, White House officials and friends of Ms. Jones have
said.
</P>
<P>
   But talks have stalled on how much money it will take to end the
lawsuit that led to Clinton's being put at risk of impeachment.
Friends of Ms. Jones have said she is inclined to reject the
president's last offer of $700,000, an increase over his previous
offer of $500,000. Ms. Jones has been asking for $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyers have not notified the White House of any decision,
and Ms. Jones and her husband are said to be mulling over whether
to stand firm on the $1 million demand.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones' husband, Stephen, has resisted making any significant
concessions, friends of Ms. Jones said Tuesday. Hillary Rodham
Clinton had been the staunchest opponent of concessions, until a
change of heart last month opened the way to settlement talks,
White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are facing a deadline of sorts on Oct. 20, when they
are scheduled to argue an appeal of Ms. Jones' case before a
three-judge appeals panel in St. Paul, Minn. Ms. Jones' lawyers are
asking the appeals court to reinstate her lawsuit against Clinton.
A federal trial judge dismissed Ms. Jones' lawsuit in April, saying
that even if her accusations were true, they would not constitute a
case of sexual harassment or deprivation of constitutional rights
as she has asserted.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Jones' lawyers have filed a brief with the appeals court
arguing that the case should be reinstated because Clinton has
admitted a sexual liaison with a former White House intern, Monica
Lewinsky. During a deposition in the case last January, Clinton
testified under oath that he had not engaged in ``sexual
relations'' with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones brought her suit in 1994, saying that three years
earlier, when Clinton was governor of Arkansas and she was a state
clerical employee, he had her summoned to a hotel suite in Little
Rock and asked her to perform oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has denied her account.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   White House advisers have said that eliminating the Jones
lawsuit from the scene could make it easier to persuade Congress to
avoid impeaching the president. Ms. Jones, who would get some money
out of a settlement, runs the risk of walking away from four years
of litigation with nothing if the appeals court rules against her.
</P>
<P>
   As is common in such negotiations, each side has sent signals
that it is losing patience and preparing to walk away from the
bargaining table. But the few hundred thousand that separates the
two sides is probably a bridgeable gap.
</P>
<P>
   The issue on which previous negotiations foundered _ Ms. Jones'
insistence on an apology from Clinton _ is no longer on the table.
Ms. Jones' lawyers have said that the president's admission about
Ms. Lewinsky has made an apology unnecessary. Indeed, some public
opinion polls have shown that a majority of people now believe
much, if not all, of Ms. Jones' account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
