<SLUG> BC-U.S.-SAUDI-EMBASSY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING SECURITY, U.S. BRIEFLY SHUTS SAUDI EMBASSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Having received information that the U.S. Embassy
in Saudi Arabia may be the target of a terrorist attack, the State
Department said Tuesday that the embassy and two other diplomatic
buildings will close Wednesday, so security can be tightened.
</P>
<P>
   The department said the embassy in Riyadh and the consulates
hundreds of miles away in Jiddah and Dhahran would be closed for
the day ``to review present security measures and to implement
physical security enhancements.''
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official said Tuesday night that he could
provide no further information on the nature or seriousness of the
threats, when and how the information had been received or what the
``enhancements'' would be.
</P>
<P>
   In its announcement, the department noted that a number of
embassies and consulates had received threats since the Aug. 7
bombings of the embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam,
Tanzania, that killed more than 250 people and injured thousands.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department official emphasized that only the
embassy in Riyadh was the target of the latest threat.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats have been wary since the United States launched
missile attacks Aug. 20 against suspected terrorist camps in
Afghanistan and Sudan. Those camps are believed to be run by Osama
bin Laden, a wealthy Saudi exile whom the United States blames for
the bombings in August. U.S. officials have said they expect bin
Laden to try to retaliate for those strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said Tuesday that Saudi authorities
``continue to provide full support to insure the security of the
embassy, as well as of the consulates general and United States
military elements'' in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   But an Arab diplomat who insisted on anonymity, described
closings as ``a bit of an overreaction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Embassy is very secure,'' the diplomat said,
describing the complex as naturally fortified by hills and further
protected by artificial obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1995 seven people were killed in a bombing at a
U.S.-run military building in Riyadh. In June 1996, 19 U.S. airmen
were killed in the bombing of an apartment complex in Dhahran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
