<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P DECLINE, WHILE DOW CLIMBS SLIGHTLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed in a volatile session as investors remained
nervous about the world economy. The Nasdaq composite index
declined 25.80, or 1.68 percent, to 1,510.89, and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index fell 3.97 percent, or 0.4 percent, to
984.59.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 16.74 points, or 0.22
percent, to 7,742.98, spurred by better-than-expected earnings at
Alcoa and Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T'S NEW LUCKY DOG PHONE UNIT
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has introduced a brand that does not mention the telephone
company's name, a first in its 113-year history. The brand, Lucky
Dog Phone, is pitching a ``dial around'' service called 10-10-345
that lets consumers gain access to special calling promotions by
dialing a code before entering a long-distance number. Lucky Dog
also intends to give away prizes to promote the service.
</P>
<P>
   A CHALLENGE FROM EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   European governments are challenging the United States over how
to address the world financial crisis, suggesting that new ideas
and leadership are needed as the turmoil persists and Congress
continues to block new funds for the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the World Bank publicly broke with the approach
that the United States and the IMF have taken in managing the
global economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZILIAN MARKET INCREASES 3.49 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian investors took the decision by Spain's central bank to
cut interest rates by half a percentage point as a sign that Europe
would begin taking steps to alleviate the crisis threatening
Brazil. This spurred the Brazilian market, the Bovespa, to jump
3.49 percent, or 213.51 points, to 6,336.35.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN LEADER APPEALS FOR CALM
</P>
<P>
   Russia's prime minister appealed for calm as communists and
trade unionists prepared to strike over the ravaged economy.
</P>
<P>
   IBM IN DEAL WITH FRANCE TELECOM
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom and IBM plan to develop a network to let
customers surf the Internet with screen-based telephones. If all
goes according to plan, the new devices would give technophobic
customers access to the Internet without using a personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE HALTS DERIVATIVE REGULATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate temporarily blocked the Commodities Futures Trading
Commission from regulating over-the-counter derivative securities.
The moratorium, contained in an agricultural spending bill that the
Senate approved by a 55-43 vote, is effective until March 30.
</P>
<P>
   OPPOSITION TO JAPAN PROPOSAL
</P>
<P>
   A plan by the Japanese government to shift debt of 180 billion
yen, or $1.34 billion, onto seven railway companies formed when the
national railroad system was privatized is receiving opposition.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINE AIRLINES WILL FLY AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   The death of Philippine Airlines was premature. The country's
president, Joseph Estrada, has settled a strike by its union and
its debt. A number of the carrier's domestic flights will be
reinstated this week, and there is talk of resuming flights to the
United States next week.
</P>
<P>
   CAN CABBAGE PATCH DOLL BE BEAT?
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Electronics has started a television campaign for this
sweet, if slightly scary-looking, little playmate called Furby,
which the company hopes will be a big seller this holiday season.
Furby, which is described as having bug eyes, big ears and a
playful voice that becomes snippy if not enough attention is paid
to the creature, sells for about $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
