<HEADER>
A2911 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUNTER-HENLEY-THEATER     10-06 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNTER-HENLEY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARING A HISTORY AS WELL AS A PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Miss., Ga.)   (ART ADV: Photo of Holly Hunter is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11)  
 (af)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Holly Hunter and Beth Henley had not been stuck in
an elevator together 16 years ago on their way to an audition for
Ms. Henley's play ``The Wake of Jamey Foster,'' the two would have
found each other eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hunter has appeared in six Henley plays and on Thursday she
will open in the seventh, ``Impossible Marriage,'' a production by
the Roundabout Theater Company at the Laura Pels Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met her under professional auspices and that is where I was
most comfortable with Beth for some time,'' said Ms. Hunter, over a
recent Manhattan dinner. ``However, we clicked in a monstrous
way.''
</P>
<P>
   With Southern roots, small physical frames and straight, cropped
hair in common, Ms. Hunter, 40, and Ms. Henley, 46, seem like two
of a kind. Ms. Henley, who was born and brought up in Mississippi,
helped advance Ms. Hunter's career as an actress; Ms. Hunter, who
comes from Georgia, helped solidify Ms. Henley's success as a
playwright.
</P>
<P>
   Both appear to have struck a delicate balance between the public
selves they dutifully present and the private lives they fiercely
protect. And they clearly share a deep affection and respect for
each other.
</P>
<P>
   So when people suggest that Ms. Henley has somehow dropped off
the map in the 14 years since her last New York hit, ``The Miss
Firecracker Contest,'` Ms. Hunter gets defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always weird to me when people talk about a comeback,''
she said. ``When somebody's life is examined up close these days,
they're always going somewhere, when really they've never been
away. She's always been a playwright, making a living at it. Beth
writes every day, all year long, every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it is largely because Ms. Henley has been absent
from the New York theater scene that the Roundabout decided to
commission her to write the play that became ``Impossible
Marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention,'' said Todd Haimes, the company's artistic
director, ``was to commission plays by established playwrights, but
perhaps playwrights who were not being produced as often as we'd
like to see them produced. We came up with a list of playwrights
that interested us who hadn't been seen recently in New York and
Beth Henley happened to be at the top of the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henley, who lives in Los Angeles with her 3-year-old son,
has, as Ms. Hunter says, been busy writing: her plays have included
two that were presented at the Manhattan Theater Club _ ``The Lucky
Spot'' in 1987 and ``Abundance'' in 1990, both of which received
mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henley has also written screenplays, including ``Nobody's
Fool,'' which starred Rosanna Arquette and Eric Roberts, and two
adaptations of her own plays. One was for the film version of her
first stage hit, the 1981 Pulitzer Prize-winning ``Crimes of the
Heart'' (for which she was nominated for an Academy Award in 1987).
</P>
<P>
   The other for ``Miss Firecracker,'' a 1989 movie that starred
Ms. Hunter, as had the 1984 stage version. Both plays were also
done at the Manhattan Theater Club.
</P>
<P>
   During a sandwich break while rehearsing ``Impossible
Marriage,'' Ms. Henley said that she writes screenplays more out of
necessity than passion. ``If I could make the same money writing
plays as writing movie scripts, I don't think I would do it,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she acknowledged, she could have lived
without writing ``Revelers,'' a 1994 play about an acting company
that gathers at a wake to spread the ashes of their teacher. But
ultimately, Ms. Henley said, every one of her projects has been
valuable. ``I've been exploring what concerns me and how it
concerns me,'' she said, ``and I would not trade writing those
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very blessed,'' she added, ``because `Crimes of the
Heart' was a hit and has allowed me to be a writer for this many
years. Of all the good things I've done well in my life, I think
life as a playwright is the one I'm most pleased with.''
</P>
<P>
   Her plays, particularly ``Crimes of the Heart'' and ``The Miss
Firecracker Contest,'' have won praise for their quirky Southern
sensibility, insights into women's relationships and Gothic humor.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hunter said she is attracted to the physicality of Ms.
Henley's characters, their wildness, how their primitive instincts
collide with civilized society. ``She writes about parts of
ourselves that we may not even want to claim,'' the actress said.
</P>
<P>
   The current play, ``Impossible Marriage,'' takes place in
Savannah, Ga., on the eve of a wedding and reveals a tangle of
family secrets surrounding three Southern women _ two sisters and
their mother. In writing it, Ms. Henley said she was interested in
investigating many kinds of incompatibility: ``How do we marry our
dark and light sides? How do you marry lust with love? Being a
mother with being a woman?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
