<DOCNO> NYT19981006.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2913 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUNTER-HENLEY-THEATER     10-06 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNTER-HENLEY-THEATER-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: a woman?''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet in spite of the complexity that these questions suggest, the
author said she also wanted to write ``a happy play, an ebullient
play.'' That is what she said her mother wanted _ that and nice
costumes. She was also eager to enter the world of fantasy. ``I was
tired of naturalness _ tired of it for the stage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Ms. Hunter's role, that of Floral Whitman, the older,
very pregnant, emotionally volatile sister of the bride, Ms. Henley
said the play was difficult to cast. ``It has a tricky tone,'' she
said. ``It requires striking some sort of balance between deep,
deep tragedy and foolish whimsy and being able to go from one to
the other as kind of a hairpin turn.'' Directed by Stephen
Wadsworth, the cast includes Christopher McCann, Lois Smith, Jon
Tenney, Gretchen Cleevely, Daniel London and Alan Mandell.
</P>
<P>
   Did she write the part of Floral with Ms. Hunter in mind? ``I
always have Holly in mind,'' Ms. Henley said. ``As soon as I see
her do a reading, it becomes impossible to think of anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   While most actors might find it heady to have roles written for
them, Ms. Hunter, who won an Academy Award in 1993 for her
performance in the film ``The Piano,'' seems to take it in stride.
``It's irrelevant,'' she said. ``I don't see any of myself in the
characters. I see more of Beth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henley made Ms. Hunter's Broadway debut possible in ``Crimes
of the Heart'' after it had opened at the Manhattan Theater Club.
Ms. Hunter, who replaced Mary Beth Hurt, said that her audition was
terrible but that Ms. Henley pulled for her anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hideous, awful, vulgar, wrong for it, much too young for
it,'' Ms. Hunter said. ``She fought for me to get the role.'' (Ms.
Hunter left ``Crimes of the Heart'' to play the lead in ``The Wake
of Jamey Foster'' in 1982.)
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the actress said, she has found each one of her
roles in Ms. Henley's plays challenging. For example, she said, it
was ``agony'' performing in Ms. Henley's ``Control Freaks,'' a
black comedy about a murderous family that she helped produce at
the Met Theater in Los Angeles in 1993. `` `Control Freaks' was one
unrelenting rage,'' Ms. Hunter said. ``I hated for it to begin and
I couldn't wait for it to end.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, she said, she is relishing the role of Floral in
``Impossible Marriage'': ``She is a radical, she is rebellious, a
truth-teller, really manipulative. She is courageous, a protector
and a fighter, an extremist. She has wickedness, she's a schemer,
she has plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Ms. Hunter added, ``she has magnificence.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Living Out Loud,'' her new film, a romantic comedy inspired
by two Chekhov stories that opens next month, the actress plays a
woman who sees life with new eyes after her husband leaves her and
she develops a friendship with her elevator operator, portrayed by
Danny DeVito.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to change how I approach acting as I get older,'' Ms.
Hunter said. ``I want there to be a reason I'm playing certain
characters at certain times. I think characters come to me when I'm
ready to play them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hunter said she does Ms. Henley's plays out of a similar
sense of necessity, not just out of loyalty. ``I do Beth's plays
because I know they will be an adventure,'' she said, elbows on the
table, chin on her hands. ``We hooked up in a way that I don't even
understand and she doesn't understand and I play homage to our
history and feel loyal to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do this for her and I've never stopped wanting to do
this with her,'' Ms. Hunter said. ``It's just a history in my life
and she's the only one I have it with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
