<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNNEMAN-NRT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. COMPANY TO BUY HUNNEMAN REAL ESTATE CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ NRT Corp., a New Jersey-based real estate brokerage
giant already in possession of several national brand names, is
expected to finalize a deal Wednesday to buy Hunneman Real Estate
Corp. _ the largest residential real estate brokerage firm in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hunneman officials and NRT refused to divulge terms of the
sale, though they did say it is not expected to result in layoffs
among the 3,000 employees in any of Hunneman's 75 New England
offices. Hunneman will still use its own name both in its
residential and commercial business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a seamless transaction from the perspective of the
agents,'' Stuart W. Pratt, Chairman and CEO of Hunneman, said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is the latest regional firm to be snapped up by a
national corporation in a consolidation frenzy that is gripping the
residential real estate industry from coast-to-coast. Fueling the
acquisition demand are well-funded buyers in search of new
companies and brokerage firms that have grown in value during a
healthy market.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the latest in a string of acquisitions by NRT, which
is expected to issue a public stock offering sometime early next
year. Since it was formed in 1997 as a joint venture between the
Cendant Corp. (HFS Inc.) and Apollo Management, NRT has acquired
more than 27 residential brokerage firms throughout the United
States in major metropolitan areas including New York, Atlanta, Los
Angeles, and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has an estimated worth of more than $63
billion, already owns several well-known real estate franchises,
including Coldwell Banker, Century 21, and ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts praised the sale, which comes at a high point in the
residential real estate market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of what's going on in the industry, it's probably the
only way to survive. What you either have to be is a real small
boutique with a specialty, or a big company with a reach around the
world,'' said analyst Ray Torto, managing director of Torto Wheaton
Research in Boston. ``You know what they say about people who stand
in the middle of the road: they get hit from traffic on both
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sales and leasing, the company also offers home
security, construction, and mortgage services. Its residential
division is affiliated with Coldwell Banker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the direction the industry has been going in for years,
it is just reaching a crescendo currently, which is something you
would anticipate during a very solid real estate market,'' said Jim
Dougherty, director of marketing for Carlson Real Estate/Better
Homes and Gardens, and president-elect of the Massachusetts
Association of Realtors. Earlier this year, Carlson aquired the
Springfield-based Landry, Lyons, &AMP; Whyte.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pratt said his company encountered other suitors _ among
them Prudential Real Estate Corp. and Insignia Financial Group _
but opted for NRT because the company permits a high degree of
local control. ``Our business is absolutely a local business and
the second you take away local autonomy, this whole thing doesn't
work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Morever, Pratt said linking with a larger, national company
should allow Hunneman to offer such things as more attractive
interest rates on its mortgage products. At the direction of NRT,
Hunneman is already making plans to itself gobble up a number of
smaller Massachusetts real estate firms, Pratt said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody touted the state's latest behemoth, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's a windfall for the owners, but the only reason
that people sell is for the money, it's not for an advantage,''
Richard B. DeWolfe, president of DeWolfe New England, said upon
learning of the acquisition. ``I hope it will dramatically improve
our business, because we are locally owned and operated.''
</P>
<P>
   Added DeWolfe: ``It's not just about business, it's also about
the community. I'm one of those people who don't think New York and
New Jersey should own Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, DeWolfe said NRT officials last year said they were
interested in purchasing his company, but he turned the company
down because ``we are not interested in selling, we are interested
in building our business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
