u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-KEY-1STLED     10-06 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-KEY-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    5 keys to Braves success in NLCS
 &HT;    (EDS: Resending correct game information)
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. GET THE BIG CAT PURRING
</P>
<P>
   No one's transformed the Braves' lineup more than Andres
Galarraga. Batting cleanup, the Big Cat led the club in homers (44,
a franchise record for first basemen), RBIs (121) and slugging
percentage (.595). With 414 RBIs over the last three seasons, he's
the first NL player in 50 years with 400 or more RBIs in a
three-year span. But after hitting his 41st and 42nd homers Aug.
30, Galarraga had a quiet September. In 20 games, he hit .283
(19-for-67) with just two homers and nine RBIs.Galarraga needs to
rediscover his August stroke and reinvigorate the middle of the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   2. NOW LEADING OFF SECOND, WALT WEISS
</P>
<P>
   Now that Atlanta's shortstop is once again healthy, wealthy and
Weiss, the Braves need Walt Weiss to be on base more, too. As adept
defensively as advertised, Weiss was, when healthy, a revelation as
a leadoff man. While Weiss hit .280 (22 points above his career
average of .258 entering 1998), his on-base percentage of .386
(157-of-407) was fourth-best among NL leadoff men. Atlanta was
68-28 (.708) when Weiss started, but he played only 96 games due to
a chronically strained right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   3. MISSION IMPOSSIBLE: TONY GWYNN
</P>
<P>
   No one hits Braves pitching like Gwynn, the eight-time NL
batting champion who hit .321 this year his 16th straight .300
season. Against Atlanta's big three of John Smoltz, Tom Glavine and
Greg Maddux, Gwynn went 4-for-8 with two doubles, a homer (off
Glavine) and two RBIs this year. His career numbers against that
six-Cy Young threesome, however, are truly staggering: 91-for-226,
.402, four homers, 17 walks and but three strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   4. BE SAFELY HOME BY 7
</P>
<P>
   In other words, score quickly, take an early lead and make sure
it's maintained by the seventh-inning stretch. If not, Atlanta's at
the mercy Trevor Hoffman. Hoffman was the premier closer in the big
leagues in '98, tying Randy Myers NL record of 53 saves. The Braves
were hitless in 10 at-bats this season (four K's) against Hoffman,
who earned saves in all three of his appearances against Atlanta
(three innings, three K's). He's historically tough on Galarraga
(2-for-10 lifetime, seven K's), Javy Lopez (1-for-7, three K's) and
Weiss (1-for-8, one walk).
</P>
<P>
   5. A SAN DIEGO BROWNOUT
</P>
<P>
   Although he won't start Game 1 and thus won't pitch three times
if the series goes the full seven games , Kevin Brown is a big
Braves hurdle to overcome.Brown beat Atlanta twice in last year's
NLCS while with Florida. Brown started just once this season
against Atlanta, a 2-0 shutout Aug. 20 in San Diego. He's
exceptionally tough against Braves batters, especially Galarraga
(2-for-11, five K's), Ryan Klesko (3-for-17) and Lopez (2-for-14,
one homer).
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
