<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Industry Hails AMD Profits As Good Sign   By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In a signal that the worst may be over for the semiconductor
industry, Advanced Micro Devices Inc. reported a surprising
third-quarter profit yesterday and stronger-than-expected sales.
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMD's net profit of $1.01 million, or 1 cent a share, comes on
the heels of Monday's announcement by Motorola Inc., the world's
third-largest chipmaker, of a profitable third quarter and upbeat
projections for 1999 sales and revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Chip industry analysts said the results showed the semiconductor
industry recovering from a painful, long-running slump but were
divided on whether it signaled an immediate upswing
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been saying for a while now that the light is at the
end of the tunnel for the semiconductor industry. The AMD results
as well as the Motorola results are evidence of that,'' said Mark
Edelstone, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we are seeing a recovery in the marketplace coming
off a very difficult environment in the first half of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ashok Kumar, an analyst with Piper Jaffray Inc., said that,
although the worst may be over, the industry still may not start
recovering for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're going to see more of an L-shaped correction,''
Kumar said. ``Things are going to drag along the bottom for quite
some time.''
</P>
<P>
   AMD, the Sunnyvale chipmaker that had posted four consecutive
losing quarters, surprised Wall Street analysts by reporting it had
turned a profit for the third quarter that ended September 27.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected AMD to lose 11 cents per share, according
to First Call Corp., and even the more optimistic projections had
AMD losing 5 cents a share. AMD itself didn't expect to regain
profitability until the fourth quarter, especially after posting a
$64.5 million loss in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   AMD said sales of its K6-2 microprocessor, launched in May as
its latest competitor to Intel's Pentium II, led the boost in
third-quarter revenues to $685.9 million for the quarter, compared
to sales of $526.5 million in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments of K6 increased by more than 1 million units to 3.8
million units, and sales increased 70 percent compared to the
second quarter, Saunders said.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders also noted PC Data showed the K6 had captured 54
percent of the sub-$1,000 computer market.
</P>
<P>
   AMD announced that Sony Corp. plans to use the K6-2 chip in its
newest Vaio computers that will be launched in Japan later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a recent forecast by Dataquest of San Jose said the
worldwide semiconductor market will grow 11.8 percent in 1999
following a decline of 6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstone said a ``snap back'' in demand for computers will
boost the semiconductor industry, and AMD in particular.
</P>
<P>
   One risk in the fourth quarter is that chip-production cutbacks
earlier this year may mean there aren't enough PCs to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were too pessimistic in their forecasts for second-half
demand,'' Edelstone said.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar was less enthusiastic about AMD's results, saying the
underlying economic problems that exacerbated the chip slump
remain. He maintained his neutral rating on AMD.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has changed?'' Kumar said. ``Japan is in the mother of
all recessions and it's going to be for years and years before they
show signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Even though AMD's K-6 chip has cut into Intel's market share,
it's at the lower-end, sub-$1,000 PC market level, which has lower
profit margins, Kumar said.
</P>
<P>
   Questions remain about whether AMD can deliver its planned K7
chip to compete in the more lucrative corporate PC market with
Intel, which has that area ``in its crosshairs,'' Kumar said.
</P>
</TEXT>
