<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 S.F. Money Manager Listed Erroneous Degrees on Resume   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Institutional money manager Frank Husic didn't get a doctorate in
economics from the University of Pennsylvania. Nor did he earn a
bachelor's degree in economics from Carnegie Mellon University in
Pittsburgh.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trouble is, documents filed by his San Francisco firm, Husic
Capital Management, with the Securities and Exchange Commission
stated that he did. And that's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Husic is, and has been for some time, a successful money
manager. The firm he founded has more than $3.6 billion under
management, meaning it handles big chunks of money for corporate
and government pension funds. In addition, it dabbles in mutual
funds. Until earlier this year, Husic Capital managed a portfolio
for Vanguard, the highly regarded mutual fund company.
</P>
<P>
   But now it remains to be seen how Husic's starched-collar
clients will react to the revelation that he may have fudged on his
academic credentials. After all, pension fund advisers aren't
exactly the boat shoe and khaki crowd that do handshake deals over
flapjacks at Buck's in Woodside. This is corporate America _ cubed
_ we're talking about here.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, the world of institutional money management
plays by the rules because it is playing with other people's money:
most likely yours and mine. These people are a very conservative
lot, and the possibility that one of their kind padded the ol'
resume isn't likely to be shoved under the rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Integrity is everything in this business,'' says B. Thomas
Willison, a longtime management and marketing consultant to money
managers who now lives near Lake Tahoe. And the falsification of
academic credentials ``would certainly call into question virtually
everything a firm has done.''
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancies in Husic's records were unveiled when his
company amended a filing to the federal government in August. Money
management firms are required to file forms with the SEC that
provide basic information about their operations and principals.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Husic Capital reported that Frank Husic had a
doctorate from Penn and an undergraduate degree from Carnegie
Mellon. Now, the company has revised its records with the SEC and
implies that the federal agency got it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``After discovering some factual inaccuracies, Husic Capital
Management earlier this year corrected information pertaining to
Frank Husic's academic background,'' according to a statement
provided by the firm's publicist in Los Angeles. Husic would not
grant an interview.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, according to the company's statement, Husic
holds an undergraduate degree in mathematics from Youngstown State
University, a master's degree in business from the University of
Pennsylvania and a master's degree in industrial administration
from Carnegie Mellon.
</P>
<P>
   And what else can Husic say? If his records were falsified, any
sign of culpability would open the money manager to greater
scrutiny by the feds and would inflict additional damage to his
credibility. Needless to say, knowingly reporting false information
to the SEC would violate its rules. For its part, the SEC isn't
saying much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as a policy matter, don't state whether we are
investigating people. So I can't comment,'' says Helane Morrison,
the SEC's head of enforcement in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it could all be a big mistake. It's possible that the
bureaucrats in Washington might have screwed up. And one might be
inclined to give Husic the benefit of the doubt if there were only
a single discrepancy. Unfortunately for Husic, there were three: no
Ph.D. and the wrong undergraduate college and degree. (Forgive me
if I'm wrong, but even an inside-the-Beltway paper-pusher ought to
recognize the difference between Youngstown State and Carnegie
Mellon.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, don't expect any official repercussions from this
credential snafu. Sources close to the SEC say the agency isn't
likely to pursue a false-records case. The offense isn't egregious
enough. Which begs the question: What's the downside to fudging on
SEC documents?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long after President Clinton admitted that he lied to
the nation about having sex with Monica Lewinsky that the debate
was reshaped to examine the degree to which he lied.
</P>
<P>
   And in other cases, the debate centers on the degree to which a
fib becomes a major offense. But ethics professor Kirk Hanson at
the Stanford Graduate School of Business says fudging on academic
records doesn't have to become a federal case to warrant serious
concern. Sometimes it leads to a pattern of breaking the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were an investor and senior management was suspected to
have falsified documents ... I would want to examine the (firm in
question) with a fine-toothed comb,'' Hanson says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
