<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 New Buy By Lycos _ Wired Digital   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Wired Digital, the last remnant of San Francisco digital media
empire Wired Ventures, was sold yesterday to Internet directory
firm Lycos for $83 million in stock.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The acquisition is the latest in a buying binge by Lycos to
establish its online service as &UR;  &LR; a major portal _ an all-in-one Web
site that combines e-mail, chat rooms, search engines and other
features to hook users and generate advertising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cements our position as a leading media company,'' Lycos
chief executive Bob Davis said in an interview. ``People want
original, brand-name news content and personality on their sites,
not just wire stories. You need to give them reasons to log on and
stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waltham, Mass., company plans to integrate all of Wired
Digital's operations into its service.
</P>
<P>
   Wired News, which posts breaking news and commentary on the
high-tech industry, will be the main source of news on Lycos.
HotWired, Wired's cultural lifestyle Web 'zine, will provide
features.
</P>
<P>
   The HotBot search engine, which reaches 4 million visitors a
month, will be combined with Lycos' popular search engine.
Webmonkey will continue as a resource for online developers, and
the satirical Suck.com magazine will be spotlighted as an
alternative Web community.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In all, Wired Digital attracts about 5 million users a month,
ranking it among the 25-most visited Internet sites, according to
Relevant Knowledge, an Atlanta market researcher. (Lycos ranked
fourth in the August poll.)
</P>
<P>
   Lycos also expects to sweeten e-commerce deals with the likes of
CDnow and Barnes and Noble because Wired users tend to buy more
goods online than other Web surfers.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos' acquisition of Wired Digital is its splashiest pickup,
but hardly its only one.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Lycos has purchased companies to create personal Web
pages (WhoWhere for $133 million) and communities (Tripod, $58
million), provide free e-mail (MailCity, a product from WhoWhere)
and offer an online travel service (Guest-World, $4 million).
</P>
<P>
   The additions are expected to bolster its audience against
rivals Yahoo, Excite and Infoseek. Industry experts said Lycos
needed to dramatically expand its online offerings to compete
against such well-known brand names.
</P>
<P>
   But one Lycos competitor said the company's challenge goes far
beyond buying popular Web sites. ``It's not about traffic and page
views,'' the rival said. ``It's about building customer loyalty and
brand-name recognition.'' The move also increases Lycos' presence
in the Bay Area. With the addition of 150 Wired Digital workers in
San Francisco, Lycos will employ 250 people on the West Coast, 600
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an inexpensive, smart acquisition _ considering the
amount of money that companies are throwing at Internet
properties,'' said analyst Andrea Williams of Volpe Brown Whelan in
San Francisco. ``Wired Digital differentiates Lycos from Yahoo and
Excite, and it is on the verge of profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Wired Digital's sales are expected to nearly double _ to $24
million this year _ and it should be profitable by the end of 1998,
company executives said.
</P>
<P>
   While the buyout signifies the emergence of Lycos as a major
portal player, it also marks the end of Wired Ventures, the
trail-blazing media company that started in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Co-founders Louis Rossetto and Jane Metcalfe will have no role
at Lycos, and Wired Venture's board of directors will be dissolved
after the deal is completed later this year, a Wired spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to mount an initial public offering in 1996,
Rossetto stepped down as CEO in July 1997. In May, Wired Ventures
sold its flagship magazine for $75 million to Advance Publications
Inc., the New York owner of the New Yorker and Conde Nast, which
publishes Vogue, Cosmopolitan and Vanity Fair, among others.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Wired Ventures executives said the sale of the
5-year-old monthly would enable it to pay off short-term debt and
plow more money into the online business.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the online division yesterday acknowledged it
had been exploring other options. Executives said they were in
discussions with Lycos and several unnamed companies for several
months about a buyout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a number of strategic alternatives: Either we remain
independent, go public, merge or sell,'' said Beth Vanderslice,
president of Wired Digital. ``Lycos gave our product and people the
best opportunity to play on a larger scale. We took it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
