<SLUG> BC-MA-COLLEGE-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESLEY, ART INSTITUTE OF BOSTON, TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Lesley College and the Art Institute of Boston plan to
announce their merger Wednesday, an improbable alliance that
highlights how colleges are scrambling to be more attractive to
applicants in an increasingly competitive field.
</P>
<P>
   Absorbing the art institute, the oldest art school in Boston,
will mean Cambridge-based Lesley can increase its lucrative adult
education programs, appealing to the fastest growing population in
higher education, and move closer to becoming a university. That
change alone can significantly boost prestige, and desirability,
for a school that now is known mostly for teacher programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an example of changing and being flexible with the
times,'' Lesley president Margaret McKenna said. ``Colleges need to
think of creative ways of doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``This doesn't mean Lesley wants to become Harvard, but within
the region of competition, it has to make itself as attractive as
it can be,'' said Clare Cotton, head of the Association of
Independent Colleges and Universities of Massachusetts. ``All
colleges are looking for ways to broaden their appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   While enrollment at small schools with ``college'' in the name
has declined since the 1970s, enrollment at ones designated
``universities'' has increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families believe that a university offers a wider spectrum of
courses and programs, and a wider variety of job options after
college,'' Cotton said. ``A lot of what families are looking for in
a school is a job after graduation. That's a major change over the
past 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 89-year-old Lesley has already begun emphasizing its
self-designation as ``a modern university,'' although the official
change would require approval by state agencies and accreditors,
and the creation of additional PhD programs. Now, Lesley offers
just one, in education, but the merger opens the possibility of a
PhD program in fine arts.
</P>
<P>
   The art institute, with 500 undergraduate students, will stay in
its current building on the edge of Kenmore Square, and become the
fifth school within Lesley, adding to the Graduate Schools of
Education, Management, and Arts and Social Sciences, and the School
of Undergraduate Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The institute boasts enrollment at a 25-year high and solid
financial status. But the merger will allow it to expand programs,
and with that, attract more students. Undergraduates have asked the
school for years to begin programs in art therapy and arts
education, and Lesley offers both. The school, as part of Lesley,
will also begin masters programs in fine arts. And if students
decide to abandon art degrees, it will mean changing majors, not
reapplying to schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about the students, it's hard to think of any
negatives,'' said AIB president Stan Trecker. &UR;  &LR; ``They just have
more options rather than fewer. If there are logical reasons to do
it for the students, you can make the distance between the campuses
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger doesn't address several weaknesses at both schools.
Between them, they still have no athletic facilities or fields. The
Art Institute still needs dorms. Lesley, with 1,500 undergraduates
and 4,500 graduates, was ranked second in the North for highest
student debt load in this year's US News and World Report rankings,
which generally means the school is expensive and doesn't offer
sufficient financial aid. And its teacher-training program, which
turns out the most of any private institution in Massachusetts,
also had the second-highest rate of failures among private schools
with significant numbers of test-takers on the state teacher tests
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the merger does offer other benefits to Lesley, which in
recent years has also started a school in Israel and programs in
other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lesley doesn't have a presence in Boston, and we have a very
strong presence in Boston,'' said Rosemarie Sansone, a board member
at the Art Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The merger has been quietly in the works since January, and was
approved by the boards at both schools this month.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna acknowledged that the merger might seem unexpected,
given that the schools are relatively far apart in distance, and
don't completely meet one another's needs. Still, she said, they
shared a similar atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to almost everyone who has done a merger,'' she
said, ``and one of the most important things is your mission, your
values, and your culture. Both institutions, despite the disparate
sides, share a real attention to students.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
