<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMOS-PRESS-SALE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Publishing company for sale after 122 years
 &HT;    By Jim Bohman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Amos Press Inc., a Sidney-based publishing
company that owns a chain of suburban Dayton newspapers plus coin
and stamp magazines, is up for sale after 122 years of family
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The company, with 1997 revenues of $41 million, has hired
Jordan, Edmiston Group Inc., a New York investment banking firm
that specializes in newspaper properties, to find a buyer. Asking
price was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The family plans to sell all of its publishing properties,
including the Sidney Daily News and other newspapers and hobby
magazines, but retain ownership of VisionMark, a Sidney-based
manufacturer of plaques and industrial name plates.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came less than a year after Amos acquired Tipp
City-based Bowling-Moorman Newspapers for an undisclosed price. At
the time, Bowling-Moorman published eight newspapers in communities
north of Dayton, while Amos published nine newspapers in Dayton's
south and east communities.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Francis, Amos board chairman, said in a letter to the
company's 375 employees, that the next generation of Amos family
heirs has pursued careers in other fields.
</P>
<P>
   Francis, 58, who married Margaret Amos, said about a dozen
family members own stock in the company. He and co-chairman John
Amos, 60, are ready to pass the torch, he said, but no one is there
to take it. The youngest of the heirs is 28.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth generation of Amos offspring has scattered around the
United States, Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've held many family meetings, and they just aren't
interested in coming back to Sidney to be owner-managers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amos family has been involved in running the company going
back to 1876, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have, therefore, reached the end of the line of
owner-managers,'' Francis and Amos wrote to employees. ``Once that
was determined, the question became when to sell. The current
market for publishing companies appears to be favorable.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis said they expect it will take six months to eight months
to find a buyer and close the deal. They chose to inform employees
``up-front,'' he said, because the family has always tried to make
Amos Press and its subsidiaries a good place to work.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, the family said it wants the company's growth to
continue. ``We have always believed that we must grow the business
or it shrinks. Amos Press has grown nicely over the years. We want
that growth to continue. To do that in the future will require
large resources to compete with large communication(s) companies.
Consolidation of the industry continues.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper industry analyst John Morton of Morton Research of
Baltimore said a general rule of thumb is that smaller publishing
chains sell for 1 to 1 times annual revenues, which for Amos last
year was $41 million. Morton said prospective buyers would include
area publishers such as Thomson Newspapers, the Toronto-based chain
that owns more than 100 small dailies, including newspapers in
Miamisburg, Monroe and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bohman writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
