<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-GAME-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Headhunter' monicker still haunts Wright
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York media, always looking to toss a match
into a rubble pile, tried to turn Jaret Wright into a Broadway
stage show villain before the 22-year-old right-hander threw his
first pitch for the Cleveland Indians on Tuesday night in Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, during a workout, Wright felt as if he was sitting
under a 100-watt light bulb in the interrogation room of NYPD Blue
, as wave after wave of reporters asked him, ``Are you a
headhunter?''
</P>
<P>
   It goes back to March 2, an early-spring exhibition game between
the Yankees and Indians. New York's Hideki Irabu hit two Indians.
Wright then hit infielder Luis Sojo, breaking his wrist as he threw
his arm in front of his face to ward off an inside fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee starter David Wells squirted some kerosene on the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``That situation with Luis Sojo, that was a long time ago,''
Wells said. ``And sometimes you have to let bygones by bygones. But
if guys are a little more aggressive and you have to pitch inside,
I understand that. But you don't have to pitch up and in and head
hunt. That is one thing I don't believe in. I don't think it's
right because you can really hurt somebody.
</P>
<P>
   Sojo believes he was wronged by Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way it happened . . . we hit two guys, then he hits me,''
Sojo said. ``It's one thing to push a guy off the plate, but he
threw at my head. You don't do that. We got family, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Wright, ``I've been asked about whether I am hitting people
on purpose time and time again. I'm just out there trying to get
outs.''
</P>
<P>
   And a lot was made of the fact that Wright hit Paul O'Neill in
June and that fact he has hit 11 batter this season.
</P>
<P>
   Uh . . . New York's David Cone has hit 15 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought the Game 2 pitching matchup would feature
Cleveland's Dwight Gooden and that David Cone would pitch Game 1
instead of Game 2 tonight. And New Yorkers wanted to see former
Met/Yankee Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   Both managers were ready with explanations.
</P>
<P>
   Said Cleveland's Mike Hargrove about Charles Nagy starting
today's game, ``Nagy has been our best pitcher the second half of
the season and the last time he pitched very well against the
Yankees.'' In two starts against New York, Nagy was 1-0 with a 1.72
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy has not lost since Sept. 11, including a 4-1 over the
Yankees on Sept. 21. Gooden is scheduled for long relief over the
first three games, then might start Game 4 if he isn't used in the
first three games, or if Dave Burba doesn't start Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   New York manager Joe Torre purposely held Cone back a day so he
could pitch in the warm sunshine of the day instead of the chill of
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cone sometimes feels numbness in his finger-tips after
undergoing surgery to correct an aneurysm in his right arm two
years ago. Cone said he felt numbness when he pitched Opening Day
April 4, but he went on to pitch 207 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be as cold as Opening Day,'' Cone said. ``That day
there was a wind-chill factor of 30. It shouldn't be that low for
Game two. I should be OK. This is fine. It's in the mid-50s. I can
get warmed up. And I have more than 200 innings under my belt. On
Opening Day, I was just starting out.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Yankees and Indians play Game two, Yankees Director of
Scouting Gene Michael and six other scouts will be in Atlanta
tonight watching the Braves and Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Before they played Texas, the Yankees had a 200-page report in a
blue binder on the Rangers and before they played Cleveland they
had a 200-page report in a red binder on the Indians put together
by Michael and his staff after they tracked the Tribe for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland outfielder Brian Giles knows all about Shane Spencer,
the career minor-leaguer who suddenly is the toast of Times Square
after hitting 10 homers in 67 at-bats at the end of the regular
season for the Yankees _ including three grand slams.
</P>
<P>
   Giles and Spencer grew up together in El Cajon, Calif., and
played Pop Warner League football together. They were 8 and played
for the Ravens. On the day they played Valencia Park, the best team
in the league, they won, 2-0, on a safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane was the guy who made the tackle for the safety,'' Giles
said. Spencer also hit two home runs in the American League
Division Series sweep of Texas and Giles said, ``I'm just hoping
he'll still talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's Bernie Williams, the American League's batting
champion (.339) is a free agent looking for a new contract. He and
the Yankees reportedly are only, uh, $2.5 million apart in
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, though, isn't making a very good statement about his
usefulness in the postseason. He was 0 for 9 in three ALDS games
this year against Texas, he was 2 for 17 against Cleveland last
fall in the ALDS and he is 6 for his last 50 (.120) postseason
at-bats going into Game 1 of the ALCS Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
