</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-CATS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cats! Fleas! Haven't we endured enough wildness?
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Wild cats don't belong in Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, nothing wild belongs in Palm Beach. Ever since the
Pulitzer divorce trial, Palm Beachers have been deeply embarrassed
by feral behavior on the island.
</P>
<P>
   And now, we mainlanders have been treated to this shocking news:
</P>
<P>
   Fleas in the Flagler.
</P>
<P>
   How unthinkable! Yes, that stately museum, the epitome of Palm
Beach elegance and stodginess, has been troubled with fleas in its
carpets.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as unlikely as finding an Astroturf lawn on Mar-a-Lago,
a Wal-Mart on Worth Avenue or a mangy pit bulldog chained outside
the Estee Lauder estate.
</P>
<P>
   The flea problem at the Flagler is all because of wild cats.
They've formed increasingly large colonies on the island, in what
must undoubtedly be a mating scene that makes Clematis Street look
like a Southern Baptist wedding reception.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's executive director, John Blades, has tried his best
to get rid of the cats, doing everything short of opening up a
Chinese restaurant in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Blades has hired a trapper to catch the cats and take them to
the pound. But his efforts have been thwarted by a local do-gooder,
a veritable cat crusader.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Bradley, a.k.a ``Cat Lady,'' has been going to the
pound, rounding up the captured cats and returning them to Palm
Beach, where she feeds them and hundreds of others on the island.
</P>
<P>
   It's her calling. Her passion.
</P>
<P>
   You usually see this kind of single-minded devotion in folks who
pray outside of abortion clinics or buy Leonardo DiCaprio
biographies.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong, I'm not anti-cat.
</P>
<P>
   I just don't understand why cats who live in the wild need
somebody to put out store-bought cat food for them every day.
</P>
<P>
   It's really a form of welfare, enabling slothful cat behavior by
feeding them when they could be out there earning a cat living on
their own by hunting and eating a host of other pesky wild
creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Lady claims she's doing a great service because she's paying
to have the cats spayed before releasing them back in Palm Beach.
But even so, the population of wild cats keeps increasing.
</P>
<P>
   The museum director is hoping he'll solve the problem by getting
another cat lover to take the cats off the island. But he tried
that already, and it didn't work. Cat Lady ended up dissuading the
alleged rescuer from relocating the Palm Beach cats.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the quickest solution to the Palm Beach cat problem
would be to stop trapping the cats and instead, set a trap for Cat
Lady.
</P>
<P>
   I've met Cat Lady, and I think she could stand another hobby,
something really time consuming like watching 'round-the-clock,
Clinton-in-crisis TV coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But I think Cat Lady should be left alone to be Cat Lady. Sure,
it's an odd calling. But certainly more understandable than say,
being Dolfan Denny.
</P>
<P>
   The cat problem can be solved another way. It rests in Palm
Beachers' quest for tax write-offs and influence.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study showed that Palm Beachers contribute more money
to federal-level political candidates than any other community in
Florida. During the 1995-96 election cycle, Palm Beachers gave more
than twice as much money as any other community in the state.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the deal: If Palm Beachers want to get rid of fleas in
the Flagler, they need to insist that all candidates who come to
town looking for cash end up leaving with at least one wild cat.
</P>
<P>
   Want the cash? Take the cat.
</P>
<P>
   It's that simple.
</P>
<P>
   We'll get the tab, if you get the Tabby.
</P>
<P>
   The island's feral cat population will then be redistributed all
over the country, and Cat Lady would have to find another
obsession.
</P>
<P>
   How about Wood-borer Insect Lady?
</P>
<P>
   As far as I know, nobody's stepped forward to champion the bugs
that are eating the pilings on the Royal Park Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
