<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Illini not a team to take lightly, Cooper insists
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ While some Ohio State fans may yawn at the
thought of this Saturday's OSU-Illinois match up, Buckeyes' coach
John Cooper knows better.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the days not so long ago when the Fighting Illini
regularly whipped the Buckeyes. In fact, behind Michigan, Illinois
is the Big Ten team with the best record (6-4) against Cooper in
his 10 seasons at Ohio State. ``When I first came into this league,
I think other than Michigan, they probably had the best talent of
anybody we played,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several NFL players, including Arizona Cardinals linebacker
Simeon Rice, Oakland Raiders quarterback Jeff George and St. Louis
Rams linebacker Dana Howard starred on Illini teams that beat the
Cooper-coached Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   OSU lost to Illinois five straight years, from 1988 _ Cooper's
first at OSU _ to 1992. It wasn't until 1993 that the Buckeyes
finally won and began to turn the tide. Ohio State is 4-1 vs. the
Fighting Illini since '93.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just talent, though, that foiled the Buckeyes in a few
of those early losses. Sometimes it was a fluke play here, or a
fluke performance there, that hurt them. For example, in 1989
Illinois won, 34-14, even with backup freshman quarterback Jason
Verduzco playing in place of the injured George. In 1992, OSU
tailback Eddie George lost two fumbles near the Illinois goal line,
which led to an 18-16 UI victory.
</P>
<P>
   The past three years, of course, have been a different story.
The Buckeyes have won by a combined score of 130-9 in the teams'
games since 1995. And there's little reason to believe the scoring
gap won't widen this year.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 Buckeyes boast a stifling defense and an offense that
averages 479.5 yards per game, the best in the conference.
Illinois, on the other hand, has defeated just one Division I-A
opponent in its last 22 games (they defeated Northwestern last
weekend, 13-10) and starts freshmen at quarterback and at running
back on a youth-laden team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find ways to build the confidence up and
nothing does that better than getting some wins,'' second-year
Illini coach Ron Turner said. ``But as young as we are, it takes
time to build that confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said coaching instability _ the Illini have had three
coaches in the past seven years _ and a slip in recruiting are
probably two reasons the fortunes have fallen for Illinois. It had
recorded eight winning seasons between 1980 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they haven't recruited as well as they used to,''
Cooper said. During their winning days, the Fighting Illini used to
get the best players out of St. Louis but that no longer is the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what, when you're down, it's hard to get back
up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
