</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UTEXAS-DEFENSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Longhorns finally feel good about run defense
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Week after week during football seasons past and
present, senior linebacker Dusty Renfro has done what might amount
to the bravest thing he's ever attempted.
</P>
<P>
   Not stand in against some of the top rushing offenses in the
nation. Show up at the Monday media conference and answer questions
about the play of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in a long time I've been able to come
in here and say good things,'' Renfro said Monday as he attacked a
plate of barbecue and beans.
</P>
<P>
   Renfro and his teammates held Darren Davis to only 53 yards, 97
below his average, and his Iowa State Cyclones to only 36 net yards
rushing _ reason enough for a big appetite and even bigger smile.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Renfro has been on teams that have won a combined 65
percent of their games, before this season he's also played on
three of the five worst rush defenses in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel good about winning, but as a unit, you don't want to
give up that many yards,'' Renfro said. ``That leaves a sour taste
in your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas has held down strong rushing attacks in consecutive weeks
against Rice and Iowa State, but the worst might be yet to come. In
the next five games the Horns face four teams that rank in the top
25 nationally in rushing, including three in the top 15 (Texas
Tech, fifth; Nebraska, sixth; and Oklahoma, 14th).
</P>
<P>
   This week the Horns will play an Oklahoma team that's still
trying to get comfortable with what was touted as a wishbone
triple-option offense, but in reality has relied more on lead and
dive option plays out of the power-I formation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to run the option, but I don't know how much or
when,'' Texas Coach Mack Brown said. ``We're not sure who we'll see
the most. They've got a guy who'll run the option (Brandon Daniels)
and a guy who'll throw more (Patrick Fletcher).''
</P>
<P>
   Even though OU will be without the left side of its line _ guard
Adam Carpenter and tackle Scott Kempenich _ with injuries, the
Sooners still have junior halfback De'Mond Parker, and that's
enough to get the Horns' attention. Last season as a sophomore,
Parker ran for 291 yards and three touchdowns, including late
scoring runs of 48 and 66 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very fast and slippery,'' Renfro said. ``He's an expert
at breaking tackles. We really have to latch on. We have to grab
cloth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can outrun our cutoff angles. So we'll run all-out to get
there, and if he sees that, he'll cut it back. ... He's probably
the best running back we'll play against.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me of Ricky (Williams),'' said strongside
linebacker Anthony Hicks. ``Both can run by you, both can run over
you. Of course, I think Ricky's better and practicing against him
is going to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing a cutback runner in Davis, defensive coordinator Carl
Reese stressed two things to his players: Swarm to Davis but don't
abandon your assignment if the play goes away from you _ more than
likely he'll come back your way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any great back can be reduced to a good back if you have
everyone around him,'' Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas will also be able to concentrate more on stopping the run
the rest of the season. None of its remaining opponents rank in the
top 50 in the NCAA in passing efficiency. Texas Tech is the best,
ranked 51st, followed by Oklahoma State (72), Nebraska (84), Baylor
(89), Texas A&AMP;M (97) and Oklahoma (104).
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of Iowa State quarterback Todd Bandhauer's
437-yard, five-touchdown performance last week, OU's moribund
passing game will be a welcome change for the Horns. The Sooners
have completed only 39 percent of their passes but have a knack for
play-action success _ five of their 23 completions have been for
touchdowns and their average completion is for 20.3 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Rush defense is one of the areas in which the Horns needed
improvement heading into this season. Here's a quick look at the
other areas that needed work:
</P>
<P>
   _ Long drives. Of the 27 touchdowns allowed, 16 have come on
drives longer than 60 yards. Of the other 11, one was scored by
special teams, one on an interception return and seven others were
set up by turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the red zone. Opponents have scored on 19 of 22 trips
inside the Texas 20-yard line, and only one of those was a field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turnovers forced. This is the one area in which the Horns are
vastly improved, with 13 this season _ one fewer than they forced
all of last year. What the Horns have to do better is turn them
into points _ they've scored only 35.
</P>
<P>
   _ Three and out. In the first three games the Horns held the
opponent without a first down in only eight of 39 possessions (21
percent). Over the last two they've improved it to 10 of 27 (37
percent).
</P>
<P>
   _ Third-down conversions. That's dropped from 50 percent to 32
percent over the same period, but the Horns continue to be dogged
by poor efficiency on fourth down, where they've stopped the
opponent only once in 10 plays all season _ a late goal-line stand
against Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wangrin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
