</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARWOOD-IRRIGATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LCRA water rights buy goes to state agency today
 &HT;    By Chuck Lindell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin and other cities near the Colorado River
will not need to search for new sources of water until 2090 if
state regulators approve a $75 million purchase of water rights
today.
</P>
<P>
   The Garwood Irrigation Co., which serves rice farmers near the
Gulf of Mexico, has agreed to sell its considerable water rights to
the Lower Colorado River Authorityfor the highest price in Texas
history.
</P>
<P>
   Before the LCRA can begin closing the deal, the sale needs
approval from the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission _
and that could come at a commission meeting this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to do a jig in the street if we get this thing
wrapped up,'' said Mark Rose, general manager of the LCRA. ``If
it's approved, you can put a bow on it. I think we can have this
closed by the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   How much water is at stake? Enough each year to cover one acre
to the depth of 25 miles. More importantly, it's enough water to
extend the LCRA's supply for cities and major industries to 2090 _
a crucial consideration in a fast-growing, drought-prone region.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to this point, however, has not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   First, Garwood and the LCRA had to overcome a half-century of
animosity over water charges that Garwood considered excessive and
over LCRA efforts to restrict the company's access to the river.
Then, the LCRA had to overcome protests from Austin, Lago Vista and
Lakeway. The cities objected to Garwood's decision to sell 20
percent of its water to Corpus Christi, which is well outside the
Colorado River basin.
</P>
<P>
   The Garwood rights are considered one of the state's top water
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Garwood's water rights are the oldest on the Colorado River,
dating to a November 1900 state permit. Under state law, Garwood's
rights must be satisfied first _ even if an extended drought limits
water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, water rights can be bought and sold like any
private property. Whoever buys the Garwood rights would stand first
in line for Colorado River water.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the value of the water rights is that Garwood forms
the largest block of privately held water on the Colorado River _
168,000 acre-feet a year, or almost 55 billion gallons. An
acre-foot is the amount of water needed to cover an acre to a depth
of one foot, or about 326,000 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   Garwood has asked the three members of the state's Natural
Resource Conservation Commission to approve the sale of water
rights for 133,000 acre-feet a year to the LCRA and 35,000
acre-feet to Corpus Christi. The commission's executive director,
Jeff Saitas, has recommended approval.
</P>
<P>
   The LCRA would pay $75 million for its share. To repay the debt,
the agency anticipates raising water rates 20 percent, beginning in
two to five years.
</P>
<P>
   The LCRA operates Lake Travis and the other Highland Lakes,
releasing enough water through dams to satisfy downstream needs.
</P>
<P>
   Most years, enough water flows down the Colorado River to easily
meet the demand. That would change, however, during an extended
drought. And that is when owning senior water rights would begin to
make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Garwood's 133,000 acre-feet would translate into slightly more
than 100,000 acre-feet of ``firm-yield'' water, or water that would
be available even during a repeat of the worst drought in Central
Texas history. That was during the early 1950s, when the level of
Lake Travis fell 67 feet below full. For comparison, during the
drought of 1996, Lake Travis dropped 29 feet below full.
</P>
<P>
   Even during a critical drought, Garwood would ensure enough
water to fill Town Lake 28 times and meet the household needs of
750,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The Garwood rights are critical for the future of Austin as well
as southern Williamson County and northern Hays County, which will
increasingly rely on LCRA water.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the LCRA has 53,000 acre-feet left to sell in the
Highland Lakes; the Garwood purchase would triple the agency's
firm-yield reserves. Austin has been seeking to buy an additional
50,000 acre-feet of firm-yield water from the LCRA, for a total of
300,000 acre-feet _ enough to last until 2050.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great deal for the region,'' Austin City Manager
Jesus Garza said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, however, Austin was considering a formal protest to
the conservation commission. The city contended that selling water
to Corpus Christi would short-change Austin by 1,500 acre-feet
during a repeat of the 1950s drought.
</P>
<P>
   The LCRA agreed to provide additional water if the sale to
Corpus Christi ever affects Austin's water supply, and Austin
dropped its protest _ ending the last serious threat to the Garwood
agreement. Lago Vista and Lakeway had already decided not to pursue
their protests, although they remain concerned about piping water
outside the Colorado River basin.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Lindell writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
