<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-SHARES-UP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forecast of chip sales lifts Motorola stock
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Motorola Inc.'s shares jumped $3.25 to $41.81
1/4 on Tuesday after executives said semiconductor sales would
rebound in 1999 and that the company would meet financial
expectations for the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They also said the company's restructuring _ including job cuts
_ was ahead of schedule. So far, the company says it has eliminated
7,800 of the 15,000 workers it plans to cut by the middle of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, with about 10,000 employees in its Austin
semiconductor operations, is one of the area's major private sector
employers. The company is based in Schaumburg, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   In a morning conference call with analysts, Motorola executives
provided more details and the company's context for the
third-quarter financial results released Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   During the call, the company said it expects worldwide
semiconductor sales to grow 7 percent to 9 percent in 1999. In the
third quarter, Motorola's computer chip sales tumbled 14 percent to
$1.8 billion from $2.1 billion in the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the company's sales and earnings have suffered, in
part, because of the worldwide weakness in semiconductor prices.
Computer chips account for about 25 percent of Motorola's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the semiconductor outlook was the key element
behind Tuesday's share price increase.
</P>
<P>
   Also during the call, Motorola officials said the company should
meet Wall Street expectations of a profit of 22 cents a share on
revenues of $7.9 billion for the current quarter. The company will,
however, take another charge against earnings as it continues
reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Motorola had posted a $42 million loss on sales of
$7.2 million after taking a $117 million charge. Shares had sunk
Monday to a 52-week low of $38.56 1/4 in anticipation of the
earnings report.
</P>
<P>
   The company has blamed many of its revenue woes on pricing
pressures and sluggish sales in Asia. In implementing the
restructuring, the company saved $140 through cuts that included
layoffs and consolidation. The company said it wants to save at
least $750 million a year through its current reduction plan.
</P>
<P>
   More reductions are in sight as workers have until Friday to
decide whether to accept a voluntary severance package from the
company. Job cuts are expected if not enough workers choose to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the company said 1,000 of its semiconductor workers
worldwide had accepted the terms of the severance plan.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the third quarter, Motorola closed major sites in
California, North Carolina, Arizona and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Omar L. Gallaga writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
