<HEADER>
A2958 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-GOV-RACE-COX     10-06 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-GOV-RACE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush campaign launches broadside against Mauro
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Gov. George W. Bush has spent most of the campaign
ignoring underdog opponent Garry Mauro, but Tuesday he dismissed
the Democratic challenger's platform as a budget-busting bucket of
promises waiting to be broken.
</P>
<P>
   The broadside against Mauro was launched for Bush by two top GOP
senators and a key Democratic House member. They said Mauro's
policies would cost the state $4 billion to $7.5 billion more than
the state will have to spend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which promises will Mauro break?'' asked Sen. David Sibley,
R-Waco, who is backing Bush. ``Inquiring minds want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro insisted his numbers balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do add up,'' he said. ``Their cooked numbers don't add
up. I think it is what you would expect from the three people that
issued them. They cooked the numbers to make their endorsed
candidate look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Any differences in the numbers, Mauro said, are due to varying
budget ``assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign said its numbers were based on analysis by
``independent budget experts such as the Legislative Budget Board
and the comptroller's office.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibley said the Mauro plan, heavy on education, fails the simple
math test. Early projections show that state lawmakers next year
could have as much as $6.3 billion more to allocate when they write
the two-year budget.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro has several big-ticket items in his platform, including:
</P>
<P>
   A $6,000 pay hike for all teachers. He says the price tag is
$3.9 billion. The Bush campaign said Legislative Budget Board
experts peg the cost at $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Hope Scholarship'' plan to pay college tuition for bright
kids. Mauro says the cost is $800 million. The Bush campaign says
the cost is $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 10,000 police officers. Mauro says that would cost
$500 million. The Bush campaign says the price tag is $731 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also is pushing two major tax changes. He wants to scrap
the sales tax on cars, vans and pickup trucks. Mauro wants to
offset part of that loss by doubling the state levy on some tobacco
and alcohol products.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't add up, Sibley said, even if lawmakers use money from
the tobacco lawsuit settlement to help pay for the Mauro plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turning point of the story of Cinderella comes when the
ugly stepsister tries to fit her very large foot into the glass
slipper,'' said Sibley. ``The political equivalent in Texas is
occurring now as Garry Mauro tries to fit $14 billion worth of
promises into $6.3 billion worth of shoe.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Bill Ratliff, R-Mount
Pleasant, and House Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell, D-San
Angelo, made the same point, if more clinically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would appear that the publicly advocated spending proposals
of the various statewide candidates are within predicted available
revenues with the exception of the Mauro campaign proposals,''
Ratliff and Junell said in a joint statement requested by the Bush
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both lawmakers have endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley, Ratliff and Junell also rapped Mauro's plan to borrow $2
billion from the Permanent School Fund to pay for classroom
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be adamantly opposed to any invasion of this trust
fund,'' said Junell and Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Karen Hughes said Bush will be talking
about the Mauro plan in upcoming campaign appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be pointing out that he has proposed a responsible
budget, that his proposals are within the means of the state and
that his opponent has proposed $14 billion worth of promises and
there is not $14 billion worth of money,'' said Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite polls showing Mauro running a distant second to Bush,
Hughes said the incumbent is taking the challenger seriously.
Campaign finance reports filed Monday showed that. Bush spent $10.8
million in the last three months, about three-quarters of it on TV
ads.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, who has had to scratch to raise money to keep his
campaign going, has not yet aired any ads.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's budget plan is highlighted by a $2 billion tax cut and
abolition of the sales tax on over-the-counter drugs, diapers and
some health-care products.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to send $1 billion in state money to school
districts to use as they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley said he is not ready to endorse Bush's property tax-cut
plan, but is convinced the governor's overall budget package
balances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the idea of a property tax reduction,'' said Sibley.
``What I'm saying is the amount is to be determined. And there are
other types of taxes we might want to reduce also.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
