<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE, ALOU ON MINDS OF DODGERS BRASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers president Bob Graziano and
general manager Kevin Malone were to fly to the Dominican Republic
this morning with hopes of bringing back a new manager _ Felipe
Alou.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano and Malone are expected to spend five days in the
Dominican to speak with Alou, 63, manager of the Montreal Expos the
past seven seasons. Alou has one season remaining on his contract
for $600,000, and the Expos have offered a three-year extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic to move forward and I am hopeful that Felipe is
a good match for the job,'' said Malone, who was Alou's GM in
Montreal from 1994-95. ``I have spoken to him by phone and have a
very good feeling, but until I meet with him I won't know for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou's wife Lucie is from Montreal and her family has told local
media outlets Alou will remain in Montreal. Despite his ties, Alou
has told members of the Expos organization the Dodgers job is too
good to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano and Malone also will inspect the estimated $333,000
damage done to the club's baseball academy by Hurricane Georges.
None of the 60 players housed at the camp was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The camp is located in the Dominican capital of Santo Domingo,
which also is Alou's residence. The most serious damage to the
camp, which recently was featured in a profile of Latin American
baseball on the Fox Network, was to the roof of one of the
dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano and Malone also might visit San Pedro de Macoris,
hometown of Dodgers players Raul Mondesi, Ramon Martinez and Adrian
Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, Malone plans to move Mondesi back to right field,
where he has won two Gold Gloves. Mondesi went to center field
after Gary Sheffield was acquired May 15 from Florida. But Mondesi
developed a sore lower back from the added running in center.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, who played 72 games with the Dodgers last season, could
be the club's starting third baseman next season if the Dodgers are
able to move Bobby Bonilla's $11.8 million contract. That is
Malone's top priority when he returns.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers hold an option on the contract for Martinez, who
will not pitch until June at the earliest after undergoing surgery
last June to repair his right rotator cuff. If the Dodgers exercise
the option, they would owe Martinez $5.6 million. They are expected
to offer the buyout of $500,000 and re-sign him at a lower figure.
It is a delicate matter, because Martinez is the leader among the
Dodgers Latin players and the club does not want to embarrass him
with too low an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we really will get into all that on this trip,''
Malone said. ``Our focus is on Felipe.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: The Dodgers on Tuesday claimed right-handed relief
pitcher Doug Bochtler off waivers from the Detroit Tigers. The team
designated catcher Henry Blanco for assignment to make room for the
28-year-old Bochtler, who led all Tigers relievers with a
career-high 67.1 innings pitched after compiling an 0-2 record and
a 6.15 ERA in 51 games in 1988. He also had 45 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Bochtler has a career 9-16 record with six saves and a 4.45 ERA
with Detroit and San Diego in four major-league seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
