<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-GAME-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Contract on line for Williams
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A new deal from the Yankees for center fielder Bernie
Williams may depend on how he plays the rest of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Williams becomes a free agent after the season, and the Yankees
want him back. But right now owner George Steinbrenner and agent
Scott Boras are apart by about $3 million a season on a deal.
Williams wants $11 million a year, but Steinbrenner must find a way
to rationalize a contract that would pay him more than Sammy Sosa,
who hit 66 homers during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who won the American League batting title, hitting
.339, could get his deal with a strong finish this October. He did
not get off to a good start against Texas, going 0-for-11, and he
looked a little apprehensive going into Tuesday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the American League Championship Series. There is no time
for relaxing out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams went on to add, ``I keep trying and there is a lot of
room for improvement now. It's not the first time I have been
0-for-a-series and it's not going to be the last.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster change
</P>
<P>
   The Indians made a change on their roster, activating reliever
Chad Ogea, who replaced veteran Doug Jones. Ogea has been bothered
by injuries all season but last year won both of his starts in the
World Series against the Marlins. He will be used in long relief.
Jones has struggled all year and was beaten up in his one
divisional series appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn
</P>
<P>
   Charisse Strawberry, the wife of hospitalized Yankees outfielder
Darryl Strawberry, threw out the first pitch Tuesday night. . . .
Said Yankees general manager Brian Cashman: ``I'm very happy for
(San Diego GM) Kevin Towers and the Padres and Jim Leyritz. I hate
to say it, but (Randy Johnson) is one of the few guys out there
that really can make you wet your pants. Right now, I'm glad that
he is not pitching against us. Obviously, it proves that one man
doesn't make the team.'' . . . Yankees manager Joe Torre's contract
extension, which is still not official, likely will bring him a
salary of $2 million in the 2000 and 2001 seasons. He is currently
making $1 million. . . . A group of five Yankees scouts has tracked
the Indians for the last 30 days and put together a huge binder of
information for Torre and his players. The information obviously
worked in the previous series against the Rangers, as scouts
noticed that Texas slugger Juan Gonzalez had walked just 46 times
during the regular season and swung at a lot of bad pitches. New
York pitchers then fed Gonzalez low off-speed pitches, and he had
just one hit in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's pitchers
</P>
<P>
   The Indians will start right-hander Charles Nagy, who was 15-10
during the regular season and was the winning pitcher in Game 3 of
the divisional series with the Red Sox, going eight innings and
allowing one run on four hits. During the regular season, Nagy was
1-0 against the Yankees with a 1.72 ERA in two starts. The Yankees
will go with right-hander David Cone, who pitched 5 2/3 shutouts
inning in Game 3 of the divisional series and was 20-7 in the
regular season, the second 20-win year of his career. He is 1-1
with a 4.05 ERA in two starts against the Indians this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
