<HEADER>
A2995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NY     10-06 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN POLLS HINT AT DEMOCRAT'S DEFEAT 
POLLS IN NEBRASKA GO AGAINST THE GRAIN  
 ARMEY'S UNCLE EXHORTS DEMOCRATS ON POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few candidates have been more outrageously outspoken this year
than Geoffrey Fieger, who aspires to be Michigan's governor after
building a reputation as a lawyer for Dr. Jack Kevorkian, the
advocate and practitioner of physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   But while Fieger, a Democrat, has enjoyed much success in
keeping Kevorkian out of jail, he appears _ because of or despite
his noisy stumping _ to be making no progress in trying to keep
Gov. John Engler from winning a third term.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger is losing ground and many political analysts and leading
Democrats have all but written him off and are focusing on whether
he will run so poorly that other Democrats on the ticket may
suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Two new polls, one by The Detroit Free Press and the other by
The Detroit News, show Engler, a Republican, ahead by a margin of
better than 2 to 1. Perhaps worse for Fieger, the polls also show
that the governor's ``positives'' are steadily going up while
Fieger's are steadily going down, to the point that roughly three
of every five voters now view him ``unfavorably.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fieger, who has recently been the target of a major
Republican advertising campaign, proclaimed at a rally: ``We're
going to create a revolution. There's going to be a surge of people
voting Nov. 3 who aren't being counted by pollsters.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was getting enough help from Democrats, he
declared, ``There is no Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLLS IN NEBRASKA GO AGAINST THE GRAIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey's hopes for running for president in 2000 got a
nice lift a few days ago when a poll in his home state, Nebraska,
found that three of five voters thought he should go for it. Often,
such polls find that voters want their elected officials to stay
put and govern rather than take up the chase after that most
elusive of political goals.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message Virginians sent to Gov. L. Douglas Wilder
in 1992 when he began spending less and less time tending the home
fires and more and more time courting primary voters in the snowy
notches of New Hampshire. More recently, it was the message voters
sent California Gov. Pete Wilson in 1996 when he briefly made a run
for president. And it is the same message they are still sending
him, according to several 1998 polls, as he prepares to leave
office early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the Nebraska poll, conducted for The Omaha
World-Herald, had added meaning for Kerrey, a Democrat, because
Nebraska happens to lie next to Iowa, home of the first
presidential caucuses. They tend to be labor-intensive affairs,
with organization and turnout crucial to success, and the new poll
indicates that Kerry, if he runs, will have little difficulty
finding scores of Nebraskans willing to cross over into Iowa to
help with the heavy political lifting.
</P>
<P>
   But will he run?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a poll that shows people approve of your
performance, and they want you to run for president, I listen to
it,'' Kerry told The World-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARMEY'S UNCLE EXHORTS DEMOCRATS ON POLLS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the all-in-the-family brand of politics ...
</P>
<P>
   The other day Joe Armey, a retired broadcaster from Seattle,
sent a letter to the Democratic Party, with copies to local papers,
in which he warned that if the party did not get out the vote in
November, the Republicans would add to their majority in Congress
with the direst of results for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The zealots and bigots of the right wing,'' Armey wrote,
``already hold all key offices of the Republican Party and have a
stranglehold on every branch of the federal government except the
presidency. Not voting and letting someone else make a choice for
you could prove disastrous for democracy as we know and love it. By
not voting we will allow the extremists of the far-right Christian
movement of Pat Robertson, Jerry Falwell, Jesse Helms, Dick Armey
and Newt Gingrich to control the future of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Armey? As in Dick Armey, House majority leader from Texas?
</P>
<P>
   Correct.
</P>
<P>
   He's Joe Armey's nephew. Not only that, as Uncle Joe sees it,
Dick Armey is the political heretic in a family of hard-core
Franklin Delano Roosevelt-style Democrats, among them the
grain-farming Armeys of Cando, N.D., hometown of Dick Armey.
</P>
<P>
   The farm-support programs Democrats pushed through Congress back
in the Roosevelt era kept Dick Armey and the rest of the North
Dakota Armeys from being economically blown away a generation back,
Joe Armey says. But today, he laments, Dick Armey is one of the
most vocal opponents of farm subsidies on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Uncle Joe has publicly taken on his
nephew. Over the years, he has periodically zinged him in letters
to editors and articles for Op-Ed pages. And a couple of years ago
he even wrote a book, ``Harvest of Contempt,'' in which he
lambasted the new Republican majority in Congress and contended
that his nephew never breathed a conservative breath until he moved
to Texas to teach economics, whereupon, Uncle Joe says, he became a
born-again Christian, a hard-right Republican and an ungrateful
opponent of farm aid.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Armey's response to all this, through an aide, was this:
``Everybody has a right to express their opinion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
