<HEADLINE>
MVP IS FOR PLAYER, NOT TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long and short of it:
</P>
<P>
   __ The scariest symptom of the national home runs delirium is
the baseball columnists' consensus that Sammy Sosa and not Mark
McGwire is the National League's Most Valuable Player. What's that,
the consolation prize?
</P>
<P>
   In baseball tradition, if the individual stats are close, the
MVP is the guy who helped his team to the playoffs, so Sosa of the
wild-card Cubs is getting the nod over McGwire of the third-place
Cardinals. But the stats AREN'T close.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the home runs. McGwire beat Sosa in slugging percentage
by 104 points; that's the difference between Ken Griffey Jr. and
Travis Fryman. McGwire beat Sosa in on-base percentage by 93
points; that's the difference between Bernie Williams and Craig
Grebeck.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's edges, slight ones, are in runs scored and batted in. If
he's the MVP because of that and because the Cubs made the
playoffs, he's being rewarded over McGwire for having better
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   __ Not that it matters to the owners, but it's better for NBA
fans if the ``Larry Bird exception'' is kept, allowing teams to
bend the salary cap in order to re-sign their own free agents. And
this time, somebody tell the Clippers about it.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the NBA's appeal is the fact its biggest stars have
tended to stay with one team. Keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   __ What's the bigger surprise, that Green Bay gave up 100-plus
yards to Minnesota receivers Randy Moss !ital!and!off! Cris Carter,
or that until Monday night the Vikings hadn't had a 100-yard
receiver this season?
</P>
<P>
   Moss looks like he should get 190 every game.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Broncos after five weeks last season: 5-0, league leaders
in points, outscoring opponents by 16.8 a game, on their way to the
Super Bowl. The Broncos after five weeks this season: 5-0, league
leaders in points, outscoring opponents by 17.8 a game, on their
way to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sat in one of the new Rose Bowl seats for the first time at a
Galaxy playoff game last week. Actually, ``wedged myself into'' was
more like it, and I'm an average-size person. Ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   I know people who wouldn't go to the Rose Bowl because of the
discomfort, and this is no improvement.
</P>
<P>
   __ Felipe Alou and Walter Alston share a page in my copy of
``The Baseball Encyclopedia.'' Easy, then, to note that Alou will
be 64 next season, and that when Alston was 64, he was in his 23rd
and final year as Dodgers manager.
</P>
<P>
   __ One more Angels tank job like this and Terry Collins, a good
guy, will be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't supposed to be here'' ought to be a way of saying
the pressure's off, not an exit line. After that first loss to
Texas in the pivotal series, the Angels players sounded beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Even the manager was saying the wrong things, talking about his
insomnia and how ``we'll be disappointed'' without adding ``if we
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   __ When Gene Mauch muses that his biggest disappointment was
failing to win a World Series for Gene Autry, that's saying a lot.
</P>
<P>
   __ On the list of matters about which I'd rather not be given
the details, Mike Tyson's psychological records rate a close
second.
</P>
<P>
   __ Note to Cal State Northridge fans: When the PA announcer
says, ``That's another Matador ...,'' you're supposed to chime in,
``... First down!''
</P>
<P>
   __ When will baseball employ the broadcast technology that
causes hockey pucks to glow and yellow ``first down'' lines to
appear on football fields? How about a vertical line marking the
outer edge of the strike zone?
</P>
<P>
   It would hover one foot outside the plate.
</P>
<P>
   __ To everyone who thought the media were rude to mention the
steroids speculation, never borne out by urine tests, in coverage
of Florence Griffith Joyner's death: How would you know the charges
were never proven if the media hadn't TOLD you the charges were
never proven?
</P>
<P>
   __ Not that it matters to the Fox people who will choose the
Dodgers' future spring-training home, but I'll bet that if you
walked down the street wearing a Giants cap, you'd take more heat
in Vero Beach, Fla., than in any other city. Including Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   __ Good move by the NHL, experimenting with two referees this
season. One to see Geoff Courtnall plowing into Jamie Storr, one to
see Sean O'Donnell beating up Courtnall.
</P>
<P>
   With two refs in that playoff game against St. Louis, maybe the
Kings wouldn't have blown a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   __ The $5 million purchase of top 2-year-old Worldly Manner by
an anonymous buyer could be horse racing's best publicity hook in
years. Here's the plan: The owner wears a wrestling mask to his
races. The jockey wears a Riddler's costume. The horse's number is
always ``X.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that $5 million price too high or too low? Yes. We'll know
which after the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   __ Naturally, a group of Raiders fans thought the recent
memorial for Jim Murray, at which Al Davis spoke, was the
appropriate site for a banner-waving demonstration in favor of the
team's return to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   __ Given the overanalysis that TV sports fans are subjected to,
an exchange like this, overheard at the Murray memorial at Dodger
Stadium, comes as no surprise. A woman said: ``Vin Scully is soooo
eloquent!'' A man replied: ``Well, he's used to speaking here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
