<HEADLINE>
NO DINING CAR  
 A RETIREMENT (SORT OF) 
NO DIVA AIRS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 BY JAMES BARRON with ALEX KUCZYNSKI and G.S. BOURDAIN 
   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was enough to make the briefcase-and-tote-bag crowd stop and
stare. There in Grand Central Terminal was a line of people in
evening clothes lined up for dinner. There was John F. Kennedy Jr.
And U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan. And actor Stanley Tucci (now
platinum blond). And an enterprising panhandler working the line
for change.
</P>
<P>
   The diners were celebrating the newly restored station and the
Municipal Art Society. They sat in the polished Vanderbilt Hall,
which has more echo capacity than a Titanic-size bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   When Brooke Astor _ who, one might note, is older than Grand
Central itself _ stepped up to the microphone, the dinnertime din
barely subsided.
</P>
<P>
   When Tom Florio and Steve Florio, the embattled brothers of
Conde Nast, smilingly delivered a speech about the society _ the
evening's sponsor _ the diners paused only a second before diving
back into their squash soup and conversation.
</P>
<P>
   But when Caroline Kennedy went to the podium, the diners set
down their silverware and became quiet. She talked about her
mother, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, who crusaded to save Grand
Central.
</P>
<P>
   Then the dinner ended and a dance floor opened. And the crowd
was joined by several drag queens _ one in a sequined thong and not
much else _ who had paid $150 ($200 at the door) to dance without
dining (or straining to hear the speeches).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A RETIREMENT, SORT OF &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An off-camera change: He was a deputy mayor under John Lindsay
in the 1960s and 1970s. Then he became a cable television
executive, eventually overseeing Time Warner's cable operations in
New York City. In 1992 he started New York 1 News, the all-news
cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Time Warner announced that Richard R. Aurelio, 70, was
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the word retirement,'' he said. ``I'm not
retiring from life.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had some projects in mind but would not elaborate,
saying only, ``I'm not going to certainly plant roses or go down to
Florida, you know.'' Steve Paulus was named general manager of New
York 1, where he has been a senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO DIVA AIRS &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Some people stay modest despite years in the spotlight. Soprano
Camilla Williams, who in 1946 became the first black singer to be
put under contract by the New York City Opera, did not play the
diva last week at a New York Philharmonic luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Williams, 72, came from her home in Indiana to celebrate
the release of a 12-compact-disk album of the complete symphonies
of Mahler broadcast by the orchestra between 1948 and 1982. She was
the soloist in Symphony No. 8 (1950), under Leopold Stokowski.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Williams _ who co-starred on the first complete recording
of Gershwin's ``Porgy and Bess'' (1951) _ spoke with pride about
her career at City Opera and at Indiana University in Bloomington,
where she was the first black voice teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pity we're still small in number,'' she said. But she did
not dwell on herself, instead speaking proudly about one of her
Indiana students, Janet Williams _ no relation _ and her opera and
concert appearances throughout the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
