<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOPEZ GAINS IN HIS BID FOR TITLE BOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Main Events, the promoter for Jose Luis Lopez, has got an
injunction to keep the World Boxing Association from sanctioning
the bout between Andrei Pestriaev and Greg Page in Paris this
Saturday as a welterweight championship match.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Superior Court Judge Amos Sanders ruled Tuesday that
the WBA must conduct a purse bid Oct. 14 for a bout between
Pestriaev, its No. 1 contender, against Lopez, the No. 2 contender.
Sanders' ruling forbids the WBA from sanctioning any title bout
between Pestriaev and a contender ranked lower than No. 2. Page is
the WBA's No. 3-ranked contender.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also threw a curve at Showtime, which will broadcast
the Pestriaev-Page bout. Jay Larkin, senior vice president of
sports and event programming, said the ruling didn't affect the
scheduled broadcast of the bout, the length of which has not been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   The WBA welterweight title has been in limbo since Ike Quartey
was stripped of the title in August for not fighting Pestriaev.
Quartey said he was sick and could not defend against Pestriaev in
a timely fashion. Quartey will fight Oscar De La Hoya for the World
Boxing Council welterweight title Nov. 21 in Las Vegas. Quartey is
still considered one of the world's best welterweights.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez is also considered one of the toughest opponents in the
welterweight division. De La Hoya named Lopez as the welterweight
contender he would least like to face. Lopez knocked down Quartey
twice last year during a bout, which ended in a draw. Since signing
with Main Events three months ago, Lopez has been maneuvered into a
top-ranked position for another world title bout.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti Cancels Rematch
</P>
<P>
   Arturo Gatti has pulled out of a rematch against Ivan Robinson
on the undercard of the Roy Jones-Otis Grant card Nov. 14. Gatti
lost a tough decision to Robinson on Aug. 22, and Pat Lynch,
Gatti's manager, said he did not believe that Gatti was ready to
fight again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a must-win fight for Arturo, because he has lost
two fights in a row,'' Lynch said. ``Physically and mentally he's
just not 100 percent right now. He wanted to fight Ivan in a
rematch right away, because he didn't think that he lost that last
fight. But it's just too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO, which will broadcast the Jones-Grant bout, has not decided
what it will do to fill the void on the undercard.
</P>
<P>
   Miscellany
</P>
<P>
   _ A light heavyweight bout between Frank Tate, the World Boxing
Organization champion, and David Telasco will headline the second
installment of ESPN2's revamped boxing show this Friday night from
the Capital Theater in Port Chester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   _ Floyd Mayweather, Jr., who took a big step up and defeated
Genaro Hernandez last Saturday night for the World Boxing Council
superfeatherweight championship, is close to signing a deal to
fight Angel Manfredy on Dec. 19. Manfredy, a tough body puncher who
took Gatti apart last year, will be a lot tougher for Mayweather to
subdue than Hernandez was.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Thomas, the lawyer for Evander Holyfield, said he would
like to get Henry Akinwande, the World Boxing Association No. 1
heavyweight title contender, to step aside from a mandatory bout so
that Holyfield can meet WBC champ Lennox Lewis in his next bout.
But Thomas isn't sure whether Holyfield's promoter, Don King, will
be able to make that happen. Lewis isn't holding his breath. Talks
are underway for Lewis to meet Lou Savarese on Dec. 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
