<SLUG> BC-PENTAGON-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 CHARGED WITH SELLING FAULTY UNIFORMS TO PENTAGON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Brooklyn-based clothing company and four of its top
officials have been charged with defrauding the Pentagon of
millions of dollars by using defective cloth in coveralls and
combat uniforms, law enforcement officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in Brooklyn said the company, Isratex Inc.,
rigged inspections to make Defense Department inspectors think they
were examining random samples of new clothing when they were
actually seeing the same small batch of properly made goods over
and over.
</P>
<P>
   Isratex had $30 million in contracts with the Defense Department
to manufacture clothing for the armed services. Prosecutors said
the rigged inspections took place at a subsidiary in Puerto Rico
that made uniforms and other military clothing.
</P>
<P>
   They said an inspector who wanted to examine a lot ready for
shipment would choose at random the numbers on the boxes that he
wished to see. ``He would then wait in a conference room and they
would bring him the boxes with those numbers,'' said Seth Marvin,
an assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But the inspectors were shown boxes that had quickly been
spray-painted with the requested numbers and that contained
garments that would pass the inspection, Marvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actual production lots manufactured by Isratex of Puerto
Rico Inc.,'' as the subsidiary was known, ``consisted mainly of
items that were manufactured with defective cloth and with inferior
workmanship,'' said a statement from the office of Zachary Carter,
the U.S. attorney for the Eastern District of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin declined to say how the fraud was discovered or how much
of the $30 million worth of clothing had actually been produced,
delivered and paid for. But he said Defense Department officials
had estimated that the agency had lost $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not know whether Isratex, based at 59 Scholes St.
in the Williamsburg section of Brooklyn, was still in business,
noting that it had been involved in bankruptcy proceedings. There
is currently no telephone listing for the company in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The officials charged are Abe Brin, 50, of Brooklyn, the
company's president; his brother Yehudah Yoav Brin, 48, of
Jerusalem, the vice president and secretary; Zvi Rosenthal, 54, of
Tenafly, N.J., the production manager, and Timothy Lafferty, 43, of
Collegeville, Pa. Lafferty is president of another Isratex
subsidiary, Marywell Ltd., which obtained the cloth used by the
companies: cotton sateen for the coveralls and a mixture of cotton
and nylon for the combat uniform parts.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges that the company used substandard cloth
in the form of ``seconds,'' a merchandising term for goods of
inferior quality, and took steps to disguise their use.
</P>
<P>
   All defendants were charged with conspiracy to defraud the
Defense Department, a crime punishable by up to 5 years in prison,
and all but Lafferty were also charged with fraud counts punishable
by up to 10 years in prison. All but Yehudah Brin, who is being
sought, have been arrested and have pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Abe Brin's lawyer, Avi Moskowitz, was reported to be out of his
office Tuesday. Lawyers for the two other men who were arrested
declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
