<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BANKING-BILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AFFORDABLE BASIC BANKING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in editorial for Wednesday, Oct. 7:
</P>
<P>
   Making banking services available to citizens who need them has
long been a worthy goal, but it will become even more important in
January, when new rules require that most recipients of federal
benefits _ including Social Security _ have the money transferred
to them electronically. Paper checks will no longer be available.
</P>
<P>
   That is why one section of the House-passed Financial Services
bill was so welcome. It directed federal regulators to require
banks setting up financial services holding companies to offer
low-cost basic banking services _ a low-fee checking account with
limited withdrawals. Such accounts do not offer the flexibility of
more popular accounts, but they are vital for many consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of such a provision in the Senate bill is a significant
problem. Before that bill is acted upon, the basic banking
provision should be reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be good if the Senate would overturn a decision to
strip the Comptroller of the Currency of important regulatory
responsibilities that were left entirely with the Federal Reserve.
That far-reaching decision seems to have been made largely because
Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, is very popular. But banking
issues sometimes are very important for the economy, and the
people, through officials appointed by the president, should have a
say in them.
</P>
<P>
   The pending bill has many good parts. But if Congress passes the
version now pending in the Senate, it may be necessary for
President Clinton to veto it and ask the next Congress to do a
better job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
