A3163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MCCALL-NYT &LR;      10-06 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MCCALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CHALLENGE FOR CARL MCCALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in editorial for Wednesday, Oct. 7:
</P>
<P>
   New York State's comptroller, Carl McCall, is not the only
Albany politician whose campaign treasury is bulging with donations
from companies and executives doing business with the state. McCall
has called for campaign finance reform in the past, and his current
fund-raising is within the law. Still, as described by Clifford J.
Levy in The Times, he has harvested a sizable amount of money from
lawyers, investment officials and others awarded contracts
involving the state's $100 billion pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller, who steadfastly denies any quid pro quo, has
received more than $1.8 million in donations from these sources _
over 35 percent of his campaign donations to date. In some cases,
the contributions landed in McCall's campaign around the same time
the companies landed the contracts. Freeman Spogli &AMP; Co. of Los
Angeles, for example, received an investment of $85 million last
December from the pension fund three days after McCall's campaign
received $16,000 from seven executives of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller, a Democrat whose huge war chest of $5.2 million
this year apparently helped ward off a strong challenge from the
Republicans, argues that he has not done anything illegal or even
wrong. Contributions do not buy state business, his communications
director, Steven Greenberg, asserts, adding that many more
businesses have contracts with the pension fund even though they
have not donated a penny to McCall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this style of fund-raising and the huge amounts of
pension money involved would make even the most trusting of
citizens uncomfortable. The pattern of the McCall campaign
donations provides another of the many reasons New Yorkers deserve
a better system for campaign fund-raising. While advocating tighter
campaign finance laws, McCall asserts that until such laws are
passed, he will not disarm unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he is in a position to lead on this issue. He is facing
a weak opponent. He already has a multimillion-dollar campaign
treasury, and plenty of contributors who are not in the financial
field. For the rest of the campaign, McCall should forswear
questionable contributions. He should promise that if re-elected he
will devise a system for insulating himself from decisions that
present a conflict of interest, and then press the Legislature for
reforms that would bar future comptrollers from taking
contributions that look compromising. McCall has acknowledged that
he has an appearance problem. This is the way to correct it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
