<SLUG> BC-LETTERMAN-STALKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN WHO STALKED LETTERMAN IS A SUICIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (mk-nk) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The woman who was repeatedly jailed for stalking David Letterman
over the last decade committed suicide on Monday by kneeling in
front of a speeding train in western Colorado, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conductor saw her run out on the railroad tracks,'' said
Fred McKee, undersheriff of Delta County.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Margaret Mary Ray, 46, was sentenced to prison
several times for harassing Letterman by trespassing on his
property in New Canaan, Conn., breaking into his house, and trying
to reach him by telephone and in person.
</P>
<P>
   She was first arrested in 1988 while driving Letterman's Porsche
through the Lincoln Tunnel. When she could not pay the toll, she
identified herself as Letterman's wife and her son as David
Letterman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent years, she was repeatedly arrested for trespassing
and for harassing and stalking Letterman. He responded by calling
the local police and using the situation as fodder for jokes on his
late-night television show.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, shortly before moving the show to CBS, he dedicated one
of his celebrated Top 10 lists to ``Things I Have to Do Before I
Leave NBC,'' and included ``Send change-of-address forms to that
woman who breaks into my house.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a 1992 interview with The Advocate of Stamford, Conn., he
had spoken seriously about the matter. ``The thing of it is, she's
insane,'' he said. ``And you don't want to do anything to make it
worse than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Letterman responded to the news of Ms. Ray's death
through a spokesman: ``This is a sad ending to a confused life.''
</P>
<P>
   Undersheriff McKee said that Ms. Ray had been living in
Crawford, Colo. She apparently did not leave a suicide note.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ray spent about 10 months in jail for the trespassing
convictions, as well as 14 months in a mental institution.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, she began to harass Story Musgrave, an astronaut
who retired in 1996 at age 61, said a police officer in Osceola
County, Fla. Ms. Ray called Musgrave repeatedly, sent unwanted
packages to him and broke into his home, turning on all the water
faucets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love him and want to spend the rest of my life with him,''
she told a local newspaper, from jail. She was released last
August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-06-98 2344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
