<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SPLIT ON BUDGET STAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 and JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While Congress and the nation have been preoccupied
with impeachment, a battle has erupted on another front and could
have an equally dramatic impact on this November's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Friday is the deadline for completing the federal budget, and
Republican congressional leaders are desperately trying to stave
off another government shutdown such as the ones three years ago
that resulted in a big public opinion backlash.
</P>
<P>
   They are jettisoning controversial provisions from
appropriations bills and promising to send President Clinton a
series of ``clean'' temporary spending measures if they can't
complete their work by Friday's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   They are doing this despite protests from the conservatives in
their own party. The reason? They don't want to give Democrats the
opportunity to exploit a shutdown and divert the public's attention
from Clinton's travails.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives want Congress to make a stand for tax cuts and
spending caps. They are convinced that backing down will gain them
nothing because Clinton will shut down the government anyway and
distract voters from his possible impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the Senate's No. 2 Republican, said
Congress will pass a temporary spending measure every day if
necessary to keep the government open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the chances of us having a government shutdown are
zero,'' he said Tuesday, after the Senate GOP's weekly caucus. ``If
the Democrats choose to shut down the government, it will clearly
be the Democrats doing it. I hope they're smarter than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress is scrambling to pass the nine remaining spending bills
before heading home to wage re-election campaigns. They must pass
some kind of spending measure by Friday, when a temporary extension
of funding authority expires, or the government will shut down as
it did for 27 non-consecutive days in 1995 and early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles said the GOP will drop its plan for $80 billion in tax
cuts because it doesn't have enough Senate votes. Also on the
chopping block are education vouchers for poor children in the
District of Columbia. Both measures are opposed by the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   As the budget casualties pile up, conservatives are growing more
and more irritated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anyone in our leadership who wants to take the
president on on a government shutdown issue,'' said Rep. Matt
Salmon, R-Ariz. ``It's really sad, because no one is well served
that way. It's not about philosophical differences. It's a
political chess game.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said he's sure that Clinton, even after he gets what he
wants out of the budget negotiations, will shut down the government
with his veto power.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he's going to shut it down anyway, we might as well
draw our philosophical line in the sand,'' he said. ``What I do
blame Republicans for is not being as philosophically committed as
they once were.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Shadegg, R-Ariz., agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot lead out of cowardice. You cannot lead out of a
position of weakness,'' he said. ``They (GOP leaders) are backing
down because they fear they'll be blamed for a government shutdown,
and they fear the retribution at the ballot box.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he's
concerned that Clinton will veto even the most innocuous spending
measures in a scenario similar to the movie ``Wag the Dog''.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned if they're thinking about a domestic ``Wag the
Dog'' to take advantage of some way to change the subject or
distract attention from the administration's problems by not coming
to an agreement on this (budget) bill,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   The House will vote Thursday on whether to open an impeachment
inquiry into the president's conduct surrounding his affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. The House Judiciary
Committee voted Monday along party lines to recommend such an
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle said Democrats have no
intention of shutting down the government for any reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not planning on any government shutdown. There's too
much at stake. . . . The only way it will happen is if the
Republicans insist on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle made it clear that many budget issues are still
outstanding and that the Senate may have to stay the weekend,
beyond Friday's end of federal funding, to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   White House chief of staff Erskine Bowles is scheduled today to
meet with congressional leaders to try to smooth out remaining
budget wrinkles, including funding for the 2000 census that has
been held up over whether to use a controversial statistical
sampling method.
</P>
<P>
   As the clock ticks toward the November election, this budget
period becomes critical for both parties, said Democrat Gene Karp,
who served as a top aide to former Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the next week to two weeks, you may see a big shift in how
the electorate feels. It could shift dramatically either way, de
pending on how these showdowns come out,'' said Karp, who recently
ended a four-year stint as a Department of Labor manager.
</P>
<P>
   Among the unresolved budget issues are whether the Republicans
would drop their push for a contentious series of environmental
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Those include increasing timber production in Alaska's Tongass
National Forest and redistributing some Indian funds so that
wealthier tribes receive less money and poorer tribes get more. &QL; 
 &UR; Adrianne Flynn can be reached at (202) 662-7262 or at
adrianne.flynn &LR; pni.com
 &UR; via e-mail. Jeff Barker can be reached at (202) 662-7264 or at
 &UR; jeff.barker &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
