<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S PLAN REVEALS ANOTHER SEASON GOING BACKWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To be a Mariner baseball executive these days is to be
able to identify a little with the disturbed sleep of Ebenezer
Scrooge.
</P>
<P>
   Every time they doze off in front of a TV screen featuring a
baseball playoff game, the nap is haunted by the Ghost of Dealings
Past.
</P>
<P>
   As you perhaps have read or counted, 25 former Mariners advanced
to the 1998 playoffs, which is, of course, 25 more than advanced
from the current Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The scariest among the ghosts was Randy Johnson, who on
postseason eve was forecast to be the decisive acquisition that
would tilt the baseball championship to the Houston Astros. It was
not hard to imagine the Big Unit as the World Series' most valuable
player, giving him the privilege of shaking his chains and moaning
in Mariner dreams throughout the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   But no.
</P>
<P>
   In a case of industrial-strength deja vu, Johnson pitched well
in Games 1 and 4 of the Division Series against the San Diego
Padres. And he and his team lost Games 1 and 4, just as the
Mariners did with him a year ago in the Division Series against the
Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? asks ``Saturday Night Live's'' Church Lady. Or is
it ... SATAN!
</P>
<P>
   Well, before we throw in a third paranormal analogy and get
completely derailed, neither ghosts nor devils have compromised
Johnson, who has now lost an astonishing five straight postseason
games to tie a major league record.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, Johnson has no effective change-up or curve ball. So
when he's up against good hitters in the postseason, the law of
averages suggest that if a bat is kept whipping through the strike
zone at the right speed, in the span of 120 or so pitches, contact
can be made five or six times.
</P>
<P>
   Since Johnson's two speeds of fast and faster supply the power,
mere contact can produce home runs or big hits.
</P>
<P>
   And since Johnson is usually matched against the other team's
premier pitcher, that usually means a dead-even game decided on
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has pitched 521/3 career innings in the postseason,
giving up 18 earned runs (3.15 ERA) while walking 16 and striking
out 62. But he has a 2-5 record, and one of the wins was in relief
_ the nearly immortal fifth game of the 1995 Division Series
against New York.
</P>
<P>
   The foregoing is not to suggest that Johnson is a choking,
losing dog and the Mariners did well by unloading him this season.
No, no. Just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   However cursed his postseason fate, the Mariners still don't
have a pitcher that can put up Johnson's numbers. Nor do they plan
to acquire one, based on their stated intentions to hunt only for a
No. 3 guy behind Jeff Fassero and Jamie Moyer.
</P>
<P>
   And if the playoffs thus far have offered anything, they have
provided the 10 essentials for postseason camping: pitching,
pitching, pitching, pitching, pitching, pitching, pitching,
pitching, pitching, pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers, perhaps the brawniest hitting club in
baseball, got one stinking run in the three-game sweep by the New
York Yankees. The Astros' ``Killer B's'' of Derek Bell, Craig
Biggio and Jeff Bagwell _ now the Killer Breeze _ are 8-for-78
combined in Houston's consecutive first-round exits in the last two
playoffs. Even the Yankee offense, which helped New York to one of
the great regular seasons in history, hit .210 against Ranger
pitching. The Cubbies, even with Sammy Sosa, were helpless against
the Atlanta Braves' mound staff.
</P>
<P>
   The vaunted Mariner lineup in the 1997 Division Series against
Baltimore hit a collective .218. In the 1995 ALCS against
Cleveland, it hit .184.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone requiring ironic emphasis upon the obvious point
about pitching, the man who dispatched Johnson and the Astros from
the playoffs was none other than Sterling Hitchcock (Mariner
executives: resume nightmare).
</P>
<P>
   The lefty who washed out of Seattle after one season in 1996
because Mariner manager Lou Piniella thought he was a wuss (as he
believed about Andy Benes, Derek Lowe and others) crushed the
Astros with 11 strikeouts over six innings. Hitchcock recovered his
allegedly lost manhood as the No. 4 Padres starter with a 9-7
record and 3.93 ERA in 176 innings, including 158 strikeouts and 48
walks.
</P>
<P>
   He was acquired from the Yankees along with third baseman Russ
Davis in the infamous 1995 deal that sent to New York All-Star
first baseman Tino Martinez and relief pitcher Jeff Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   But after the '96 season in which Hitchcock faded at the end, he
was traded for pitcher Scott Sanders, who was subsequently dealt to
Detroit for two more pitchers, Omar Olivares and Felipe Lira.
</P>
<P>
   Lira was mostly a bust. Olivares was not re-signed and went to
Anaheim, where this year he picked up two wins over the Mariners
and finished 9-9 with a 4.03 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners seem to have had a whole bunch of No. 3 starters
the last few seasons. But they failed to develop or keep them,
instead putting the payroll emphasis upon the aspect of the game
that comes up second-best in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   What is left is a team built backwards, with little plausible
plan for going forward.
</P>
<P>
   At least the players will be making the playoffs, as long as no
one minds the different-colored shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
