<SLUG> BC-NY-JAIL-HEALTHCARE-210&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR SAYS MEDICAL CARE FOR NYC PRISONERS HAS ERODED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The doctor responsible for monitoring the quality of
medical care in city jails said in an interview Tuesday that she
resigned recently because the medical care for prisoners has eroded
under a new managed care contract, and she accused city officials
of refusing to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Audrey Compton, who until Friday was the medical director of
the Health and Hospital Corp.'s Office of Correctional Health
Services, said she resigned from her post because she felt she
could no longer effectively perform her job.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Compton accused city officials of not doing enough to
monitor St. Barnabas Hospital's performance under its contract with
the city to provide health care at Rikers Island and in the
Manhattan Detention Complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left because I was frustrated with the lack of monitoring,''
Dr. Compton said. ``I personally didn't feel as though the contract
was being enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Manhattan district attorney and city's
Board of Correction have been investigating the care of inmates,
including the cases of four prisoners who died.
</P>
<P>
   While city officials last week acknowledged problems in
monitoring St. Barnabas' performance, they pledged to improve their
oversight of medical care in the jails.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tuesday, Joseph Erazo, the executive director of the Office of
Correctional Health Services, said he and his senior staff would be
moving their offices to Rikers Island within the next few weeks to
keep better track of the quality of care in the jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have looked at the issues she was concerned with,'' Erazo
said. ``And I think we're moving to deal with a lot of the issues
that concern her.''
</P>
<P>
   But Erazo suggested that Dr. Compton herself might be partly
responsible for the problems in the jails, given that under state
law she was legally responsible for insuring that inmates received
adequate medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsibility for quality of care is on the medical
director,'' Erazo said, referring to Dr. Compton. ``That's where
the buck stops.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Compton countered that her superiors, including Erazo,
failed to act on her recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel that I was empowered to do my job,'' she said.
``There should have been more of an on-site presence in all the
facilities. It never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Compton is the fifth senior official to have left the Office
of Correctional Health Services since St. Barnabas took over the
contract in January.
</P>
<P>
   Erazo, who took his position in June after the last executive
director resigned, said the departures were routine and not part of
a systemic problem.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the resignations reflect the difficulties
surrounding the Giuliani administration's implementation of the
contract, which they say provides an incentive for St. Barnabas to
increase its profits by withholding medical care from prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   As in many managed care contracts, St. Barnabas is given an
annual lump sum to provide care. Whatever funds the hospital does
not spend at the end of the year can be kept as its profit.
</P>
<P>
   Since St. Barnabas took over the contract in January, visits by
inmates to hospitals outside the jail _ one of the most expensive
forms of care _ have fallen 57 percent. Some city officials said
that St. Barnabas was on track to make a profit of 14 million to
$18 million.
</P>
<P>
   But St. Barnabas officials and Erazo said that the profit would
be far less than that. St. Barnabas officials have said that the
quality of care remained high and that they had added new types of
specialized care that reduced the need for hospital trips.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, city officials said Tuesday that the
district attorney's office had begun a preliminary investigation
into allegations that St. Barnabas used funds from the jail health
contract to pay the full salaries of St. Barnabas medical staff who
did not actually work on Rikers Island, or only worked there part
time.
</P>
<P>
   The new inquiry is part of a review by prosecutors of St.
Barnabas' handling of the contract that includes looking into
allegations that prisoners' medical charts have been tampered with
and medical supplies are in short supply in jail clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Geto, a spokesman for St. Barnabas, did not respond to a
call requesting comment Tuesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
