<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-GAMEONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All's Wells as Yankees win opener
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is there really any reason to go further? Why not
just call off the rest of the postseason, hand the Yankees the
trophy and start the vacation early.
</P>
<P>
   After winning 114 games in the regular season, the Yankees are
beginning to appear invulnerable, having ripped through their first
four playoff games after a 7-2 beating of the Indians Tuesday night
to open the American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   This game, in front of 57,138 at Yankee Stadium, was over
shortly after Indians starter Jaret Wright took the mound. The
right-hander never made it out of the first inning. The Yankees
batted around, and when it was over they led by five runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have now scored 16 runs in the playoffs, allowing
just three in 36 innings, and it doesn't appear right now that the
Indians are going to put up much more of a fight than the Texas
Rangers did.
</P>
<P>
   What is becoming very apparent is the Yankees won 22 more games
than any other team in the American League for a reason. They are
simply very good, perhaps great, as they pursue their second world
title in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Has any team run the table in the postseason, not lost a game,
since baseball went to divisional play in 1969? It has happened
just once, in 1976, when Cincinnati's Big Red Machine took three
straight from the Phillies and swept the Yankees in the World
Series. But the league championship had a best-of-5 format then,
and there was no division series round.
</P>
<P>
   This Yankee team has the ability to pull off such an October
sweep. Again Tuesday, they got super starting pitching from David
Wells, the portly left-hander who had a shutout until he gave up a
two-run homer to Manny Ramirez with one out in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the New York offense has come to life. The first four
hitters in the order went a combined 4-for-42 against the Rangers
with Paul O'Neill getting four of those hits. But in the first
inning against Wright, they all opened with singles.
</P>
<P>
   So about the only suspense on this chilly night was whether the
wife of Darryl Strawberry would throw a strike when she delivered
the ceremonial first pitch. Strawberry, who underwent surgery to
remove a tumor from his colon, watched from a nearby hospital and
Charisse's throw bounced at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   It was about the only thing that fell short for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
