<HEADER>
A3185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALCS-RAIL-COX     10-06 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-RAIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALCS Report
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME 1: YANKEES 7, INDIANS 2
</P>
<P>
   _ TURNING POINT
</P>
<P>
   First inning. The Yankees opened with four straight hits off
Jaret Wright, scoring two runs. It was quite a contrast from the
previous series as the top of the lineup struggled in a three-game
sweep of the Rangers. The Yankees went on to score three more in
the inning, batting around as they sent 10 players to the plate.
The team batted around 36 times during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   _ GAME'S BEST
</P>
<P>
   Yankees left-hander David Wells threw 8 1/3 shutout innings and
has now allowed two runs _ both on Manny Ramirez's ninth-inning
homer Tuesday night _ in 16 1/3 postseason innings.
</P>
<P>
   _ PLAYING UP
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are now 4-0 in the postseason and have done little
wrong. But the Indians are not a club that typically opens a series
with a win. Of the last four postseason series wins, the Indians
have lost the first game, including last week's set to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   _ PLAYING DOWN
</P>
<P>
   A Yankee killer in the playoffs last year, Wright was horrible,
allowing five runs on five hits and not even getting out of the
first inning. His performance was the shortest outing for a
starting pitcher in an ALCS game since Kansas City's Dennis Leonard
failed to retire any of three batters when he faced the Yankees in
Game 5 in 1976. Wright has now allowed 11 runs in five innings in
two postseason starts. . . . Kenny Lofton certainly didn't help his
team, striking out on his first two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   _ WORST PLAY
</P>
<P>
   With Yankees at second and third in the first and two outs,
Wright had a chance to get out of the inning allowing just two
runs. But he let loose a wild pitch against Shane Spencer, bouncing
one past catcher Sandy Alomar, and a runner came home.
</P>
<P>
   _ AT THE PLATE
</P>
<P>
   Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter went 1-for-11 in the divisional
series but had hits on his first two at-bats Tuesday. . . . Yankees
catcher Jorge Posada hit the game's only home run, a solo shot in
the sixth. . . . Spencer, who homered in his first two postseason
games, didn't go deep on this night, going 0-for-x with a walk and
a run scored.
</P>
<P>
   _ ON THE MOUND
</P>
<P>
   Indians righthander Chad Ogea came on for Wright in the first
and tried to limit the damage, but gave up a run-scoring single to
Scott Brosius. ... The six singles the Yankees had in the first
inning were an ALCS record for any inning. ... Also, the five runs
scored in the first inning are the most to open an ALCS, surpassing
the old record of four. ... Jim Poole has nine lives, the Indians
reliever entering the game in the seventh. Poole was in the
playoffs last year with the Giants and he was the pitcher that gave
up the deciding home run to David Justice in Game 6 of the World
Series when the Braves and Indians met. They are now teammates.
</P>
<P>
   _ IN THE FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Justice, in left field for the Indians, saved a run in the
second with a sliding catch on a ball hit by Tino Martinez. ... In
the fourth, Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter went to his right and
grabbed hard hit ball by Travis Fryman, throwing off his back foot
to get the out.
</P>
<P>
   _ ON THE BASES
</P>
<P>
   The Indians reached second base just three times and didn't get
a runner to third. Their best chance to score off Wells came in the
seventh when they had runners at first and second and one out and
Wells fell behind 3-0 to Richie Sexson. But Wells came back and
struck out Sexson.
</P>
<P>
   _ IN THE STANDS
</P>
<P>
   New York sold out its game, packing 57,138 into Yankee Stadium,
the eighth largest crowd since the park was remodeled 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
